{"title_page": "Eclipse", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Eclipse (disambiguation)|Total Eclipse (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Astronomical event where one body is hidden by another}}\n[[File:Solar eclipse 1999 4 NR.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Totality during the 1999 solar eclipse. [[Solar prominence]]s can be seen along the limb (in red) as well as extensive [[solar corona|coronal]] filaments.]]\n\nAn '''eclipse''' is an [[astronomical event]] that occurs when an [[astronomical object]] or [[spacecraft]] is temporarily obscured, by passing into the shadow of another body or by having another body pass between it and the viewer. This alignment of three celestial objects is known as a [[syzygy (astronomy)|syzygy]].<ref>{{cite press release |author=Staff |date=March 31, 1981 |work=The New York Times |title=Science Watch: A Really Big Syzygy |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9F02E5DB1039F932A05750C0A967948260&fta=y |accessdate=2008-02-29 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210100651/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9F02E5DB1039F932A05750C0A967948260&fta=y |archivedate=December 10, 2008 }}</ref> Apart from syzygy, the term eclipse is also used when a spacecraft reaches a position where it can observe two celestial bodies so aligned. An eclipse is the result of either an [[occultation]] (completely hidden) or a [[transit (astronomy)|transit]] (partially hidden).\n\nThe term eclipse is most often used to describe either a [[solar eclipse]], when the Moon's shadow crosses the Earth's surface, or a [[lunar eclipse]], when the Moon moves into the Earth's shadow. However, it can also refer to such events beyond the Earth\u2013Moon system: for example, a planet moving into the shadow cast by one of its moons, a moon passing into the shadow cast by its host planet, or a moon passing into the shadow of another moon. A [[binary star]] system can also produce eclipses if the plane of the orbit of its constituent stars intersects the observer's position.\n\nFor the special cases of solar and lunar eclipses, these only happen during an \"[[eclipse season]]\", the two times of each year when the plane of the Earth's orbit around the Sun crosses with the plane of the Moon's orbit around the Earth. The [[Solar eclipse#Types|type of solar eclipse]] that happens during each season (whether total, annular, hybrid, or partial) depends on [[apparent size]]s of the Sun and Moon. If the orbit of the Earth around the Sun, and the Moon's orbit around the Earth were both in the same plane with each other, then eclipses would happen each and every month. There would be a lunar eclipse at every full moon, and a solar eclipse at every new moon. And if both orbits were perfectly circular, then each solar eclipse would be the same type every month. It is because of the non-planar and non-circular differences that eclipses are not a common event. Lunar eclipses can be viewed from the entire nightside half of the Earth. But solar eclipses, particularly total eclipses occurring at any one particular point on the Earth's surface, are very rare events that can be many decades apart.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe term is derived from the [[ancient Greek]] noun {{lang|grc|\u1f14\u03ba\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03c8\u03b9\u03c2}} (''{{lang|grc-Latn|\u00e9kleipsis}}''), which means \"the abandonment\", \"the downfall\", or \"the darkening of a heavenly body\", which is derived from the verb {{lang|grc|\u1f10\u03ba\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03c0\u03c9}} (''{{lang|grc-Latn|ekle\u00edp\u014d}}'') which means \"to abandon\", \"to darken\", or \"to cease to exist,\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.in.gr/dictionary/lookup.asp?Word=%E5%EA%EB%E5%DF%F0%F9+++&x=0&y=0  |accessdate=2009-09-24 |df= |title=in.gr}}</ref> a combination of prefix {{lang|grc|\u1f10\u03ba-}} (''{{lang|grc-Latn|ek-}}''), from preposition {{lang|grc|\u1f10\u03ba}} (''{{lang|grc-Latn|ek}}''), \"out,\" and of verb {{lang|grc|\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03c0\u03c9}} (''{{lang|grc-Latn|le\u00edp\u014d}}''), \"to be absent\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lingvozone.com/main.jsp?action=translation&do=dictionary&language_id_from=23&language_id_to=8&word=%CE%BB%CE%B5%CE%AF%CF%80%CF%89+&t.x=55&t.y=16|title=LingvoSoft|website=lingvozone.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130128095850/http://www.lingvozone.com/main.jsp?action=translation&do=dictionary&language_id_from=23&language_id_to=8&word=%CE%BB%CE%B5%CE%AF%CF%80%CF%89+&t.x=55&t.y=16|archivedate=2013-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate_t?prev=hp&hl=en&js=y&text=%CE%BB%CE%B5%CE%AF%CF%80%CF%89&sl=el&tl=en&history_state0=&swap=1#|title=Google Translate|author=|date=|website=translate.google.com}}</ref>\n\n== Umbra, penumbra and antumbra ==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=November 2017}}\n{{Main|Umbra, penumbra and antumbra}}\n\n[[File:Umbra01.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|Umbra, penumbra and antumbra cast by an opaque object occulting a larger light source]]\nFor any two objects in space, a line can be extended from the first through the second. The latter object will block some amount of light being emitted by the former, creating a region of shadow around the axis of the line. Typically these objects are moving with respect to each other and their surroundings, so the resulting shadow will sweep through a region of space, only passing through any particular location in the region for a fixed interval of time. As viewed from such a location, this shadowing event is known as an eclipse.<ref name=westfall2014>{{citation | title=Celestial Shadows: Eclipses, Transits, and Occultations | volume=410 | series=Astrophysics and Space Science Library | first1=John | last1=Westfall | first2=William | last2=Sheehan | publisher=Springer | year=2014 | isbn=978-1493915354 | pages=1\u22125 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W9mLBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1 | postscript=. }}</ref>\n\nTypically the cross-section of the objects involved in an astronomical eclipse are roughly disk shaped.<ref name=westfall2014/> The region of an object's shadow during an eclipse is divided into three parts:<ref name=glossary>{{cite web | last=Espenak | first=Fred | date=September 21, 2007 | url=http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/SEhelp/SEglossary.html | title=Glossary of Solar Eclipse Terms | publisher=NASA | accessdate=2008-02-28 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080224074526/http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/SEhelp/SEglossary.html | archivedate=February 24, 2008 }}</ref>\n* The ''umbra'', within which the object completely covers the light source. For the [[Sun]], this light source is the photosphere.\n* The ''antumbra'', extending beyond the tip of the umbra, within which the object is completely in front of the light source but too small to completely cover it.\n* The ''penumbra'', within which the object is only partially in front of the light source.\n\n[[File:Solar eclipse types.svg|right|thumb|upright=0.9|Sun-Moon configurations that produce a total (A), annular (B), and partial (C) solar eclipse]]\nA '''total eclipse''' occurs when the observer is within the umbra, an '''annular eclipse''' when the observer is within the antumbra, and a '''partial eclipse''' when the observer is within the penumbra. During a lunar eclipse only the umbra and penumbra are applicable. This is because Earth's apparent diameter from the viewpoint of the Moon is nearly four times that of the Sun. The same terms may be used analogously in describing other eclipses, e.g., the antumbra of [[Deimos (moon)|Deimos]] crossing [[Mars]], or [[Phobos (moon)|Phobos]] entering Mars's penumbra.\n\nThe ''first contact'' occurs when the eclipsing object's disc first starts to impinge on the light source; ''second contact'' is when the disc moves completely within the light source; ''third contact'' when it starts to move out of the light; and ''fourth'' or ''last contact'' when it finally leaves the light source's disc entirely.\n\nFor spherical bodies, when the occulting object is smaller than the star, the length (''L'') of the umbra's cone-shaped shadow is given by:\n\n:<math>L\\ =\\ \\frac{r \\cdot R_o}{R_s - R_o}</math>\n\nwhere ''R<sub>s</sub>'' is the radius of the star, ''R<sub>o</sub>'' is the occulting object's radius, and ''r'' is the distance from the star to the occulting object. For [[Earth]], on average ''L'' is equal to 1.384{{e|6}}&nbsp;[[kilometer|km]], which is much larger than the Moon's [[semimajor axis]] of 3.844{{e|5}}&nbsp;km. Hence the umbral cone of the Earth can completely envelop the Moon during a [[lunar eclipse]].<ref>{{cite book \n|first=Robin M. |last=Green |date=1985 \n|title=Spherical Astronomy |publisher=Oxford University Press \n|isbn=978-0-521-31779-5 }}</ref> If the occulting object has an atmosphere, however, some of the luminosity of the star can be [[refraction|refracted]] into the volume of the umbra. This occurs, for example, during an eclipse of the Moon by the Earth&mdash;producing a faint, [[red|ruddy]] illumination of the Moon even at totality.\n\nOn Earth, the shadow cast during an eclipse moves very approximately at 1&nbsp;km per sec. This depends on the location of the shadow on the Earth and the angle in which it is moving.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciforums.com/threads/speed-of-eclipse-shadow.53722/|title=Speed of eclipse shadow? - Sciforums|website=sciforums.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402094757/http://www.sciforums.com/threads/speed-of-eclipse-shadow.53722/|archivedate=2015-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Eclipse cycles ==\n{{Main|Eclipse cycle}}\n\nAn [[eclipse cycle]] takes place when eclipses in a series are separated by a certain interval of time. This happens when the orbital motions of the bodies form repeating harmonic patterns. A particular instance is the [[saros (astronomy)|saros]], which results in a repetition of a solar or lunar eclipse every 6,585.3&nbsp;days, or a little over 18 years. Because this is not a whole number of days, successive eclipses will be visible from different parts of the world.<ref>{{cite web\n |last=Espenak \n |first=Fred \n |date=July 12, 2007 \n |url=http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/SEsaros/SEsaros.html \n |title=Eclipses and the Saros \n |publisher=NASA \n |accessdate=2007-12-13 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030225501/http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/SEsaros/SEsaros.html \n |archivedate=2007-10-30 \n}}</ref>\n\n==Earth\u2013Moon system==\n[[Image:Lunar eclipse diagram-en.svg|240px|thumb|A symbolic orbital diagram from the view of the Earth at the center, with the Sun and Moon projected upon the [[celestial sphere]], showing the Moon's two nodes where eclipses can occur.]]\nAn eclipse involving the Sun, Earth, and Moon can occur only when they are nearly in a straight line, allowing one to be hidden behind another, viewed from the third. Because the [[orbit of the Moon|orbital plane of the Moon]] is tilted with respect to the orbital plane of the Earth (the [[ecliptic]]), eclipses can occur only when the Moon is close to the intersection of these two planes (the [[node (astronomy)|node]]s). The Sun, Earth and nodes are aligned twice a year (during an [[eclipse season]]), and eclipses can occur during a period of about two months around these times. There can be from four to seven eclipses in a calendar year, which repeat according to various [[eclipse cycle]]s, such as a [[saros (astronomy)|saros]].\n\nBetween 1901 and 2100 there are the maximum of seven eclipses in:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://moonblink.info/Eclipse/lists/stats|title=Eclipse Statistics|website=moonblink.info|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527212303/http://moonblink.info/Eclipse/lists/stats|archivedate=2014-05-27}}</ref>\n* four (penumbral) lunar and three solar eclipses: 1908, [[Solar eclipse of December 26, 2038#Related eclipses|2038]].\n* four solar and three lunar eclipses: 1918, [[December 1982 lunar eclipse#Related eclipses|1973]], 2094.\n* five solar and two lunar eclipses: 1934.\n\nExcluding penumbral lunar eclipses, there are a maximum of seven eclipses in:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staff.science.uu.nl/~gent0113/eclipse/eclipsecycles.htm|title=A Catalogue of Eclipse Cycles|first=R.H. van|last=Gent|website=staff.science.uu.nl|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110905080517/http://www.staff.science.uu.nl/~gent0113/eclipse/eclipsecycles.htm|archivedate=2011-09-05}}</ref>\n* 1591, 1656, 1787, 1805, 1918, 1935, 1982, and 2094.\n\n===Solar eclipse===\n{{main|Solar eclipse}}\n[[Image:2008-08-01 Solar eclipse progression with timestamps.jpg|thumb|right|The progression of a [[solar eclipse]] on August 1, 2008, viewed from [[Novosibirsk, Russia]]. The time between shots is three minutes.]]\nAs observed from the Earth, a [[solar eclipse]] occurs when the Moon passes in front of the Sun. The type of solar eclipse event depends on the distance of the Moon from the Earth during the event. A total solar eclipse occurs when the Earth intersects the umbra portion of the Moon's shadow. When the umbra does not reach the surface of the Earth, the Sun is only partially occulted, resulting in an annular eclipse. Partial solar eclipses occur when the viewer is inside the penumbra.<ref>{{cite web\n |first       = R.\n |last        = Hipschman\n |title       = Solar Eclipse: Why Eclipses Happen\n |url         = http://www.exploratorium.edu/eclipse/why.html\n |accessdate  = 2008-12-01\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20081205073238/http://www.exploratorium.edu/eclipse/why.html\n |archivedate = 2008-12-05\n|date        = 2015-10-29\n }}</ref>\n[[File:Solar eclipse visualisation.svg|thumb|upright|Each icon shows the view from the centre of its black spot, representing the Moon (not to scale)]]\nThe [[Magnitude of eclipse|eclipse magnitude]] is the fraction of the Sun's diameter that is covered by the Moon. For a total eclipse, this value is always greater than or equal to one. In both annular and total eclipses, the eclipse magnitude is the ratio of the angular sizes of the Moon to the Sun.<ref>{{cite book \n|first=Martin V. |last=Zombeck |date=2006 \n|title=Handbook of Space Astronomy and Astrophysics \n|edition=Third |page=48 \n|publisher=Cambridge University Press \n|isbn=978-0-521-78242-5 }}</ref>\n\nSolar eclipses are relatively brief events that can only be viewed in totality along a relatively narrow track. Under the most favorable circumstances, a total solar eclipse can last for 7&nbsp;minutes, 31&nbsp;seconds, and can be viewed along a track that is up to 250&nbsp;km wide. However, the region where a partial eclipse can be observed is much larger. The Moon's umbra will advance eastward at a rate of 1,700&nbsp;km/h, until it no longer intersects the Earth's surface.\n\n[[File:Geometry of a Total Solar Eclipse.svg|thumb|300px|right|Geometry of a total solar eclipse (not to scale)]]\n\nDuring a solar eclipse, the Moon can sometimes perfectly cover the Sun because its apparent size is nearly the same as the Sun's when viewed from the Earth. A total solar eclipse is in fact an [[occultation]] while an annular solar eclipse is a [[Astronomical transit|transit]].\n\nWhen observed at points in space other than from the Earth's surface, the Sun can be eclipsed by bodies other than the Moon. Two examples include when the crew of [[Apollo 12]] observed the [[:File:Earth Eclipses Sun-ap12-s80-37406.jpg|Earth to eclipse the Sun]] in 1969 and when the ''[[Cassini\u2013Huygens|Cassini]]'' [[Space probe|probe]] observed [[:File:Saturn eclipse.jpg|Saturn to eclipse the Sun]] in 2006.\n\n===Lunar eclipse===\n{{main|Lunar eclipse}}\n[[Image:Eclipse lune.jpg|thumb|250px|right|The progression of a [[lunar eclipse]] from right to left. Totality is shown with the first two images. These required a longer [[exposure time]] to make the details visible.]]\n\nLunar eclipses occur when the Moon passes through the Earth's shadow. This happens only during a [[full moon]], when the Moon is on the far side of the Earth from the Sun. Unlike a solar eclipse, an eclipse of the Moon can be observed from nearly an entire hemisphere. For this reason it is much more common to observe a lunar eclipse from a given location. A lunar eclipse lasts longer, taking several hours to complete, with totality itself usually averaging anywhere from about 30 minutes to over an hour.<ref>{{cite web\n |author      = Staff\n |date        = January 6, 2006\n |url         = http://www.crh.noaa.gov/fsd/astro/suneclipse.php\n |title       = Solar and Lunar Eclipses\n |publisher   = NOAA\n |accessdate  = 2007-05-02\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070512191007/http://www.crh.noaa.gov/fsd/astro/suneclipse.php\n |archivedate = May 12, 2007\n}}</ref>\n\nThere are three types of lunar eclipses: penumbral, when the Moon crosses only the Earth's penumbra; partial, when the Moon crosses partially into the Earth's [[umbra]]; and total, when the Moon crosses entirely into the Earth's umbra. Total lunar eclipses pass through all three phases. Even during a total lunar eclipse, however, the Moon is not completely dark. Sunlight refracted through the Earth's atmosphere enters the umbra and provides a faint illumination. Much as in a sunset, the atmosphere tends to more strongly scatter light with shorter wavelengths, so the illumination of the Moon by refracted light has a red hue,<ref>\n{{cite web |last=Phillips |first=Tony |date=February 13, 2008 |url=https://science.nasa.gov/headlines/y2008/13feb_lunareclipse.htm |title=Total Lunar Eclipse |publisher=NASA |accessdate=2008-03-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080301221225/http://science.nasa.gov/headlines/y2008/13feb_lunareclipse.htm |archivedate=March 1, 2008 }}</ref> thus the phrase 'Blood Moon' is often found in descriptions of such lunar events as far back as eclipses are recorded.<ref>Ancient Timekeepers, {{cite web |url=http://blog.world-mysteries.com/science/ancient-timekeepers-part-1-movements-of-the-earth/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-25 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026041145/http://blog.world-mysteries.com/science/ancient-timekeepers-part-1-movements-of-the-earth/ |archivedate=2011-10-26 |date=2011-09-16 }}</ref>\n\n===Historical record===\n\nRecords of solar eclipses have been kept since ancient times. Eclipse dates can be used for [[chronological dating]] of historical records. A [[Syria]]n clay tablet, in the Ugaritic language, records a solar eclipse which occurred on March 5, 1223 B.C.,<ref>{{cite journal |last=de Jong |first=T. |last2=van Soldt |first2=W. H. |title=The earliest known solar eclipse record redated |journal=Nature |date=1989 |volume=338 |issue=6212 |pages=238\u2013240 |doi=10.1038/338238a0 |bibcode=1989Natur.338..238D }}</ref> while Paul Griffin argues that a stone in Ireland records an eclipse on November 30, 3340 B.C.<ref>{{cite web\n |last        = Griffin\n |first       = Paul\n |date        = 2002\n |url         = http://www.astronomy.ca/3340eclipse/\n |title       = Confirmation of World's Oldest Solar Eclipse Recorded in Stone\n |publisher   = The Digital Universe\n |accessdate  = 2007-05-02\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070409070529/http://www.astronomy.ca/3340eclipse/\n |archivedate = 2007-04-09\n}}</ref> Positing classical-era astronomers' use of Babylonian eclipse records mostly from the 13th century BC provides a feasible and mathematically consistent<ref><!--\n\n-->See [http://www.dioi.org/vols/wg0.pdf DIO 16] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726000734/http://www.dioi.org/vols/wg0.pdf |date=2011-07-26 }} p.2 (2009). Though those Greek and perhaps Babylonian astronomers who determined the three previously unsolved lunar motions were spread over more than four centuries (263 BC to 160 AD), the math-indicated early eclipse records are all from a [http://www.dioi.org/thr.htm#ufnr much smaller span] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402105220/http://www.dioi.org/thr.htm |date=2015-04-02 }}: the 13th century BC. The anciently attested Greek technique: use of eclipse cycles, automatically providing integral ratios, which is how all ancient astronomers' lunar motions were expressed. Long-eclipse-cycle-based reconstructions precisely produce all of the 24 digits appearing in the three attested ancient motions just cited: 6247 synod = 6695 anom (System A), 5458 synod = 5923 drac (Hipparchos), 3277 synod = 3512 anom (Planetary Hypotheses). By contrast, the System B motion, 251 synod = 269 anom (Aristarchos?), could have been determined without recourse to remote eclipse data, simply by using a few eclipse-pairs 4267 months apart.<!--\n\n--></ref> explanation for the Greek finding all three lunar mean motions (synodic, anomalistic, draconitic) to a precision of about one part in a million or better. Chinese historical records of solar eclipses date back over 3,000 years and have been used to measure changes in the Earth's rate of spin.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.bibalex.org/eclipse2006/HistoricalObservationsofSolarEclipses.htm\n |title       = Solar Eclipses in History and Mythology\n |publisher   = Bibliotheca Alexandrina\n |accessdate  = 2007-05-02\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070408050126/http://www.bibalex.org/eclipse2006/HistoricalObservationsofSolarEclipses.htm\n |archivedate = 2007-04-08\n}}</ref>\n\nBy the 1600s, European astronomers were publishing books with diagrams explaining how lunar and solar eclipses occurred.<ref>{{cite book|last=Girault|first=Simon|title=Globe dv monde contenant un bref traite du ciel & de la terra|date=1592|location=Langres, France|page=Fol. 8V}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Hevelius|first=Johannes|title=Observatio Eclipseos Solaris Gedani|date=1652|location=Danzig, Poland}}</ref>  In order to disseminate this information to a broader audience and decrease fear of the consequences of eclipses, booksellers printed broadsides explaining the event either using the science or via astrology.<ref>{{cite book|last=Stephanson|first=Bruce |last2=Bolt|first2=Marvin |last3=Friedman|first3=Anna Felicity |title=The Universe Unveiled: Instruments and Images through History|date=2000|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, UK|isbn=978-0521791434|pages=32\u201333}}</ref>\n\n==Other planets and dwarf planets==\n\n===Gas giants===\n{{see also|Solar eclipses on Jupiter|Solar eclipses on Saturn|Solar eclipses on Uranus|Solar eclipses on Neptune}}\n[[Image:JupiterandIo.jpg|thumb|right|A picture of [[Jupiter]] and its moon [[Io (moon)|Io]] taken by [[Hubble Space Telescope|Hubble]]. The black spot is Io's shadow.]]\n[[Image:Saturn eclipse.jpg|250px|right|thumb|[[Saturn]] occults the Sun as seen from the ''[[Cassini\u2013Huygens]]'' space probe]]\nThe [[gas giant]] planets have many moons and thus frequently display eclipses. The most striking involve [[Jupiter]], which has four large moons and a low [[axial tilt]], making eclipses more frequent as these bodies pass through the shadow of the larger planet. Transits occur with equal frequency. It is common to see the larger moons casting circular shadows upon Jupiter's cloudtops.\n\nThe eclipses of the [[Galilean moon]]s by Jupiter became accurately predictable once their orbital elements were known. During the 1670s, it was discovered that these events were occurring about 17 minutes later than expected when Jupiter was on the far side of the Sun. [[Ole R\u00f8mer]] deduced that the delay was caused by the time needed for light to travel from Jupiter to the Earth. This was used to produce the first estimate of the [[speed of light]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.mathpages.com/home/kmath203/kmath203.htm\n |title       = Roemer's Hypothesis\n |publisher   = MathPages\n |accessdate  = 2007-01-12\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20110224015233/http://www.mathpages.com/home/kmath203/kmath203.htm\n |archivedate = 2011-02-24\n}}</ref>\n\nOn the other three [[gas giant]]s ([[Saturn]], [[Uranus]] and [[Neptune]]) eclipses only occur at certain periods during the planet's orbit, due to their higher [[inclination]] between the orbits of the moon and the [[orbital plane (astronomy)|orbital plane]] of the planet. The moon [[Titan (moon)|Titan]], for example, has an orbital plane tilted about 1.6\u00b0 to Saturn's equatorial plane. But Saturn has an axial tilt of nearly 27\u00b0. The orbital plane of Titan only crosses the line of sight to the Sun at two points along Saturn's orbit. As the orbital period of Saturn is 29.7&nbsp;years, an eclipse is only possible about every 15 years.\n\nThe timing of the Jovian satellite eclipses was also used to calculate an observer's [[longitude]] upon the Earth. By knowing the expected time when an eclipse would be observed at a standard longitude (such as [[Greenwich]]), the time difference could be computed by accurately observing the local time of the eclipse. The time difference gives the longitude of the observer because every hour of difference corresponded to 15\u00b0 around the Earth's equator. This technique was used, for example, by [[Giovanni Domenico Cassini|Giovanni D. Cassini]] in 1679 to re-map [[France]].<ref>{{cite journal\n |last        = Cassini\n |first       = Giovanni D.\n |authorlink  = Giovanni Domenico Cassini\n |title       = Monsieur Cassini His New and Exact Tables for the Eclipses of the First Satellite of Jupiter, Reduced to the Julian Stile, and Meridian of London\n |journal     = [[Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society]]\n |date        = 1694\n |volume      = 18\n |issue       = 207\u2013214\n |pages       = 237\u2013256\n |doi         = 10.1098/rstl.1694.0048\n |jstor       = 102468\n }}</ref>\n\n===Mars===\n{{main|Transit of Phobos from Mars}}\n[[Image:PIA05553.gif|right|thumbnail|[[Transit of Phobos from Mars]], as seen by the Mars ''[[Opportunity (rover)|Opportunity rover]]'' (10 March 2004).]]\nOn [[Mars]], only partial solar eclipses ([[Transit of Phobos from Mars|transits]]) are possible, because neither of its moons is large enough, at their respective orbital radii, to cover the Sun's disc as seen from the surface of the planet. Eclipses of the moons by Mars are not only possible, but commonplace, with hundreds occurring each Earth year. There are also rare occasions when Deimos is eclipsed by Phobos.<ref>{{cite book \n|first=Norman |last=Davidson |date=1985 \n|title=Astronomy and the Imagination: A New Approach to Man's Experience of the Stars \n|publisher=Routledge \n|isbn=978-0-7102-0371-7 }}</ref> Martian eclipses have been photographed from both the surface of Mars and from orbit.\n\n===Pluto===\n{{main|Solar eclipses on Pluto}}\n[[Pluto]], with its proportionately largest moon [[Charon (moon)|Charon]], is also the site of many eclipses. A series of such mutual eclipses occurred between 1985 and 1990.<ref>{{cite journal \n|last=Buie |first=M. W. |author2=Polk, K. S. \n|title=Polarization of the Pluto-Charon System During a Satellite Eclipse \n|journal=Bulletin of the American Astronomical Society \n|date=1988 |volume=20 |page=806 \n|bibcode=1988BAAS...20..806B }}</ref> These daily events led to the first accurate measurements of the physical parameters of both objects.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Tholen |first=D. J. |author2=Buie, M. W. |author3=Binzel, R. P. |author4=Frueh, M. L. |title=Improved Orbital and Physical Parameters for the Pluto-Charon System |journal=Science |date=1987 |volume=237 |issue=4814 |pages=512&ndash;514 |doi=10.1126/science.237.4814.512 |pmid=17730324 |bibcode=1987Sci...237..512T }}</ref>\n\n===Mercury and Venus===\nEclipses are impossible on [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] and [[Venus]], which have no moons. However, both have been observed to [[Astronomical transit|transit]] across the face of the Sun. There are on average 13 transits of Mercury each century. Transits of Venus occur in pairs separated by an interval of eight years, but each pair of events happen less than once a century.<ref>{{cite web |last=Espenak |first=Fred |date=May 29, 2007 |url=http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/transit/transit.html |title=Planetary Transits Across the Sun |publisher=NASA |accessdate=2008-03-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311033452/http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/transit/transit.html |archivedate=March 11, 2008 }}</ref> According to NASA, the next pair of transits will occur on December 10, 2117 and December 8, 2125. Transits on Mercury are much more common.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eclipse2017.nasa.gov/when-will-next-transits-mercury-and-venus-occur-during-total-solar-eclipse|title=When will the next transits of Mercury and Venus occur during a total solar eclipse? {{!}} Total Solar Eclipse 2017|website=eclipse2017.nasa.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-09-25|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918151937/https://eclipse2017.nasa.gov/when-will-next-transits-mercury-and-venus-occur-during-total-solar-eclipse|archivedate=2017-09-18}}</ref>\n\n==Eclipsing binaries==\nA [[binary star]] system consists of two stars that orbit around their common [[centre of mass]]. The movements of both stars lie on a common [[Orbital plane (astronomy)|orbital plane]] in space. When this plane is very closely aligned with the location of an observer, the stars can be seen to pass in front of each other. The result is a type of extrinsic [[variable star]] system called an [[eclipsing binary]].\n\nThe maximum [[luminosity]] of an eclipsing binary system is equal to the sum of the luminosity contributions from the individual stars. When one star passes in front of the other, the luminosity of the system is seen to decrease. The luminosity returns to normal once the two stars are no longer in alignment.<ref>{{cite web\n |last=Bruton \n |first=Dan \n |url=http://www.physics.sfasu.edu/astro/ebstar/ebstar.html \n |title=Eclipsing binary stars \n |publisher=Midnightkite Solutions \n |accessdate=2007-05-01 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070414144827/http://www.physics.sfasu.edu/astro/ebstar/ebstar.html \n |archivedate=2007-04-14 \n}}</ref>\n\nThe first eclipsing binary star system to be discovered was [[Algol]], a star system in the constellation [[Perseus (constellation)|Perseus]]. Normally this star system has a [[visual magnitude]] of 2.1. However, every 2.867 days the magnitude decreases to 3.4 for more than nine hours. This is caused by the passage of the dimmer member of the pair in front of the brighter star.<ref>{{cite web \n|last=Price \n|first=Aaron \n|date=January 1999 \n|url=http://www.aavso.org/vstar/vsots/0199.shtml \n|title=Variable Star Of The Month: Beta Persei (Algol) \n|publisher=AAVSO \n|accessdate=2007-05-01 \n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070405003853/http://www.aavso.org/vstar/vsots/0199.shtml <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=2007-04-05 }}</ref> The concept that an eclipsing body caused these luminosity variations was introduced by [[John Goodricke]] in 1783.<ref>{{cite journal \n|last=Goodricke \n|first=John \n|authorlink=John Goodricke \n|last2=Englefield \n|first2=H. C. \n|title=Observations of a New Variable Star \n|journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London \n|date=1785 \n|volume=75 \n|pages=153\u2013164 \n|bibcode=1785RSPT...75..153G \n|doi=10.1098/rstl.1785.0009 }}</ref>\n\n== Types ==\n'''Sun - Moon - Earth:''' '''[[Solar eclipse]]''' | [[annular eclipse]] | [[hybrid eclipse]] | [[Solar eclipse|partial eclipse]]\n\n'''Sun - Earth - Moon:''' '''[[Lunar eclipse]]''' | [[penumbral eclipse]] | [[partial lunar eclipse]] | [[central lunar eclipse]]\n\n'''Sun - Phobos - Mars: [[Transit of Phobos from Mars]]''' | [[Solar eclipses on Mars]]\n\n'''Sun - Deimos - Mars: [[Transit of Deimos from Mars]]''' | [[Solar eclipses on Mars]]\n\n'''Other types:''' [[Solar eclipses on Jupiter]] | [[Solar eclipses on Saturn]] | [[Solar eclipses on Uranus]] | [[Solar eclipses on Neptune]] | [[Solar eclipses on Pluto]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of solar eclipses in the 21st century]]\n* [[Mursili's eclipse]]\n* [[Transit of Venus]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons|Eclipse}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Wiktionary|eclipse}}\n* {{Britannica|178098|Eclipse (astronomy)}}\n* {{YouTube|id=VwklVTy03Wc|title=Phobos Eclipsing Mars Observed by Curiosity Rover}}\n* [http://www.staff.science.uu.nl/~gent0113/eclipse/eclipsecycles.htm A Catalogue of Eclipse Cycles]\n* [http://moonblink.info/Eclipse/lists/search Search 5,000 years of eclipses]\n* [http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse.html NASA eclipse home page]\n* [http://www.eclipses.info International Astronomical Union's Working Group on Solar Eclipses]\n* [http://xjubier.free.fr/en/site_pages/SolarEclipsesGoogleMaps.html Interactive eclipse maps site]\n* [https://demos.smu.ca/demos/astronomy/200-eclipses Classroom demonstration of how an eclipse occurs]\n\n;Image galleries\n*[http://www.twanight.org/newTWAN/gallery.asp?Gallery=Eclipses&page=1 The World at Night Eclipse Gallery]\n* [http://www.perseus.gr/Astro-Eclipses.htm Solar and Lunar Eclipse Image Gallery]\n* [http://www.williams.edu/astronomy/eclipse Williams College eclipse collection of images]\n\n{{lunar eclipses}}\n{{Solar eclipses}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Eclipses| ]]\n[[Category:Astrological aspects]]\n[[Category:Astronomical events]]\n[[Category:Earth phenomena]]\n\n[[de:Sonnenfinsternis]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Astronomical event where one body is hidden by another}}\n{{Other uses|Eclipse (disambiguation)|Total Eclipse (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n[[File:Solar eclipse 1999 4 NR.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Totality during the 1999 solar eclipse. [[Solar prominence]]s can be seen along the limb (in red) as well as extensive [[corona]]l filaments.]]\n\nAn '''eclipse''' is an [[astronomical event]] that occurs when an [[astronomical object]] or [[spacecraft]] is temporarily obscured, by passing into the shadow of another body or by having another body pass between it and the viewer. This alignment of three celestial objects is known as a [[syzygy (astronomy)|syzygy]].<ref>{{cite press release |author=Staff |date=March 31, 1981 |work=The New York Times |title=Science Watch: A Really Big Syzygy |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9F02E5DB1039F932A05750C0A967948260&fta=y |accessdate=2008-02-29 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210100651/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9F02E5DB1039F932A05750C0A967948260&fta=y |archivedate=December 10, 2008 }}</ref> Apart from syzygy, the term eclipse is also used when a spacecraft reaches a position where it can observe two celestial bodies so aligned. An eclipse is the result of either an [[occultation]] (completely hidden) or a [[transit (astronomy)|transit]] (partially hidden).\n\nThe term eclipse is most often used to describe either a [[solar eclipse]], when the Moon's shadow crosses the Earth's surface, or a [[lunar eclipse]], when the Moon moves into the Earth's shadow. However, it can also refer to such events beyond the Earth\u2013Moon system: for example, a planet moving into the shadow cast by one of its moons, a moon passing into the shadow cast by its host planet, or a moon passing into the shadow of another moon. A [[binary star]] system can also produce eclipses if the plane of the orbit of its constituent stars intersects the observer's position.\n\nFor the special cases of solar and lunar eclipses, these only happen during an \"[[eclipse season]]\", the two times of each year when the plane of the Earth's orbit around the Sun crosses with the plane of the Moon's orbit around the Earth. The [[Solar eclipse#Types|type of solar eclipse]] that happens during each season (whether total, annular, hybrid, or partial) depends on [[apparent size]]s of the Sun and Moon. If the orbit of the Earth around the Sun, and the Moon's orbit around the Earth were both in the same plane with each other, then eclipses would happen each and every month. There would be a lunar eclipse at every full moon, and a solar eclipse at every new moon. And if both orbits were perfectly circular, then each solar eclipse would be the same type every month. It is because of the non-planar and non-circular differences that eclipses are not a common event. Lunar eclipses can be viewed from the entire nightside half of the Earth. But solar eclipses, particularly total eclipses occurring at any one particular point on the Earth's surface, are very rare events that can be many decades apart.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe term is derived from the [[ancient Greek]] noun {{lang|grc|\u1f14\u03ba\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03c8\u03b9\u03c2}} (''{{lang|grc-Latn|\u00e9kleipsis}}''), which means \"the abandonment\", \"the downfall\", or \"the darkening of a heavenly body\", which is derived from the verb {{lang|grc|\u1f10\u03ba\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03c0\u03c9}} (''{{lang|grc-Latn|ekle\u00edp\u014d}}'') which means \"to abandon\", \"to darken\", or \"to cease to exist,\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.in.gr/dictionary/lookup.asp?Word=%E5%EA%EB%E5%DF%F0%F9+++&x=0&y=0  |accessdate=2009-09-24 |df= |title=in.gr}}</ref> a combination of prefix {{lang|grc|\u1f10\u03ba-}} (''{{lang|grc-Latn|ek-}}''), from preposition {{lang|grc|\u1f10\u03ba}} (''{{lang|grc-Latn|ek}}''), \"out,\" and of verb {{lang|grc|\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03c0\u03c9}} (''{{lang|grc-Latn|le\u00edp\u014d}}''), \"to be absent\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lingvozone.com/main.jsp?action=translation&do=dictionary&language_id_from=23&language_id_to=8&word=%CE%BB%CE%B5%CE%AF%CF%80%CF%89+&t.x=55&t.y=16|title=LingvoSoft|website=lingvozone.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130128095850/http://www.lingvozone.com/main.jsp?action=translation&do=dictionary&language_id_from=23&language_id_to=8&word=%CE%BB%CE%B5%CE%AF%CF%80%CF%89+&t.x=55&t.y=16|archivedate=2013-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate_t?prev=hp&hl=en&js=y&text=%CE%BB%CE%B5%CE%AF%CF%80%CF%89&sl=el&tl=en&history_state0=&swap=1#|title=Google Translate|author=|date=|website=translate.google.com}}</ref>\n\n== Umbra, penumbra and antumbra ==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=November 2017}}\n{{Main|Umbra, penumbra and antumbra}}\n\n[[File:Umbra01.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|Umbra, penumbra and antumbra cast by an opaque object occulting a larger light source]]\nFor any two objects in space, a line can be extended from the first through the second. The latter object will block some amount of light being emitted by the former, creating a region of shadow around the axis of the line. Typically these objects are moving with respect to each other and their surroundings, so the resulting shadow will sweep through a region of space, only passing through any particular location in the region for a fixed interval of time. As viewed from such a location, this shadowing event is known as an eclipse.<ref name=westfall2014>{{citation | title=Celestial Shadows: Eclipses, Transits, and Occultations | volume=410 | series=Astrophysics and Space Science Library | first1=John | last1=Westfall | first2=William | last2=Sheehan | publisher=Springer | year=2014 | isbn=978-1493915354 | pages=1\u22125 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W9mLBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1 | postscript=. }}</ref>\n\nTypically the cross-section of the objects involved in an astronomical eclipse are roughly disk shaped.<ref name=westfall2014/> The region of an object's shadow during an eclipse is divided into three parts:<ref name=glossary>{{cite web | last=Espenak | first=Fred | date=September 21, 2007 | url=http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/SEhelp/SEglossary.html | title=Glossary of Solar Eclipse Terms | publisher=NASA | accessdate=2008-02-28 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080224074526/http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/SEhelp/SEglossary.html | archivedate=February 24, 2008 }}</ref>\n* The ''umbra'', within which the object completely covers the light source. For the [[Sun]], this light source is the photosphere.\n* The ''antumbra'', extending beyond the tip of the umbra, within which the object is completely in front of the light source but too small to completely cover it.\n* The ''penumbra'', within which the object is only partially in front of the light source.\n\n[[File:Solar eclipse types.svg|right|thumb|upright=0.9|Sun-Moon configurations that produce a total (A), annular (B), and partial (C) solar eclipse]]\nA '''total eclipse''' occurs when the observer is within the umbra, an '''annular eclipse''' when the observer is within the antumbra, and a '''partial eclipse''' when the observer is within the penumbra. During a lunar eclipse only the umbra and penumbra are applicable. This is because Earth's apparent diameter from the viewpoint of the Moon is nearly four times that of the Sun. The same terms may be used analogously in describing other eclipses, e.g., the antumbra of [[Deimos (moon)|Deimos]] crossing [[Mars]], or [[Phobos (moon)|Phobos]] entering Mars's penumbra.\n\nThe ''first contact'' occurs when the eclipsing object's disc first starts to impinge on the light source; ''second contact'' is when the disc moves completely within the light source; ''third contact'' when it starts to move out of the light; and ''fourth'' or ''last contact'' when it finally leaves the light source's disc entirely.\n\nFor spherical bodies, when the occulting object is smaller than the star, the length (''L'') of the umbra's cone-shaped shadow is given by:\n\n:<math>L\\ =\\ \\frac{r \\cdot R_o}{R_s - R_o}</math>\n\nwhere ''R<sub>s</sub>'' is the radius of the star, ''R<sub>o</sub>'' is the occulting object's radius, and ''r'' is the distance from the star to the occulting object. For [[Earth]], on average ''L'' is equal to 1.384{{e|6}}&nbsp;[[kilometer|km]], which is much larger than the Moon's [[semimajor axis]] of 3.844{{e|5}}&nbsp;km. Hence the umbral cone of the Earth can completely envelop the Moon during a [[lunar eclipse]].<ref>{{cite book \n|first=Robin M. |last=Green |date=1985 \n|title=Spherical Astronomy |publisher=Oxford University Press \n|isbn=978-0-521-31779-5 }}</ref> If the occulting object has an atmosphere, however, some of the luminosity of the star can be [[refraction|refracted]] into the volume of the umbra. This occurs, for example, during an eclipse of the Moon by the Earth&mdash;producing a faint, [[red|ruddy]] illumination of the Moon even at totality.\n\nOn Earth, the shadow cast during an eclipse moves very approximately at 1&nbsp;km per sec. This depends on the location of the shadow on the Earth and the angle in which it is moving.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciforums.com/threads/speed-of-eclipse-shadow.53722/|title=Speed of eclipse shadow? - Sciforums|website=sciforums.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402094757/http://www.sciforums.com/threads/speed-of-eclipse-shadow.53722/|archivedate=2015-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Eclipse cycles ==\n{{Main|Eclipse cycle}}\n\nAn [[eclipse cycle]] takes place when eclipses in a series are separated by a certain interval of time. This happens when the orbital motions of the bodies form repeating harmonic patterns. A particular instance is the [[saros (astronomy)|saros]], which results in a repetition of a solar or lunar eclipse every 6,585.3&nbsp;days, or a little over 18 years. Because this is not a whole number of days, successive eclipses will be visible from different parts of the world.<ref>{{cite web\n |last=Espenak \n |first=Fred \n |date=July 12, 2007 \n |url=http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/SEsaros/SEsaros.html \n |title=Eclipses and the Saros \n |publisher=NASA \n |accessdate=2007-12-13 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030225501/http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/SEsaros/SEsaros.html \n |archivedate=2007-10-30 \n}}</ref>\n\n==Earth\u2013Moon system==\n[[Image:Lunar eclipse diagram-en.svg|240px|thumb|A symbolic orbital diagram from the view of the Earth at the center, with the Sun and Moon projected upon the [[celestial sphere]], showing the Moon's two nodes where eclipses can occur.]]\nAn eclipse involving the Sun, Earth, and Moon can occur only when they are nearly in a straight line, allowing one to be hidden behind another, viewed from the third. Because the [[orbit of the Moon|orbital plane of the Moon]] is tilted with respect to the orbital plane of the Earth (the [[ecliptic]]), eclipses can occur only when the Moon is close to the intersection of these two planes (the [[node (astronomy)|node]]s). The Sun, Earth and nodes are aligned twice a year (during an [[eclipse season]]), and eclipses can occur during a period of about two months around these times. There can be from four to seven eclipses in a calendar year, which repeat according to various [[eclipse cycle]]s, such as a [[saros (astronomy)|saros]].\n\nBetween 1901 and 2100 there are the maximum of seven eclipses in:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://moonblink.info/Eclipse/lists/stats|title=Eclipse Statistics|website=moonblink.info|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527212303/http://moonblink.info/Eclipse/lists/stats|archivedate=2014-05-27}}</ref>\n* four (penumbral) lunar and three solar eclipses: 1908, [[Solar eclipse of December 26, 2038#Related eclipses|2038]].\n* four solar and three lunar eclipses: 1918, [[December 1982 lunar eclipse#Related eclipses|1973]], 2094.\n* five solar and two lunar eclipses: 1934.\n\nExcluding penumbral lunar eclipses, there are a maximum of seven eclipses in:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staff.science.uu.nl/~gent0113/eclipse/eclipsecycles.htm|title=A Catalogue of Eclipse Cycles|first=R.H. van|last=Gent|website=staff.science.uu.nl|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110905080517/http://www.staff.science.uu.nl/~gent0113/eclipse/eclipsecycles.htm|archivedate=2011-09-05}}</ref>\n* 1591, 1656, 1787, 1805, 1918, 1935, 1982, and 2094.\n\n===Solar eclipse===\n{{main|Solar eclipse}}\n[[Image:2008-08-01 Solar eclipse progression with timestamps.jpg|thumb|right|The progression of a [[solar eclipse]] on August 1, 2008, viewed from [[Novosibirsk, Russia]]. The time between shots is three minutes.]]\nAs observed from the Earth, a [[solar eclipse]] occurs when the Moon passes in front of the Sun. The type of solar eclipse event depends on the distance of the Moon from the Earth during the event. A total solar eclipse occurs when the Earth intersects the umbra portion of the Moon's shadow. When the umbra does not reach the surface of the Earth, the Sun is only partially occulted, resulting in an annular eclipse. Partial solar eclipses occur when the viewer is inside the penumbra.<ref>{{cite web\n |first       = R.\n |last        = Hipschman\n |title       = Solar Eclipse: Why Eclipses Happen\n |url         = http://www.exploratorium.edu/eclipse/why.html\n |accessdate  = 2008-12-01\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20081205073238/http://www.exploratorium.edu/eclipse/why.html\n |archivedate = 2008-12-05\n|date        = 2015-10-29\n }}</ref>\n[[File:Solar eclipse visualisation.svg|thumb|upright|Each icon shows the view from the centre of its black spot, representing the Moon (not to scale)]]\nThe [[Magnitude of eclipse|eclipse magnitude]] is the fraction of the Sun's diameter that is covered by the Moon. For a total eclipse, this value is always greater than or equal to one. In both annular and total eclipses, the eclipse magnitude is the ratio of the angular sizes of the Moon to the Sun.<ref>{{cite book \n|first=Martin V. |last=Zombeck |date=2006 \n|title=Handbook of Space Astronomy and Astrophysics \n|edition=Third |page=48 \n|publisher=Cambridge University Press \n|isbn=978-0-521-78242-5 }}</ref>\n\nSolar eclipses are relatively brief events that can only be viewed in totality along a relatively narrow track. Under the most favorable circumstances, a total solar eclipse can last for 7&nbsp;minutes, 31&nbsp;seconds, and can be viewed along a track that is up to 250&nbsp;km wide. However, the region where a partial eclipse can be observed is much larger. The Moon's umbra will advance eastward at a rate of 1,700&nbsp;km/h, until it no longer intersects the Earth's surface.\n\n[[File:Geometry of a Total Solar Eclipse.svg|thumb|300px|right|Geometry of a total solar eclipse (not to scale)]]\n\nDuring a solar eclipse, the Moon can sometimes perfectly cover the Sun because its apparent size is nearly the same as the Sun's when viewed from the Earth. A total solar eclipse is in fact an [[occultation]] while an annular solar eclipse is a [[Astronomical transit|transit]].\n\nWhen observed at points in space other than from the Earth's surface, the Sun can be eclipsed by bodies other than the Moon. Two examples include when the crew of [[Apollo 12]] observed the [[:File:Earth Eclipses Sun-ap12-s80-37406.jpg|Earth to eclipse the Sun]] in 1969 and when the ''[[Cassini\u2013Huygens|Cassini]]'' [[Space probe|probe]] observed [[:File:Saturn eclipse.jpg|Saturn to eclipse the Sun]] in 2006.\n\n===Lunar eclipse===\n{{main|Lunar eclipse}}\n[[Image:Eclipse lune.jpg|thumb|250px|right|The progression of a [[lunar eclipse]] from right to left. Totality is shown with the first two images. These required a longer [[exposure time]] to make the details visible.]]\n\nLunar eclipses occur when the Moon passes through the Earth's shadow. This happens only during a [[full moon]], when the Moon is on the far side of the Earth from the Sun. Unlike a solar eclipse, an eclipse of the Moon can be observed from nearly an entire hemisphere. For this reason it is much more common to observe a lunar eclipse from a given location. A lunar eclipse lasts longer, taking several hours to complete, with totality itself usually averaging anywhere from about 30 minutes to over an hour.<ref>{{cite web\n |author      = Staff\n |date        = January 6, 2006\n |url         = http://www.crh.noaa.gov/fsd/astro/suneclipse.php\n |title       = Solar and Lunar Eclipses\n |publisher   = NOAA\n |accessdate  = 2007-05-02\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070512191007/http://www.crh.noaa.gov/fsd/astro/suneclipse.php\n |archivedate = May 12, 2007\n}}</ref>\n\nThere are three types of lunar eclipses: penumbral, when the Moon crosses only the Earth's penumbra; partial, when the Moon crosses partially into the Earth's [[umbra]]; and total, when the Moon crosses entirely into the Earth's umbra. Total lunar eclipses pass through all three phases. Even during a total lunar eclipse, however, the Moon is not completely dark. Sunlight refracted through the Earth's atmosphere enters the umbra and provides a faint illumination. Much as in a sunset, the atmosphere tends to more strongly scatter light with shorter wavelengths, so the illumination of the Moon by refracted light has a red hue,<ref>\n{{cite web |last=Phillips |first=Tony |date=February 13, 2008 |url=https://science.nasa.gov/headlines/y2008/13feb_lunareclipse.htm |title=Total Lunar Eclipse |publisher=NASA |accessdate=2008-03-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080301221225/http://science.nasa.gov/headlines/y2008/13feb_lunareclipse.htm |archivedate=March 1, 2008 }}</ref> thus the phrase 'Blood Moon' is often found in descriptions of such lunar events as far back as eclipses are recorded.<ref>Ancient Timekeepers, {{cite web |url=http://blog.world-mysteries.com/science/ancient-timekeepers-part-1-movements-of-the-earth/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-25 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026041145/http://blog.world-mysteries.com/science/ancient-timekeepers-part-1-movements-of-the-earth/ |archivedate=2011-10-26 |date=2011-09-16 }}</ref>\n\n===Historical record===\n\nRecords of solar eclipses have been kept since ancient times. Eclipse dates can be used for [[chronological dating]] of historical records. A [[Syria]]n clay tablet, in the Ugaritic language, records a solar eclipse which occurred on March 5, 1223 B.C.,<ref>{{cite journal |last=de Jong |first=T. |last2=van Soldt |first2=W. H. |title=The earliest known solar eclipse record redated |journal=Nature |date=1989 |volume=338 |issue=6212 |pages=238\u2013240 |doi=10.1038/338238a0 |bibcode=1989Natur.338..238D }}</ref> while Paul Griffin argues that a stone in Ireland records an eclipse on November 30, 3340 B.C.<ref>{{cite web\n |last        = Griffin\n |first       = Paul\n |date        = 2002\n |url         = http://www.astronomy.ca/3340eclipse/\n |title       = Confirmation of World's Oldest Solar Eclipse Recorded in Stone\n |publisher   = The Digital Universe\n |accessdate  = 2007-05-02\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070409070529/http://www.astronomy.ca/3340eclipse/\n |archivedate = 2007-04-09\n}}</ref> Positing classical-era astronomers' use of Babylonian eclipse records mostly from the 13th century BC provides a feasible and mathematically consistent<ref><!--\n\n-->See [http://www.dioi.org/vols/wg0.pdf DIO 16] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726000734/http://www.dioi.org/vols/wg0.pdf |date=2011-07-26 }} p.2 (2009). Though those Greek and perhaps Babylonian astronomers who determined the three previously unsolved lunar motions were spread over more than four centuries (263 BC to 160 AD), the math-indicated early eclipse records are all from a [http://www.dioi.org/thr.htm#ufnr much smaller span] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402105220/http://www.dioi.org/thr.htm |date=2015-04-02 }}: the 13th century BC. The anciently attested Greek technique: use of eclipse cycles, automatically providing integral ratios, which is how all ancient astronomers' lunar motions were expressed. Long-eclipse-cycle-based reconstructions precisely produce all of the 24 digits appearing in the three attested ancient motions just cited: 6247 synod = 6695 anom (System A), 5458 synod = 5923 drac (Hipparchos), 3277 synod = 3512 anom (Planetary Hypotheses). By contrast, the System B motion, 251 synod = 269 anom (Aristarchos?), could have been determined without recourse to remote eclipse data, simply by using a few eclipse-pairs 4267 months apart.<!--\n\n--></ref> explanation for the Greek finding all three lunar mean motions (synodic, anomalistic, draconitic) to a precision of about one part in a million or better. Chinese historical records of solar eclipses date back over 3,000 years and have been used to measure changes in the Earth's rate of spin.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.bibalex.org/eclipse2006/HistoricalObservationsofSolarEclipses.htm\n |title       = Solar Eclipses in History and Mythology\n |publisher   = Bibliotheca Alexandrina\n |accessdate  = 2007-05-02\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070408050126/http://www.bibalex.org/eclipse2006/HistoricalObservationsofSolarEclipses.htm\n |archivedate = 2007-04-08\n}}</ref>\n\nBy the 1600s, European astronomers were publishing books with diagrams explaining how lunar and solar eclipses occurred.<ref>{{cite book|last=Girault|first=Simon|title=Globe dv monde contenant un bref traite du ciel & de la terra|date=1592|location=Langres, France|page=Fol. 8V}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Hevelius|first=Johannes|title=Observatio Eclipseos Solaris Gedani|date=1652|location=Danzig, Poland}}</ref>  In order to disseminate this information to a broader audience and decrease fear of the consequences of eclipses, booksellers printed broadsides explaining the event either using the science or via astrology.<ref>{{cite book|last=Stephanson|first=Bruce |last2=Bolt|first2=Marvin |last3=Friedman|first3=Anna Felicity |title=The Universe Unveiled: Instruments and Images through History|date=2000|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, UK|isbn=978-0521791434|pages=32\u201333}}</ref>\n\n==Other planets and dwarf planets==\n\n===Gas giants===\n{{see also|Solar eclipses on Jupiter|Solar eclipses on Saturn|Solar eclipses on Uranus|Solar eclipses on Neptune}}\n[[Image:JupiterandIo.jpg|thumb|right|A picture of [[Jupiter]] and its moon [[Io (moon)|Io]] taken by [[Hubble Space Telescope|Hubble]]. The black spot is Io's shadow.]]\n[[Image:Saturn eclipse.jpg|250px|right|thumb|[[Saturn]] occults the Sun as seen from the ''[[Cassini\u2013Huygens]]'' space probe]]\nThe [[gas giant]] planets have many moons and thus frequently display eclipses. The most striking involve [[Jupiter]], which has four large moons and a low [[axial tilt]], making eclipses more frequent as these bodies pass through the shadow of the larger planet. Transits occur with equal frequency. It is common to see the larger moons casting circular shadows upon Jupiter's cloudtops.\n\nThe eclipses of the [[Galilean moon]]s by Jupiter became accurately predictable once their orbital elements were known. During the 1670s, it was discovered that these events were occurring about 17 minutes later than expected when Jupiter was on the far side of the Sun. [[Ole R\u00f8mer]] deduced that the delay was caused by the time needed for light to travel from Jupiter to the Earth. This was used to produce the first estimate of the [[speed of light]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.mathpages.com/home/kmath203/kmath203.htm\n |title       = Roemer's Hypothesis\n |publisher   = MathPages\n |accessdate  = 2007-01-12\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20110224015233/http://www.mathpages.com/home/kmath203/kmath203.htm\n |archivedate = 2011-02-24\n}}</ref>\n\nOn the other three [[gas giant]]s ([[Saturn]], [[Uranus]] and [[Neptune]]) eclipses only occur at certain periods during the planet's orbit, due to their higher [[inclination]] between the orbits of the moon and the [[orbital plane (astronomy)|orbital plane]] of the planet. The moon [[Titan (moon)|Titan]], for example, has an orbital plane tilted about 1.6\u00b0 to Saturn's equatorial plane. But Saturn has an axial tilt of nearly 27\u00b0. The orbital plane of Titan only crosses the line of sight to the Sun at two points along Saturn's orbit. As the orbital period of Saturn is 29.7&nbsp;years, an eclipse is only possible about every 15 years.\n\nThe timing of the Jovian satellite eclipses was also used to calculate an observer's [[longitude]] upon the Earth. By knowing the expected time when an eclipse would be observed at a standard longitude (such as [[Greenwich]]), the time difference could be computed by accurately observing the local time of the eclipse. The time difference gives the longitude of the observer because every hour of difference corresponded to 15\u00b0 around the Earth's equator. This technique was used, for example, by [[Giovanni Domenico Cassini|Giovanni D. Cassini]] in 1679 to re-map [[France]].<ref>{{cite journal\n |last        = Cassini\n |first       = Giovanni D.\n |authorlink  = Giovanni Domenico Cassini\n |title       = Monsieur Cassini His New and Exact Tables for the Eclipses of the First Satellite of Jupiter, Reduced to the Julian Stile, and Meridian of London\n |journal     = [[Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society]]\n |date        = 1694\n |volume      = 18\n |issue       = 207\u2013214\n |pages       = 237\u2013256\n |doi         = 10.1098/rstl.1694.0048\n |jstor       = 102468\n }}</ref>\n\n===Mars===\n{{main|Transit of Phobos from Mars}}\n[[Image:PIA05553.gif|right|thumbnail|[[Transit of Phobos from Mars]], as seen by the Mars ''[[Opportunity (rover)|Opportunity rover]]'' (10 March 2004).]]\nOn [[Mars]], only partial solar eclipses ([[Transit of Phobos from Mars|transits]]) are possible, because neither of its moons is large enough, at their respective orbital radii, to cover the Sun's disc as seen from the surface of the planet. Eclipses of the moons by Mars are not only possible, but commonplace, with hundreds occurring each Earth year. There are also rare occasions when Deimos is eclipsed by Phobos.<ref>{{cite book \n|first=Norman |last=Davidson |date=1985 \n|title=Astronomy and the Imagination: A New Approach to Man's Experience of the Stars \n|publisher=Routledge \n|isbn=978-0-7102-0371-7 }}</ref> Martian eclipses have been photographed from both the surface of Mars and from orbit.\n\n===Pluto===\n{{main|Solar eclipses on Pluto}}\n[[Pluto]], with its proportionately largest moon [[Charon (moon)|Charon]], is also the site of many eclipses. A series of such mutual eclipses occurred between 1985 and 1990.<ref>{{cite journal \n|last=Buie |first=M. W. |author2=Polk, K. S. \n|title=Polarization of the Pluto-Charon System During a Satellite Eclipse \n|journal=Bulletin of the American Astronomical Society \n|date=1988 |volume=20 |page=806 \n|bibcode=1988BAAS...20..806B }}</ref> These daily events led to the first accurate measurements of the physical parameters of both objects.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Tholen |first=D. J. |author2=Buie, M. W. |author3=Binzel, R. P. |author4=Frueh, M. L. |title=Improved Orbital and Physical Parameters for the Pluto-Charon System |journal=Science |date=1987 |volume=237 |issue=4814 |pages=512&ndash;514 |doi=10.1126/science.237.4814.512 |pmid=17730324 |bibcode=1987Sci...237..512T }}</ref>\n\n===Mercury and Venus===\nEclipses are impossible on [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] and [[Venus]], which have no moons. However, both have been observed to [[Astronomical transit|transit]] across the face of the Sun. There are on average 13 transits of Mercury each century. Transits of Venus occur in pairs separated by an interval of eight years, but each pair of events happen less than once a century.<ref>{{cite web |last=Espenak |first=Fred |date=May 29, 2007 |url=http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/transit/transit.html |title=Planetary Transits Across the Sun |publisher=NASA |accessdate=2008-03-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311033452/http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/transit/transit.html |archivedate=March 11, 2008 }}</ref> According to NASA, the next pair of transits will occur on December 10, 2117 and December 8, 2125. Transits on Mercury are much more common.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eclipse2017.nasa.gov/when-will-next-transits-mercury-and-venus-occur-during-total-solar-eclipse|title=When will the next transits of Mercury and Venus occur during a total solar eclipse? {{!}} Total Solar Eclipse 2017|website=eclipse2017.nasa.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-09-25|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918151937/https://eclipse2017.nasa.gov/when-will-next-transits-mercury-and-venus-occur-during-total-solar-eclipse|archivedate=2017-09-18}}</ref>\n\n==Eclipsing binaries==\nA [[binary star]] system consists of two stars that orbit around their common [[centre of mass]]. The movements of both stars lie on a common [[Orbital plane (astronomy)|orbital plane]] in space. When this plane is very closely aligned with the location of an observer, the stars can be seen to pass in front of each other. The result is a type of extrinsic [[variable star]] system called an [[eclipsing binary]].\n\nThe maximum [[luminosity]] of an eclipsing binary system is equal to the sum of the luminosity contributions from the individual stars. When one star passes in front of the other, the luminosity of the system is seen to decrease. The luminosity returns to normal once the two stars are no longer in alignment.<ref>{{cite web\n |last=Bruton \n |first=Dan \n |url=http://www.physics.sfasu.edu/astro/ebstar/ebstar.html \n |title=Eclipsing binary stars \n |publisher=Midnightkite Solutions \n |accessdate=2007-05-01 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070414144827/http://www.physics.sfasu.edu/astro/ebstar/ebstar.html \n |archivedate=2007-04-14 \n}}</ref>\n\nThe first eclipsing binary star system to be discovered was [[Algol]], a star system in the constellation [[Perseus (constellation)|Perseus]]. Normally this star system has a [[visual magnitude]] of 2.1. However, every 2.867 days the magnitude decreases to 3.4 for more than nine hours. This is caused by the passage of the dimmer member of the pair in front of the brighter star.<ref>{{cite web \n|last=Price \n|first=Aaron \n|date=January 1999 \n|url=http://www.aavso.org/vstar/vsots/0199.shtml \n|title=Variable Star Of The Month: Beta Persei (Algol) \n|publisher=AAVSO \n|accessdate=2007-05-01 \n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070405003853/http://www.aavso.org/vstar/vsots/0199.shtml <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=2007-04-05 }}</ref> The concept that an eclipsing body caused these luminosity variations was introduced by [[John Goodricke]] in 1783.<ref>{{cite journal \n|last=Goodricke \n|first=John \n|authorlink=John Goodricke \n|last2=Englefield \n|first2=H. C. \n|title=Observations of a New Variable Star \n|journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London \n|date=1785 \n|volume=75 \n|pages=153\u2013164 \n|bibcode=1785RSPT...75..153G \n|doi=10.1098/rstl.1785.0009 }}</ref>\n\n== Types ==\n'''Sun - Moon - Earth:''' '''[[Solar eclipse]]''' | [[annular eclipse]] | [[hybrid eclipse]] | [[Solar eclipse|partial eclipse]]\n\n'''Sun - Earth - Moon:''' '''[[Lunar eclipse]]''' | [[penumbral eclipse]] | [[partial lunar eclipse]] | [[central lunar eclipse]]\n\n'''Sun - Phobos - Mars: [[Transit of Phobos from Mars]]''' | [[Solar eclipses on Mars]]\n\n'''Sun - Deimos - Mars: [[Transit of Deimos from Mars]]''' | [[Solar eclipses on Mars]]\n\n'''Other types:''' [[Solar eclipses on Jupiter]] | [[Solar eclipses on Saturn]] | [[Solar eclipses on Uranus]] | [[Solar eclipses on Neptune]] | [[Solar eclipses on Pluto]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of solar eclipses in the 21st century]]\n* [[Mursili's eclipse]]\n* [[Transit of Venus]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons|Eclipse}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Wiktionary|eclipse}}\n* {{Britannica|178098|Eclipse (astronomy)}}\n* {{YouTube|id=VwklVTy03Wc|title=Phobos Eclipsing Mars Observed by Curiosity Rover}}\n* [http://www.staff.science.uu.nl/~gent0113/eclipse/eclipsecycles.htm A Catalogue of Eclipse Cycles]\n* [http://moonblink.info/Eclipse/lists/search Search 5,000 years of eclipses]\n* [http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse.html NASA eclipse home page]\n* [http://www.eclipses.info International Astronomical Union's Working Group on Solar Eclipses]\n* [http://xjubier.free.fr/en/site_pages/SolarEclipsesGoogleMaps.html Interactive eclipse maps site]\n* [https://demos.smu.ca/demos/astronomy/200-eclipses Classroom demonstration of how an eclipse occurs]\n\n;Image galleries\n*[http://www.twanight.org/newTWAN/gallery.asp?Gallery=Eclipses&page=1 The World at Night Eclipse Gallery]\n* [http://www.perseus.gr/Astro-Eclipses.htm Solar and Lunar Eclipse Image Gallery]\n* [http://www.williams.edu/astronomy/eclipse Williams College eclipse collection of images]\n\n{{lunar eclipses}}\n{{Solar eclipses}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Eclipses| ]]\n[[Category:Astrological aspects]]\n[[Category:Astronomical events]]\n[[Category:Earth phenomena]]\n\n[[de:Sonnenfinsternis]]\n", "name_user": "Netoholic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:post-move link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eclipse"}
{"title_page": "Airline", "text_new": "{{short description|Company that provides air transport services for travelling passengers and freight}}\n{{Other uses}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Europe to South American in 3 Days Poster (19482266291).jpg|thumb|1930s German poster advertising a weekly [[airmail]] service from [[Deutsche Luft Hansa|Deutsche Lufthansa]], [[Syndicato Condor]] and [[Deutsche Zeppelin Reederei]]]]\n\nAn '''airline''' is a company that provides [[civil aviation|air transport services]] for traveling [[passenger]]s and [[freight]]. Airlines utilize [[aircraft]] to supply these services and may form [[partnership]]s or [[Airline alliance|alliances]] with other airlines for [[codeshare agreements]], in which they both offer and operate the same flight. Generally, airline companies are recognized with an [[Air operator's certificate|air operating certificate]] or license issued by a governmental aviation body. Airlines may be scheduled or [[Air charter|charter]] operators.\n\nThe [[List of airlines by foundation date|first airline]] was the German [[airship]] company [[DELAG]], founded on 16 November 1909.<ref name=\":0\" /> The four oldest non-airship airlines that still exist are the Netherlands' [[KLM]] (1919),<ref name=\":1\" /> Colombia's [[Avianca]] (1919),<ref name=\":2\" /> Australia's [[Qantas]] (1921)<ref name=\":3\" /> and the Czech Republic's [[Czech Airlines]] (1923).<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAirline ownership has seen a shift from mostly personal ownership until the 1930s to government-ownership of major airlines from the 1940s to 1980s and back to large-scale [[privatiation]] following the mid-1980s.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xK4QxAVSd5gC&pg=PA185|title=The Airline Business in the Twenty-first Century|last=Doganis|first=Rigas|date=2001|publisher=Psychology Press|year=|isbn=978-0-415-20883-3|location=|pages=185|language=en}}</ref> Since the 1980s, there has also been a trend of major airline [[mergers]] and the formation of airline alliances.<ref name=\":6\">{{Citation|last=Kumar|first=B. Rajesh|title=Mergers and Acquisitions in the Airline Industry|date=2012|url=https://doi.org/10.1057/9781137005908_11|work=Mega Mergers and Acquisitions: Case Studies from Key Industries|pages=226\u2013230|editor-last=Kumar|editor-first=B. Rajesh|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|language=en|doi=10.1057/9781137005908_11|isbn=978-1-137-00590-8|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> The largest alliances are [[Star Alliance]], [[SkyTeam]] and [[Oneworld]], and these three collectively accounted for more than 60% of global commercial air traffic in 2015.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iata.org/en/pressroom/pr/2016-07-05-01/|title=India Sees Highest Domestic Market Growth in 2015|website=www.iata.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> Airline alliances coordinate their passenger service programs (such as [[Airport lounge|lounges]] and [[frequent-flyer programs]]), offer special [[Interlining|interline]] tickets and often engage in extensive codesharing (sometimes systemwide).\n\n{{As of|2019||df=}}, the [[largest airline]] by passengers carried and fleet size was the [[American Airlines Group]], while [[Delta Air Lines]] was the largest by [[revenue]]. [[Lufthansa Group]] was the largest by number of [[Employee|employees]], [[FedEx Express]] by freight [[tonne-kilometres]], [[Turkish Airlines]] by number of countries served and [[UPS Airlines]] by number of destinations served<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressroom.ups.com/pressroom/ContentDetailsViewer.page?ConceptType=FactSheets&id=1426321563187-193|title=UPS Fact Sheet|last=|first=|date=|website=UPS Pressroom|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231144152/https://pressroom.ups.com/pressroom/ContentDetailsViewer.page?ConceptType=FactSheets&id=1426321563187-193|archive-date=2019-12-31|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> (though [[United Airlines]] was the largest passenger airline by number of destinations served).<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://hub.united.com/Corporate-Fact-Sheet|title=Corporate fact sheet|last=|first=|date=|website=United Hub|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205134015/https://hub.united.com/corporate-fact-sheet/|archive-date=2019-12-05|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://skyrefund.com/en/blog/biggest-airlines-in-the-world|title=Titans: The Biggest Airlines in the World in 2019|website=skyrefund.com|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===The first airlines===\n[[DELAG]], ''Deutsche Luftschiffahrts-Aktiengesellschaft I'' was the [[List of airlines by foundation date|world's first airline]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.airships.net/delag-passenger-zeppelins |title=DELAG: The World's First Airline, using dirgibles. |publisher=Airships.net |date= |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref> It was founded on November 16, 1909, with government assistance, and operated airships manufactured by The [[Zeppelin|Zeppelin Corporation]]. Its headquarters were in [[Frankfurt]]. The first [[fixed-wing]] scheduled airline was started on January 1, 1914, from [[St. Petersburg, Florida]], to [[Tampa, Florida]], operated by the St. Petersburg and Tampa Airboat Line.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.space.com/16657-worlds-first-commercial-airline-the-greatest-moments-in-flight.html|title=World\u2019s First Commercial Airline {{!}} The Greatest Moments in Flight|work=Space.com|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref> The four [[List of airlines by foundation|oldest non-dirigible airlines]] that still exist are the Netherlands' [[KLM]] (1919),<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.klm.com/corporate/en/about-klm/history/index.html|title=History - KLM Corporate|access-date=2017-10-14|language=nl-en}}</ref> Colombia's [[Avianca]] (1919),<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.aviancaholdings.com/en/history|title=History - Avianca Holdings S.A. - www.aviancaholdings.com|website=www.aviancaholdings.com|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref> Australia's [[Qantas]] (1921),<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.qantas.com/travel/airlines/history-founders/global/en|title=Founders of Qantas {{!}} Qantas|website=www.qantas.com|language=en-AU|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref> and the Czech Republic's [[Czech Airlines]] (1923).<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.csa.cz/cz-en/about-us/|title=About Us {{!}} Czech Airlines|website=\u010cSA.cz|language=en|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>\n\n===European airline industry===\n====Beginnings====\n[[File:Klm-poster-1919.jpg|thumb|upright|A 1919 advertisement for the Dutch airline [[KLM]], founded on 7 October 1919, the [[List of airlines by foundation date|oldest running airline still operating under its original name]]]]\n\n[[File:Tanken van een vliegtuig Airplane provided with fuel.jpg|thumb|The [[Handley Page Type W|Handley Page W.8b]] was used by [[Handley Page Transport]], an early British airline established in 1919.]]\nThe earliest fixed wing airline in Europe was [[Aircraft Transport and Travel]], formed by [[George Holt Thomas]] in 1916; via a series of takeovers and mergers, this company is an ancestor of modern-day [[British Airways]]. Using a fleet of former military [[Airco DH.4]]A biplanes that had been modified to carry two passengers in the [[fuselage]], it operated relief flights between [[Folkestone]] and [[Ghent]]. On 15 July 1919, the company flew a proving flight across the [[English Channel]], despite a lack of support from the British government. Flown by Lt. H Shaw in an [[Airco DH.9]] between [[RAF Hendon]] and [[Paris \u2013 Le Bourget Airport]], the flight took 2 hours and 30 minutes at \u00a321 per passenger.\n\nOn 25 August 1919, the company used [[Airco DH.16|DH.16s]] to pioneer a regular service from [[Hounslow Heath Aerodrome]] to Le Bourget, the first regular international service in the world. The airline soon gained a reputation for reliability, despite problems with bad weather, and began to attract European competition. In November 1919, it won the first British civil [[airmail]] contract. Six [[Royal Air Force]] [[Airco DH.9A]] aircraft were lent to the company, to operate the airmail service between [[Hawkinge]] and [[Cologne]]. In 1920, they were returned to the Royal Air Force.<ref>''The Putnam Aeronautical Review'' edited by John Motum, p170 Volume one 1990 Naval Institute Press</ref>\n\nOther British competitors were quick to follow \u2013 [[Handley Page Transport]] was established in 1919 and used the company's converted [[World War One|wartime]] [[Handley Page Type O|Type O/400]] [[bomber]]s with a capacity for 12 passengers,<ref>https://www.flightglobal.com/FlightPDFArchive/1961/1961%20-%200055.PDF</ref> to run a [[London]]-[[Paris]] passenger service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.airlinehistory.co.uk/Airline%20History/History1903.asp|title=Airline History 1903 to 1919|website=www.airlinehistory.co.uk|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>\n\nThe first French airline was [[A\u00e9ropostale (aviation)|Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des lignes Lat\u00e9co\u00e8re]], later known as A\u00e9ropostale, which started its first service in late 1918 to Spain. The [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale des Transports A\u00e9riens]] was created in late 1919, by the [[Farman]] brothers and the [[Farman F.60 Goliath]] plane flew scheduled services from [[Toussus-le-Noble]] to [[Kenley]], near [[Croydon]], England. Another early French airline was the [[Compagnie des Messageries A\u00e9riennes]], established in 1919 by [[Louis-Charles Breguet]], offering a mail and freight service between [[Paris \u2013 Le Bourget Airport|Le Bourget Airport]], [[Paris]] and [[Lesquin Airport]], [[Lille]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafmuseum.org.uk/milestones-of-flight/world/1919.cfm |title=World Aviation in 1919 - Part 1 |publisher=Royal Air Force Museum |accessdate=28 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105130943/http://www.rafmuseum.org.uk/milestones-of-flight/world/1919.cfm |archivedate=5 January 2011 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-00007, Berlin, Start eines Junkers-Flugzeuges.jpg|thumb| [[Junkers F.13]] ''D-190'' of [[Junkers Luftverkehr]]]]\nThe first German airline to use heavier than air aircraft was [[Deutsche Luft-Reederei]] established in 1917 which started operating in February 1919. In its first year, the D.L.R. operated regularly scheduled flights on routes with a combined length of nearly 1000 miles. By 1921 the D.L.R. network was more than 3000&nbsp;km (1865 miles) long, and included destinations in the Netherlands, Scandinavia and the Baltic Republics. Another important German airline was [[Junkers Luftverkehr]], which began operations in 1921. It was a division of the aircraft manufacturer [[Junkers]], which became a separate company in 1924. It operated joint-venture airlines in Austria, Denmark, Estonia, Finland, Hungary, Latvia, Norway, Poland, Sweden and Switzerland.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe [[Netherlands|Dutch]] airline [[KLM]] made its first flight in 1920, and is the oldest continuously operating airline in the world. Established by aviator [[Albert Plesman]],<ref>{{cite journal|journal=International Directory of Company Histories|year=1999|volume=28|title=Koninklijke Luchtvaart Maatschappij, N.V. History| url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/koninklijke-luchtvaart-maatschappij-n-v-history/|accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref> it was immediately awarded a \"Royal\" predicate from [[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands|Queen Wilhelmina]].<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.klm.com/corporate/en/about-klm/history/index.html|work=KLM Corporate|publisher=KLM|accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref> Its first flight was from [[Croydon Airport]], [[London]] to [[Amsterdam]], using a leased [[Aircraft Transport and Travel]] [[Airco DH.16|DH-16]], and carrying two British journalists and a number of newspapers. In 1921, KLM started scheduled services.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn [[Finland]], the charter establishing Aero O/Y (now [[Finnair]]) was signed in the city of [[Helsinki]] on September 12, 1923. [[Junkers F.13]] D-335 became the first aircraft of the company, when Aero took delivery of it on March 14, 1924. The first flight was between Helsinki and [[Tallinn]], capital of [[Estonia]], and it took place on March 20, 1924, one week later.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn the [[Soviet Union]], the Chief Administration of the Civil Air Fleet was established in 1921. One of its first acts was to help found Deutsch-Russische Luftverkehrs A.G. (Deruluft), a German-Russian joint venture to provide air transport from Russia to the West. Domestic air service began around the same time, when Dobrolyot started operations on 15 July 1923 between Moscow and Nizhni Novgorod. Since 1932 all operations had been carried under the name [[Aeroflot]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aeroflot.ru/us-en/about/history|title=Aeroflot History {{!}} Aeroflot|website=www.aeroflot.ru|language=en|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>\n\nEarly European airlines tended to favor comfort \u2013 the passenger cabins were often spacious with luxurious interiors \u2013 over speed and efficiency. The relatively basic navigational capabilities of pilots at the time also meant that delays due to the weather were commonplace.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n====Rationalization====\n[[File:National Audit Office - Victoria - London - 020504.jpg|upright=0.7|thumb|The [[Imperial Airways]] Empire Terminal, Victoria, London. Trains ran from here to [[flying boats]] in [[Southampton]], and to [[Croydon Airport]].]]\nBy the early 1920s, small airlines were struggling to compete, and there was a movement towards increased rationalization and consolidation. In 1924, [[Imperial Airways]] was formed from the merger of [[Instone Air Line|Instone Air Line Company]], [[British Marine Air Navigation Co Ltd|British Marine Air Navigation]], [[Daimler Airway]] and [[Handley Page Transport|Handley Page Transport Co Ltd.]], to allow British airlines to compete with stiff competition from French and German airlines that were enjoying heavy government subsidies. The airline was a pioneer in surveying and opening up air routes across the world to serve far-flung parts of the [[British Empire]] and to enhance trade and integration.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1923/1923%20-%200760.html |title = Imperial Air Transport Company: Appointment of Government Directors|work = Flight|date = December 20, 1923|page = 760}}</ref>\n\nThe first new airliner ordered by Imperial Airways, was the [[Handley Page W8f]] ''City of Washington'', delivered on 3 November 1924.<ref>http://www.century-of-flight.net/Aviation%20history/coming%20of%20age/imperial%20airways.htm</ref> In the first year of operation the company carried 11,395 passengers and 212,380 letters. In April 1925, the film ''[[The Lost World (1925 film)|The Lost World]]'' became the first film to be screened for passengers on a scheduled airliner flight when it was shown on the London-Paris route.\n\nTwo French airlines also merged to form [[Air Union]] on 1 January 1923. This later merged with four other French airlines to become [[Air France]], the country's flagship carrier to this day, on 17 May 1933.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Britannica Concise Encyclopedia|publisher=Britannica Digital Learning|year=2017|isbn=|location=|pages=Air France|via=Credo Reference}}</ref>\n\nGermany's [[Deutsche Luft Hansa]] was created in 1926 by merger of two airlines, one of them [[Junkers Luftverkehr]]. Luft Hansa, due to the [[Hugo Junkers|Junkers]] heritage and unlike most other airlines at the time, became a major investor in airlines outside of Europe, providing capital to [[Varig]] and Avianca. German airliners built by [[Junkers (Aircraft)|Junkers]], [[Dornier GmbH|Dornier]], and [[Fokker]] were among the most advanced in the world at the time.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n====Global expansion====\nIn 1926, [[Alan Cobham]] surveyed a flight route from the UK to [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]], following this up with another proving flight to [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]. Other routes to [[British India]] and the [[Far East]] were also charted and demonstrated at this time. Regular services to [[Cairo]] and [[Basra]] began in 1927 and were extended to [[Karachi]] in 1929. The London-[[Australia]] service was inaugurated in 1932 with the [[Handley Page HP 42]] airliners. Further services were opened up to [[Kolkata|Calcutta]], [[Rangoon]], [[Singapore]], [[Brisbane]] and [[Hong Kong]] passengers departed London on 14 March 1936 following the establishment of a branch from Penang to Hong Kong.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n[[File:Imperial routes April 1935.jpg|thumb|April 1935 map showing [[Imperial Airways]]' routes from the [[United Kingdom|UK]] to [[Australia]] and [[Union of South Africa|South Africa]]]] Imperial's aircraft were small, most seating fewer than twenty passengers, and catered for the rich. Only about 50,000 passengers used Imperial Airways in the 1930s. Most passengers on intercontinental routes or on services within and between British colonies were men doing colonial administration, business or research.<ref>Pirie, G.H. Incidental tourism: British imperial air travel in the 1930s. ''Journal of Tourism History'', 1 (2009) 49\u201366.</ref>\n\nLike Imperial Airways, [[Air France]] and [[KLM]]'s early growth depended heavily on the needs to service links with far-flung colonial possessions ([[French North Africa|North Africa]] and [[French Indochina|Indochina]] for the French and the [[Dutch Indies|East Indies]] for the Dutch). France began an air mail service to [[Morocco]] in 1919 that was bought out in 1927, renamed [[A\u00e9ropostale (aviation)|A\u00e9ropostale]], and injected with capital to become a major international carrier. In 1933, A\u00e9ropostale went [[Bankruptcy|bankrupt]], was nationalized and merged into [[Air France]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nAlthough Germany lacked colonies, it also began expanding its services globally. In 1931, the airship [[LZ 127 Graf Zeppelin|Graf Zeppelin]] began offering regular scheduled passenger service between Germany and South America, usually every two weeks, which continued until 1937.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airships.net/lz127-graf-zeppelin/history |title=LZ-127 Graf Zeppelin |publisher=Airships.net |date= |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref> In 1936, the airship [[LZ 129 Hindenburg|Hindenburg]] entered passenger service and successfully crossed the Atlantic 36 times before crashing at Lakehurst, New Jersey, on May 6, 1937.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airships.net/hindenburg |title=Hindenburg |publisher=Airships.net |date=2009-06-10 |accessdate=2010-08-22| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101005073820/http://www.airships.net/hindenburg| archivedate= 5 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In 1938, a weekly air service from Berlin to [[Kabul]], [[Afghanistan]], started operating.<ref>http://books.stonebooks.com/history/afghanistan.shtml</ref>\n\nFrom February 1934 until World War II began in 1939 [[Deutsche Luft Hansa|Deutsche Lufthansa]] operated an airmail service from [[Stuttgart]], [[Germany]] via [[Spain]], the [[Canary Islands]] and West Africa to [[Natal, Rio Grande do Norte|Natal]] in [[Brazil]]. This was the first time an airline flew across an ocean.<ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.com/?id=pigDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA13&dq=Popular+Science+1931+plane#v=onepage&q=Popular%20Science%201931%20plane&f=true |title=First Transatlantic Air Line Links Two Continents|date=February 1933 |journal=Popular Science|pages = 13\u201315 and 104|volume = 122|issue = 2|editor-last = Brown|editor-first = Raymond J.}}</ref><ref name=\"Graue&Duggan\">James W. Graue & John Duggan \"Deutsche Lufthansa South Atlantic Airmail Service 1934\u20131939\", Zeppelin Study Group, Ickenham, UK 2000 {{ISBN|0-9514114-5-4}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of the 1930s [[Aeroflot]] had become the world's largest airline, employing more than 4,000 pilots and 60,000 other service personnel and operating around 3,000 aircraft (of which 75% were considered obsolete by its own standards). During the Soviet era Aeroflot was synonymous with Russian civil aviation, as it was the only air carrier. It became the first airline in the world to operate sustained regular jet services on 15 September 1956 with the [[Tupolev Tu-104]]. <ref>{{cite web |title=First sustained jet airline service |url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/first-sustained-jet-airline-service/ |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====EU airline deregulation====\nDeregulation of the [[European Union]] airspace in the early 1990s has had substantial effect on the structure of the industry there. The shift towards 'budget' airlines on shorter routes has been significant. Airlines such as [[EasyJet]] and [[Ryanair]] have often grown at the expense of the traditional national airlines.\n\nThere has also been a trend for these national airlines themselves to be privatized such as has occurred for [[Aer Lingus]] and [[British Airways]]. Other national airlines, including Italy's [[Alitalia]], have suffered \u2013 particularly with the rapid increase of oil prices in early 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/alitalia-future-hinges-on-rescue-package/a-1320328|title=Alitalia Future Hinges on Rescue Package {{!}} Business {{!}} DW {{!}} 07.09.2004|last=(www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche Welle|website=DW.COM|language=en|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>\n\n===U.S. airline industry===\n{{main|Air transportation in the United States}}\n\n====Early development====\n[[File:TWA 1940.jpg|thumb|[[TWA]] [[Douglas DC-3]] in 1940. The DC-3, often regarded as one of the most influential aircraft in the history of commercial aviation, revolutionized air travel.]]\n\n[[Tony Jannus]] conducted the United States' first scheduled commercial airline flight on 1 January 1914 for the [[St. Petersburg-Tampa Airboat Line]].<ref name=Society>{{cite web | title=Tony Jannus, an enduring legacy of aviation | work=Tony Jannus Distinguished Aviation Society | publisher=tonyjannusaward.com | url=http://www.tonyjannusaward.com/history/ | accessdate=2010-12-02 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717073628/http://www.tonyjannusaward.com/history/ | archivedate=2011-07-17 }}</ref> The 23-minute flight traveled between [[St. Petersburg, Florida]] and [[Tampa, Florida]], passing some {{convert|50|ft|m}} above Tampa Bay in Jannus' [[Benoist XIV]] wood and muslin biplane flying boat. His passenger was a former mayor of St. Petersburg, who paid $400 for the privilege of sitting on a wooden bench in the open cockpit. The Airboat line operated for about four months, carrying more than 1,200 passengers who paid $5 each.<ref>Carey, Susan, First airline offered no frills, many thrills, [[Wall Street Journal]], December 31, 2013, p. B4</ref> [[Chalk's International Airlines]] began service between Miami and Bimini in the [[Bahamas]] in February 1919. Based in [[Ft. Lauderdale]], Chalk's claimed to be the oldest continuously operating airline in the United States until its closure in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airportbusiness.com/web/online/Top-News-Headlines/CHALKS-AIRLINES-LOSES-FLIGHT-LICENSE-ITS-AIRPORT-LEASE-COULD-BE-CANCELED/1$15115 |title=Chalks Airlines Loses Flight License | publisher=airportbusiness.com|date= |accessdate=2010-12-02}}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[World War I]], the United States found itself swamped with aviators. Many decided to take their war-surplus aircraft on barnstorming campaigns, performing aerobatic maneuvers to woo crowds. In 1918, the [[United States Postal Service]] won the financial backing of [[United States Congress|Congress]] to begin experimenting with [[air mail]] service, initially using [[Curtiss Jenny]]<ref>Amick, George. \"How The Airmail Got Off The Ground.\" American History 33.3 (1998): 48. Academic Search Premier. Web. 3 Nov. 2011.</ref> aircraft that had been procured by the [[United States Army Air Service]]. Private operators were the first to fly the mail but due to numerous accidents the US Army was tasked with mail delivery. During the Army's involvement they proved to be too unreliable and lost their air mail duties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historynet.com/airmail-service-it-began-with-army-air-service-pilots.htm|title=Airmail Service: It Began with Army Air Service Pilots {{!}} HistoryNet|website=www.historynet.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>  By the mid-1920s, the [[United States Postal Service|Postal Service]] had developed its own air mail network, based on a transcontinental backbone between [[New York City]] and [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]].<ref>Clark, Anders (22 August 2014). \"[https://disciplesofflight.com/big-arrow/ Now That's a Big Arrow]\". Disciples of Flight. Retrieved 16 July 2015</ref> To supplement this service, they offered twelve contracts for spur routes to independent bidders. Some of the carriers that won these routes would, through time and mergers, evolve into [[Pan American World Airways|Pan Am]], [[Delta Air Lines]], [[Braniff Airways]], [[American Airlines]], [[United Airlines]] (originally a division of [[Boeing]]), [[Trans World Airlines]], [[Northwest Airlines]], and [[Eastern Air Lines]].\n\nService during the early 1920s was sporadic: most airlines at the time were focused on [[airmail#History|carrying bags of mail]]. In 1925, however, the [[Ford Motor Company]] bought out the [[William Bushnell Stout|Stout Aircraft Company]] and began construction of the all-metal [[Ford Trimotor]], which became the first successful American airliner. With a 12-passenger capacity, the Trimotor made passenger service potentially profitable.<ref>{{ cite web | url = https://postalmuseum.si.edu/exhibits/current/airmail-in-america/the-airplanes/the-ford-trimotor.html | title = The Ford Trimotor and Douglas M-2 Mail Planes | work = Postal Museum | accessdate = July 27, 2017 }}</ref> Air service was seen as a supplement to [[rail transport|rail]] service in the American transportation network.\n\nAt the same time, [[Juan Trippe]] began a crusade to create an air network that would link America to the world, and he achieved this goal through his airline, [[Pan American World Airways]], with a fleet of flying boats that linked [[Los Angeles]] to [[Shanghai]] and [[Boston]] to [[London]]. Pan Am and Northwest Airways (which began flights to Canada in the 1920s) were the only U.S. airlines to go international before the 1940s.\n\nWith the introduction of the [[Boeing 247]] and [[Douglas DC-3]] in the 1930s, the U.S. airline industry was generally profitable, even during the [[Great Depression]]. This trend continued until the beginning of [[World War II]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ASLAUrX3UE8C&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=boeing+247+profitable#v=onepage&q=boeing%20247%20profitable&f=false|title=A Companion to International History 1900\u20132001|last=Martel|first=Gordon|date=2008-04-15|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470766293|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Development since 1945====\n[[File:Stratocruiser op Schiphol, Bestanddeelnr 903-5913.jpg|thumb|[[Boeing 377]] of [[American Export Airlines]], the first airline to offer landplane flights across the North Atlantic in October 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centennialofflight.net/essay/Commercial_Aviation/atlantic_route/Tran4.htm |title=Air Transportation: The Beginnings of Commercial Transatlantic Service |publisher=centennialofflight.net |date= |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref>]]\n\nWorld War II, like World War I, brought new life to the airline industry. Many airlines in the Allied countries were flush from lease contracts to the military, and foresaw a future explosive demand for civil air transport, for both passengers and cargo. They were eager to invest in the newly emerging flagships of air travel such as the [[Boeing Stratocruiser]], [[Lockheed Constellation]], and [[Douglas DC-6]]. Most of these new aircraft were based on American bombers such as the [[B-29]], which had spearheaded research into new technologies such as [[pressurization]]. Most offered increased efficiency from both added speed and greater payload.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.century-of-flight.net/Aviation%20history/airliners/2nd%20upload/timeline%2050s1.htm|title=history of airliners 1950 to 1959|website=www.century-of-flight.net|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jal.com/en/history/aircraft/60s/pick_61-70_01.html|title=History of JAL {{!}} DC-8-32|website=www.jal.com|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1950s, the [[De Havilland Comet]], [[Boeing 707]], [[Douglas DC-8]], and [[Sud Aviation Caravelle]] became the first flagships of the Jet Age in the West, while the Eastern bloc had [[Tupolev Tu-104]] and [[Tupolev Tu-124]] in the fleets of state-owned carriers such as Czechoslovak [[Czech Airlines|\u010cSA]], Soviet [[Aeroflot]] and East-German [[Interflug]]. The [[Vickers Viscount]] and [[Lockheed L-188 Electra]] inaugurated turboprop transport.\n\nOn 4 October 1958, [[BOAC]] started [[transatlantic flight]]s between [[London Heathrow]] and [[New York-Idlewild Airport|New York Idlewild]] with a Comet 4, and [[Pan Am]] followed on 26 October with a B707 service between New York and Paris.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/analysis-how-the-jet-travel-era-began-in-earnest-449222/ |title= How the jet travel era began in earnest \u2013 60 years ago |date= 4 Oct 2018 |author= Max Kingsley Jones |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\nThe next big boost for the airlines would come in the 1970s, when the [[Boeing 747]], [[McDonnell Douglas DC-10]], and [[Lockheed L-1011]] inaugurated [[widebody]] (\"jumbo jet\") service, which is still the standard in international travel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/boeing-747-first-flight-47years-ago-2016-2|title=The Boeing 747 jumbo jet changed air travel with this momentous event 47 years ago|work=Business Insider|access-date=2017-10-14|language=en}}</ref> The [[Tupolev Tu-144]] and its Western counterpart, [[Concorde]], made supersonic travel a reality.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.history.com/news/the-cold-war-race-to-build-the-concorde|title=The Cold War Race to Build the Concorde|work=HISTORY.com|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>  Concorde first flew in 1969 and operated through 2003. In 1972, [[Airbus]] began producing Europe's most commercially successful line of airliners to date. The added efficiencies for these aircraft were often not in speed, but in passenger capacity, payload, and range. Airbus also features modern electronic cockpits that were common across their aircraft to enable pilots to fly multiple models with minimal cross-training.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n====US airline deregulation====\n\n[[File:Pan Am Boeing 747 at Zurich Airport in May 1985.jpg|thumb|[[Pan Am]] [[Boeing 747]] ''Clipper Neptune's Car'' in 1985. The deregulation of the American airline industry increased the financial troubles of the airline which ultimately filed for bankruptcy in December 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centennialofflight.net/essay/Commercial_Aviation/Bankruptcy/Tran9.htm |title=Air Transportation: The Airline Bankruptcies of the 1980s |publisher=centennialofflight.net |date= |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref>]]\n\nThe 1978 U.S. [[Airline deregulation act|airline industry deregulation]] lowered federally controlled barriers for new airlines just as a downturn in the nation's economy occurred. New start-ups entered during the downturn, during which time they found aircraft and funding, contracted hangar and maintenance services, trained new employees, and recruited laid-off staff from other airlines.\n\nMajor airlines dominated their routes through aggressive pricing and additional capacity offerings, often swamping new start-ups. In the place of high barriers to entry imposed by regulation, the major airlines implemented an equally high barrier called [[loss leader]] pricing.<ref name=\"Andrew R. Thomas\">{{cite news|url = http://my.safaribooksonline.com/book/current-affairs/9781430236771 |title=Mr. Soft Landing: Airline Industry Strategy, Service, and Safety|publisher=Apress |year=2007}}</ref> In this strategy an already established and dominant airline stomps out its competition by lowering airfares on specific routes, below the cost of operating on it, choking out any chance a start-up airline may have. The industry side effect is an overall drop in revenue and service quality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asq.org/quality-report/10-year-analysis.html |website =American Society of Quality (ASQ)|title = The American Society for Quality Debuts Quarterly Quality Report with 10-Year Analysis}}</ref> Since deregulation in 1978 the average domestic ticket price has dropped by 40%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mit.edu/airlines/analysis/analysis_airline_industry.html |publisher =Massachusetts Institute of Technology|title = Airline Industry Overview}}</ref> So has airline employee pay. By incurring massive losses, the airlines of the USA now rely upon a scourge of cyclical Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings to continue doing business.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.slate.com/articles/business/moneybox/2011/12/blame_jimmy_carter_for_all_the_airline_bankruptcies_or_better_yet_thank_him_.html |title=Air Fail|publisher = Slate |work = Moneybox|date = 1 December 2011|last = Yglesias|first = Matthew}}</ref> [[America West Airlines]] (which has since merged with US Airways) remained a significant survivor from this new entrant era, as dozens, even hundreds, have gone under.\n\nIn many ways, the biggest winner in the deregulated environment was the air passenger. Although not exclusively attributable to deregulation, indeed the U.S. witnessed an explosive growth in demand for air travel. Many millions who had never or rarely flown before became regular fliers, even joining [[frequent flyer]] loyalty programs and receiving free flights and other benefits from their flying. New services and higher frequencies meant that business fliers could fly to another city, do business, and return the same day, from almost any point in the country. Air travel's advantages put long distance intercity [[railroad]] travel and bus lines under pressure, with most of the latter having withered away, whilst the former is still protected under [[nationalization]] through the continuing existence of [[Amtrak]].\n\nBy the 1980s, almost half of the total flying in the world took place in the U.S., and today the domestic industry operates over 10,000 daily departures nationwide.\n\nToward the end of the century, a new style of [[low-cost carrier|low cost airline]] emerged, offering a no-frills product at a lower price. [[Southwest Airlines]], [[JetBlue]], [[AirTran Airways]], [[Skybus Airlines]] and other low-cost carriers began to represent a serious challenge to the so-called \"legacy airlines\", as did their low-cost counterparts in many other countries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/travel/article/budget-airline-trends-2016/index.html|title=Budget airlines changed the world. What next?|date=2016-03-21|work=CNN Travel|access-date=2017-10-14|language=en}}</ref> Their commercial viability represented a serious competitive threat to the legacy carriers. However, of these, [[ATA Airlines|ATA]] and Skybus have since ceased operations.\n\nIncreasingly since 1978, US airlines have been reincorporated and [[off spin|spun off]] by newly created and internally led management companies, and thus becoming nothing more than operating units and subsidiaries with limited financially decisive control. Among some of these [[holding company|holding companies]] and [[parent company|parent companies]] which are relatively well known, are the [[UAL Corporation]], along with the [[AMR Corporation]], among a long [[list of airline holding companies]] sometime recognized worldwide. Less recognized are the [[private equity firm]]s which often seize managerial, financial, and [[board of directors]] control of distressed airline companies by temporarily investing large sums of [[Equity (finance)|capital]] in air carriers, to rescheme an airlines assets into a profitable organization or [[liquidate|liquidating]] an air carrier of their profitable and worthwhile routes and business operations.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nThus the last 50 years of the airline industry have varied from reasonably profitable, to devastatingly depressed. As the first major market to deregulate the industry in 1978, U.S. airlines have experienced more turbulence than almost any other country or region. In fact, no U.S. [[legacy carrier]] survived bankruptcy-free. Among the outspoken critics of deregulation, former CEO of American Airlines, [[Robert Crandall]] has publicly stated:\n\n<blockquote>\"Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection filing shows airline industry deregulation was a mistake.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/45477274/AMR_Filing_Shows_Airline_Deregulation_Failed_Ex_CEO |title=Robert Cranall former CEO AA, CNBC |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429202738/http://www.cnbc.com/id/45477274/AMR_Filing_Shows_Airline_Deregulation_Failed_Ex_CEO |archivedate=2013-04-29 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n====The airline industry bailout====\n\nCongress passed the [https://www.congress.gov/bill/107th-congress/house-bill/2926 Air Transportation Safety and System Stabilization Act] (P.L. 107-42) in response to a severe liquidity crisis facing the already-troubled airline industry in the aftermath of the [[September 11 attacks|September 11th terrorist attacks]]. Through the [[Air Transportation Stabilization Board|ATSB]] Congress sought to provide cash infusions to carriers for both the cost of the four-day federal shutdown of the airlines and the incremental losses incurred through December 31, 2001, as a result of the terrorist attacks. This resulted in the first government bailout of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ostpxweb.ost.dot.gov/aviation/Data/stabilizationact.pdf |title=Air Transportation Safety and System Stabilization Act |accessdate=2009-06-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409061950/http://ostpxweb.ost.dot.gov/aviation/Data/stabilizationact.pdf |archivedate=2009-04-09 }}</ref> Between 2000 and 2005 US airlines lost $30 billion with wage cuts of over $15 billion and 100,000 employees laid off.<ref name=\"Bamber, G.J., Gittell, J.H., Kochan, T.A. & von Nordenflytch, A. 2009\">{{cite book|url=http://www.cornellpress.cornell.edu/book/?GCOI=80140100965480 |author=Bamber, G.J. |author2=Gittell, J.H. |author3=Kochan, T.A. |author4=von Nordenflytch, A. |year=2009 |title=Up in the Air: How Airlines Can Improve Performance by Engaging their Employees|publisher=Cornell University Press, Ithaca |chapter=chapter 5}}</ref>\n\nIn recognition of the essential national economic role of a healthy aviation system, Congress authorized partial compensation of up to $5 billion in cash subject to review by the [[U.S. Department of Transportation]] and up to $10 billion in loan guarantees subject to review by a newly created [[Air Transportation Stabilization Board]] (ATSB). The applications to DOT for reimbursements were subjected to rigorous multi-year reviews not only by DOT program personnel but also by the [[Government Accountability Office]]<ref>http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d04725r.pdf</ref> and the DOT Inspector General.<ref>[http://www.oig.dot.gov/StreamFile?file=/data/pdfdocs/aa20011024.pdf ]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090717225216/http://www.oig.dot.gov/StreamFile?file=%2Fdata%2Fpdfdocs%2Faa20011024.pdf |date=July 17, 2009 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.oig.dot.gov/StreamFile?file=/data/pdfdocs/cr2003092.pdf ]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090717231319/http://www.oig.dot.gov/StreamFile?file=%2Fdata%2Fpdfdocs%2Fcr2003092.pdf |date=July 17, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nUltimately, the federal government provided $4.6 billion in one-time, subject-to-income-tax cash payments to 427 U.S. air carriers, with no provision for repayment, essentially a gift from the taxpayers. (Passenger carriers operating scheduled service received approximately $4 billion, subject to tax.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dot.gov/affairs/carrierpayments.htm |title=U |publisher=Dot.gov |accessdate=2010-08-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527104415/http://www.dot.gov/affairs/carrierpayments.htm |archivedate=2010-05-27 }}</ref> In addition, the ATSB approved loan guarantees to six airlines totaling approximately $1.6 billion. Data from the [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S. Treasury Department]] show that the government recouped the $1.6 billion and a profit of $339 million from the fees, interest and purchase of discounted airline stock associated with loan guarantees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treas.gov/offices/domestic-finance/atsb/ |title=Air Transportation Stabilization Board |publisher=Treas.gov |date=2001-09-22 |accessdate=2010-08-22|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080709052637/http://www.treas.gov/offices/domestic-finance/atsb/ |archivedate = July 9, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe three largest [[major carrier]]s and [[Southwest Airlines]] control 70% of the U.S. passenger market.<ref name=AvWeek14May2018/>\n\n===Asian airline industry===\n[[File:Tata Sons' Airline Timetable Image, Summer 1935 (interior).jpg|thumb|1935 Timetable of [[Tata Airlines]], founded in 1932]]\n\nAlthough [[Philippine Airlines]] (PAL) was officially founded on February 26, 1941, its license to operate as an airliner was derived from merged Philippine Aerial Taxi Company (PATCO) established by mining magnate Emmanuel N. Bachrach on December 3, 1930, making it Asia's oldest scheduled carrier still in operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hawaii.gov/hawaiiaviation/hawaii-commercial-aviation/philippine-air-lines |title=Above the Pacific |first=William Joseph |last=Horvat |date=1966 |isbn=978-0-8168-0000-1 |publisher=Hawaii.gov |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref> Commercial air service commenced three weeks later from [[Manila]] to [[Baguio]], making it Asia's first airline route. Bachrach's death in 1937 paved the way for its eventual merger with Philippine Airlines in March 1941 and made it Asia's oldest airline. It is also the oldest airline in Asia still operating under its current name.<ref name=\"PAL\">Jane, ''[http://www.janes.com Jane's airlines & airliners By Jeremy Flack]'', First Edition, 2003, {{ISBN|978-0-00-715174-5}}</ref> Bachrach's majority share in PATCO was bought by beer magnate Andres R. Soriano in 1939 upon the advice of General [[Douglas MacArthur]] and later merged with newly formed Philippine Airlines with PAL as the surviving entity. Soriano has controlling interest in both airlines before the merger. PAL restarted service on March 15, 1941, with a single [[Beech Model 18]] NPC-54 aircraft, which started its daily services between [[Manila]] (from [[Nielson Field]]) and [[Baguio]], later to expand with larger aircraft such as the DC-3 and Vickers Viscount.\n\n[[Korean Air]] was one of the first airlines to be launched among the other Asian countries in 1946 along with [[Asiana Airlines]], which later joined in 1988. The license to operate as an airliner was granted by the federal government body after reviewing the necessity at the national assembly. The [[Hanjin]] occupies the largest ownership of Korean Air as well as few low-budget airlines as of now. The Korean Air is among the founders of [[SkyTeam]], which was established in 2000. Asiana Airlines joined [[Star Alliance]] in 2003. Korean Air and Asiana Airlines comprise one of the largest combined airline miles and number of passenger served at the regional market of Asian airline industry\n\n[[India]] was also one of the first countries to embrace civil aviation.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Pran Nath Seth|author2=Pran Nath Seth, Sushma Seth Bhat|title=An Introduction To Travel And Tourism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AcGn-Fmc43sC&pg=PA111|year=2003|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|isbn=978-81-207-2482-2|page=111}}</ref> One of the first Asian airline companies was [[Air India]], which was founded as [[Tata Airlines]] in 1932, a division of Tata Sons Ltd. (now [[Tata Group]]). The airline was founded by India's leading industrialist, [[JRD Tata]]. On October 15, 1932, J. R. D. Tata himself flew a single engined [[De Havilland Puss Moth]] carrying air mail (postal mail of [[Imperial Airways]]) from [[Karachi]] to [[Mumbai|Bombay]] via [[Ahmedabad]]. The aircraft continued to [[Madras]] via Bellary piloted by [[Royal Air Force]] pilot [[Nevill Vintcent]]. Tata Airlines was also one of the world's first major airlines which began its operations without any support from the Government.<ref>{{cite book|author=S Bhatt|title=International Environmental Law|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s0g7tCYYu-gC&pg=PA175|year=2007|publisher=APH Publishing|isbn=978-81-313-0125-8|page=175}}</ref>\n\nWith the outbreak of World War II, the airline presence in Asia came to a relative halt, with many new flag carriers donating their aircraft for military aid and other uses. Following the end of the war in 1945, regular commercial service was restored in India and Tata Airlines became a public limited company on July 29, 1946, under the name Air India. After the [[independence of India]], 49% of the airline was acquired by the [[Government of India]]. In return, the airline was granted status to operate international services from India as the designated flag carrier under the name [[Air India International]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nOn July 31, 1946, a chartered Philippine Airlines (PAL) [[DC-4]] ferried 40 American servicemen to [[Oakland, California|Oakland]], [[California]], from Nielson Airport in [[Makati City]] with stops in [[Guam]], [[Wake Island]], [[Johnston Atoll]] and [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]], making PAL the first Asian airline to cross the [[Pacific Ocean]]. A regular service between [[Manila]] and [[San Francisco]] was started in December. It was during this year that the airline was designated as the flag carrier of Philippines.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nDuring the era of [[decolonization]], newly born Asian countries started to embrace air transport. Among the first Asian carriers during the era were [[Cathay Pacific]] of [[Hong Kong]] (founded in September 1946), [[Orient Airways]] (later [[Pakistan International Airlines]]; founded in October 1946), [[Air Ceylon]] (later [[SriLankan Airlines]]; founded in 1947), [[Malayan Airways Limited]] in 1947 (later [[Singapore Airlines|Singapore]] and [[Malaysia Airlines]]), [[El Al]] in [[Israel]] in 1948, [[Garuda Indonesia]] in 1949, [[Japan Airlines]] in 1951, [[Thai Airways International]] in 1960, and [[Korean National Airlines]] in 1947.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Latin American and Caribbean airline industry===\n[[File:Tam.a330-200.pt-mvl.arp.jpg|thumb|[[TAM Airlines]] is the largest airline in [[Latin America]] in terms of number of annual passengers flown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airtravel.about.com/od/basedincaribbeansa/tp/top10la.htm |title=Top 10 Airlines in Latin America By Arlene Fleming |publisher=Airtravel.about.com |date=2010-06-10 |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref>]]\n\nAmong the first countries to have regular airlines in Latin America and the Caribbean were [[Bolivia]] with [[Lloyd A\u00e9reo Boliviano]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Bolivia/Transportation#ref312761|title=Bolivia - Transportation {{!}} history - geography|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-10-14|language=en}}</ref> [[Cuba]] with [[Cubana de Aviaci\u00f3n]], [[Colombia]] with [[Avianca]] (the first airline established in the Americas), Argentina with [[Aerolineas Argentinas]], [[Chile]] with [[LAN Chile]] (today [[LATAM Airlines]]), [[Brazil]] with [[Varig]], [[Dominican Republic]] with [[Dominicana de Aviaci\u00f3n]], [[Mexico]] with [[Mexicana de Aviaci\u00f3n]], [[Trinidad and Tobago]] with [[BWIA West Indies Airways]] (today [[Caribbean Airlines]]), [[Venezuela]] with [[Aeropostal]], [[Puerto Rico]] with [[Aerovias nacionales de puerto rico|Puertorriquena]]; and [[Grupo TACA|TACA]] based in [[El Salvador]] and representing several airlines of [[Central America]] ([[Costa Rica]], [[Guatemala]], [[Honduras]] and [[Nicaragua]]). All the previous airlines started regular operations well before [[World War II]]. Puerto Rican commercial airlines such as [[Prinair]], [[Oceanair]], [[Fina Air]] and [[Vieques Air Link]] came much after the second world war, as did several others from other countries like Mexico's [[Interjet]] and [[Volaris]], Venezuela's [[Aserca Airlines]] and others.\n\nThe air travel market has evolved rapidly over recent years in [[Latin America]]. Some industry estimates indicate that over 2,000 new aircraft will begin service over the next five years in this region.<ref>{{cite web|title=Latin America needs more than 2,000 new passenger aircraft in next 20 years|url=http://www.airbus.com/presscentre/pressreleases/press-release-detail/detail/latin-america-needs-more-than-2000-new-passenger-aircraft-in-next-20-years/|accessdate=3 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nThese airlines serve domestic flights within their countries, as well as connections within Latin America and also overseas flights to North America, Europe, Australia, and Asia.\n\nOnly two airlines \u2013 [[Avianca]] and [[LATAM Airlines]] \u2013 have international subsidiaries and cover many destinations within the Americas as well as major hubs in other continents. LATAM with [[Chile]] as the central operation along with [[Peru]], [[Ecuador]], [[Colombia]], [[Brazil]] and [[Argentina]] and formerly with some operations in the [[Dominican Republic]]. The [[Avianca Holdings|Avianca]] group has its main operation in Colombia based around the hub in [[El Dorado International Airport|Bogot\u00e1]], Colombia, as well as subsidiaries in various Latin American countries with hubs in [[Monse\u00f1or \u00d3scar Arnulfo Romero (airport)|San Salvador]], El Salvador, as well as [[Lima International Airport|Lima]], Peru, with a smaller operation in Ecuador.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Regulatory considerations==\n\n===National===\n[[File:British Airways (27078321943).jpg|thumb|[[Union Jack]] tails of [[British Airways]], UK's [[flag carrier]]]]\n\nMany countries have [[Flag carrier|national airline]]s that the government owns and operates. Fully private airlines are subject to a great deal of government regulation for economic, political, and safety concerns. For instance, governments often intervene to halt airline labor actions to protect the free flow of people, communications, and goods between different regions without compromising safety.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe United States, Australia, and to a lesser extent Brazil, Mexico, India, the United Kingdom, and Japan have \"deregulated\" their airlines. In the past, these governments dictated airfares, route networks, and other operational requirements for each airline. Since deregulation, airlines have been largely free to negotiate their own operating arrangements with different airports, enter and exit routes easily, and to levy airfares and supply flights according to market demand.\nThe entry barriers for new airlines are lower in a deregulated market, and so the U.S. has seen hundreds of airlines start up (sometimes for only a brief operating period). This has produced far greater competition than before deregulation in most markets. The added competition, together with pricing freedom, means that new entrants often take market share with highly reduced rates that, to a limited degree, full service airlines must match. This is a major constraint on profitability for established carriers, which tend to have a higher cost base.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nAs a result, profitability in a deregulated market is uneven for most airlines. These forces have caused some major airlines to go out of business, in addition to most of the poorly established new entrants.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn the United States, the airline industry is dominated by four large firms. Because of industry consolidation, after fuel prices dropped considerably in 2015, very little of the savings were passed on to consumers.<ref>\"Too Much of a Good Thing.\" ''The Economist'' 26 March 2016: 23. print.</ref>\n\n===International===\n{{Unreferenced|section|date=January 2020}}[[File:La Maison de l-OACI - 11a.jpg|thumb|[[International Civil Aviation Organization]] headquarters in [[Montreal]]]]\n\nGroups such as the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] establish worldwide standards for safety and other vital concerns. Most international air traffic is regulated by bilateral agreements between countries, which designate specific carriers to operate on specific routes. The model of such an agreement was the [[Bermuda Agreement]] between the US and UK following World War II, which designated airports to be used for transatlantic flights and gave each government the authority to nominate carriers to operate routes.\n\nBilateral agreements are based on the \"[[freedoms of the air]]\", a group of generalized traffic rights ranging from the freedom to overfly a country to the freedom to provide domestic flights within a country (a very rarely granted right known as [[cabotage]]). Most agreements permit airlines to fly from their home country to designated airports in the other country: some also extend the freedom to provide continuing service to a third country, or to another destination in the other country while carrying passengers from overseas.\n\nIn the 1990s, \"[[open skies]]\" agreements became more common. These agreements take many of these regulatory powers from state governments and open up international routes to further competition. Open skies agreements have met some criticism, particularly within the European Union, whose airlines would be at a comparative disadvantage with the United States' because of [[cabotage]] restrictions.\n\n==Economic considerations==\n\nIn 2017, 4.1 billion passengers have been carried by airlines in 41.9 million commercial scheduled flights (an average payload of {{#expr:4100/41.9round0}} passengers), for 7.75 trillion [[passenger kilometre]]s (an average trip of {{#expr:7750/4.100round0}} km) over 45,091 airline routes served globally.<!--<ref name=ATAGOct2018>--> In 2016, air transport generated $704.4 billion of revenue in 2016, employed 10.2 million workers, supported 65.5 million jobs and $2.7 trillion of economic activity: 3.6% of the global [[GDP]].<ref name=ATAGOct2018>{{cite web |url= https://www.aviationbenefits.org/media/166344/abbb18_full-report_web.pdf |publisher= Air Transport Action Group |title= Aviation: Benefits Beyond Borders |date= October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, the total weekly airline capacity was 181.1 billion [[Available Seat Kilometers]] (+6.9% compared to July 2015): 57.6bn in Asia-Pacific, 47.7bn in Europe, 46.2bn in North America, 12.2bn in Middle East, 12.0bn in Latin America and 5.4bn in Africa.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://html5.pagesuite-professional.co.uk/desktop/stage/default.aspx?pnum=78&edid=e030c749-44c6-4ab0-af51-84e8f4424689 |title= Capacity snapshot |work= Airline Business |date= July\u2013August 2016 |publisher= Flight Global |page= 78}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Top 150 airline groups<ref name=WorldAirlineRankings2017>{{cite web |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/asset/18223 |title= World Airline Rankings |date= 2017 |work= Flight Global}}</ref>\n! !! 2016 !! 2015 !! 2014 !! 2013 !! 2012 !! 2011 !! 2010 !! 2009 !! 2008\n|-\n! Revenue ($bn) \n| 694 || 698 || 704 || 684 || 663 || 634 || 560 || 481 || 540\n|-\n! Operating result ($bn)\n| 58.9 || 65.0 || 30.4 || 27.5 || 20.7 || 21.3 || 32.4 || 1.7 || \u221215.3\n|-\n! Operating margin (%)\n| 8.5% || 9.3% || 4.3% || 4.0% || 3.1% || 3.4% || 5.8% || 0.4% || \u22122.8%\n|-\n! Net result ($bn)\n| 34.2 || 42.4 || 11.7 || 15.3 || 4.6 || 0.3 || 19.0 || \u22125.7 || \u221232.5\n|-\n! Net margin (%)\n| 4.9% || 6.1% || 1.7% || 2.2% || 0.7% || 0.0% || 3.4% || \u22121.2% || \u22126.0%\n|}\n\n==History===\nHistorically, air travel has survived largely through state support, whether in the form of equity or subsidies. The airline industry as a whole has made a cumulative loss during its 100-year history.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/airlines/story/0,,1715861,00.html Wings of Desire], Guardian, Thursday February 23, 2006</ref><ref>[http://www.johnkay.com/2005/09/27/airlines-and-the-canine-features-of-unprofitable-industries/ Airlines and the canine features of unprofitable industries], Financial Times, September 27, 2005</ref>\n\nOne argument is that [[positive externalities]], such as higher growth due to global mobility, outweigh the microeconomic losses and justify continuing government intervention. A historically high level of government intervention in the airline industry can be seen as part of a wider political consensus on strategic forms of transport, such as [[highway]]s and [[Rail transport|railways]], both of which receive public funding in most parts of the world. Although many countries continue to operate state-owned or parastatal airlines, many large airlines today are privately owned and are therefore governed by microeconomic principles to maximize shareholder profit.<ref>Rigas Doganis, \"Alternative Pricing Strategies\", ''Flying Off Course: The Economics of International Airlines'' (London: Routledge, 1991), 267-69. {{ISBN|1134887779}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1991, the collapse of Pan Am, an airline often credited for shaping the international airline industry, highlighted the financial complexities faced by major airline companies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Airline Facts for Kids |url=https://kids.kiddle.co/Airline |website=Kiddle |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Airline Deregulation Act|1978 deregulation]], U.S. carriers did not manage to make an aggregate [[economic profit|profit]] for 12 years in 31, including four years where combined [[economic loss|losses]] amounted to $10 billion, but rebounded with eight consecutive years of profits since 2010, including its four with over $10 billion profits.<!--<ref name=AvWeek14May2018/>--> They drop loss-making routes, avoid [[fare war]]s and [[market share]] battles, limit [[Seating capacity|capacity]] growth, add [[airline hub|hub]] feed with [[regional jet]]s to increase their [[profitability]]. They change [[schedule]]s to create more connections, buy used aircraft, reduce international frequencies and leverage [[partnership]]s to optimise capacities and benefit from overseas connectivity.<ref name=AvWeek14May2018>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/big-us-airlines-seek-long-term-profitability |title= Big U.S. Airlines Seek Long-term Profitability |date= May 14, 2018 |author= Sean Broderick |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref>\n\n=== Largest airlines ===\nThe [[world's largest airlines]] can be defined in several ways. {{As of|2019||df=}}, [[American Airlines Group]] was the largest by fleet size, [[passenger]]s carried and [[revenue passenger mile]]. [[Delta Air Lines]] was the largest by [[revenue]], [[asset]]s value and [[market capitalization]]. [[Lufthansa Group]] was the largest by number of [[employee]]s, [[FedEx Express]] by freight [[tonne-kilometres]], [[Turkish Airlines]] by number of countries served and [[UPS Airlines]] by number of destinations served<ref name=\":8\" /> (though [[United Airlines]] was the largest passenger airline by number of destinations served).<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":10\" />\n{{main|World's largest airlines}}\n\n===Ticket revenue===\n[[File:Diagram of an airline Global Distribution System.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Diagram of an airline [[Global Distribution System]]]]\n\nAirlines assign prices to their services in an attempt to maximize profitability. The pricing of airline tickets has become increasingly complicated over the years and is now largely determined by computerized [[yield management]] systems.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nBecause of the complications in scheduling flights and maintaining profitability, airlines have many loopholes that can be used by the knowledgeable traveler. Many of these airfare secrets are becoming more and more known to the general public, so airlines are forced to make constant adjustments.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nMost airlines use differentiated pricing, a form of [[price discrimination]], to sell air services at varying prices simultaneously to different segments. Factors influencing the price include the days remaining until departure, the booked load factor, the forecast of total demand by price point, competitive pricing in force, and variations by day of week of departure and by time of day. Carriers often accomplish this by dividing each cabin of the aircraft (first, business and economy) into a number of [[travel class]]es for pricing purposes.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nA complicating factor is that of origin-destination control (\"O&D control\"). Someone purchasing a ticket from Melbourne to Sydney (as an example) for A$200 is competing with someone else who wants to fly Melbourne to Los Angeles through Sydney on the same flight, and who is willing to pay A$1400. Should the airline prefer the $1400 passenger, or the $200 passenger plus a possible Sydney-Los Angeles passenger willing to pay $1300? Airlines have to make hundreds of thousands of similar pricing decisions daily.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe advent of advanced computerized reservations systems in the late 1970s, most notably [[Sabre (computer system)|Sabre]], allowed airlines to easily perform [[cost-benefit analysis|cost-benefit analyses]] on different pricing structures, leading to almost perfect price discrimination in some cases (that is, filling each seat on an aircraft at the highest price that can be charged without driving the consumer elsewhere).{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe intense nature of airfare pricing has led to the term \"[[fare war]]\" to describe efforts by airlines to undercut other airlines on competitive routes. Through computers, new airfares can be published quickly and efficiently to the airlines' sales channels. For this purpose the airlines use the [[Airline Tariff Publishing Company]] (ATPCO), who distribute latest fares for more than 500 airlines to [[Computer Reservation System]]s across the world.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe extent of these pricing phenomena is strongest in \"legacy\" carriers. In contrast, low fare carriers usually offer pre-announced and simplified price structure, and sometimes quote prices for each leg of a trip separately.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nComputers also allow airlines to predict, with some accuracy, how many passengers will actually fly after making a reservation to fly. This allows airlines to overbook their flights enough to fill the aircraft while accounting for \"no-shows\", but not enough (in most cases) to force paying passengers off the aircraft for lack of seats, stimulative pricing for low demand flights coupled with [[overbooking]] on high demand flights can help reduce this figure. This is especially crucial during tough economic times as airlines undertake massive cuts to ticket prices to retain demand.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.cheapflights.co.uk/flights/2009/05/recession-prompts-surge-in-cheap-flights.html |title=Recession 'prompts surge in cheap flights' |publisher=News.cheapflights.co.uk |date=2009-05-13 |accessdate=2010-08-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091130120521/http://news.cheapflights.co.uk/flights/2009/05/recession-prompts-surge-in-cheap-flights.html |archive-date=2009-11-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOver January/February 2018, the cheapest airline surveyed by price comparator [[rome2rio]] was [[Tigerair Australia]] with $0.06/km followed by [[AirAsia X]] with $0.07/km, while the most expensive was [[Charterlines, Inc.]] with $1.26/km followed by [[Buddha Air]] with $1.18/km.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.rome2rio.com/labs/2018-global-flight-price-ranking/ |title= 2018 Global Flight Price Ranking: What\u2019s the world\u2019s cheapest airline? |publisher= [[rome2rio]] |date= April 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFor the [[IATA]], the global airline industry [[revenue]] was $754 billion in 2017 for a $38.4 billion collective [[Profit (accounting)|profit]], and should rise by 10.7% to $834 billion in 2018 for a $33.8 billion profit forecast, down by 12% due to rising [[jet fuel]] and [[Workforce|labor]] costs.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/airlines-formula-protecting-profits-higher-fares |title= Airlines\u2019 Formula For Protecting Profits: Higher Fares |date= Jun 12, 2018 |author= Jens Flottau, Adrian Schofield and Aaron Karp |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref>\n\n==== Elasticity ====\n\nThe demand for air transport will be less [[Elasticity (economics)|elastic]] for [[flight length|longer flights]] than for shorter flights, and more elastic for leisure travel than for [[business travel]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.fin.gc.ca/consultresp/Airtravel/airtravStdy_-eng.asp |title= Air Travel Demand Elasticities: Concepts, Issues and Measurement |author=David W. Gillen |author2=William G. Morrison |author3=Christopher Stewart |date= 2008-10-06 |publisher= [[Department of Finance Canada]]}}</ref>\n\n===Operating costs===\n[[File:virgin atlantic a340-600 g-vyou arp.jpg|thumb|An [[Airbus A340]]-600 of [[Virgin Atlantic Airways]]. In October 2008, Virgin Atlantic offered to combine its operations with [[BMI (airline)|BMI]] in an effort to reduce operating costs.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/transport/article5037731.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=Virgin proposes tieup with BMI and Lufthansa | date=October 29, 2008 | accessdate=April 23, 2010 | first=David | last=Robertson}}</ref>]]\n\nAirlines have substantial fixed and operating costs to establish and maintain air services: labor, fuel, airplanes, engines, spares and parts, IT services and networks, airport equipment, airport handling services, booking commissions, advertising, catering, training, [[aviation insurance]] and other costs. Thus all but a small percentage of the income from ticket sales is paid out to a wide variety of external providers or internal cost centers.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nMoreover, the industry is structured so that airlines often act as tax collectors. Airline fuel is untaxed because of a series of treaties existing between countries. Ticket prices include a number of fees, taxes and surcharges beyond the control of airlines. Airlines are also responsible for enforcing government regulations. If airlines carry passengers without proper documentation on an international flight, they are responsible for returning them back to the original country.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nAnalysis of the 1992\u20131996 period shows that every player in the air transport chain is far more profitable than the airlines, who collect and pass through fees and revenues to them from ticket sales. While airlines as a whole earned 6% return on capital employed (2\u20133.5% less than the cost of capital), airports earned 10%, catering companies 10\u201313%, handling companies 11\u201314%, aircraft lessors 15%, aircraft manufacturers 16%, and global distribution companies more than 30%. (Source: Spinetta, 2000, quoted in Doganis, 2002){{Citation needed|date=January 2020|reason=Needs inline and page number}}\n\nThere has been continuing cost competition from [[low cost airline]]s. Many companies emulate [[Southwest Airlines]] in various respects.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/business/airlines/2015/10/08/the-southwest-effect-is-alive-and-well-airline-executives-say|title=The Southwest effect is|date=2015-10-08|work=Dallas News|access-date=2017-10-14|language=en}}</ref> The lines between full-service and low-cost airlines have become blurred \u2013 e.g., with most \"full service\" airlines introducing baggage check fees despite Southwest not doing so.\n\nMany airlines in the U.S. and elsewhere have experienced business difficulty. U.S. airlines that have declared [[Chapter 11]] bankruptcy since 1990 have included [[American Airlines]], [[Continental Airlines]] (twice), [[Delta Air Lines]], [[Northwest Airlines]], [[Pan Am]], [[United Airlines]], and [[US Airways]] (twice).<!-- This list is ordered alphabetically. -->\n\nWhere an airline has established an engineering base at an airport, then there may be considerable economic advantages in using that same airport as a preferred focus (or \"hub\") for its scheduled flights.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nOperating costs for US [[major airline]]s are primarily aircraft [[operating expense]] including [[jet fuel]], [[aircraft maintenance]], [[depreciation]] and [[aircrew]] for 44%, servicing expense for 29% (traffic 11%, passenger 11% and aircraft 7%), 14% for reservations and sales and 13% for [[overheads]] (administration 6% and advertising 2%).<!--<ref name=ICAO20feb2017/>-->\nAn average US major [[Boeing 757]]-200 flies {{cvt|1252|mile|km}} stages 11.3 block hours per day and costs $2,550 per block hour : $923 of ownership, $590 of maintenance, $548 of fuel and $489 of crew; or $13.34 per 186 seats per block hour.<!--<ref name=ICAO20feb2017/>-->\nFor a [[Boeing 737-500]], a low-cost carrier like Southwest have lower operating costs at $1,526 than a full service one like United at $2,974, and higher [[productivity]] with 399,746 [[available seat miles|ASM]] per day against 264,284, resulting in a unit cost of {{#expr:152600/399746round2}} $cts/ASM against {{#expr:297400/264284round2}} $cts/ASM.<ref name=ICAO20feb2017>{{cite web |url= https://www.icao.int/MID/Documents/2017/Aviation%20Data%20and%20Analysis%20Seminar/PPT3%20-%20Airlines%20Operating%20costs%20and%20productivity.pdf |title= Airline Operating Costs and Productivity |date= 20 February 2017 |publisher= ICAO}}</ref>\n\n===Assets and financing===\n[[File:Maslounge.jpg|thumb|The 'Golden Lounge' of [[Malaysia Airlines]] at [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]] (KLIA). The airline has ownership of special slots at KLIA, giving it a competitive edge over other airlines operating at the airport.]]\nAirline financing is quite complex, since airlines are highly leveraged operations. Not only must they purchase (or lease) new airliner bodies and engines regularly, they must make major long-term fleet decisions with the goal of meeting the demands of their markets while producing a fleet that is relatively economical to operate and maintain; comparably Southwest Airlines and their reliance on a single airplane type (the [[Boeing 737]] and derivatives), with the now defunct [[Eastern Air Lines]] which operated 17 different aircraft types, each with varying pilot, engine, maintenance, and support needs.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nA second financial issue is that of [[Hedge (finance)|hedging]] [[Petroleum|oil]] and [[fuel]] purchases, which are usually second only to [[Labour (economics)|labor]] in its relative cost to the company. However, with the current high fuel prices it has become the largest cost to an airline. Legacy airlines, compared with new entrants, have been hit harder by rising fuel prices partly due to the running of older, less fuel efficient aircraft.<ref name=\"Bamber, G.J., Gittell, J.H., Kochan, T.A. & von Nordenflytch, A. 2009\"/> While hedging instruments can be expensive, they can easily pay for themselves many times over in periods of increasing fuel costs, such as in the 2000\u20132005 period.\n\nIn view of the congestion apparent at many international [[airport]]s, the ownership of slots at certain airports (the right to take-off or land an aircraft at a particular time of day or night) has become a significant tradable asset for many airlines. Clearly take-off slots at popular times of the day can be critical in attracting the more profitable business traveler to a given airline's flight and in establishing a competitive advantage against a competing airline.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIf a particular city has two or more airports, market forces will tend to attract the less profitable routes, or those on which competition is weakest, to the less congested airport, where slots are likely to be more available and therefore cheaper. For example, [[Reagan National Airport]] attracts profitable routes due partly to its congestion, leaving less-profitable routes to [[Baltimore-Washington International Airport]] and [[Dulles International Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wtop.com/baltimore/2018/11/which-d-c-area-airport-is-busiest/|title=Which DC-area airport is busiest?|date=2018-11-21|website=WTOP|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOther factors, such as surface transport facilities and onward connections, will also affect the relative appeal of different airports and some long distance flights may need to operate from the one with the longest runway. For example, [[LaGuardia Airport]] is the preferred airport for most of [[Manhattan]] due to its proximity, while long-distance routes must use [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]]'s longer runways.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Airline partnerships===\n{{largest airline alliances}}\n\n[[Codesharing]] is the most common type of airline partnership; it involves one airline selling tickets for another airline's flights under its own airline code. An early example of this was Japan Airlines' (JAL) codesharing partnership with Aeroflot in the 1960s on [[Tokyo]]\u2013[[Moscow]] flights; Aeroflot operated the flights using Aeroflot aircraft, but JAL sold tickets for the flights as if they were JAL flights. This practice allows airlines to expand their operations, at least on paper, into parts of the world where they cannot afford to establish bases or purchase aircraft. Another example was the [[Austrian Airlines|Austrian]]\u2013[[Sabena]] partnership on the [[Vienna]]\u2013[[Brussels]]\u2013[[New York City|New York]]/JFK route during the late '60s, using a Sabena [[Boeing 707]] with Austrian [[Aircraft livery|livery]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nSince airline reservation requests are often made by city-pair (such as \"show me flights from Chicago to D\u00fcsseldorf\"), an airline that can codeshare with another airline for a variety of routes might be able to be listed as indeed offering a Chicago\u2013[[D\u00fcsseldorf]] flight. The passenger is advised however, that airline no. 1 operates the flight from say Chicago to Amsterdam, and airline no. 2 operates the continuing flight (on a different airplane, sometimes from another terminal) to D\u00fcsseldorf. Thus the primary rationale for code sharing is to expand one's service offerings in city-pair terms to increase sales.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nA more recent development is the [[airline alliance]], which became prevalent in the late 1990s. These alliances can act as virtual mergers to get around government restrictions. The largest are [[Star Alliance]], [[SkyTeam]] and [[Oneworld]], and these accounted for over 60% of global commercial air traffic {{As of|2015||df=|lc=y}}.<ref name=\":7\" /> Alliances of airlines coordinate their passenger service programs (such as [[Airport lounge|lounges]] and [[frequent-flyer program]]s), offer special [[Interlining|interline]] tickets and often engage in extensive [[codesharing]] (sometimes systemwide). These are increasingly integrated business combinations\u2014sometimes including cross-equity arrangements\u2014in which products, service standards, schedules, and airport facilities are standardized and combined for higher efficiency. One of the first airlines to start an alliance with another airline was [[KLM]], who partnered with [[Northwest Airlines]]. Both airlines later entered the SkyTeam alliance after the [[Air France-KLM|fusion of KLM and Air France]] in 2004.\n\nOften the companies combine [[Information technology|IT]] operations, or purchase fuel and aircraft as a bloc to achieve higher bargaining power. However, the alliances have been most successful at purchasing invisible supplies and services, such as fuel. Airlines usually prefer to purchase items visible to their passengers to differentiate themselves from local competitors. If an airline's main domestic competitor flies Boeing airliners, then the airline may prefer to use Airbus aircraft regardless of what the rest of the alliance chooses.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Fuel hedging===\n{{Main|Fuel Hedging}}Fuel hedging is a [[contractual]] tool used by transportation companies like airlines to reduce their exposure to volatile and potentially rising fuel costs. Several low-cost carriers such as Southwest Airlines adopt this practice.<ref name = economist>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/gulliver/2015/01/fuel-hedging-and-airlines|title=Gambles that haven't paid off|newspaper=The Economist|issn=0013-0613|access-date= | language =en}}</ref>\n\nSouthwest is credited with maintaining strong business profits between 1999 and the early 2000s due to its fuel hedging policy. Many other airlines are replicating Southwest's hedging policy to control their fuel costs.<ref name = economist/>\n\n=== Seasonality ===\nAirlines often have a strong [[seasonality]], with traffic low in [[Winter]] and peaking in [[Summer]]. In Europe the most extreme market are the [[Greek islands]] with July/August having more than ten times the winter traffic, as [[Jet2]] is the most seasonal among [[low-cost carrier]]s with July having seven times the January traffic, whereas [[legacy carrier]]s are much less with only 85/115% variability.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.anna.aero/2017/03/01/greek-islands-jet2-com-seasonality-losers-europe/ |title= Seasonality: Jet2.com and Greek Islands most extreme in anna.aero leisure-legacy comparison |work= Airline Network News and Analysis |date= 1 Mar 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Environmental impacts==\n{{Main|Environmental impact of aviation}}\n[[File:Contrails southeast lrg.png|thumb|[[Moderate-Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer|MODIS]] tracking of [[contrail]]s generated by air traffic over the southeastern United States on January 29, 2004.]]\n\nAircraft engines emit [[noise pollution]], gases and particulate emissions, and contribute to [[global dimming]].<ref name=contrails>{{cite journal|title=Contrails reduce daily temperature range |first=David J. |last=Travis |author2=Carleton, Andrew M. |author3=Lauritsen, Ryan G |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |page=601 |volume=418 |year=2002 |url=http://facstaff.uww.edu/travisd/pdf/jetcontrailsrecentresearch.pdf |doi=10.1038/418601a |format=PDF |pmid=12167846 |issue=6898 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060503192714/http://facstaff.uww.edu/travisd/pdf/jetcontrailsrecentresearch.pdf |archivedate=2006-05-03 |bibcode=2002Natur.418..601T }}</ref>\n\nGrowth of the industry in recent years raised a number of ecological questions.\n\nDomestic air transport grew in China at 15.5 percent annually from 2001 to 2006. The rate of air travel globally increased at 3.7 percent per year over the same time. In the EU [[greenhouse gas]] emissions from aviation increased by 87% between 1990 and 2006.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Climate change: Commission proposes bringing air transport into EU Emissions Trading Scheme |publisher=EU press release |date=2006-12-20 |url=http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=IP/06/1862 |accessdate=2008-01-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080112155545/http://www.europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=IP%2F06%2F1862 |archivedate=12 January 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> However it must be compared with the flights increase, only in UK, between 1990 and 2006 terminal passengers increased from 100 000 thousands to 250 000 thousands.,<ref>http://www.parliament.uk/briefing-papers/SN03760.pdf</ref> according to AEA reports every year, 750 million passengers travel by European airlines, which also share 40% of merchandise value in and out of Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aea.be/about/airtransportineurope/index.html |title=About Us \u00bb Air Transport in Europe |accessdate=2014-01-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130724203254/http://www.aea.be/about/airtransportineurope/index.html |archivedate=2013-07-24 }}</ref> Without even pressure from \"green activists\", targeting lower ticket prices, generally, airlines do what is possible to cut the fuel consumption (and gas emissions connected therewith). Further, according to some reports, it can be concluded that the last piston-powered aircraft were as fuel-efficient as the average jet in 2005.<ref>http://www.transportenvironment.org/sites/default/files//docs/Publications/2005pubs/2005-12_nlr_aviation_fuel_efficiency.pdf</ref>\n\nDespite continuing efficiency improvements from the major aircraft manufacturers, the expanding demand for global air travel has resulted in growing greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions. Currently, the aviation sector, including US domestic and global international travel, make approximately 1.6 percent of global anthropogenic GHG emissions per annum. North America accounts for nearly 40 percent of the world's GHG emissions from aviation fuel use.<ref>David McCollum, Gregory Gould, and David Greene. Greenhouse Gas Emissions from Aviation and Marine Transportation: Mitigation Potential and Policies, 2009.</ref>\n\nCO2 emissions from the [[jet fuel]] burned per passenger on an average {{convert|3200|km|mi|sp=us}} airline flight is about 353 kilograms (776&nbsp;pounds).<ref>{{cite web|title=carbon-footprint-calculator |url=http://www.terrapass.com/carbon-footprint-calculator/methodology-popup.html |publisher=TerraPass.com |accessdate=Feb 19, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090131210919/http://www.terrapass.com/carbon-footprint-calculator/methodology-popup.html |archivedate=2009-01-31 }}</ref> Loss of natural habitat potential associated with the jet fuel burned per passenger on a {{convert|3200|km|mi|sp=us}} airline flight is estimated to be 250 square meters (2700 square feet).<ref>{{cite web|title=environmental impact of airline flights|url=http://xoearth.org/ecofx-airline-flights/|publisher=ecofx.org|accessdate=Apr 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the context of climate change and [[peak oil]], there is a debate about possible [[taxation]] of air travel and the inclusion of aviation in an [[emissions trading]] scheme, with a view to ensuring that the total [[external costs]] of aviation are taken into account.<ref>[http://www.defra.gov.uk/environment/climatechange/trading/eu/pdf/including-aviation-icf.pdf Including Aviation into the EU ETS: Impact on EU allowance prices] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060215004933/http://www.defra.gov.uk/environment/climatechange/trading/eu/pdf/including-aviation-icf.pdf |date=February 15, 2006 }} ICF Consulting for DEFRA February 2006</ref>\n\nThe airline industry is responsible for about 11 percent of [[greenhouse gas]]es emitted by the U.S. transportation sector. [[Boeing]] estimates that [[biofuel]]s could reduce flight-related greenhouse-gas emissions by 60 to 80 percent. The solution would be blending algae fuels with existing jet fuel:<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/01/03/AR2008010303907.html | work=The Washington Post | title=A Promising Oil Alternative: Algae Energy | date=January 6, 2008 | accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n* Boeing and [[Air New Zealand]] are collaborating with leading Brazilian biofuel maker [[Tecbio]], [[New Zealand]]'s [[Aquaflow Bionomic]] and other jet biofuel developers around the world.\n* [[Virgin Atlantic]] and [[Virgin Green Fund]] are looking into the technology as part of a biofuel initiative.<ref>{{cite web|author=\u00c1ngel Gonz\u00e1lez |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/boeingaerospace/2003858756_boeingenergy30.html |title=To go green in jet fuel, Boeing looks at algae|work = Seattle Times Newspaper |date=2007-08-30 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n* [[KLM]] has made the first commercial flight with biofuel in 2009.\n\nThere are projects on [[electric aircraft]], and some of them are fully operational as of 2013.\n\n==Call signs==\n{{Unreferenced|section|date=January 2020}}\nEach operator of a scheduled or charter flight uses an [[Airline codes|airline call sign]] when communicating with airports or air traffic control centres. Most of these call-signs are derived from the airline's trade name, but for reasons of history, marketing, or the need to reduce ambiguity in spoken English (so that pilots do not mistakenly make navigational decisions based on instructions issued to a different aircraft), some airlines and air forces use call-signs less obviously connected with their trading name. For example, British Airways uses a ''Speedbird'' call-sign, named after the logo of one of its predecessors, [[British Overseas Airways Corporation|BOAC]], while [[SkyEurope]] used ''Relax''.\n\n==Airline personnel==\n\n[[File:787 Dreamliner cabin crew and pilots (10167536115).jpg|thumb|The [[aircrew]] of a [[Jetstar Airways]] Boeing 787]]\n\nThe various types of airline personnel include:\n* [[Flight crew]], responsible for the operation of the aircraft. Flight crew members include:\n** [[Aviator|Pilots]] ([[Pilot in command|Captain]] and [[First officer (civil aviation)|First Officer]]: some older aircraft also required a [[Flight Engineer]] and/or a [[Navigator]])\n** [[Flight attendant]]s (led by a [[purser]] on larger aircraft)\n** [[Sky marshal|In-flight security personnel]] on some airlines (most notably [[El Al]])\n* [[Groundcrew]], responsible for operations at airports. Ground crew members include:\n** Aerospace and avionics engineers responsible for certifying the aircraft for flight and management of aircraft maintenance\n*** [[Aerospace]] engineers, responsible for airframe, powerplant and electrical systems maintenance\n*** [[Avionics]] engineers responsible for avionics and instruments maintenance\n** [[Airframe]] and [[Aircraft engine|powerplant]] technicians\n** Electric System technicians, responsible for maintenance of electrical systems\n** [[Flight dispatcher]]s\n** [[Baggage handler]]s\n** Ramp Agents\n** Remote centralised weight and balancing<ref>http://www.globalloadcontrol.com</ref>\n** [[Gate agent]]s\n** Ticket agents\n** Passenger service agents (such as [[airline lounge]] employees)\n** Reservation agents, usually (but not always) at facilities outside the airport.\n** Crew schedulers\n** \nAirlines follow a [[corporation|corporate]] structure where each broad area of operations (such as maintenance, flight operations (including flight safety), and passenger service) is supervised by a vice president. Larger airlines often appoint vice presidents to oversee each of the airline's hubs as well. Airlines employ [[lawyers]] to deal with regulatory procedures and other administrative tasks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hklaw.com/practices/aviation-regulation/|title=Aviation Regulation|website=www.hklaw.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>\n\n==Industry trends==\n[[File:World-airline-routemap-2009.png|thumb|Map of scheduled airline traffic in 2009]]\n[[File:011 Aircraft of various airlines together at Narita Airport, Japan. Swiss Air Lines, United Airlines, Thai Airways.JPG|thumb|Aircraft of various airlines parked side by side at Tokyo Narita Airport, Japan]]\n\nThe pattern of ownership has been privatized since the mid-1980s, that is, the ownership has gradually changed from governments to private and individual sectors or organizations. This occurs as regulators permit greater freedom and non-government ownership, in steps that are usually decades apart. This pattern is not seen for all airlines in all regions.<ref>{{cite web|title=List of Government-owned and Privatized Airlines (unofficial preliminary compilation) |publisher = [[International Civil Aviation Organization|ICAO]] |url = https://www.icao.int/sustainability/Documents/PrivatizedAirlines.pdf|date = 4 July 2008}}</ref> Many major airlines operating between the 1940s and 1980s were government-owned or government-established. However, most airlines from the earliest days of air travel in the 1920s and 1930s were personal businesses.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nGrowth rates are not consistent in all regions, but countries with a de-regulated airline industry have more competition and greater pricing freedom. This results in lower fares and sometimes dramatic spurts in traffic growth. The U.S., Australia, Canada, [[Japan]], [[Brazil]], [[India]] and other markets exhibit this trend. The industry has been observed to be cyclical in its financial performance. Four or five years of poor earnings precede five or six years of improvement. But profitability even in the good years is generally low, in the range of 2\u20133% net profit after interest and tax. In times of profit, airlines lease new generations of airplanes and upgrade services in response to higher demand. Since 1980, the industry has not earned back the cost of capital during the best of times. Conversely, in bad times losses can be dramatically worse. [[Warren Buffett]] in 1999 said \"the money that had been made since the dawn of aviation by all of this country's airline companies was zero. Absolutely zero.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadiancapitalist.com/buffetts-spot-on-advice/ |title=Buffett\u2019s spot-on advice |publisher=Money Sense |date= |accessdate=2008-10-20}}</ref>\n\nAs in many mature industries, consolidation is a trend. Airline groupings may consist of limited bilateral partnerships, long-term, multi-faceted alliances between carriers, equity arrangements, [[Mergers and acquisitions|mergers]], or [[takeover]]s.<ref name=\":6\" /> Since governments often restrict ownership and merger between companies in different countries, most consolidation takes place within a country. In the U.S., over 200 airlines have merged, been taken over, or gone out of business since the [[Airline Deregulation Act]] in 1978. Many international airline managers are lobbying their governments to permit greater consolidation to achieve higher economy and efficiency.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=18em|\n* [[Air charter]]\n* [[Air ferry]]\n* [[Airline alliance]]\n* [[Airline complaints]]\n* [[Airline timetable]]\n* [[Airliners.net]]\n* [[Airlines of Africa]]\n* [[Airport security]]\n* [[Aviation safety]]\n* [[Freedoms of the air#Beyond rights|Beyond rights]]\n* [[Cargo airline]]\n* [[Domestic flight]]\n* [[Environmental impact of aviation]]\n* [[Federal Aviation Administration]]\n* [[Flight length]]\n* [[Flight planning]]\n* [[FlightAware]]\n* [[Government contract flight]]\n* [[Hypermobility (travel)|Hyper-mobile travel]]\n* [[Inflight magazine]]\n* [[International Air Transport Association]]\n* [[International flight]]\n* [[Legacy carrier]]\n* [[Low-cost carrier]]\n* [[Red-eye flight]]\n* [[Regional airline]]\n* [[Transportation Security Administration]]\n* [[World's busiest passenger air routes]]\n}}\n\n===Airline related lists===\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=18em|\n* [[Airline codes]]\n* [[Airline liveries and logos]]\n* [[List of airlines]]\n* [[List of accidents and incidents involving commercial aircraft]]\n* [[List of airline holding companies]]\n* [[List of airline mergers and acquisitions]]\n* [[List of defunct airlines]]\n* [[List of helicopter airlines]]\n* [[List of hub airports]]\n* [[List of low-cost airlines]]\n* [[Flag carrier|List of national airlines]]\n* [[List of regional airlines]]\n* [[Airline bankruptcies in the United States]]\n* [[World's largest airlines]]\n}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n# \"A history of the world's airlines\", [[R. E. G. Davies|R.E.G. Davies]], Oxford U.P, 1964\n# \"The airline encyclopedia, 1909\u20132000.\u201d Myron J. Smith, Scarecrow Press, 2002\n# \"Flying Off Course: The Economics of International Airlines,\" 3rd edition. Rigas Doganis, Routledge, New York, 2002.\n# \"The Airline Business in the 21st Century.\" Rigas Doganis, Routledge, New York, 2001.\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130809141040/http://www.pbs.org/kcet/chasingthesun/ |title= Chasing the Sun |quote= \"History of commercial aviation\" |publisher= [[PBS]]}}\n* {{cite web |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070616175821/http://www.zinnov.com/presentation/Global_Aviation-Markets-An_Ananlysis.pdf |title= Global Aviation Markets - Analysis |publisher= [[Zinnov LLC]] |date= Jan 2007}} \n* {{cite web |url= https://www.iata.org/whatwedo/Documents/economics/airline_cost_performance.pdf |title= Airline Cost Performance |publisher= IATA |date= July 2006 }}\n* {{cite web |title= Airline industry |work= [[Encyclopedia.com]] |date= 2005 |url= https://www.encyclopedia.com/social-sciences-and-law/economics-business-and-labor/businesses-and-occupations/airline-industry}}\n\n{{Commons category|Airlines|position=left}}\n\n{{Commercial air travel}}\n{{Portal bar|Aviation}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Airlines| ]]\n[[Category:Economics of transport and utility industries]]\n[[Category:Aviation industry]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Company that provides air transport services for travelling passengers and freight}}\n{{Other uses}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Europe to South American in 3 Days Poster (19482266291).jpg|thumb|1930s German poster advertising a weekly [[airmail]] service from [[Deutsche Luft Hansa|Deutsche Lufthansa]], [[Syndicato Condor]] and [[Deutsche Zeppelin Reederei]]]]\n\nAn '''airline''' is a company that provides [[civil aviation|air transport services]] for traveling [[passenger]]s and [[freight]]. Airlines utilize [[aircraft]] to supply these services and may form [[partnership]]s or [[Airline alliance|alliances]] with other airlines for [[codeshare agreements]], in which they both offer and operate the same flight. Generally, airline companies are recognized with an [[Air operator's certificate|air operating certificate]] or license issued by a governmental aviation body. Airlines may be scheduled or [[Air charter|charter]] operators.\n\nThe [[List of airlines by foundation date|first airline]] was the German [[airship]] company [[DELAG]], founded on 16 November 1909.<ref name=\":0\" /> The four oldest non-airship airlines that still exist are the Netherlands' [[KLM]] (1919),<ref name=\":1\" /> Colombia's [[Avianca]] (1919),<ref name=\":2\" /> Australia's [[Qantas]] (1921)<ref name=\":3\" /> and the Czech Republic's [[Czech Airlines]] (1923).<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAirline ownership has seen a shift from mostly personal ownership until the 1930s to government-ownership of major airlines from the 1940s to 1980s and back to large-scale [[privatisation]] following the mid-1980s.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xK4QxAVSd5gC&pg=PA185|title=The Airline Business in the Twenty-first Century|last=Doganis|first=Rigas|date=2001|publisher=Psychology Press|year=|isbn=978-0-415-20883-3|location=|pages=185|language=en}}</ref> Since the 1980s, there has also been a trend of major airline [[mergers]] and the formation of airline alliances.<ref name=\":6\">{{Citation|last=Kumar|first=B. Rajesh|title=Mergers and Acquisitions in the Airline Industry|date=2012|url=https://doi.org/10.1057/9781137005908_11|work=Mega Mergers and Acquisitions: Case Studies from Key Industries|pages=226\u2013230|editor-last=Kumar|editor-first=B. Rajesh|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|language=en|doi=10.1057/9781137005908_11|isbn=978-1-137-00590-8|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> The largest alliances are [[Star Alliance]], [[SkyTeam]] and [[Oneworld]], and these three collectively accounted for more than 60% of global commercial air traffic in 2015.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iata.org/en/pressroom/pr/2016-07-05-01/|title=India Sees Highest Domestic Market Growth in 2015|website=www.iata.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> Airline alliances coordinate their passenger service programs (such as [[Airport lounge|lounges]] and [[frequent-flyer programs]]), offer special [[Interlining|interline]] tickets and often engage in extensive codesharing (sometimes systemwide).\n\n{{As of|2019||df=}}, the [[largest airline]] by passengers carried and fleet size was the [[American Airlines Group]], while [[Delta Air Lines]] was the largest by [[revenue]]. [[Lufthansa Group]] was the largest by number of [[Employee|employees]], [[FedEx Express]] by freight [[tonne-kilometres]], [[Turkish Airlines]] by number of countries served and [[UPS Airlines]] by number of destinations served<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressroom.ups.com/pressroom/ContentDetailsViewer.page?ConceptType=FactSheets&id=1426321563187-193|title=UPS Fact Sheet|last=|first=|date=|website=UPS Pressroom|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231144152/https://pressroom.ups.com/pressroom/ContentDetailsViewer.page?ConceptType=FactSheets&id=1426321563187-193|archive-date=2019-12-31|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> (though [[United Airlines]] was the largest passenger airline by number of destinations served).<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://hub.united.com/Corporate-Fact-Sheet|title=Corporate fact sheet|last=|first=|date=|website=United Hub|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205134015/https://hub.united.com/corporate-fact-sheet/|archive-date=2019-12-05|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://skyrefund.com/en/blog/biggest-airlines-in-the-world|title=Titans: The Biggest Airlines in the World in 2019|website=skyrefund.com|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===The first airlines===\n[[DELAG]], ''Deutsche Luftschiffahrts-Aktiengesellschaft I'' was the [[List of airlines by foundation date|world's first airline]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.airships.net/delag-passenger-zeppelins |title=DELAG: The World's First Airline, using dirgibles. |publisher=Airships.net |date= |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref> It was founded on November 16, 1909, with government assistance, and operated airships manufactured by The [[Zeppelin|Zeppelin Corporation]]. Its headquarters were in [[Frankfurt]]. The first [[fixed-wing]] scheduled airline was started on January 1, 1914, from [[St. Petersburg, Florida]], to [[Tampa, Florida]], operated by the St. Petersburg and Tampa Airboat Line.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.space.com/16657-worlds-first-commercial-airline-the-greatest-moments-in-flight.html|title=World\u2019s First Commercial Airline {{!}} The Greatest Moments in Flight|work=Space.com|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref> The four [[List of airlines by foundation|oldest non-dirigible airlines]] that still exist are the Netherlands' [[KLM]] (1919),<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.klm.com/corporate/en/about-klm/history/index.html|title=History - KLM Corporate|access-date=2017-10-14|language=nl-en}}</ref> Colombia's [[Avianca]] (1919),<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.aviancaholdings.com/en/history|title=History - Avianca Holdings S.A. - www.aviancaholdings.com|website=www.aviancaholdings.com|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref> Australia's [[Qantas]] (1921),<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.qantas.com/travel/airlines/history-founders/global/en|title=Founders of Qantas {{!}} Qantas|website=www.qantas.com|language=en-AU|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref> and the Czech Republic's [[Czech Airlines]] (1923).<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.csa.cz/cz-en/about-us/|title=About Us {{!}} Czech Airlines|website=\u010cSA.cz|language=en|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>\n\n===European airline industry===\n====Beginnings====\n[[File:Klm-poster-1919.jpg|thumb|upright|A 1919 advertisement for the Dutch airline [[KLM]], founded on 7 October 1919, the [[List of airlines by foundation date|oldest running airline still operating under its original name]]]]\n\n[[File:Tanken van een vliegtuig Airplane provided with fuel.jpg|thumb|The [[Handley Page Type W|Handley Page W.8b]] was used by [[Handley Page Transport]], an early British airline established in 1919.]]\nThe earliest fixed wing airline in Europe was [[Aircraft Transport and Travel]], formed by [[George Holt Thomas]] in 1916; via a series of takeovers and mergers, this company is an ancestor of modern-day [[British Airways]]. Using a fleet of former military [[Airco DH.4]]A biplanes that had been modified to carry two passengers in the [[fuselage]], it operated relief flights between [[Folkestone]] and [[Ghent]]. On 15 July 1919, the company flew a proving flight across the [[English Channel]], despite a lack of support from the British government. Flown by Lt. H Shaw in an [[Airco DH.9]] between [[RAF Hendon]] and [[Paris \u2013 Le Bourget Airport]], the flight took 2 hours and 30 minutes at \u00a321 per passenger.\n\nOn 25 August 1919, the company used [[Airco DH.16|DH.16s]] to pioneer a regular service from [[Hounslow Heath Aerodrome]] to Le Bourget, the first regular international service in the world. The airline soon gained a reputation for reliability, despite problems with bad weather, and began to attract European competition. In November 1919, it won the first British civil [[airmail]] contract. Six [[Royal Air Force]] [[Airco DH.9A]] aircraft were lent to the company, to operate the airmail service between [[Hawkinge]] and [[Cologne]]. In 1920, they were returned to the Royal Air Force.<ref>''The Putnam Aeronautical Review'' edited by John Motum, p170 Volume one 1990 Naval Institute Press</ref>\n\nOther British competitors were quick to follow \u2013 [[Handley Page Transport]] was established in 1919 and used the company's converted [[World War One|wartime]] [[Handley Page Type O|Type O/400]] [[bomber]]s with a capacity for 12 passengers,<ref>https://www.flightglobal.com/FlightPDFArchive/1961/1961%20-%200055.PDF</ref> to run a [[London]]-[[Paris]] passenger service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.airlinehistory.co.uk/Airline%20History/History1903.asp|title=Airline History 1903 to 1919|website=www.airlinehistory.co.uk|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>\n\nThe first French airline was [[A\u00e9ropostale (aviation)|Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des lignes Lat\u00e9co\u00e8re]], later known as A\u00e9ropostale, which started its first service in late 1918 to Spain. The [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale des Transports A\u00e9riens]] was created in late 1919, by the [[Farman]] brothers and the [[Farman F.60 Goliath]] plane flew scheduled services from [[Toussus-le-Noble]] to [[Kenley]], near [[Croydon]], England. Another early French airline was the [[Compagnie des Messageries A\u00e9riennes]], established in 1919 by [[Louis-Charles Breguet]], offering a mail and freight service between [[Paris \u2013 Le Bourget Airport|Le Bourget Airport]], [[Paris]] and [[Lesquin Airport]], [[Lille]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafmuseum.org.uk/milestones-of-flight/world/1919.cfm |title=World Aviation in 1919 - Part 1 |publisher=Royal Air Force Museum |accessdate=28 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105130943/http://www.rafmuseum.org.uk/milestones-of-flight/world/1919.cfm |archivedate=5 January 2011 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-00007, Berlin, Start eines Junkers-Flugzeuges.jpg|thumb| [[Junkers F.13]] ''D-190'' of [[Junkers Luftverkehr]]]]\nThe first German airline to use heavier than air aircraft was [[Deutsche Luft-Reederei]] established in 1917 which started operating in February 1919. In its first year, the D.L.R. operated regularly scheduled flights on routes with a combined length of nearly 1000 miles. By 1921 the D.L.R. network was more than 3000&nbsp;km (1865 miles) long, and included destinations in the Netherlands, Scandinavia and the Baltic Republics. Another important German airline was [[Junkers Luftverkehr]], which began operations in 1921. It was a division of the aircraft manufacturer [[Junkers]], which became a separate company in 1924. It operated joint-venture airlines in Austria, Denmark, Estonia, Finland, Hungary, Latvia, Norway, Poland, Sweden and Switzerland.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe [[Netherlands|Dutch]] airline [[KLM]] made its first flight in 1920, and is the oldest continuously operating airline in the world. Established by aviator [[Albert Plesman]],<ref>{{cite journal|journal=International Directory of Company Histories|year=1999|volume=28|title=Koninklijke Luchtvaart Maatschappij, N.V. History| url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/koninklijke-luchtvaart-maatschappij-n-v-history/|accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref> it was immediately awarded a \"Royal\" predicate from [[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands|Queen Wilhelmina]].<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.klm.com/corporate/en/about-klm/history/index.html|work=KLM Corporate|publisher=KLM|accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref> Its first flight was from [[Croydon Airport]], [[London]] to [[Amsterdam]], using a leased [[Aircraft Transport and Travel]] [[Airco DH.16|DH-16]], and carrying two British journalists and a number of newspapers. In 1921, KLM started scheduled services.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn [[Finland]], the charter establishing Aero O/Y (now [[Finnair]]) was signed in the city of [[Helsinki]] on September 12, 1923. [[Junkers F.13]] D-335 became the first aircraft of the company, when Aero took delivery of it on March 14, 1924. The first flight was between Helsinki and [[Tallinn]], capital of [[Estonia]], and it took place on March 20, 1924, one week later.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn the [[Soviet Union]], the Chief Administration of the Civil Air Fleet was established in 1921. One of its first acts was to help found Deutsch-Russische Luftverkehrs A.G. (Deruluft), a German-Russian joint venture to provide air transport from Russia to the West. Domestic air service began around the same time, when Dobrolyot started operations on 15 July 1923 between Moscow and Nizhni Novgorod. Since 1932 all operations had been carried under the name [[Aeroflot]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aeroflot.ru/us-en/about/history|title=Aeroflot History {{!}} Aeroflot|website=www.aeroflot.ru|language=en|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>\n\nEarly European airlines tended to favor comfort \u2013 the passenger cabins were often spacious with luxurious interiors \u2013 over speed and efficiency. The relatively basic navigational capabilities of pilots at the time also meant that delays due to the weather were commonplace.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n====Rationalization====\n[[File:National Audit Office - Victoria - London - 020504.jpg|upright=0.7|thumb|The [[Imperial Airways]] Empire Terminal, Victoria, London. Trains ran from here to [[flying boats]] in [[Southampton]], and to [[Croydon Airport]].]]\nBy the early 1920s, small airlines were struggling to compete, and there was a movement towards increased rationalization and consolidation. In 1924, [[Imperial Airways]] was formed from the merger of [[Instone Air Line|Instone Air Line Company]], [[British Marine Air Navigation Co Ltd|British Marine Air Navigation]], [[Daimler Airway]] and [[Handley Page Transport|Handley Page Transport Co Ltd.]], to allow British airlines to compete with stiff competition from French and German airlines that were enjoying heavy government subsidies. The airline was a pioneer in surveying and opening up air routes across the world to serve far-flung parts of the [[British Empire]] and to enhance trade and integration.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1923/1923%20-%200760.html |title = Imperial Air Transport Company: Appointment of Government Directors|work = Flight|date = December 20, 1923|page = 760}}</ref>\n\nThe first new airliner ordered by Imperial Airways, was the [[Handley Page W8f]] ''City of Washington'', delivered on 3 November 1924.<ref>http://www.century-of-flight.net/Aviation%20history/coming%20of%20age/imperial%20airways.htm</ref> In the first year of operation the company carried 11,395 passengers and 212,380 letters. In April 1925, the film ''[[The Lost World (1925 film)|The Lost World]]'' became the first film to be screened for passengers on a scheduled airliner flight when it was shown on the London-Paris route.\n\nTwo French airlines also merged to form [[Air Union]] on 1 January 1923. This later merged with four other French airlines to become [[Air France]], the country's flagship carrier to this day, on 17 May 1933.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Britannica Concise Encyclopedia|publisher=Britannica Digital Learning|year=2017|isbn=|location=|pages=Air France|via=Credo Reference}}</ref>\n\nGermany's [[Deutsche Luft Hansa]] was created in 1926 by merger of two airlines, one of them [[Junkers Luftverkehr]]. Luft Hansa, due to the [[Hugo Junkers|Junkers]] heritage and unlike most other airlines at the time, became a major investor in airlines outside of Europe, providing capital to [[Varig]] and Avianca. German airliners built by [[Junkers (Aircraft)|Junkers]], [[Dornier GmbH|Dornier]], and [[Fokker]] were among the most advanced in the world at the time.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n====Global expansion====\nIn 1926, [[Alan Cobham]] surveyed a flight route from the UK to [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]], following this up with another proving flight to [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]. Other routes to [[British India]] and the [[Far East]] were also charted and demonstrated at this time. Regular services to [[Cairo]] and [[Basra]] began in 1927 and were extended to [[Karachi]] in 1929. The London-[[Australia]] service was inaugurated in 1932 with the [[Handley Page HP 42]] airliners. Further services were opened up to [[Kolkata|Calcutta]], [[Rangoon]], [[Singapore]], [[Brisbane]] and [[Hong Kong]] passengers departed London on 14 March 1936 following the establishment of a branch from Penang to Hong Kong.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n[[File:Imperial routes April 1935.jpg|thumb|April 1935 map showing [[Imperial Airways]]' routes from the [[United Kingdom|UK]] to [[Australia]] and [[Union of South Africa|South Africa]]]] Imperial's aircraft were small, most seating fewer than twenty passengers, and catered for the rich. Only about 50,000 passengers used Imperial Airways in the 1930s. Most passengers on intercontinental routes or on services within and between British colonies were men doing colonial administration, business or research.<ref>Pirie, G.H. Incidental tourism: British imperial air travel in the 1930s. ''Journal of Tourism History'', 1 (2009) 49\u201366.</ref>\n\nLike Imperial Airways, [[Air France]] and [[KLM]]'s early growth depended heavily on the needs to service links with far-flung colonial possessions ([[French North Africa|North Africa]] and [[French Indochina|Indochina]] for the French and the [[Dutch Indies|East Indies]] for the Dutch). France began an air mail service to [[Morocco]] in 1919 that was bought out in 1927, renamed [[A\u00e9ropostale (aviation)|A\u00e9ropostale]], and injected with capital to become a major international carrier. In 1933, A\u00e9ropostale went [[Bankruptcy|bankrupt]], was nationalized and merged into [[Air France]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nAlthough Germany lacked colonies, it also began expanding its services globally. In 1931, the airship [[LZ 127 Graf Zeppelin|Graf Zeppelin]] began offering regular scheduled passenger service between Germany and South America, usually every two weeks, which continued until 1937.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airships.net/lz127-graf-zeppelin/history |title=LZ-127 Graf Zeppelin |publisher=Airships.net |date= |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref> In 1936, the airship [[LZ 129 Hindenburg|Hindenburg]] entered passenger service and successfully crossed the Atlantic 36 times before crashing at Lakehurst, New Jersey, on May 6, 1937.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airships.net/hindenburg |title=Hindenburg |publisher=Airships.net |date=2009-06-10 |accessdate=2010-08-22| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101005073820/http://www.airships.net/hindenburg| archivedate= 5 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In 1938, a weekly air service from Berlin to [[Kabul]], [[Afghanistan]], started operating.<ref>http://books.stonebooks.com/history/afghanistan.shtml</ref>\n\nFrom February 1934 until World War II began in 1939 [[Deutsche Luft Hansa|Deutsche Lufthansa]] operated an airmail service from [[Stuttgart]], [[Germany]] via [[Spain]], the [[Canary Islands]] and West Africa to [[Natal, Rio Grande do Norte|Natal]] in [[Brazil]]. This was the first time an airline flew across an ocean.<ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.com/?id=pigDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA13&dq=Popular+Science+1931+plane#v=onepage&q=Popular%20Science%201931%20plane&f=true |title=First Transatlantic Air Line Links Two Continents|date=February 1933 |journal=Popular Science|pages = 13\u201315 and 104|volume = 122|issue = 2|editor-last = Brown|editor-first = Raymond J.}}</ref><ref name=\"Graue&Duggan\">James W. Graue & John Duggan \"Deutsche Lufthansa South Atlantic Airmail Service 1934\u20131939\", Zeppelin Study Group, Ickenham, UK 2000 {{ISBN|0-9514114-5-4}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of the 1930s [[Aeroflot]] had become the world's largest airline, employing more than 4,000 pilots and 60,000 other service personnel and operating around 3,000 aircraft (of which 75% were considered obsolete by its own standards). During the Soviet era Aeroflot was synonymous with Russian civil aviation, as it was the only air carrier. It became the first airline in the world to operate sustained regular jet services on 15 September 1956 with the [[Tupolev Tu-104]]. <ref>{{cite web |title=First sustained jet airline service |url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/first-sustained-jet-airline-service/ |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====EU airline deregulation====\nDeregulation of the [[European Union]] airspace in the early 1990s has had substantial effect on the structure of the industry there. The shift towards 'budget' airlines on shorter routes has been significant. Airlines such as [[EasyJet]] and [[Ryanair]] have often grown at the expense of the traditional national airlines.\n\nThere has also been a trend for these national airlines themselves to be privatized such as has occurred for [[Aer Lingus]] and [[British Airways]]. Other national airlines, including Italy's [[Alitalia]], have suffered \u2013 particularly with the rapid increase of oil prices in early 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/alitalia-future-hinges-on-rescue-package/a-1320328|title=Alitalia Future Hinges on Rescue Package {{!}} Business {{!}} DW {{!}} 07.09.2004|last=(www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche Welle|website=DW.COM|language=en|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>\n\n===U.S. airline industry===\n{{main|Air transportation in the United States}}\n\n====Early development====\n[[File:TWA 1940.jpg|thumb|[[TWA]] [[Douglas DC-3]] in 1940. The DC-3, often regarded as one of the most influential aircraft in the history of commercial aviation, revolutionized air travel.]]\n\n[[Tony Jannus]] conducted the United States' first scheduled commercial airline flight on 1 January 1914 for the [[St. Petersburg-Tampa Airboat Line]].<ref name=Society>{{cite web | title=Tony Jannus, an enduring legacy of aviation | work=Tony Jannus Distinguished Aviation Society | publisher=tonyjannusaward.com | url=http://www.tonyjannusaward.com/history/ | accessdate=2010-12-02 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717073628/http://www.tonyjannusaward.com/history/ | archivedate=2011-07-17 }}</ref> The 23-minute flight traveled between [[St. Petersburg, Florida]] and [[Tampa, Florida]], passing some {{convert|50|ft|m}} above Tampa Bay in Jannus' [[Benoist XIV]] wood and muslin biplane flying boat. His passenger was a former mayor of St. Petersburg, who paid $400 for the privilege of sitting on a wooden bench in the open cockpit. The Airboat line operated for about four months, carrying more than 1,200 passengers who paid $5 each.<ref>Carey, Susan, First airline offered no frills, many thrills, [[Wall Street Journal]], December 31, 2013, p. B4</ref> [[Chalk's International Airlines]] began service between Miami and Bimini in the [[Bahamas]] in February 1919. Based in [[Ft. Lauderdale]], Chalk's claimed to be the oldest continuously operating airline in the United States until its closure in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airportbusiness.com/web/online/Top-News-Headlines/CHALKS-AIRLINES-LOSES-FLIGHT-LICENSE-ITS-AIRPORT-LEASE-COULD-BE-CANCELED/1$15115 |title=Chalks Airlines Loses Flight License | publisher=airportbusiness.com|date= |accessdate=2010-12-02}}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[World War I]], the United States found itself swamped with aviators. Many decided to take their war-surplus aircraft on barnstorming campaigns, performing aerobatic maneuvers to woo crowds. In 1918, the [[United States Postal Service]] won the financial backing of [[United States Congress|Congress]] to begin experimenting with [[air mail]] service, initially using [[Curtiss Jenny]]<ref>Amick, George. \"How The Airmail Got Off The Ground.\" American History 33.3 (1998): 48. Academic Search Premier. Web. 3 Nov. 2011.</ref> aircraft that had been procured by the [[United States Army Air Service]]. Private operators were the first to fly the mail but due to numerous accidents the US Army was tasked with mail delivery. During the Army's involvement they proved to be too unreliable and lost their air mail duties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historynet.com/airmail-service-it-began-with-army-air-service-pilots.htm|title=Airmail Service: It Began with Army Air Service Pilots {{!}} HistoryNet|website=www.historynet.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>  By the mid-1920s, the [[United States Postal Service|Postal Service]] had developed its own air mail network, based on a transcontinental backbone between [[New York City]] and [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]].<ref>Clark, Anders (22 August 2014). \"[https://disciplesofflight.com/big-arrow/ Now That's a Big Arrow]\". Disciples of Flight. Retrieved 16 July 2015</ref> To supplement this service, they offered twelve contracts for spur routes to independent bidders. Some of the carriers that won these routes would, through time and mergers, evolve into [[Pan American World Airways|Pan Am]], [[Delta Air Lines]], [[Braniff Airways]], [[American Airlines]], [[United Airlines]] (originally a division of [[Boeing]]), [[Trans World Airlines]], [[Northwest Airlines]], and [[Eastern Air Lines]].\n\nService during the early 1920s was sporadic: most airlines at the time were focused on [[airmail#History|carrying bags of mail]]. In 1925, however, the [[Ford Motor Company]] bought out the [[William Bushnell Stout|Stout Aircraft Company]] and began construction of the all-metal [[Ford Trimotor]], which became the first successful American airliner. With a 12-passenger capacity, the Trimotor made passenger service potentially profitable.<ref>{{ cite web | url = https://postalmuseum.si.edu/exhibits/current/airmail-in-america/the-airplanes/the-ford-trimotor.html | title = The Ford Trimotor and Douglas M-2 Mail Planes | work = Postal Museum | accessdate = July 27, 2017 }}</ref> Air service was seen as a supplement to [[rail transport|rail]] service in the American transportation network.\n\nAt the same time, [[Juan Trippe]] began a crusade to create an air network that would link America to the world, and he achieved this goal through his airline, [[Pan American World Airways]], with a fleet of flying boats that linked [[Los Angeles]] to [[Shanghai]] and [[Boston]] to [[London]]. Pan Am and Northwest Airways (which began flights to Canada in the 1920s) were the only U.S. airlines to go international before the 1940s.\n\nWith the introduction of the [[Boeing 247]] and [[Douglas DC-3]] in the 1930s, the U.S. airline industry was generally profitable, even during the [[Great Depression]]. This trend continued until the beginning of [[World War II]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ASLAUrX3UE8C&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=boeing+247+profitable#v=onepage&q=boeing%20247%20profitable&f=false|title=A Companion to International History 1900\u20132001|last=Martel|first=Gordon|date=2008-04-15|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470766293|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Development since 1945====\n[[File:Stratocruiser op Schiphol, Bestanddeelnr 903-5913.jpg|thumb|[[Boeing 377]] of [[American Export Airlines]], the first airline to offer landplane flights across the North Atlantic in October 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centennialofflight.net/essay/Commercial_Aviation/atlantic_route/Tran4.htm |title=Air Transportation: The Beginnings of Commercial Transatlantic Service |publisher=centennialofflight.net |date= |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref>]]\n\nWorld War II, like World War I, brought new life to the airline industry. Many airlines in the Allied countries were flush from lease contracts to the military, and foresaw a future explosive demand for civil air transport, for both passengers and cargo. They were eager to invest in the newly emerging flagships of air travel such as the [[Boeing Stratocruiser]], [[Lockheed Constellation]], and [[Douglas DC-6]]. Most of these new aircraft were based on American bombers such as the [[B-29]], which had spearheaded research into new technologies such as [[pressurization]]. Most offered increased efficiency from both added speed and greater payload.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.century-of-flight.net/Aviation%20history/airliners/2nd%20upload/timeline%2050s1.htm|title=history of airliners 1950 to 1959|website=www.century-of-flight.net|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jal.com/en/history/aircraft/60s/pick_61-70_01.html|title=History of JAL {{!}} DC-8-32|website=www.jal.com|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1950s, the [[De Havilland Comet]], [[Boeing 707]], [[Douglas DC-8]], and [[Sud Aviation Caravelle]] became the first flagships of the Jet Age in the West, while the Eastern bloc had [[Tupolev Tu-104]] and [[Tupolev Tu-124]] in the fleets of state-owned carriers such as Czechoslovak [[Czech Airlines|\u010cSA]], Soviet [[Aeroflot]] and East-German [[Interflug]]. The [[Vickers Viscount]] and [[Lockheed L-188 Electra]] inaugurated turboprop transport.\n\nOn 4 October 1958, [[BOAC]] started [[transatlantic flight]]s between [[London Heathrow]] and [[New York-Idlewild Airport|New York Idlewild]] with a Comet 4, and [[Pan Am]] followed on 26 October with a B707 service between New York and Paris.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/analysis-how-the-jet-travel-era-began-in-earnest-449222/ |title= How the jet travel era began in earnest \u2013 60 years ago |date= 4 Oct 2018 |author= Max Kingsley Jones |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\nThe next big boost for the airlines would come in the 1970s, when the [[Boeing 747]], [[McDonnell Douglas DC-10]], and [[Lockheed L-1011]] inaugurated [[widebody]] (\"jumbo jet\") service, which is still the standard in international travel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/boeing-747-first-flight-47years-ago-2016-2|title=The Boeing 747 jumbo jet changed air travel with this momentous event 47 years ago|work=Business Insider|access-date=2017-10-14|language=en}}</ref> The [[Tupolev Tu-144]] and its Western counterpart, [[Concorde]], made supersonic travel a reality.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.history.com/news/the-cold-war-race-to-build-the-concorde|title=The Cold War Race to Build the Concorde|work=HISTORY.com|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>  Concorde first flew in 1969 and operated through 2003. In 1972, [[Airbus]] began producing Europe's most commercially successful line of airliners to date. The added efficiencies for these aircraft were often not in speed, but in passenger capacity, payload, and range. Airbus also features modern electronic cockpits that were common across their aircraft to enable pilots to fly multiple models with minimal cross-training.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n====US airline deregulation====\n\n[[File:Pan Am Boeing 747 at Zurich Airport in May 1985.jpg|thumb|[[Pan Am]] [[Boeing 747]] ''Clipper Neptune's Car'' in 1985. The deregulation of the American airline industry increased the financial troubles of the airline which ultimately filed for bankruptcy in December 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centennialofflight.net/essay/Commercial_Aviation/Bankruptcy/Tran9.htm |title=Air Transportation: The Airline Bankruptcies of the 1980s |publisher=centennialofflight.net |date= |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref>]]\n\nThe 1978 U.S. [[Airline deregulation act|airline industry deregulation]] lowered federally controlled barriers for new airlines just as a downturn in the nation's economy occurred. New start-ups entered during the downturn, during which time they found aircraft and funding, contracted hangar and maintenance services, trained new employees, and recruited laid-off staff from other airlines.\n\nMajor airlines dominated their routes through aggressive pricing and additional capacity offerings, often swamping new start-ups. In the place of high barriers to entry imposed by regulation, the major airlines implemented an equally high barrier called [[loss leader]] pricing.<ref name=\"Andrew R. Thomas\">{{cite news|url = http://my.safaribooksonline.com/book/current-affairs/9781430236771 |title=Mr. Soft Landing: Airline Industry Strategy, Service, and Safety|publisher=Apress |year=2007}}</ref> In this strategy an already established and dominant airline stomps out its competition by lowering airfares on specific routes, below the cost of operating on it, choking out any chance a start-up airline may have. The industry side effect is an overall drop in revenue and service quality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asq.org/quality-report/10-year-analysis.html |website =American Society of Quality (ASQ)|title = The American Society for Quality Debuts Quarterly Quality Report with 10-Year Analysis}}</ref> Since deregulation in 1978 the average domestic ticket price has dropped by 40%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mit.edu/airlines/analysis/analysis_airline_industry.html |publisher =Massachusetts Institute of Technology|title = Airline Industry Overview}}</ref> So has airline employee pay. By incurring massive losses, the airlines of the USA now rely upon a scourge of cyclical Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings to continue doing business.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.slate.com/articles/business/moneybox/2011/12/blame_jimmy_carter_for_all_the_airline_bankruptcies_or_better_yet_thank_him_.html |title=Air Fail|publisher = Slate |work = Moneybox|date = 1 December 2011|last = Yglesias|first = Matthew}}</ref> [[America West Airlines]] (which has since merged with US Airways) remained a significant survivor from this new entrant era, as dozens, even hundreds, have gone under.\n\nIn many ways, the biggest winner in the deregulated environment was the air passenger. Although not exclusively attributable to deregulation, indeed the U.S. witnessed an explosive growth in demand for air travel. Many millions who had never or rarely flown before became regular fliers, even joining [[frequent flyer]] loyalty programs and receiving free flights and other benefits from their flying. New services and higher frequencies meant that business fliers could fly to another city, do business, and return the same day, from almost any point in the country. Air travel's advantages put long distance intercity [[railroad]] travel and bus lines under pressure, with most of the latter having withered away, whilst the former is still protected under [[nationalization]] through the continuing existence of [[Amtrak]].\n\nBy the 1980s, almost half of the total flying in the world took place in the U.S., and today the domestic industry operates over 10,000 daily departures nationwide.\n\nToward the end of the century, a new style of [[low-cost carrier|low cost airline]] emerged, offering a no-frills product at a lower price. [[Southwest Airlines]], [[JetBlue]], [[AirTran Airways]], [[Skybus Airlines]] and other low-cost carriers began to represent a serious challenge to the so-called \"legacy airlines\", as did their low-cost counterparts in many other countries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/travel/article/budget-airline-trends-2016/index.html|title=Budget airlines changed the world. What next?|date=2016-03-21|work=CNN Travel|access-date=2017-10-14|language=en}}</ref> Their commercial viability represented a serious competitive threat to the legacy carriers. However, of these, [[ATA Airlines|ATA]] and Skybus have since ceased operations.\n\nIncreasingly since 1978, US airlines have been reincorporated and [[off spin|spun off]] by newly created and internally led management companies, and thus becoming nothing more than operating units and subsidiaries with limited financially decisive control. Among some of these [[holding company|holding companies]] and [[parent company|parent companies]] which are relatively well known, are the [[UAL Corporation]], along with the [[AMR Corporation]], among a long [[list of airline holding companies]] sometime recognized worldwide. Less recognized are the [[private equity firm]]s which often seize managerial, financial, and [[board of directors]] control of distressed airline companies by temporarily investing large sums of [[Equity (finance)|capital]] in air carriers, to rescheme an airlines assets into a profitable organization or [[liquidate|liquidating]] an air carrier of their profitable and worthwhile routes and business operations.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nThus the last 50 years of the airline industry have varied from reasonably profitable, to devastatingly depressed. As the first major market to deregulate the industry in 1978, U.S. airlines have experienced more turbulence than almost any other country or region. In fact, no U.S. [[legacy carrier]] survived bankruptcy-free. Among the outspoken critics of deregulation, former CEO of American Airlines, [[Robert Crandall]] has publicly stated:\n\n<blockquote>\"Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection filing shows airline industry deregulation was a mistake.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/45477274/AMR_Filing_Shows_Airline_Deregulation_Failed_Ex_CEO |title=Robert Cranall former CEO AA, CNBC |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429202738/http://www.cnbc.com/id/45477274/AMR_Filing_Shows_Airline_Deregulation_Failed_Ex_CEO |archivedate=2013-04-29 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n====The airline industry bailout====\n\nCongress passed the [https://www.congress.gov/bill/107th-congress/house-bill/2926 Air Transportation Safety and System Stabilization Act] (P.L. 107-42) in response to a severe liquidity crisis facing the already-troubled airline industry in the aftermath of the [[September 11 attacks|September 11th terrorist attacks]]. Through the [[Air Transportation Stabilization Board|ATSB]] Congress sought to provide cash infusions to carriers for both the cost of the four-day federal shutdown of the airlines and the incremental losses incurred through December 31, 2001, as a result of the terrorist attacks. This resulted in the first government bailout of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ostpxweb.ost.dot.gov/aviation/Data/stabilizationact.pdf |title=Air Transportation Safety and System Stabilization Act |accessdate=2009-06-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409061950/http://ostpxweb.ost.dot.gov/aviation/Data/stabilizationact.pdf |archivedate=2009-04-09 }}</ref> Between 2000 and 2005 US airlines lost $30 billion with wage cuts of over $15 billion and 100,000 employees laid off.<ref name=\"Bamber, G.J., Gittell, J.H., Kochan, T.A. & von Nordenflytch, A. 2009\">{{cite book|url=http://www.cornellpress.cornell.edu/book/?GCOI=80140100965480 |author=Bamber, G.J. |author2=Gittell, J.H. |author3=Kochan, T.A. |author4=von Nordenflytch, A. |year=2009 |title=Up in the Air: How Airlines Can Improve Performance by Engaging their Employees|publisher=Cornell University Press, Ithaca |chapter=chapter 5}}</ref>\n\nIn recognition of the essential national economic role of a healthy aviation system, Congress authorized partial compensation of up to $5 billion in cash subject to review by the [[U.S. Department of Transportation]] and up to $10 billion in loan guarantees subject to review by a newly created [[Air Transportation Stabilization Board]] (ATSB). The applications to DOT for reimbursements were subjected to rigorous multi-year reviews not only by DOT program personnel but also by the [[Government Accountability Office]]<ref>http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d04725r.pdf</ref> and the DOT Inspector General.<ref>[http://www.oig.dot.gov/StreamFile?file=/data/pdfdocs/aa20011024.pdf ]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090717225216/http://www.oig.dot.gov/StreamFile?file=%2Fdata%2Fpdfdocs%2Faa20011024.pdf |date=July 17, 2009 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.oig.dot.gov/StreamFile?file=/data/pdfdocs/cr2003092.pdf ]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090717231319/http://www.oig.dot.gov/StreamFile?file=%2Fdata%2Fpdfdocs%2Fcr2003092.pdf |date=July 17, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nUltimately, the federal government provided $4.6 billion in one-time, subject-to-income-tax cash payments to 427 U.S. air carriers, with no provision for repayment, essentially a gift from the taxpayers. (Passenger carriers operating scheduled service received approximately $4 billion, subject to tax.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dot.gov/affairs/carrierpayments.htm |title=U |publisher=Dot.gov |accessdate=2010-08-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527104415/http://www.dot.gov/affairs/carrierpayments.htm |archivedate=2010-05-27 }}</ref> In addition, the ATSB approved loan guarantees to six airlines totaling approximately $1.6 billion. Data from the [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S. Treasury Department]] show that the government recouped the $1.6 billion and a profit of $339 million from the fees, interest and purchase of discounted airline stock associated with loan guarantees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treas.gov/offices/domestic-finance/atsb/ |title=Air Transportation Stabilization Board |publisher=Treas.gov |date=2001-09-22 |accessdate=2010-08-22|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080709052637/http://www.treas.gov/offices/domestic-finance/atsb/ |archivedate = July 9, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe three largest [[major carrier]]s and [[Southwest Airlines]] control 70% of the U.S. passenger market.<ref name=AvWeek14May2018/>\n\n===Asian airline industry===\n[[File:Tata Sons' Airline Timetable Image, Summer 1935 (interior).jpg|thumb|1935 Timetable of [[Tata Airlines]], founded in 1932]]\n\nAlthough [[Philippine Airlines]] (PAL) was officially founded on February 26, 1941, its license to operate as an airliner was derived from merged Philippine Aerial Taxi Company (PATCO) established by mining magnate Emmanuel N. Bachrach on December 3, 1930, making it Asia's oldest scheduled carrier still in operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hawaii.gov/hawaiiaviation/hawaii-commercial-aviation/philippine-air-lines |title=Above the Pacific |first=William Joseph |last=Horvat |date=1966 |isbn=978-0-8168-0000-1 |publisher=Hawaii.gov |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref> Commercial air service commenced three weeks later from [[Manila]] to [[Baguio]], making it Asia's first airline route. Bachrach's death in 1937 paved the way for its eventual merger with Philippine Airlines in March 1941 and made it Asia's oldest airline. It is also the oldest airline in Asia still operating under its current name.<ref name=\"PAL\">Jane, ''[http://www.janes.com Jane's airlines & airliners By Jeremy Flack]'', First Edition, 2003, {{ISBN|978-0-00-715174-5}}</ref> Bachrach's majority share in PATCO was bought by beer magnate Andres R. Soriano in 1939 upon the advice of General [[Douglas MacArthur]] and later merged with newly formed Philippine Airlines with PAL as the surviving entity. Soriano has controlling interest in both airlines before the merger. PAL restarted service on March 15, 1941, with a single [[Beech Model 18]] NPC-54 aircraft, which started its daily services between [[Manila]] (from [[Nielson Field]]) and [[Baguio]], later to expand with larger aircraft such as the DC-3 and Vickers Viscount.\n\n[[Korean Air]] was one of the first airlines to be launched among the other Asian countries in 1946 along with [[Asiana Airlines]], which later joined in 1988. The license to operate as an airliner was granted by the federal government body after reviewing the necessity at the national assembly. The [[Hanjin]] occupies the largest ownership of Korean Air as well as few low-budget airlines as of now. The Korean Air is among the founders of [[SkyTeam]], which was established in 2000. Asiana Airlines joined [[Star Alliance]] in 2003. Korean Air and Asiana Airlines comprise one of the largest combined airline miles and number of passenger served at the regional market of Asian airline industry\n\n[[India]] was also one of the first countries to embrace civil aviation.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Pran Nath Seth|author2=Pran Nath Seth, Sushma Seth Bhat|title=An Introduction To Travel And Tourism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AcGn-Fmc43sC&pg=PA111|year=2003|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|isbn=978-81-207-2482-2|page=111}}</ref> One of the first Asian airline companies was [[Air India]], which was founded as [[Tata Airlines]] in 1932, a division of Tata Sons Ltd. (now [[Tata Group]]). The airline was founded by India's leading industrialist, [[JRD Tata]]. On October 15, 1932, J. R. D. Tata himself flew a single engined [[De Havilland Puss Moth]] carrying air mail (postal mail of [[Imperial Airways]]) from [[Karachi]] to [[Mumbai|Bombay]] via [[Ahmedabad]]. The aircraft continued to [[Madras]] via Bellary piloted by [[Royal Air Force]] pilot [[Nevill Vintcent]]. Tata Airlines was also one of the world's first major airlines which began its operations without any support from the Government.<ref>{{cite book|author=S Bhatt|title=International Environmental Law|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s0g7tCYYu-gC&pg=PA175|year=2007|publisher=APH Publishing|isbn=978-81-313-0125-8|page=175}}</ref>\n\nWith the outbreak of World War II, the airline presence in Asia came to a relative halt, with many new flag carriers donating their aircraft for military aid and other uses. Following the end of the war in 1945, regular commercial service was restored in India and Tata Airlines became a public limited company on July 29, 1946, under the name Air India. After the [[independence of India]], 49% of the airline was acquired by the [[Government of India]]. In return, the airline was granted status to operate international services from India as the designated flag carrier under the name [[Air India International]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nOn July 31, 1946, a chartered Philippine Airlines (PAL) [[DC-4]] ferried 40 American servicemen to [[Oakland, California|Oakland]], [[California]], from Nielson Airport in [[Makati City]] with stops in [[Guam]], [[Wake Island]], [[Johnston Atoll]] and [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]], making PAL the first Asian airline to cross the [[Pacific Ocean]]. A regular service between [[Manila]] and [[San Francisco]] was started in December. It was during this year that the airline was designated as the flag carrier of Philippines.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nDuring the era of [[decolonization]], newly born Asian countries started to embrace air transport. Among the first Asian carriers during the era were [[Cathay Pacific]] of [[Hong Kong]] (founded in September 1946), [[Orient Airways]] (later [[Pakistan International Airlines]]; founded in October 1946), [[Air Ceylon]] (later [[SriLankan Airlines]]; founded in 1947), [[Malayan Airways Limited]] in 1947 (later [[Singapore Airlines|Singapore]] and [[Malaysia Airlines]]), [[El Al]] in [[Israel]] in 1948, [[Garuda Indonesia]] in 1949, [[Japan Airlines]] in 1951, [[Thai Airways International]] in 1960, and [[Korean National Airlines]] in 1947.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Latin American and Caribbean airline industry===\n[[File:Tam.a330-200.pt-mvl.arp.jpg|thumb|[[TAM Airlines]] is the largest airline in [[Latin America]] in terms of number of annual passengers flown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airtravel.about.com/od/basedincaribbeansa/tp/top10la.htm |title=Top 10 Airlines in Latin America By Arlene Fleming |publisher=Airtravel.about.com |date=2010-06-10 |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref>]]\n\nAmong the first countries to have regular airlines in Latin America and the Caribbean were [[Bolivia]] with [[Lloyd A\u00e9reo Boliviano]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Bolivia/Transportation#ref312761|title=Bolivia - Transportation {{!}} history - geography|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-10-14|language=en}}</ref> [[Cuba]] with [[Cubana de Aviaci\u00f3n]], [[Colombia]] with [[Avianca]] (the first airline established in the Americas), Argentina with [[Aerolineas Argentinas]], [[Chile]] with [[LAN Chile]] (today [[LATAM Airlines]]), [[Brazil]] with [[Varig]], [[Dominican Republic]] with [[Dominicana de Aviaci\u00f3n]], [[Mexico]] with [[Mexicana de Aviaci\u00f3n]], [[Trinidad and Tobago]] with [[BWIA West Indies Airways]] (today [[Caribbean Airlines]]), [[Venezuela]] with [[Aeropostal]], [[Puerto Rico]] with [[Aerovias nacionales de puerto rico|Puertorriquena]]; and [[Grupo TACA|TACA]] based in [[El Salvador]] and representing several airlines of [[Central America]] ([[Costa Rica]], [[Guatemala]], [[Honduras]] and [[Nicaragua]]). All the previous airlines started regular operations well before [[World War II]]. Puerto Rican commercial airlines such as [[Prinair]], [[Oceanair]], [[Fina Air]] and [[Vieques Air Link]] came much after the second world war, as did several others from other countries like Mexico's [[Interjet]] and [[Volaris]], Venezuela's [[Aserca Airlines]] and others.\n\nThe air travel market has evolved rapidly over recent years in [[Latin America]]. Some industry estimates indicate that over 2,000 new aircraft will begin service over the next five years in this region.<ref>{{cite web|title=Latin America needs more than 2,000 new passenger aircraft in next 20 years|url=http://www.airbus.com/presscentre/pressreleases/press-release-detail/detail/latin-america-needs-more-than-2000-new-passenger-aircraft-in-next-20-years/|accessdate=3 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nThese airlines serve domestic flights within their countries, as well as connections within Latin America and also overseas flights to North America, Europe, Australia, and Asia.\n\nOnly two airlines \u2013 [[Avianca]] and [[LATAM Airlines]] \u2013 have international subsidiaries and cover many destinations within the Americas as well as major hubs in other continents. LATAM with [[Chile]] as the central operation along with [[Peru]], [[Ecuador]], [[Colombia]], [[Brazil]] and [[Argentina]] and formerly with some operations in the [[Dominican Republic]]. The [[Avianca Holdings|Avianca]] group has its main operation in Colombia based around the hub in [[El Dorado International Airport|Bogot\u00e1]], Colombia, as well as subsidiaries in various Latin American countries with hubs in [[Monse\u00f1or \u00d3scar Arnulfo Romero (airport)|San Salvador]], El Salvador, as well as [[Lima International Airport|Lima]], Peru, with a smaller operation in Ecuador.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Regulatory considerations==\n\n===National===\n[[File:British Airways (27078321943).jpg|thumb|[[Union Jack]] tails of [[British Airways]], UK's [[flag carrier]]]]\n\nMany countries have [[Flag carrier|national airline]]s that the government owns and operates. Fully private airlines are subject to a great deal of government regulation for economic, political, and safety concerns. For instance, governments often intervene to halt airline labor actions to protect the free flow of people, communications, and goods between different regions without compromising safety.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe United States, Australia, and to a lesser extent Brazil, Mexico, India, the United Kingdom, and Japan have \"deregulated\" their airlines. In the past, these governments dictated airfares, route networks, and other operational requirements for each airline. Since deregulation, airlines have been largely free to negotiate their own operating arrangements with different airports, enter and exit routes easily, and to levy airfares and supply flights according to market demand.\nThe entry barriers for new airlines are lower in a deregulated market, and so the U.S. has seen hundreds of airlines start up (sometimes for only a brief operating period). This has produced far greater competition than before deregulation in most markets. The added competition, together with pricing freedom, means that new entrants often take market share with highly reduced rates that, to a limited degree, full service airlines must match. This is a major constraint on profitability for established carriers, which tend to have a higher cost base.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nAs a result, profitability in a deregulated market is uneven for most airlines. These forces have caused some major airlines to go out of business, in addition to most of the poorly established new entrants.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn the United States, the airline industry is dominated by four large firms. Because of industry consolidation, after fuel prices dropped considerably in 2015, very little of the savings were passed on to consumers.<ref>\"Too Much of a Good Thing.\" ''The Economist'' 26 March 2016: 23. print.</ref>\n\n===International===\n{{Unreferenced|section|date=January 2020}}[[File:La Maison de l-OACI - 11a.jpg|thumb|[[International Civil Aviation Organization]] headquarters in [[Montreal]]]]\n\nGroups such as the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] establish worldwide standards for safety and other vital concerns. Most international air traffic is regulated by bilateral agreements between countries, which designate specific carriers to operate on specific routes. The model of such an agreement was the [[Bermuda Agreement]] between the US and UK following World War II, which designated airports to be used for transatlantic flights and gave each government the authority to nominate carriers to operate routes.\n\nBilateral agreements are based on the \"[[freedoms of the air]]\", a group of generalized traffic rights ranging from the freedom to overfly a country to the freedom to provide domestic flights within a country (a very rarely granted right known as [[cabotage]]). Most agreements permit airlines to fly from their home country to designated airports in the other country: some also extend the freedom to provide continuing service to a third country, or to another destination in the other country while carrying passengers from overseas.\n\nIn the 1990s, \"[[open skies]]\" agreements became more common. These agreements take many of these regulatory powers from state governments and open up international routes to further competition. Open skies agreements have met some criticism, particularly within the European Union, whose airlines would be at a comparative disadvantage with the United States' because of [[cabotage]] restrictions.\n\n==Economic considerations==\n\nIn 2017, 4.1 billion passengers have been carried by airlines in 41.9 million commercial scheduled flights (an average payload of {{#expr:4100/41.9round0}} passengers), for 7.75 trillion [[passenger kilometre]]s (an average trip of {{#expr:7750/4.100round0}} km) over 45,091 airline routes served globally.<!--<ref name=ATAGOct2018>--> In 2016, air transport generated $704.4 billion of revenue in 2016, employed 10.2 million workers, supported 65.5 million jobs and $2.7 trillion of economic activity: 3.6% of the global [[GDP]].<ref name=ATAGOct2018>{{cite web |url= https://www.aviationbenefits.org/media/166344/abbb18_full-report_web.pdf |publisher= Air Transport Action Group |title= Aviation: Benefits Beyond Borders |date= October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, the total weekly airline capacity was 181.1 billion [[Available Seat Kilometers]] (+6.9% compared to July 2015): 57.6bn in Asia-Pacific, 47.7bn in Europe, 46.2bn in North America, 12.2bn in Middle East, 12.0bn in Latin America and 5.4bn in Africa.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://html5.pagesuite-professional.co.uk/desktop/stage/default.aspx?pnum=78&edid=e030c749-44c6-4ab0-af51-84e8f4424689 |title= Capacity snapshot |work= Airline Business |date= July\u2013August 2016 |publisher= Flight Global |page= 78}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Top 150 airline groups<ref name=WorldAirlineRankings2017>{{cite web |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/asset/18223 |title= World Airline Rankings |date= 2017 |work= Flight Global}}</ref>\n! !! 2016 !! 2015 !! 2014 !! 2013 !! 2012 !! 2011 !! 2010 !! 2009 !! 2008\n|-\n! Revenue ($bn) \n| 694 || 698 || 704 || 684 || 663 || 634 || 560 || 481 || 540\n|-\n! Operating result ($bn)\n| 58.9 || 65.0 || 30.4 || 27.5 || 20.7 || 21.3 || 32.4 || 1.7 || \u221215.3\n|-\n! Operating margin (%)\n| 8.5% || 9.3% || 4.3% || 4.0% || 3.1% || 3.4% || 5.8% || 0.4% || \u22122.8%\n|-\n! Net result ($bn)\n| 34.2 || 42.4 || 11.7 || 15.3 || 4.6 || 0.3 || 19.0 || \u22125.7 || \u221232.5\n|-\n! Net margin (%)\n| 4.9% || 6.1% || 1.7% || 2.2% || 0.7% || 0.0% || 3.4% || \u22121.2% || \u22126.0%\n|}\n\n==History===\nHistorically, air travel has survived largely through state support, whether in the form of equity or subsidies. The airline industry as a whole has made a cumulative loss during its 100-year history.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/airlines/story/0,,1715861,00.html Wings of Desire], Guardian, Thursday February 23, 2006</ref><ref>[http://www.johnkay.com/2005/09/27/airlines-and-the-canine-features-of-unprofitable-industries/ Airlines and the canine features of unprofitable industries], Financial Times, September 27, 2005</ref>\n\nOne argument is that [[positive externalities]], such as higher growth due to global mobility, outweigh the microeconomic losses and justify continuing government intervention. A historically high level of government intervention in the airline industry can be seen as part of a wider political consensus on strategic forms of transport, such as [[highway]]s and [[Rail transport|railways]], both of which receive public funding in most parts of the world. Although many countries continue to operate state-owned or parastatal airlines, many large airlines today are privately owned and are therefore governed by microeconomic principles to maximize shareholder profit.<ref>Rigas Doganis, \"Alternative Pricing Strategies\", ''Flying Off Course: The Economics of International Airlines'' (London: Routledge, 1991), 267-69. {{ISBN|1134887779}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1991, the collapse of Pan Am, an airline often credited for shaping the international airline industry, highlighted the financial complexities faced by major airline companies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Airline Facts for Kids |url=https://kids.kiddle.co/Airline |website=Kiddle |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Airline Deregulation Act|1978 deregulation]], U.S. carriers did not manage to make an aggregate [[economic profit|profit]] for 12 years in 31, including four years where combined [[economic loss|losses]] amounted to $10 billion, but rebounded with eight consecutive years of profits since 2010, including its four with over $10 billion profits.<!--<ref name=AvWeek14May2018/>--> They drop loss-making routes, avoid [[fare war]]s and [[market share]] battles, limit [[Seating capacity|capacity]] growth, add [[airline hub|hub]] feed with [[regional jet]]s to increase their [[profitability]]. They change [[schedule]]s to create more connections, buy used aircraft, reduce international frequencies and leverage [[partnership]]s to optimise capacities and benefit from overseas connectivity.<ref name=AvWeek14May2018>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/big-us-airlines-seek-long-term-profitability |title= Big U.S. Airlines Seek Long-term Profitability |date= May 14, 2018 |author= Sean Broderick |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref>\n\n=== Largest airlines ===\nThe [[world's largest airlines]] can be defined in several ways. {{As of|2019||df=}}, [[American Airlines Group]] was the largest by fleet size, [[passenger]]s carried and [[revenue passenger mile]]. [[Delta Air Lines]] was the largest by [[revenue]], [[asset]]s value and [[market capitalization]]. [[Lufthansa Group]] was the largest by number of [[employee]]s, [[FedEx Express]] by freight [[tonne-kilometres]], [[Turkish Airlines]] by number of countries served and [[UPS Airlines]] by number of destinations served<ref name=\":8\" /> (though [[United Airlines]] was the largest passenger airline by number of destinations served).<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":10\" />\n{{main|World's largest airlines}}\n\n===Ticket revenue===\n[[File:Diagram of an airline Global Distribution System.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Diagram of an airline [[Global Distribution System]]]]\n\nAirlines assign prices to their services in an attempt to maximize profitability. The pricing of airline tickets has become increasingly complicated over the years and is now largely determined by computerized [[yield management]] systems.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nBecause of the complications in scheduling flights and maintaining profitability, airlines have many loopholes that can be used by the knowledgeable traveler. Many of these airfare secrets are becoming more and more known to the general public, so airlines are forced to make constant adjustments.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nMost airlines use differentiated pricing, a form of [[price discrimination]], to sell air services at varying prices simultaneously to different segments. Factors influencing the price include the days remaining until departure, the booked load factor, the forecast of total demand by price point, competitive pricing in force, and variations by day of week of departure and by time of day. Carriers often accomplish this by dividing each cabin of the aircraft (first, business and economy) into a number of [[travel class]]es for pricing purposes.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nA complicating factor is that of origin-destination control (\"O&D control\"). Someone purchasing a ticket from Melbourne to Sydney (as an example) for A$200 is competing with someone else who wants to fly Melbourne to Los Angeles through Sydney on the same flight, and who is willing to pay A$1400. Should the airline prefer the $1400 passenger, or the $200 passenger plus a possible Sydney-Los Angeles passenger willing to pay $1300? Airlines have to make hundreds of thousands of similar pricing decisions daily.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe advent of advanced computerized reservations systems in the late 1970s, most notably [[Sabre (computer system)|Sabre]], allowed airlines to easily perform [[cost-benefit analysis|cost-benefit analyses]] on different pricing structures, leading to almost perfect price discrimination in some cases (that is, filling each seat on an aircraft at the highest price that can be charged without driving the consumer elsewhere).{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe intense nature of airfare pricing has led to the term \"[[fare war]]\" to describe efforts by airlines to undercut other airlines on competitive routes. Through computers, new airfares can be published quickly and efficiently to the airlines' sales channels. For this purpose the airlines use the [[Airline Tariff Publishing Company]] (ATPCO), who distribute latest fares for more than 500 airlines to [[Computer Reservation System]]s across the world.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe extent of these pricing phenomena is strongest in \"legacy\" carriers. In contrast, low fare carriers usually offer pre-announced and simplified price structure, and sometimes quote prices for each leg of a trip separately.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nComputers also allow airlines to predict, with some accuracy, how many passengers will actually fly after making a reservation to fly. This allows airlines to overbook their flights enough to fill the aircraft while accounting for \"no-shows\", but not enough (in most cases) to force paying passengers off the aircraft for lack of seats, stimulative pricing for low demand flights coupled with [[overbooking]] on high demand flights can help reduce this figure. This is especially crucial during tough economic times as airlines undertake massive cuts to ticket prices to retain demand.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.cheapflights.co.uk/flights/2009/05/recession-prompts-surge-in-cheap-flights.html |title=Recession 'prompts surge in cheap flights' |publisher=News.cheapflights.co.uk |date=2009-05-13 |accessdate=2010-08-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091130120521/http://news.cheapflights.co.uk/flights/2009/05/recession-prompts-surge-in-cheap-flights.html |archive-date=2009-11-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOver January/February 2018, the cheapest airline surveyed by price comparator [[rome2rio]] was [[Tigerair Australia]] with $0.06/km followed by [[AirAsia X]] with $0.07/km, while the most expensive was [[Charterlines, Inc.]] with $1.26/km followed by [[Buddha Air]] with $1.18/km.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.rome2rio.com/labs/2018-global-flight-price-ranking/ |title= 2018 Global Flight Price Ranking: What\u2019s the world\u2019s cheapest airline? |publisher= [[rome2rio]] |date= April 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFor the [[IATA]], the global airline industry [[revenue]] was $754 billion in 2017 for a $38.4 billion collective [[Profit (accounting)|profit]], and should rise by 10.7% to $834 billion in 2018 for a $33.8 billion profit forecast, down by 12% due to rising [[jet fuel]] and [[Workforce|labor]] costs.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/airlines-formula-protecting-profits-higher-fares |title= Airlines\u2019 Formula For Protecting Profits: Higher Fares |date= Jun 12, 2018 |author= Jens Flottau, Adrian Schofield and Aaron Karp |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref>\n\n==== Elasticity ====\n\nThe demand for air transport will be less [[Elasticity (economics)|elastic]] for [[flight length|longer flights]] than for shorter flights, and more elastic for leisure travel than for [[business travel]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.fin.gc.ca/consultresp/Airtravel/airtravStdy_-eng.asp |title= Air Travel Demand Elasticities: Concepts, Issues and Measurement |author=David W. Gillen |author2=William G. Morrison |author3=Christopher Stewart |date= 2008-10-06 |publisher= [[Department of Finance Canada]]}}</ref>\n\n===Operating costs===\n[[File:virgin atlantic a340-600 g-vyou arp.jpg|thumb|An [[Airbus A340]]-600 of [[Virgin Atlantic Airways]]. In October 2008, Virgin Atlantic offered to combine its operations with [[BMI (airline)|BMI]] in an effort to reduce operating costs.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/transport/article5037731.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=Virgin proposes tieup with BMI and Lufthansa | date=October 29, 2008 | accessdate=April 23, 2010 | first=David | last=Robertson}}</ref>]]\n\nAirlines have substantial fixed and operating costs to establish and maintain air services: labor, fuel, airplanes, engines, spares and parts, IT services and networks, airport equipment, airport handling services, booking commissions, advertising, catering, training, [[aviation insurance]] and other costs. Thus all but a small percentage of the income from ticket sales is paid out to a wide variety of external providers or internal cost centers.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nMoreover, the industry is structured so that airlines often act as tax collectors. Airline fuel is untaxed because of a series of treaties existing between countries. Ticket prices include a number of fees, taxes and surcharges beyond the control of airlines. Airlines are also responsible for enforcing government regulations. If airlines carry passengers without proper documentation on an international flight, they are responsible for returning them back to the original country.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nAnalysis of the 1992\u20131996 period shows that every player in the air transport chain is far more profitable than the airlines, who collect and pass through fees and revenues to them from ticket sales. While airlines as a whole earned 6% return on capital employed (2\u20133.5% less than the cost of capital), airports earned 10%, catering companies 10\u201313%, handling companies 11\u201314%, aircraft lessors 15%, aircraft manufacturers 16%, and global distribution companies more than 30%. (Source: Spinetta, 2000, quoted in Doganis, 2002){{Citation needed|date=January 2020|reason=Needs inline and page number}}\n\nThere has been continuing cost competition from [[low cost airline]]s. Many companies emulate [[Southwest Airlines]] in various respects.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/business/airlines/2015/10/08/the-southwest-effect-is-alive-and-well-airline-executives-say|title=The Southwest effect is|date=2015-10-08|work=Dallas News|access-date=2017-10-14|language=en}}</ref> The lines between full-service and low-cost airlines have become blurred \u2013 e.g., with most \"full service\" airlines introducing baggage check fees despite Southwest not doing so.\n\nMany airlines in the U.S. and elsewhere have experienced business difficulty. U.S. airlines that have declared [[Chapter 11]] bankruptcy since 1990 have included [[American Airlines]], [[Continental Airlines]] (twice), [[Delta Air Lines]], [[Northwest Airlines]], [[Pan Am]], [[United Airlines]], and [[US Airways]] (twice).<!-- This list is ordered alphabetically. -->\n\nWhere an airline has established an engineering base at an airport, then there may be considerable economic advantages in using that same airport as a preferred focus (or \"hub\") for its scheduled flights.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nOperating costs for US [[major airline]]s are primarily aircraft [[operating expense]] including [[jet fuel]], [[aircraft maintenance]], [[depreciation]] and [[aircrew]] for 44%, servicing expense for 29% (traffic 11%, passenger 11% and aircraft 7%), 14% for reservations and sales and 13% for [[overheads]] (administration 6% and advertising 2%).<!--<ref name=ICAO20feb2017/>-->\nAn average US major [[Boeing 757]]-200 flies {{cvt|1252|mile|km}} stages 11.3 block hours per day and costs $2,550 per block hour : $923 of ownership, $590 of maintenance, $548 of fuel and $489 of crew; or $13.34 per 186 seats per block hour.<!--<ref name=ICAO20feb2017/>-->\nFor a [[Boeing 737-500]], a low-cost carrier like Southwest have lower operating costs at $1,526 than a full service one like United at $2,974, and higher [[productivity]] with 399,746 [[available seat miles|ASM]] per day against 264,284, resulting in a unit cost of {{#expr:152600/399746round2}} $cts/ASM against {{#expr:297400/264284round2}} $cts/ASM.<ref name=ICAO20feb2017>{{cite web |url= https://www.icao.int/MID/Documents/2017/Aviation%20Data%20and%20Analysis%20Seminar/PPT3%20-%20Airlines%20Operating%20costs%20and%20productivity.pdf |title= Airline Operating Costs and Productivity |date= 20 February 2017 |publisher= ICAO}}</ref>\n\n===Assets and financing===\n[[File:Maslounge.jpg|thumb|The 'Golden Lounge' of [[Malaysia Airlines]] at [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]] (KLIA). The airline has ownership of special slots at KLIA, giving it a competitive edge over other airlines operating at the airport.]]\nAirline financing is quite complex, since airlines are highly leveraged operations. Not only must they purchase (or lease) new airliner bodies and engines regularly, they must make major long-term fleet decisions with the goal of meeting the demands of their markets while producing a fleet that is relatively economical to operate and maintain; comparably Southwest Airlines and their reliance on a single airplane type (the [[Boeing 737]] and derivatives), with the now defunct [[Eastern Air Lines]] which operated 17 different aircraft types, each with varying pilot, engine, maintenance, and support needs.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nA second financial issue is that of [[Hedge (finance)|hedging]] [[Petroleum|oil]] and [[fuel]] purchases, which are usually second only to [[Labour (economics)|labor]] in its relative cost to the company. However, with the current high fuel prices it has become the largest cost to an airline. Legacy airlines, compared with new entrants, have been hit harder by rising fuel prices partly due to the running of older, less fuel efficient aircraft.<ref name=\"Bamber, G.J., Gittell, J.H., Kochan, T.A. & von Nordenflytch, A. 2009\"/> While hedging instruments can be expensive, they can easily pay for themselves many times over in periods of increasing fuel costs, such as in the 2000\u20132005 period.\n\nIn view of the congestion apparent at many international [[airport]]s, the ownership of slots at certain airports (the right to take-off or land an aircraft at a particular time of day or night) has become a significant tradable asset for many airlines. Clearly take-off slots at popular times of the day can be critical in attracting the more profitable business traveler to a given airline's flight and in establishing a competitive advantage against a competing airline.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIf a particular city has two or more airports, market forces will tend to attract the less profitable routes, or those on which competition is weakest, to the less congested airport, where slots are likely to be more available and therefore cheaper. For example, [[Reagan National Airport]] attracts profitable routes due partly to its congestion, leaving less-profitable routes to [[Baltimore-Washington International Airport]] and [[Dulles International Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wtop.com/baltimore/2018/11/which-d-c-area-airport-is-busiest/|title=Which DC-area airport is busiest?|date=2018-11-21|website=WTOP|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOther factors, such as surface transport facilities and onward connections, will also affect the relative appeal of different airports and some long distance flights may need to operate from the one with the longest runway. For example, [[LaGuardia Airport]] is the preferred airport for most of [[Manhattan]] due to its proximity, while long-distance routes must use [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]]'s longer runways.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Airline partnerships===\n{{largest airline alliances}}\n\n[[Codesharing]] is the most common type of airline partnership; it involves one airline selling tickets for another airline's flights under its own airline code. An early example of this was Japan Airlines' (JAL) codesharing partnership with Aeroflot in the 1960s on [[Tokyo]]\u2013[[Moscow]] flights; Aeroflot operated the flights using Aeroflot aircraft, but JAL sold tickets for the flights as if they were JAL flights. This practice allows airlines to expand their operations, at least on paper, into parts of the world where they cannot afford to establish bases or purchase aircraft. Another example was the [[Austrian Airlines|Austrian]]\u2013[[Sabena]] partnership on the [[Vienna]]\u2013[[Brussels]]\u2013[[New York City|New York]]/JFK route during the late '60s, using a Sabena [[Boeing 707]] with Austrian [[Aircraft livery|livery]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nSince airline reservation requests are often made by city-pair (such as \"show me flights from Chicago to D\u00fcsseldorf\"), an airline that can codeshare with another airline for a variety of routes might be able to be listed as indeed offering a Chicago\u2013[[D\u00fcsseldorf]] flight. The passenger is advised however, that airline no. 1 operates the flight from say Chicago to Amsterdam, and airline no. 2 operates the continuing flight (on a different airplane, sometimes from another terminal) to D\u00fcsseldorf. Thus the primary rationale for code sharing is to expand one's service offerings in city-pair terms to increase sales.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nA more recent development is the [[airline alliance]], which became prevalent in the late 1990s. These alliances can act as virtual mergers to get around government restrictions. The largest are [[Star Alliance]], [[SkyTeam]] and [[Oneworld]], and these accounted for over 60% of global commercial air traffic {{As of|2015||df=|lc=y}}.<ref name=\":7\" /> Alliances of airlines coordinate their passenger service programs (such as [[Airport lounge|lounges]] and [[frequent-flyer program]]s), offer special [[Interlining|interline]] tickets and often engage in extensive [[codesharing]] (sometimes systemwide). These are increasingly integrated business combinations\u2014sometimes including cross-equity arrangements\u2014in which products, service standards, schedules, and airport facilities are standardized and combined for higher efficiency. One of the first airlines to start an alliance with another airline was [[KLM]], who partnered with [[Northwest Airlines]]. Both airlines later entered the SkyTeam alliance after the [[Air France-KLM|fusion of KLM and Air France]] in 2004.\n\nOften the companies combine [[Information technology|IT]] operations, or purchase fuel and aircraft as a bloc to achieve higher bargaining power. However, the alliances have been most successful at purchasing invisible supplies and services, such as fuel. Airlines usually prefer to purchase items visible to their passengers to differentiate themselves from local competitors. If an airline's main domestic competitor flies Boeing airliners, then the airline may prefer to use Airbus aircraft regardless of what the rest of the alliance chooses.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Fuel hedging===\n{{Main|Fuel Hedging}}Fuel hedging is a [[contractual]] tool used by transportation companies like airlines to reduce their exposure to volatile and potentially rising fuel costs. Several low-cost carriers such as Southwest Airlines adopt this practice.<ref name = economist>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/gulliver/2015/01/fuel-hedging-and-airlines|title=Gambles that haven't paid off|newspaper=The Economist|issn=0013-0613|access-date= | language =en}}</ref>\n\nSouthwest is credited with maintaining strong business profits between 1999 and the early 2000s due to its fuel hedging policy. Many other airlines are replicating Southwest's hedging policy to control their fuel costs.<ref name = economist/>\n\n=== Seasonality ===\nAirlines often have a strong [[seasonality]], with traffic low in [[Winter]] and peaking in [[Summer]]. In Europe the most extreme market are the [[Greek islands]] with July/August having more than ten times the winter traffic, as [[Jet2]] is the most seasonal among [[low-cost carrier]]s with July having seven times the January traffic, whereas [[legacy carrier]]s are much less with only 85/115% variability.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.anna.aero/2017/03/01/greek-islands-jet2-com-seasonality-losers-europe/ |title= Seasonality: Jet2.com and Greek Islands most extreme in anna.aero leisure-legacy comparison |work= Airline Network News and Analysis |date= 1 Mar 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Environmental impacts==\n{{Main|Environmental impact of aviation}}\n[[File:Contrails southeast lrg.png|thumb|[[Moderate-Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer|MODIS]] tracking of [[contrail]]s generated by air traffic over the southeastern United States on January 29, 2004.]]\n\nAircraft engines emit [[noise pollution]], gases and particulate emissions, and contribute to [[global dimming]].<ref name=contrails>{{cite journal|title=Contrails reduce daily temperature range |first=David J. |last=Travis |author2=Carleton, Andrew M. |author3=Lauritsen, Ryan G |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |page=601 |volume=418 |year=2002 |url=http://facstaff.uww.edu/travisd/pdf/jetcontrailsrecentresearch.pdf |doi=10.1038/418601a |format=PDF |pmid=12167846 |issue=6898 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060503192714/http://facstaff.uww.edu/travisd/pdf/jetcontrailsrecentresearch.pdf |archivedate=2006-05-03 |bibcode=2002Natur.418..601T }}</ref>\n\nGrowth of the industry in recent years raised a number of ecological questions.\n\nDomestic air transport grew in China at 15.5 percent annually from 2001 to 2006. The rate of air travel globally increased at 3.7 percent per year over the same time. In the EU [[greenhouse gas]] emissions from aviation increased by 87% between 1990 and 2006.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Climate change: Commission proposes bringing air transport into EU Emissions Trading Scheme |publisher=EU press release |date=2006-12-20 |url=http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=IP/06/1862 |accessdate=2008-01-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080112155545/http://www.europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=IP%2F06%2F1862 |archivedate=12 January 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> However it must be compared with the flights increase, only in UK, between 1990 and 2006 terminal passengers increased from 100 000 thousands to 250 000 thousands.,<ref>http://www.parliament.uk/briefing-papers/SN03760.pdf</ref> according to AEA reports every year, 750 million passengers travel by European airlines, which also share 40% of merchandise value in and out of Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aea.be/about/airtransportineurope/index.html |title=About Us \u00bb Air Transport in Europe |accessdate=2014-01-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130724203254/http://www.aea.be/about/airtransportineurope/index.html |archivedate=2013-07-24 }}</ref> Without even pressure from \"green activists\", targeting lower ticket prices, generally, airlines do what is possible to cut the fuel consumption (and gas emissions connected therewith). Further, according to some reports, it can be concluded that the last piston-powered aircraft were as fuel-efficient as the average jet in 2005.<ref>http://www.transportenvironment.org/sites/default/files//docs/Publications/2005pubs/2005-12_nlr_aviation_fuel_efficiency.pdf</ref>\n\nDespite continuing efficiency improvements from the major aircraft manufacturers, the expanding demand for global air travel has resulted in growing greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions. Currently, the aviation sector, including US domestic and global international travel, make approximately 1.6 percent of global anthropogenic GHG emissions per annum. North America accounts for nearly 40 percent of the world's GHG emissions from aviation fuel use.<ref>David McCollum, Gregory Gould, and David Greene. Greenhouse Gas Emissions from Aviation and Marine Transportation: Mitigation Potential and Policies, 2009.</ref>\n\nCO2 emissions from the [[jet fuel]] burned per passenger on an average {{convert|3200|km|mi|sp=us}} airline flight is about 353 kilograms (776&nbsp;pounds).<ref>{{cite web|title=carbon-footprint-calculator |url=http://www.terrapass.com/carbon-footprint-calculator/methodology-popup.html |publisher=TerraPass.com |accessdate=Feb 19, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090131210919/http://www.terrapass.com/carbon-footprint-calculator/methodology-popup.html |archivedate=2009-01-31 }}</ref> Loss of natural habitat potential associated with the jet fuel burned per passenger on a {{convert|3200|km|mi|sp=us}} airline flight is estimated to be 250 square meters (2700 square feet).<ref>{{cite web|title=environmental impact of airline flights|url=http://xoearth.org/ecofx-airline-flights/|publisher=ecofx.org|accessdate=Apr 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the context of climate change and [[peak oil]], there is a debate about possible [[taxation]] of air travel and the inclusion of aviation in an [[emissions trading]] scheme, with a view to ensuring that the total [[external costs]] of aviation are taken into account.<ref>[http://www.defra.gov.uk/environment/climatechange/trading/eu/pdf/including-aviation-icf.pdf Including Aviation into the EU ETS: Impact on EU allowance prices] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060215004933/http://www.defra.gov.uk/environment/climatechange/trading/eu/pdf/including-aviation-icf.pdf |date=February 15, 2006 }} ICF Consulting for DEFRA February 2006</ref>\n\nThe airline industry is responsible for about 11 percent of [[greenhouse gas]]es emitted by the U.S. transportation sector. [[Boeing]] estimates that [[biofuel]]s could reduce flight-related greenhouse-gas emissions by 60 to 80 percent. The solution would be blending algae fuels with existing jet fuel:<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/01/03/AR2008010303907.html | work=The Washington Post | title=A Promising Oil Alternative: Algae Energy | date=January 6, 2008 | accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n* Boeing and [[Air New Zealand]] are collaborating with leading Brazilian biofuel maker [[Tecbio]], [[New Zealand]]'s [[Aquaflow Bionomic]] and other jet biofuel developers around the world.\n* [[Virgin Atlantic]] and [[Virgin Green Fund]] are looking into the technology as part of a biofuel initiative.<ref>{{cite web|author=\u00c1ngel Gonz\u00e1lez |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/boeingaerospace/2003858756_boeingenergy30.html |title=To go green in jet fuel, Boeing looks at algae|work = Seattle Times Newspaper |date=2007-08-30 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n* [[KLM]] has made the first commercial flight with biofuel in 2009.\n\nThere are projects on [[electric aircraft]], and some of them are fully operational as of 2013.\n\n==Call signs==\n{{Unreferenced|section|date=January 2020}}\nEach operator of a scheduled or charter flight uses an [[Airline codes|airline call sign]] when communicating with airports or air traffic control centres. Most of these call-signs are derived from the airline's trade name, but for reasons of history, marketing, or the need to reduce ambiguity in spoken English (so that pilots do not mistakenly make navigational decisions based on instructions issued to a different aircraft), some airlines and air forces use call-signs less obviously connected with their trading name. For example, British Airways uses a ''Speedbird'' call-sign, named after the logo of one of its predecessors, [[British Overseas Airways Corporation|BOAC]], while [[SkyEurope]] used ''Relax''.\n\n==Airline personnel==\n\n[[File:787 Dreamliner cabin crew and pilots (10167536115).jpg|thumb|The [[aircrew]] of a [[Jetstar Airways]] Boeing 787]]\n\nThe various types of airline personnel include:\n* [[Flight crew]], responsible for the operation of the aircraft. Flight crew members include:\n** [[Aviator|Pilots]] ([[Pilot in command|Captain]] and [[First officer (civil aviation)|First Officer]]: some older aircraft also required a [[Flight Engineer]] and/or a [[Navigator]])\n** [[Flight attendant]]s (led by a [[purser]] on larger aircraft)\n** [[Sky marshal|In-flight security personnel]] on some airlines (most notably [[El Al]])\n* [[Groundcrew]], responsible for operations at airports. Ground crew members include:\n** Aerospace and avionics engineers responsible for certifying the aircraft for flight and management of aircraft maintenance\n*** [[Aerospace]] engineers, responsible for airframe, powerplant and electrical systems maintenance\n*** [[Avionics]] engineers responsible for avionics and instruments maintenance\n** [[Airframe]] and [[Aircraft engine|powerplant]] technicians\n** Electric System technicians, responsible for maintenance of electrical systems\n** [[Flight dispatcher]]s\n** [[Baggage handler]]s\n** Ramp Agents\n** Remote centralised weight and balancing<ref>http://www.globalloadcontrol.com</ref>\n** [[Gate agent]]s\n** Ticket agents\n** Passenger service agents (such as [[airline lounge]] employees)\n** Reservation agents, usually (but not always) at facilities outside the airport.\n** Crew schedulers\n** \nAirlines follow a [[corporation|corporate]] structure where each broad area of operations (such as maintenance, flight operations (including flight safety), and passenger service) is supervised by a vice president. Larger airlines often appoint vice presidents to oversee each of the airline's hubs as well. Airlines employ [[lawyers]] to deal with regulatory procedures and other administrative tasks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hklaw.com/practices/aviation-regulation/|title=Aviation Regulation|website=www.hklaw.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>\n\n==Industry trends==\n[[File:World-airline-routemap-2009.png|thumb|Map of scheduled airline traffic in 2009]]\n[[File:011 Aircraft of various airlines together at Narita Airport, Japan. Swiss Air Lines, United Airlines, Thai Airways.JPG|thumb|Aircraft of various airlines parked side by side at Tokyo Narita Airport, Japan]]\n\nThe pattern of ownership has been privatized since the mid-1980s, that is, the ownership has gradually changed from governments to private and individual sectors or organizations. This occurs as regulators permit greater freedom and non-government ownership, in steps that are usually decades apart. This pattern is not seen for all airlines in all regions.<ref>{{cite web|title=List of Government-owned and Privatized Airlines (unofficial preliminary compilation) |publisher = [[International Civil Aviation Organization|ICAO]] |url = https://www.icao.int/sustainability/Documents/PrivatizedAirlines.pdf|date = 4 July 2008}}</ref> Many major airlines operating between the 1940s and 1980s were government-owned or government-established. However, most airlines from the earliest days of air travel in the 1920s and 1930s were personal businesses.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nGrowth rates are not consistent in all regions, but countries with a de-regulated airline industry have more competition and greater pricing freedom. This results in lower fares and sometimes dramatic spurts in traffic growth. The U.S., Australia, Canada, [[Japan]], [[Brazil]], [[India]] and other markets exhibit this trend. The industry has been observed to be cyclical in its financial performance. Four or five years of poor earnings precede five or six years of improvement. But profitability even in the good years is generally low, in the range of 2\u20133% net profit after interest and tax. In times of profit, airlines lease new generations of airplanes and upgrade services in response to higher demand. Since 1980, the industry has not earned back the cost of capital during the best of times. Conversely, in bad times losses can be dramatically worse. [[Warren Buffett]] in 1999 said \"the money that had been made since the dawn of aviation by all of this country's airline companies was zero. Absolutely zero.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadiancapitalist.com/buffetts-spot-on-advice/ |title=Buffett\u2019s spot-on advice |publisher=Money Sense |date= |accessdate=2008-10-20}}</ref>\n\nAs in many mature industries, consolidation is a trend. Airline groupings may consist of limited bilateral partnerships, long-term, multi-faceted alliances between carriers, equity arrangements, [[Mergers and acquisitions|mergers]], or [[takeover]]s.<ref name=\":6\" /> Since governments often restrict ownership and merger between companies in different countries, most consolidation takes place within a country. In the U.S., over 200 airlines have merged, been taken over, or gone out of business since the [[Airline Deregulation Act]] in 1978. Many international airline managers are lobbying their governments to permit greater consolidation to achieve higher economy and efficiency.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=18em|\n* [[Air charter]]\n* [[Air ferry]]\n* [[Airline alliance]]\n* [[Airline complaints]]\n* [[Airline timetable]]\n* [[Airliners.net]]\n* [[Airlines of Africa]]\n* [[Airport security]]\n* [[Aviation safety]]\n* [[Freedoms of the air#Beyond rights|Beyond rights]]\n* [[Cargo airline]]\n* [[Domestic flight]]\n* [[Environmental impact of aviation]]\n* [[Federal Aviation Administration]]\n* [[Flight length]]\n* [[Flight planning]]\n* [[FlightAware]]\n* [[Government contract flight]]\n* [[Hypermobility (travel)|Hyper-mobile travel]]\n* [[Inflight magazine]]\n* [[International Air Transport Association]]\n* [[International flight]]\n* [[Legacy carrier]]\n* [[Low-cost carrier]]\n* [[Red-eye flight]]\n* [[Regional airline]]\n* [[Transportation Security Administration]]\n* [[World's busiest passenger air routes]]\n}}\n\n===Airline related lists===\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=18em|\n* [[Airline codes]]\n* [[Airline liveries and logos]]\n* [[List of airlines]]\n* [[List of accidents and incidents involving commercial aircraft]]\n* [[List of airline holding companies]]\n* [[List of airline mergers and acquisitions]]\n* [[List of defunct airlines]]\n* [[List of helicopter airlines]]\n* [[List of hub airports]]\n* [[List of low-cost airlines]]\n* [[Flag carrier|List of national airlines]]\n* [[List of regional airlines]]\n* [[Airline bankruptcies in the United States]]\n* [[World's largest airlines]]\n}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n# \"A history of the world's airlines\", [[R. E. G. Davies|R.E.G. Davies]], Oxford U.P, 1964\n# \"The airline encyclopedia, 1909\u20132000.\u201d Myron J. Smith, Scarecrow Press, 2002\n# \"Flying Off Course: The Economics of International Airlines,\" 3rd edition. Rigas Doganis, Routledge, New York, 2002.\n# \"The Airline Business in the 21st Century.\" Rigas Doganis, Routledge, New York, 2001.\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130809141040/http://www.pbs.org/kcet/chasingthesun/ |title= Chasing the Sun |quote= \"History of commercial aviation\" |publisher= [[PBS]]}}\n* {{cite web |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070616175821/http://www.zinnov.com/presentation/Global_Aviation-Markets-An_Ananlysis.pdf |title= Global Aviation Markets - Analysis |publisher= [[Zinnov LLC]] |date= Jan 2007}} \n* {{cite web |url= https://www.iata.org/whatwedo/Documents/economics/airline_cost_performance.pdf |title= Airline Cost Performance |publisher= IATA |date= July 2006 }}\n* {{cite web |title= Airline industry |work= [[Encyclopedia.com]] |date= 2005 |url= https://www.encyclopedia.com/social-sciences-and-law/economics-business-and-labor/businesses-and-occupations/airline-industry}}\n\n{{Commons category|Airlines|position=left}}\n\n{{Commercial air travel}}\n{{Portal bar|Aviation}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Airlines| ]]\n[[Category:Economics of transport and utility industries]]\n[[Category:Aviation industry]]\n", "name_user": "Thaddeus Ballantine", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Airline"}
{"title_page": "Alex Gordon", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name        = Alex Gordon\n|image       = Alex Gordon listens to reporters on -WSMediaDay (22888475465).jpg\n|image_size  = 250\n|team        = Kansas City Royals\n|number      = 4\n|position    = [[Outfielder]]\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1984|2|10}}\n|birth_place = [[Lincoln, Nebraska]]\n|bats        = Left\n|throws      = Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate   = April 2\n|debutyear   = 2007\n|debutteam   = Kansas City Royals\n|statleague  = MLB\n|statyear    = 2019 season\n|stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value  = .258\n|stat2label  = [[Home run]]s\n|stat2value  = 186\n|stat3label  = [[Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value  = 738\n|stat4label  = [[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n|stat4value  = 1,608\n|teams       = \n* [[Kansas City Royals]] ({{mlby|2007}}\u2013present)\n|awards     = \n* 3\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2013]]\u2013[[2015 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2015]])\n* [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|2015}})\n* 7\u00d7 [[Gold Glove Award]] (2011\u20132014, 2017\u20132019)\n* 2014 [[Platinum Glove Award]]\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{bb|USA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World University Baseball Championship|World University Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[World University Baseball Championship|2004 Tainan]] | [[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Alexander Jonathan Gordon''' (born February 10, 1984) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[left fielder]] for the [[Kansas City Royals]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). Prior to playing professionally, Gordon attended the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln]], where he played [[college baseball]] for the [[Nebraska Cornhuskers baseball|Nebraska Cornhuskers]].\n\nAt Nebraska, Gordon won the [[Brooks Wallace Award]], [[Dick Howser Trophy]], and [[Golden Spikes Award]] in 2005. That year, the Royals selected Gordon with the second overall pick in the [[2005 MLB Draft]]. Gordon made his major league debut at a [[third baseman]], but had an inconsistent beginning to his career.  In 2010, the Royals made Gordon an [[outfielder]].  Gordon was a member of the Royals' [[2015 World Series]] championship team, and signed a [[free agent]] contract that offseason to remain with the team. Gordon has won seven [[Gold Glove Award]]s, four [[Fielding Bible Award]]s, and a [[Wilson Defensive Player of the Year Award]] in MLB, all after the move to the outfield.\n\n==Early life==\nGordon was born on February 10, 1984 to a family heavily involved in baseball. Gordon's father had played baseball for the [[University of Nebraska]], and his brother played college baseball at the [[University of Nebraska-Omaha]].  Gordon had a successful high school baseball career at [[Lincoln Southeast High School]], where he was named the Gatorade Nebraska Player of the Year in 2002.  Gordon was also listed as one of the top high school prospects by ''[[Baseball America]]'' his senior year, and also received All-State honors in football that same year.<ref name=\"huskers bio\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon |url=https://huskers.com/sports/baseball/roster/alex-gordon/6966 |publisher=Nebraska Huskers |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring his teen years, Gordon played [[American Legion Baseball]].  He won the organization's Graduate of the Year award in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.legion.org/baseball/awards/graduate\n| title = Graduate of the Year \n| publisher = The American Legion\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160305040326/http://www.legion.org/baseball/awards/graduate\n| archive-date = March 5, 2016\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nGordon attended the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln]] and played third base.  At Nebraska, Gordon majored in criminal justice.<ref name=\"huskers bio\" /> In his junior year in 2005, he swept the collegiate baseball awards for college player of the year, winning the [[Dick Howser Trophy]], [[Golden Spikes Award]], the [[Brooks Wallace Award]], and the [[American Baseball Coaches Association]] Rawlings Player of the Year.<ref name=\"huskers bio\" /> He was also an ESPY Award Finalist for the Best Male College Athlete.<ref name=\"nebraska greatest\" /> Over the course of his collegiate career, he posted a .355 career [[batting average]], with 44 [[home runs]] and 189 [[runs batted in]] (RBI)s and finished in the top ten in eight different offensive statistical categories at Nebraksa.  Gordon was also a two-time [[Big 12 Conference]] Player of the Year Award recipient.<ref name=\"huskers bio\" />\n\n==U.S. National Team==\nDuring his time at the University of Nebraska, Gordon was a member of the 2004 [[United States National Baseball Team]], which included players from 15 different colleges.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gordon Named to USA Baseball Team |url=https://huskers.com/news/2004/6/29/65921.aspx |publisher=Nebraska Huskers Baseball |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=29 June 2004 }}</ref>  He helped lead Team USA to an 18\u20137 overall record, seeing the majority of his playing time at [[first base]]. He hit .388 with four home runs, 12 RBI and 18 [[Run (baseball)|runs]] scored in 24 contests and was named the top offensive player at the [[World University Baseball Championship]] in [[Tainan, Taiwan]] after leading all players with a .524 average (11-for-21) with two home runs, five RBI, and eight [[runs scored]] in eight games.<ref>{{cite web |title=Team USA Wins Gold at World University Baseball Championship |url=https://huskers.com/news/2004/8/1/67795.aspx |publisher=Nebraska Huskers Baseball |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=1 August 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Draft and minors==\n\nGordon was [[2005 Major League Baseball Draft|drafted in 2005]] by the [[Kansas City Royals]] with the second pick overall, becoming the highest draft pick out of Nebraska since [[Darin Erstad]] was selected with the first pick of the [[1995 MLB draft]]. He hit 29 home runs and stole 22 bases with an OPS over 1.000 in his first full season in [[minor league baseball]] with the [[Double-A (baseball)|Double-A]] [[Wichita Wranglers]]. By midseason, Gordon was receiving accolades for being one of the best hitting prospects in baseball.  He participated in the [[Texas League]] All-Star game and was selected for the [[All-Star Futures Game|2006 All-Star Futures Game]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Gordon Selected for All-Star Futures Game |url=https://huskers.com/news/2006/6/22/301134.aspx |publisher=Nebraska Huskers Baseball |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=22 June 2006}}</ref> Declining to play for Team USA in 2006, Gordon led the Wichita Wranglers to the Texas League playoffs. He performed well in his first full minor league season, and won the Texas League Player of the Year<ref name=\"texas league awards\">{{cite web |title=Texas League Awards |url=https://www.milb.com/texas/history/award-winners |publisher=milb.com |accessdate=21 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927170453/https://www.milb.com/texas/history/award-winners |archive-date=September 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and ''Baseball America's'' Minor League Player of the Year awards after the season ended.<ref name=\"mlpya\" />\n\n==Kansas City Royals==\n\n===Third base: 2007\u201309===\n\nIn his first major league [[at-bat]], Gordon struck out with the bases loaded against [[Curt Schilling]]<ref name=\"robbins 2011\">{{cite web |last1=Robbins |first1=Bill |title=Alex Gordon Has Come Full Circle in 2011 |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/837428 |publisher=Bleacher Report |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> but eventually got his first major league [[Hit (baseball)|hit]] on April 5, 2007, against the [[2007 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Grein-K, Royals edged out |last=Eskew |first=Alan |date=5 April 2007 |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20070405&content_id=1881141&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=home |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> On April 10, 2007, he hit his first major league home run off [[pitcher]] [[Josh Towers]] of the [[2007 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Gordon, Greinke Lead KC |date=10 April 2007 |last=Peak |first=John |url=http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20070410&content_id=1890794&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=away |publisher=Seattle Mariners |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDespite Gordon hitting .185 with three home runs and eight RBI through his first two months as an everyday starter.<ref name=\"broken nose\">{{cite web |last1=Mass |first1=AJ |title=Is It Time to Give Up on Alex Gordon |url=https://www.espn.in/fantasy/baseball/flb/story?page=mlbdk2k1030qroyals |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>, the Royals remained patient with him.<ref>[http://sandiego.padres.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070531&content_id=1996996&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc Royals Stay Patient with Gordon] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527160729/http://sandiego.padres.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070531&content_id=1996996&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |date=May 27, 2011 }}, Nicholl, Conor (31 May 2007), San Diego Padres.</ref> Gordon performed better for the rest of the season, but broke his nose in the last game of the season.<ref name=\"broken nose\" />\n\nOn September 2, Gordon had the first multi-home run game of his career, connecting off [[Boof Bonser]] of the [[Minnesota Twins]] in the second inning, and in the 3rd inning off [[Julio DePaula]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Kansas City Royals at Minnesota Twins |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/MIN/MIN200709020.shtml |publisher=Baseball-Reference |accessdate=23 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224053429/https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/MIN/MIN200709020.shtml |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On September 12, Gordon hit his 34th double of the year against the [[2007 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]], establishing a Royals rookie record.<ref>{{cite web |title=Meche, Royals End Lengthy Skids in Win Over Twins |author=The Associated Press|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/mlb/recap?gameId=270912107 |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Alex_Gordon.JPG|right|120px|thumb|Gordon before a game against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] during the [[2008 Kansas City Royals season|2008 season]]]]\n\nBefore the 2008 season, Gordon switched his uniform number from #7, the number he had as a rookie, to #4, his college number.<ref name=\"powder blues\">Kaegel, Dick.[http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071207&content_id=2320779&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc Royals to bring back powder blues] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080629032831/http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071207&content_id=2320779&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |date=June 29, 2008 }} Kansas City Royals, December 6, 2007.</ref> On [[Opening Day]], 2008 (which occurred on March 31) Gordon hit a two-run home run off [[Detroit Tigers]] [[Ace (baseball)|ace]] [[Justin Verlander]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Royals at Tigers Box Score 3-31-2008 |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/DET/DET200803310.shtml |publisher=Baseball-Reference |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Royals placed Gordon on the 15-day [[disabled list]] on August 23 because of a torn muscle in his right quadriceps.<ref name=\"broken nose\" /> Gordon finished the season with a .260 batting average and 16 home runs and led the Royals with 66 [[base on balls|walks]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2008 Kansas City Royals Stats |url=http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/stats/sortable.jsp?c_id=kc#elem=%5Bobject+Object%5D&tab_level=child&click_text=Sortable+Player+hitting&game_type='R'&season=2008&season_type=ANY&league_code='MLB'&sectionType=sp&statType=hitting&page=1&ts=1583174754061&playerType=ALL&sportCode='mlb'&split=&team_id=118&active_sw=&position=&page_type=SortablePlayer&sortOrder='desc'&sortColumn=bb&results=&perPage=50&timeframe=&last_x_days=&extended=0 |publisher=Kansas City Royals |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nGordon made the most [[Error (baseball)|errors]] (16) and had the lowest [[fielding percentage]] (.955) of all [[American League]] (AL) third basemen in 2008.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/stats/fielding?groupId=9&season=2008&seasonType=2&split=81&sortColumn=errors MLB Player Fielding Stats: 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026072553/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/stats/fielding?groupId=9&season=2008&seasonType=2&split=81&sortColumn=errors |date=October 26, 2012 }}, [[ESPN]].</ref>\n\nGordon struggled at the beginning of the 2009 season, hitting just 2-for-21 (.095) with one home run and three RBIs in seven games before being injured while sliding.<ref name=\"broken nose\" /> He underwent surgery on April 17 to repair a tear in the labral cartilage of the right hip, and was on the disabled list for twelve weeks.<ref>[http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090417&content_id=4312206&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc Alex out until at least late June] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314145444/http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090417&content_id=4312206&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |date=March 14, 2012 }}, [[Kansas City Royals]]. Published April 17, 2009. Retrieved April 22, 2009.</ref> After playing a few games in the minors, Gordon came off the disabled list and rejoined the Royals on July 17 going 1 for 4 against the [[Tampa Bay Rays]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Dick Kaegel |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090716&content_id=5896282&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |title=Betancourt, Gordon coming off DL |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103043119/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090716&content_id=5896282&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |archive-date=November 3, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Dick Kaegel |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090721&content_id=5977490&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Good signs from Gordon following surgery |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103043133/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090721&content_id=5977490&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |archive-date=November 3, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Gordon [[stolen base|stole home]] for the first time in his career on August 2 against the Rays, becoming the first Royal to do that since [[Mendy Lopez]] in [[2003 Kansas City Royals season|2003]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Dick Kaegel |date=2 August 2009|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090802&content_id=6205200&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |title=Royals escape no-no, win for Bannister |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103055305/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090802&content_id=6205200&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |archive-date=November 3, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Royals optioned Gordon to the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] [[Omaha Royals]] on August 18.<ref>{{cite web |title=August 18, 2009 MLB Trades and Transactions |url=http://proxy.espn.com/mlb/transactions?date=20090818 |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> After Omaha finished up its season, Gordon returned to the Royals in September.<ref>{{cite web |author=Jesse Temple |url=http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090818&content_id=6484002&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |title=Royals option Gordon to Triple-A Omaha |publisher=Kansas City Royals |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329132135/http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090818&content_id=6484002&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |archive-date=March 29, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Move to outfield: 2010\u201313===\n\nGordon began the 2010 season on a minor league rehab assignment with Class-A Advanced [[Wilmington Blue Rocks|Wilmington]], following a broken thumb suffered in [[Spring Training]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Dick Kaegel |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100406&content_id=9103930&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Gordon set for rehab assignment|publisher=Major League Baseball |date=January 1, 2011 |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605115309/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100406&content_id=9103930&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |archive-date=June 5, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Gordon was activated from the disabled list on April 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100417&content_id=9366844&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Royals' Gordon activated from disabled list|accessdate=April 17, 2010|last=Kaegel |first=Dick |date=April 17, 2010 |publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100420142146/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100417&content_id=9366844&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate= April 20, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>  He was demoted to the minor leagues in May, where he played left field.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2010/05/royals-demote-3b-draft-bust-gordon-to-minors-switch-to-left-field/1 | work=USA Today | title=Royals demote draft-bust Gordon to minors; switch from 3B to left field | date=May 3, 2010 | access-date=May 20, 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100526161229/http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2010/05/royals-demote-3b-draft-bust-gordon-to-minors-switch-to-left-field/1 | archive-date=May 26, 2010 | url-status=live }}</ref>  Gordon was recalled from Triple-A on July 23, 2010, to take the place of [[David DeJesus]] in the Royals' outfield, who was placed on the disabled list with a right thumb sprain.<ref>{{cite web |author=Alden Gonzalez |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100723&content_id=12543426&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Gordon recalled; DeJesus lands on DL |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104231810/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100723&content_id=12543426&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |archive-date=November 4, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nIn 2010, Gordon officially moved from being a third baseman to playing the outfield.<ref name=\"seven gold gloves\" />\n\nIn Spring Training in 2011, he led the major leagues in RBIs, with 23.<ref>{{cite web |title=2011 MLB Spring Training Stats |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/stats/sortable.jsp?c_id=mlb#playerType=ALL&elem=%5Bobject+Object%5D&tab_level=child&click_text=Sortable+Player+hitting&game_type='S'&season=2011&season_type=ANY&league_code='MLB'&sectionType=sp&statType=hitting&page=1&ts=1585962925182&sportCode='mlb'&split=&team_id=&active_sw=&position=&page_type=SortablePlayer&sortOrder='desc'&sortColumn=rbi&results=&perPage=50&timeframe=&last_x_days=&extended=0 |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> Gordon was selected as an American League finalist for the 2011 [[All-Star Final Vote]], but [[Paul Konerko]] won the vote.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dodd |first1=Mike |title=Paul Konerko, Shane Victorino Win Final Vote for All-Star Game Berths |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2011/07/paul-konerko-shane-victorino-all-star-game/1#.Xl8vvqhKhPY |publisher=USA Today Daily Pitch |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> He was also tied for sixth in the major leagues in doubles, with 45.<ref>{{cite web |title=2011 MLB Doubles Leaders |url=http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/stats/sortable.jsp?c_id=kc#elem=%5Bobject+Object%5D&tab_level=child&click_text=Sortable+Player+hitting&game_type='R'&season=2011&season_type=ANY&league_code='MLB'&sectionType=sp&statType=hitting&page=1&ts=1583296677633&playerType=ALL&sportCode='mlb'&split=&team_id=&active_sw=&position=&page_type=SortablePlayer&sortOrder='desc'&sortColumn=d&results=&perPage=50&timeframe=&last_x_days=&extended=0 |publisher=Kansas City Royals |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, he led all major league outfielders in [[Assist (baseball)|assists]], with 20<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2011-fielding-leaders.shtml |title=2011 Major League Baseball Fielding Leaders |publisher=Baseball-Reference |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111113162818/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2011-fielding-leaders.shtml |archive-date=November 13, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> and won his first American League [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove Award]].<ref name=\"seven gold gloves\" />  His success during Spring Training carried over into the regular season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robbins |first1=Bill |title=Kansas City Royals: The Real Alex Gordon Has Arrived |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/672906-kansas-city-royals-the-real-alex-gordon-has-finally-arrived |publisher=Bleacher Report |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=April 21, 2011}}</ref>  Gordon's 20 outfield assists also set a Royals franchise record.<ref>{{cite web |title=Royals Resign OF Gordon to 4-year, $37.5 Million Deal |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/ct-xpm-2012-03-30-chi-gordon-story.html |publisher=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 9, 2012, Gordon signed a one-year, $4.775 million deal with the Royals to avoid arbitration. In the process, Gordon filed for $5.45, while the Royals countered with $4.15. Under that agreement, he could have earned an additional $25K if he had reached 700 plate appearances, putting him at the original midpoint.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2012/02/royals-avoid-arbitration-with-alex-gordon.html |title=Royals Avoid Arbitration With Alex Gordon |work=MLB Trade Rumors |first=Mike |last=Axisa |date=February 9, 2012 |access-date=February 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212020358/http://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2012/02/royals-avoid-arbitration-with-alex-gordon.html |archive-date=February 12, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, on March 30, he signed a four-year, $37.5 million extension with the Royals with a player option for 2016, becoming the third Royal player to sign an extension in the off season. Gordon earned $6 million in 2012, $9 million in 2013, $10 million in 2014 and $12.5 million in 2015, but declined to exercise his player option of $12.5 million for 2016. Gordon would otherwise have become a free agent after 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2012/03/royals-alex-gordon-agree-to-extension.html |title=Royals, Alex Gordon Agree To Extension |work=MLB Trade Rumors |first=Zach |last=Links |date=March 30, 2012 |access-date=March 30, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331205147/http://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2012/03/royals-alex-gordon-agree-to-extension.html |archive-date=March 31, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Gordon won a [[Fielding Bible Award]] as the best fielding left fielder in MLB. He also won the Gold Glove Award.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 2012 Awards |date=October 25, 2012 |url=http://www.actasports.com/stats_detail/?StatId=345 |publisher=ACTA Sports |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BhthK48v?url=http://www.actasports.com/stats_detail/?StatId=345 |archivedate=October 26, 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nGordon finished the 2012 season with a .294 batting average and led the majors with 51 doubles.<ref name=\"bill james\" />\n\nGordon again performed well in 2013. He finished with the season with 90 runs scored, 168 hits, 27 doubles, six [[Triple (baseball)|triples]], 20 home runs, 81 RBIs, and a .265 batting average.<ref name=\"bill james\" /> He earned his third consecutive Gold Glove Award for his defense in left field<ref name=\"fielding bible\" /> and earned his first career All-Star selection.<ref name=\"capitol-journal\">{{cite web |last1=Fertig |first1=Todd |title=Royals Rundown |url=https://www.cjonline.com/sports/20190706/royals-rundown-seeing-only-one-star-kc-faces-looming-decision-on-alex-gordon |publisher=Topeka Capitol-Journal |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Playoff appearances: 2014\u201315===\n\nIn the 2014 season, Gordon scored 87 runs, had 150 hits, 34 doubles, one triple, 19 home runs, 74 RBI, 12 stolen bases, and a .266 BA.<ref name=\"ESPN\" /> On July 6, 2014, he was named to the 2014 All-Star Team for the second consecutive year.  On August 6, he recorded his 1,000th career hit when he [[Single (baseball)|singled]] off [[2014 Arizona Diamondbacks season|Arizona Diamondbacks]] pitcher [[Wade Miley]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCullough |first1=Andy |title=Alex Gordon Thrilled to Record 1,000 Hits |url=https://www.kansascity.com/opinion/article1137464.html |publisher=The Kansas City Star |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> On August 26, he tied [[Wade Boggs]] for the most home runs hit by a Nebraskan in the Major Leagues.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bruntz |first1=Michael |title=Gordon Hits Walk-Off Winner for KC |url=https://247sports.com/college/nebraska/Article/Gordon-hits-walk-off-winner-for-KC-30598750/ |publisher=24/7 Sports |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Royals qualified for the 2014 postseason.  Gordon mostly struggled during the playoffs, although he did hit a home run in the 10th inning of Game 1 of the [[2014 American League Championship Series|AL Championship Series]] against the [[2014 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Postseason History \u2013 2014 ALCS |url=http://m.mlb.com/postseason/history/2014/alcs/ |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> He represented the tying run in the 9th inning of Game 7 of the [[2014 World Series]], when with two outs, he lined a long single to left center.  He reached third base when Giants' center fielder [[Gregor Blanco]] misplayed the ball, but was stranded when catcher [[Salvador P\u00e9rez]] fouled out to [[Pablo Sandoval]] to end the game and the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=341029107|title=Madison Bumgarner, Giants hold off Royals to win World Series|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=January 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116005620/http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=341029107|archive-date=January 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[2014 Major League Baseball season#Postseason|2014 postseason]], Gordon batted just .204, including six doubles, four stolen bases, and one home run.<ref>{{cite web |title=2014 Postseason Stats \u2013 Kansas City Royals |url=http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/stats/sortable.jsp?c_id=kc#elem=%5Bobject+Object%5D&tab_level=child&click_text=Sortable+Player+hitting&game_type='P'&season=2014&season_type=ANY&league_code='MLB'&sectionType=sp&statType=hitting&page=1&ts=1583104098248&playerType=ALL&sportCode='mlb'&split=&team_id=118&active_sw=&position=&page_type=SortablePlayer&sortOrder='desc'&sortColumn=avg&results=&perPage=50&timeframe=&last_x_days=&extended=0 |publisher=Kansas City Royals |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn July 8, 2015, against the Tampa Bay Rays, Gordon was injured attempting to chase down a fly ball hit by [[Logan Forsythe]], which resulted in an [[inside-the-park home run]] as Gordon could not get back up.  After being carted off the field, he was diagnosed with a left groin strain was and placed on the 15-Day [[disabled list]] (DL).<ref>{{cite web |title=Royals All-Star Alex Gordon Could Miss Eight Weeks With Groin Strain |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/07/09/kansas-city-royals-alex-gordon-injury-groin-strain |publisher=Sports Illustrated |date=8 July 2015|accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref>  Gordon had just come off a 7-hit double header the night before against the Rays (tying the Royals record for most hits in a double header) in which he hit a double and a home run.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brzezinski |first1=Alex |title=Alex Gordon Collects 7 Hits, 6 RBIs in Doubleheader Sweep of Rays |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/mlb/news/mlb-nightly-9-alex-gordon-collects-7-hits-6-rbis-in-doubleheader-sweep-against-rays/dk7yfpla4i6y1txeket8cg9zk |publisher=Sporting News |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref>  On September 2, Gordon was activated from the DL and went 2-for-3, with an RBI and run scored against the [[Detroit Tigers]] .<ref>{{Cite web|title = Alex Gordon returns from injury, goes 2-for-3 in Royals\u2019 loss to Tigers |last=Kerkhoff |first=Blair |date=1 September 2015|url = http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article33318009.html |publisher=The Kansas City Star|accessdate = September 8, 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150906024245/http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article33318009.html|archive-date = September 6, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nHe finished the regular season with a .271 batting average/.377 [[on-base percentage]]/.432 [[slugging percentage]] with 18 doubles, 13 home runs, and 48 RBIs.<ref name=\"bill james\">{{cite book |last1=James |first1=Bill |title=The Bill James Handbook 2016 |date=2015 |publisher=Acta Sports |location=Chicago |isbn=978-0-87946-545-2 |page=157}}</ref>\n\nThe Royals qualified for the postseason in 2015.  In Game 1 of the [[2015 World Series]], Gordon hit a ninth-inning home run off of [[2015 New York Mets season|New York Mets]] closer [[Jeurys Familia]] to tie the game at 4. The Royals would go on to win, 5\u20134, in 14 innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/gametracker/recap/MLB_20151027_NYM@KC/hosmer-sacrifice-fly-in-14th-lifts-royals-to-ws-game-1-win|title=MLB Recap \u2013 New York Mets at Kansas City Royals \u2013 Oct 27, 2015|date=October 28, 2015|publisher=CBSSports.com|accessdate=January 6, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116005620/http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/gametracker/recap/MLB_20151027_NYM%40KC/hosmer-sacrifice-fly-in-14th-lifts-royals-to-ws-game-1-win|archivedate=January 16, 2016}}</ref> Gordon became a [[List of World Series champions|World Champion]] when the Royals won the World Series in five games over the Mets, the first World Series won by the Royals since 1985. Combined in the postseason, Gordon hit .241 with 2 homers, 6 RBI and a .775 OPS.<ref>{{cite web |title=2015 Postseason Stats \u2013 Kansas City Royals |url=http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/stats/sortable.jsp?c_id=kc#elem=%5Bobject+Object%5D&tab_level=child&click_text=Sortable+Player+hitting&game_type='P'&season=2015&season_type=ANY&league_code='MLB'&sectionType=sp&statType=hitting&page=1&ts=1583104098248&playerType=ALL&sportCode='mlb'&split=&team_id=118&active_sw=&position=&page_type=SortablePlayer&sortOrder='desc'&sortColumn=avg&results=&perPage=50&timeframe=&last_x_days=&extended=0 |publisher=Kansas City Royals |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> Gordon, along with all of the Royals, attended the World Series parade and pep rally in downtown Kansas City, Missouri at [[Union Station (Kansas City, Missouri)|Union Station]] on November 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/kansas-city-royals-world-series-parade-champions-hosmer-perez-moustakas-escobar-zobrist-110315|title=Kansas City Royals fans jam the streets at their World Series parade|publisher=Fox Sports|accessdate=January 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116005619/http://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/kansas-city-royals-world-series-parade-champions-hosmer-perez-moustakas-escobar-zobrist-110315|archive-date=January 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Later career: 2016\u2013present===\nOn January 6, 2016, Gordon signed a four-year deal worth $72 million to remain with the Royals with a mutual option for the 2020 season.<ref>{{cite web|last=Flanagan|first=Jeffrey|title=Gordon returns to fold for Royals|url=http://m.royals.mlb.com/news/article/161154866/alex-gordon-returns-to-royals|publisher=Major League Baseball|date=January 6, 2016|accessdate=January 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109164946/http://m.royals.mlb.com/news/article/161154866/alex-gordon-returns-to-royals|archive-date=January 9, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>  On May 22, 2016, Gordon collided with Royals' third-baseman [[Mike Moustakas]] while chasing a [[Melky Cabrera]] pop-up into foul territory down the left field line against the Chicago White Sox.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dodd|first=Rustin|title=Royals' Alex Gordon has broken bone in wrist, could miss three to four weeks.|url=http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article79381672.html|publisher=The Kansas City Star|date=May 23, 2016|accessdate=May 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921000426/http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article79381672.html|archive-date=September 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Gordon suffered a scaphoid fracture in his right wrist and was placed on the disabled-list where he missed 29 games.<ref>{{cite web|last=Doherty|first=Cole|title=Kansas City Royals: The Return of Alex Gordon|url=http://www.isportsweb.com/2016/06/22/kansas-city-royals-return-alex-gordon/|publisher=isportsweb|date=June 25, 2016|accessdate=May 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920190932/http://www.isportsweb.com/2016/06/22/kansas-city-royals-return-alex-gordon/|archive-date=September 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He finished 2016 hitting .220/.312/.380 with a career high 148 strikeouts in 445 at-bats.<ref name=\"ESPN\" />\n\nOn May 4, 2017, Gordon was [[hit by pitch|hit by a pitch]] from the White Sox's [[Derek Holland]].  This was Gordon's 79th career hit by pitch, setting the Royals' franchise record, previously held by [[Mike Macfarlane]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Dodd|first=Rustin|title=Royals\u2019 Alex Gordon is hit by a pitch for 79th time, breaking all-time franchise record|url=http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article148740239.html|publisher=The Kansas City Star|date=May 4, 2017|accessdate=May 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920190953/http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article148740239.html|archive-date=September 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> When asked about how he was able to be hit by so many pitches, Gordon responded \"[I] don't move.\"  While he stated that he didn't lean in towards the pitch to give himself a better chance of being hit, Gordon did admit that he had done so during his college career.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Flanagan |first1=Jeffrey |title=HBP-Magnet Gordon's Method? Don't Move. |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/alex-gordon-holds-royals-hit-by-pitch-record |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=6 April 2019}}</ref>  On September 19, Gordon hit the 5,694th home run of the [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] season against [[Ryan Tepera]], breaking the record for the most home runs in an MLB season, with the previous record having been set in the [[2000 Major League Baseball season|2000]] season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article174286581.html|title=Watch the Royals\u2019 Alex Gordon hit the record-breaking 5,694th homer of the MLB season|work=The Kansas City Star|access-date=2017-09-22|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922012730/http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article174286581.html|archive-date=September 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> For the season, he batted .208/.293/.315.<ref name=\"ESPN\" /> His .315 slugging percentage in 2017 was the lowest of all qualified major league batters.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=8&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=15,a |title=Major League Leaderboards 2017 |publisher=Fangraphs|access-date=December 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228035207/https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=8&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=15,a |archive-date=December 28, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the offseason before the 2018 season, Gordon was inducted into the Lincoln Southeast High School Athletics Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon Highlights LSE's 2018 Hall Class |url=https://journalstar.com/sports/high-school/baseball/alex-gordon-highlights-lse-s-hall-class/article_2a3720b7-909c-5791-980d-744edabd0ebc.html |publisher=Lincoln Journal Star |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=11 January 2018}}</ref>  In 2018, Gordon hit .245/.324/.370 with 13 home runs and 54 RBIs and won his sixth Gold Glove.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article221127630.html |title=KC Royals Gordon, Perez wins MLB Gold Glove awards<!-- Bot generated title --> |publisher=The Kansas City Star |access-date=November 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108031237/https://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article221127630.html |archive-date=November 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>  On May 8, Gordon collected a season-high four hits, and he drove in five runs on September 15.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon 2018 Batting Game Log |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=gordoal01&t=b&year=2018 |publisher=Baseball-Reference |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Gordon rebounded to hit .266/.345/.396 with 13 home runs and 76 RBIs in his best offensive season since 2015.<ref name=\"ESPN\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon Player Profile |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/player/stats/_/id/28636/alex-gordon |website=ESPN |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=November 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928032049/http://www.espn.com/mlb/player/stats/_/id/28636/alex-gordon |archive-date=September 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Early in April that season, Gordon recorded his first four-hit game since May 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Flanagan |first1=Jeffrey |title=Alex Gordon Honors Friend with Home Run in Six-Run First Inning |url=https://www.mlb.com/royals/news/alex-gordon-s-hr-highlights-six-run-first-inning |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=13 April 2019}}</ref>  In early May, Gordon reached a career total of 1,500 hits.  In the same game, Gordon also hit two home runs off of [[Jake Arrieta]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Flanagan |first1=Jeffrey |title=Gordon Happy to Homer Twice for 1,500 Hits |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/alex-gordon-multi-homer-game-for-royals |date=11 May 2019|publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>  On August 26, Gordon made his first professional pitching appearance, pitching {{frac|1|1|3}} innings in a blowout loss to the [[2019 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland A's]].<ref name=\"pitching\">{{cite web |last1=Flanagan |first1=Jeffrey |title=Gordon Happy to \"Pitch\" in for Royals Bullpen |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/alex-gordon-pitches-in-royals-loss-to-a-s |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214042456/https://www.mlb.com/news/alex-gordon-pitches-in-royals-loss-to-a-s |archive-date=December 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  He also won his seventh career Gold Glove.<ref name=\"Gold Glove Winners 2019\">{{cite web |last1=Casella |first1=Paul |last2=Harrigan |first2=Thomas |last3=Langs |first3=Sarah |title=Gold Glove Awards Handed Out |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/2019-gold-glove-winners |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=7 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105032427/https://www.mlb.com/news/2019-gold-glove-winners |archive-date=November 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn November 2, 2019, Gordon elected free agency.<ref name=\"mlb profile\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon Stats and Transactions |url=https://www.mlb.com/player/alex-gordon-460086 |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=21 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224032430/https://www.mlb.com/player/alex-gordon-460086 |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On January 22, 2020, he signed a one-year, $4 million contract to remain with the Royals for the 2020 season.<ref name=\"2020 contract\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon, Royals agree on deal |url=https://www.mlb.com/royals/news/alex-gordon-royals-deal |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=22 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200121104408/https://www.mlb.com/royals/news/alex-gordon-royals-deal |archive-date=January 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==2006 ''Topps'' baseball card==\nGordon's [[baseball card]] gained notoriety shortly after Gordon was drafted in 2006. ''[[Topps]]'' issued Gordon's [[rookie card]] prematurely, as only players on 25-man rosters or who have played in at least one Major League game are eligible. As a result, ''Topps'' stopped producing the card and cut holes in some of the existing cards. Examples that found their way into retail stores have garnered bids in the thousands of dollars on [[eBay]].<ref name=\"baseball card\">{{cite web |last1=Rovell |first1=Darren |title=This Card Costs 'Cause You Aren't Supposed to Have It |url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/news/story?id=2429888 |website=espn.com |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=23 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105015223/https://www.espn.com/mlb/news/story?id=2429888 |archive-date=November 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n\n===Collegiate career===\nIn 2004, Gordon was named to the First-Team All-Big 12 and was recognized as the Big 12 Player of the Year, both of which Gordon also received in 2005.<ref name=\"baseball cube\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon Awards |url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/profile.asp?ID=54849#Awards |publisher=The Baseball Cube |accessdate=22 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028032837/http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/profile.asp?ID=54849#Awards |archive-date=October 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Gordon won the [[Golden Spikes Award]], [[Dick Howser Trophy]], [[Brooks Wallace Award]], and the ''[[Baseball America]]'' College Player of the Year awards.<ref name=\"almanac\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon |url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/awards.php?p=gordoal01 |publisher=Baseball Almanac |accessdate=22 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912124908/https://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/awards.php?p=gordoal01 |archive-date=September 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Gordon was also a finalist for the ESPY Male College Athlete of the Year Award and was named a first team All-American, the latter of which Gordon was recognized as in 2004.<ref name=\"nebraska greatest\">{{cite web |title=Nebraska's Greatest Athletes: #33 Alex Gordon |url=https://dataomaha.com/neb100/player/33 |website=dataomaha.com |publisher=Omaha World-Herald |accessdate = 4 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Minor leagues===\nIn 2006, Gordon was named the Minor League Player of the Year by ''Baseball America'' and ''Topps''<ref name=\"mlpya\">{{cite web |title=Minor League Player of the Year |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Minor_League_Player_of_the_Year |publisher=Baseball-Reference |accessdate=22 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222153506/https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Minor_League_Player_of_the_Year |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the Texas League Player of the Year.<ref name=\"texas league awards\" />  He also was named the MLB.com Double-A Offensive Player of the Year.<ref name=\"double a\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon Profile |url=http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?sid=t3410&player_id=460086#/career/R/hitting/2019/ALL |publisher=milb.com |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Major leagues===\nOver the course of his career, Gordon has won seven [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award]]s (2011\u201314 and 2017\u201319).<ref name=\"seven gold gloves\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon Wins Seventh Gold Glove |url=https://www.mlb.com/press-release/alex-gordon-wins-seventh-gold-glove |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=22 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222001526/https://www.mlb.com/press-release/alex-gordon-wins-seventh-gold-glove |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Gordon's defensive abilities were also recognized through his receipt of four [[Fielding Bible Award]]s (2012\u201314 and 2018)<ref name=\"fielding bible\">{{cite web |title=Fielding Bible Awards \u2013 The Winners |url=http://fieldingbible.com/the-winners.asp |website=fieldingbible.com |publisher=Sports Info Solutions |accessdate=22 December 2019 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/62sERzLeS?url=http://fieldingbible.com/the-winners.asp |archive-date=November 1, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the 2014 [[Platinum Glove Award]].<ref name=\"plat glove\">{{cite web |title=2014 Rawlings Platinum Glove Awards |url=https://sabr.org/content/2014-rawlings-platinum-glove-award-winners  |publisher=Society for American Baseball Research |accessdate=22 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222001525/https://sabr.org/content/2014-rawlings-platinum-glove-award-winners |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGordon also represented the American League in the 2013, 2014, and 2015 MLB All-Star Games, although he did not play in the latter two due to injuries.  Gordon also won the [[Hutch Award]] in 2015 for his off-the field actions, including raising over $1 million for a nonprofit organization supporting cancer research and his support of youth baseball in his hometown of Omaha.<ref name=\"hutch\">{{cite web |last=Mapes |first=Diane |date=29 January 2015 |title=Gordon Receives 50th Hutch Award |url=https://www.fredhutch.org/en/news/center-news/2015/01/kansas-city-royals-alex-gordon-receives-50th-hutch-award.html |publisher=fredhutch.org |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nGordon and his wife, Jamie, have two sons and one daughter.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gordon, wife welcome baby girl to family |url=https://www.mlb.com/royals/news/alex-gordon-s-wife-gives-birth-to-baby-girl-c231795410 |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=12 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213004437/https://www.mlb.com/royals/news/alex-gordon-s-wife-gives-birth-to-baby-girl-c231795410 |archive-date=February 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> During his rookie year in with the Royals, Gordon lived in Lincoln. He moved to [[Leawood, Kansas]] in 2009. After his first child was born in 2010, he moved back to Lincoln to be closer to his grandparents. When he signed a four-year contract with the Royals in 2016, he moved back to Leawood with his family in order to pick a convenient full-time school for his children.<ref>{{cite web |title=Q&A: Gordon talks about Nebraska roots |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/alex-gordon-talks-about-nebraska-roots |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=12 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031093948/https://www.mlb.com/news/alex-gordon-talks-about-nebraska-roots |archive-date=October 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Baseballstats |mlb=460086 |espn=28636 |br=g/gordoal01 |fangraphs=5209|brm=gordon001ale}}\n\n{{Kansas City Royals roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes|title=Alex Gordon&nbsp;\u2013 College baseball navigation boxes|list1=\n{{Dick Howser Trophy}}\n{{Baseball America CollegePOY}}\n{{Golden Spikes Award}}\n{{Brooks Wallace Award}}\n{{Big 12 Conference Baseball Player of the Year navbox|state=collapsed}}\n{{2004 College Baseball Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{2005 College Baseball Consensus All-Americans}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes|title=Alex Gordon&nbsp;\u2013 Professional baseball navigation boxes|list1=\n{{Texas League Player of the Year}}\n{{2015 Kansas City Royals}}\n{{AL Platinum Glove Awards}}\n{{AL OF Gold Glove Award}}\n{{LF Fielding Bible Award}}\n{{Hutch Award}}\n{{Baseball America Minor League Player of the Year Award}}\n{{2005 MLB Draft}}\n{{Kansas City Royals first-round draft picks}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Baseball}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gordon, Alex}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All-American college baseball players]]\n[[Category:All-Star Futures Game players]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Arizona League Royals players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Gold Glove Award winners]]\n[[Category:Golden Spikes Award winners]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Royals players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball center fielders]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball left fielders]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball third basemen]]\n[[Category:Nebraska Cornhuskers baseball players]]\n[[Category:Northwest Arkansas Naturals players]]\n[[Category:Omaha Royals players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lincoln, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Surprise Scorpions players]]\n[[Category:Wichita Wranglers players]]\n[[Category:Wilmington Blue Rocks players]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name        = Alex Gordon\n|image       = Alex Gordon listens to reporters on -WSMediaDay (22888475465).jpg\n|image_size  = 250\n|team        = Kansas City Royals\n|number      = 4\n|position    = [[Outfielder]]\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1984|2|10}}\n|birth_place = [[Lincoln, Nebraska]]\n|bats        = Left\n|throws      = Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate   = April 2\n|debutyear   = 2007\n|debutteam   = Kansas City Royals\n|statleague  = MLB\n|statyear    = 2019 season\n|stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value  = .258\n|stat2label  = [[Home run]]s\n|stat2value  = 186\n|stat3label  = [[Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value  = 738\n|stat4label  = [[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n|stat4value  = 1,608\n|teams       = \n* [[Kansas City Royals]] ({{mlby|2007}}\u2013present)\n|awards     = \n* 3\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2013]]\u2013[[2015 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2015]])\n* [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|2015}})\n* 7\u00d7 [[Gold Glove Award]] (2011\u20132014, 2017\u20132019)\n* 2014 [[Platinum Glove Award]]\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{bb|USA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World University Baseball Championship|World University Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[World University Baseball Championship|2004 Tainan]] | [[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Alexander Jonathan Gordon''' (born February 10, 1984) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[left fielder]] for the [[Kansas City Royals]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). Prior to playing professionally, Gordon attended the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln]], where he played [[college baseball]] for the [[Nebraska Cornhuskers baseball|Nebraska Cornhuskers]].\n\nAt Nebraska, Gordon won the [[Brooks Wallace Award]], [[Dick Howser Trophy]], and [[Golden Spikes Award]] in 2005. That year, the Royals selected Gordon with the second overall pick in the [[2005 MLB Draft]]. Gordon made his major league debut at a [[third baseman]], but had an inconsistent beginning to his career.  In 2010, the Royals made Gordon an [[outfielder]].  Gordon was a member of the Royals' [[2015 World Series]] championship team, and signed a [[free agent]] contract that offseason to remain with the team. Gordon has won seven [[Gold Glove Award]]s, four [[Fielding Bible Award]]s, and a [[Wilson Defensive Player of the Year Award]] in MLB, all after the move to the outfield.\n\n==Early life==\nGordon was born on February 10, 1984 to a family heavily involved in baseball. Gordon's father had played baseball for the [[University of Nebraska]], and his brother played college baseball at the [[University of Nebraska-Omaha]].  Gordon had a successful high school baseball career at [[Lincoln Southeast High School]], where he was named the Gatorade Nebraska Player of the Year in 2002.  Gordon was also listed as one of the top high school prospects by ''[[Baseball America]]'' his senior year, and also received All-State honors in football that same year.<ref name=\"huskers bio\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon |url=https://huskers.com/sports/baseball/roster/alex-gordon/6966 |publisher=Nebraska Huskers |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring his teen years, Gordon played [[American Legion Baseball]].  He won the organization's Graduate of the Year award in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.legion.org/baseball/awards/graduate\n| title = Graduate of the Year \n| publisher = The American Legion\n| access-date = 2016-02-26\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160305040326/http://www.legion.org/baseball/awards/graduate\n| archive-date = March 5, 2016\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nGordon attended the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln]] and played third base.  At Nebraska, Gordon majored in criminal justice.<ref name=\"huskers bio\" /> In his junior year in 2005, he swept the collegiate baseball awards for college player of the year, winning the [[Dick Howser Trophy]], [[Golden Spikes Award]], the [[Brooks Wallace Award]], and the [[American Baseball Coaches Association]] Rawlings Player of the Year.<ref name=\"huskers bio\" /> He was also an ESPY Award Finalist for the Best Male College Athlete.<ref name=\"nebraska greatest\" /> Over the course of his collegiate career, he posted a .355 career [[batting average]], with 44 [[home runs]] and 189 [[runs batted in]] (RBI)s and finished in the top ten in eight different offensive statistical categories at Nebraksa.  Gordon was also a two-time [[Big 12 Conference]] Player of the Year Award recipient.<ref name=\"huskers bio\" />\n\n==U.S. National Team==\nDuring his time at the University of Nebraska, Gordon was a member of the 2004 [[United States National Baseball Team]], which included players from 15 different colleges.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gordon Named to USA Baseball Team |url=https://huskers.com/news/2004/6/29/65921.aspx |publisher=Nebraska Huskers Baseball |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=29 June 2004 }}</ref>  He helped lead Team USA to an 18\u20137 overall record, seeing the majority of his playing time at [[first base]]. He hit .388 with four home runs, 12 RBI and 18 [[Run (baseball)|runs]] scored in 24 contests and was named the top offensive player at the [[World University Baseball Championship]] in [[Tainan, Taiwan]] after leading all players with a .524 average (11-for-21) with two home runs, five RBI, and eight [[runs scored]] in eight games.<ref>{{cite web |title=Team USA Wins Gold at World University Baseball Championship |url=https://huskers.com/news/2004/8/1/67795.aspx |publisher=Nebraska Huskers Baseball |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=1 August 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Draft and minors==\n\nGordon was [[2005 Major League Baseball Draft|drafted in 2005]] by the [[Kansas City Royals]] with the second pick overall, becoming the highest draft pick out of Nebraska since [[Darin Erstad]] was selected with the first pick of the [[1995 MLB draft]]. He hit 29 home runs and stole 22 bases with an OPS over 1.000 in his first full season in [[minor league baseball]] with the [[Double-A (baseball)|Double-A]] [[Wichita Wranglers]]. By midseason, Gordon was receiving accolades for being one of the best hitting prospects in baseball.  He participated in the [[Texas League]] All-Star game and was selected for the [[All-Star Futures Game|2006 All-Star Futures Game]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Gordon Selected for All-Star Futures Game |url=https://huskers.com/news/2006/6/22/301134.aspx |publisher=Nebraska Huskers Baseball |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=22 June 2006}}</ref> Declining to play for Team USA in 2006, Gordon led the Wichita Wranglers to the Texas League playoffs. He performed well in his first full minor league season, and won the Texas League Player of the Year<ref name=\"texas league awards\">{{cite web |title=Texas League Awards |url=https://www.milb.com/texas/history/award-winners |publisher=milb.com |accessdate=21 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927170453/https://www.milb.com/texas/history/award-winners |archive-date=September 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and ''Baseball America's'' Minor League Player of the Year awards after the season ended.<ref name=\"mlpya\" />\n\n==Kansas City Royals==\n\n===Third base: 2007-09===\n\nIn his first major league [[at-bat]], Gordon struck out with the bases loaded against [[Curt Schilling]]<ref name=\"robbins 2011\">{{cite web |last1=Robbins |first1=Bill |title=Alex Gordon Has Come Full Circle in 2011 |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/837428 |publisher=Bleacher Report |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> but eventually got his first major league [[Hit (baseball)|hit]] on April 5, 2007, against the [[2007 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Grein-K, Royals edged out |last=Eskew |first=Alan |date=5 April 2007 |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20070405&content_id=1881141&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=home |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> On April 10, 2007, he hit his first major league home run off [[pitcher]] [[Josh Towers]] of the [[2007 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Gordon, Greinke Lead KC |date=10 April 2007 |last=Peak |first=John |url=http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20070410&content_id=1890794&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=away |publisher=Seattle Mariners |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDespite Gordon hitting .185 with three home runs and eight RBI through his first two months as an everyday starter.<ref name=\"broken nose\">{{cite web |last1=Mass |first1=AJ |title=Is It Time to Give Up on Alex Gordon |url=https://www.espn.in/fantasy/baseball/flb/story?page=mlbdk2k1030qroyals |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>, the Royals remained patient with him.<ref>[http://sandiego.padres.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070531&content_id=1996996&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc Royals Stay Patient with Gordon] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527160729/http://sandiego.padres.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070531&content_id=1996996&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |date=May 27, 2011 }}, Nicholl, Conor (31 May 2007), San Diego Padres.</ref> Gordon performed better for the rest of the season, but broke his nose in the last game of the season.<ref name=\"broken nose\" />\n\nOn September 2, Gordon had the first multi-home run game of his career, connecting off [[Boof Bonser]] of the [[Minnesota Twins]] in the second inning, and in the 3rd inning off [[Julio DePaula]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Kansas City Royals at Minnesota Twins |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/MIN/MIN200709020.shtml |publisher=Baseball-Reference |accessdate=23 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224053429/https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/MIN/MIN200709020.shtml |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On September 12, Gordon hit his 34th double of the year against the [[2007 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]], establishing a Royals rookie record.<ref>{{cite web |title=Meche, Royals End Lengthy Skids in Win Over Twins |author=The Associated Press|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/mlb/recap?gameId=270912107 |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Alex_Gordon.JPG|right|120px|thumb|Gordon before a game against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] during the [[2008 Kansas City Royals season|2008 season]]]]\n\nBefore the 2008 season, Gordon switched his uniform number from #7, the number he had as a rookie, to #4, his college number.<ref name=\"powder blues\">Kaegel, Dick.[http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071207&content_id=2320779&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc Royals to bring back powder blues] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080629032831/http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071207&content_id=2320779&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |date=June 29, 2008 }} Kansas City Royals, December 6, 2007.</ref> On [[Opening Day]], 2008 (which occurred on March 31) Gordon hit a two-run home run off [[Detroit Tigers]] [[Ace (baseball)|ace]] [[Justin Verlander]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Royals at Tigers Box Score 3-31-2008 |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/DET/DET200803310.shtml |publisher=Baseball-Reference |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Royals placed Gordon on the 15-day [[disabled list]] on August 23 because of a torn muscle in his right quadriceps.<ref name=\"broken nose\" /> Gordon finished the season with a .260 batting average and 16 home runs and led the Royals with 66 [[base on balls|walks]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2008 Kansas City Royals Stats |url=http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/stats/sortable.jsp?c_id=kc#elem=%5Bobject+Object%5D&tab_level=child&click_text=Sortable+Player+hitting&game_type='R'&season=2008&season_type=ANY&league_code='MLB'&sectionType=sp&statType=hitting&page=1&ts=1583174754061&playerType=ALL&sportCode='mlb'&split=&team_id=118&active_sw=&position=&page_type=SortablePlayer&sortOrder='desc'&sortColumn=bb&results=&perPage=50&timeframe=&last_x_days=&extended=0 |publisher=Kansas City Royals |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nGordon made the most [[Error (baseball)|errors]] (16) and had the lowest [[fielding percentage]] (.955) of all [[American League]] (AL) third basemen in 2008.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/stats/fielding?groupId=9&season=2008&seasonType=2&split=81&sortColumn=errors MLB Player Fielding Stats: 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026072553/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/stats/fielding?groupId=9&season=2008&seasonType=2&split=81&sortColumn=errors |date=October 26, 2012 }}, [[ESPN]].</ref>\n\nGordon struggled at the beginning of the 2009 season, hitting just 2-for-21 (.095) with one home run and three RBIs in seven games before being injured while sliding.<ref name=\"broken nose\" /> He underwent surgery on April 17 to repair a tear in the labral cartilage of the right hip, and was on the disabled list for twelve weeks.<ref>[http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090417&content_id=4312206&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc Alex out until at least late June] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314145444/http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090417&content_id=4312206&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |date=March 14, 2012 }}, [[Kansas City Royals]]. Published April 17, 2009. Retrieved April 22, 2009.</ref> After playing a few games in the minors, Gordon came off the disabled list and rejoined the Royals on July 17 going 1 for 4 against the [[Tampa Bay Rays]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Dick Kaegel |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090716&content_id=5896282&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |title=Betancourt, Gordon coming off DL |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103043119/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090716&content_id=5896282&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |archive-date=November 3, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Dick Kaegel |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090721&content_id=5977490&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Good signs from Gordon following surgery |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103043133/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090721&content_id=5977490&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |archive-date=November 3, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Gordon [[stolen base|stole home]] for the first time in his career on August 2 against the Rays, becoming the first Royal to do that since [[Mendy Lopez]] in [[2003 Kansas City Royals season|2003]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Dick Kaegel |date=2 August 2009|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090802&content_id=6205200&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |title=Royals escape no-no, win for Bannister |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103055305/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090802&content_id=6205200&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |archive-date=November 3, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Royals optioned Gordon to the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] [[Omaha Royals]] on August 18.<ref>{{cite web |title=August 18, 2009 MLB Trades and Transactions |url=http://proxy.espn.com/mlb/transactions?date=20090818 |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> After Omaha finished up its season, Gordon returned to the Royals in September.<ref>{{cite web |author=Jesse Temple |url=http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090818&content_id=6484002&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |title=Royals option Gordon to Triple-A Omaha |publisher=Kansas City Royals |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329132135/http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090818&content_id=6484002&vkey=news_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |archive-date=March 29, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Move to outfield: 2010-13===\n\nGordon began the 2010 season on a minor league rehab assignment with Class-A Advanced [[Wilmington Blue Rocks|Wilmington]], following a broken thumb suffered in [[Spring Training]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Dick Kaegel |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100406&content_id=9103930&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Gordon set for rehab assignment|publisher=Major League Baseball |date=January 1, 2011 |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605115309/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100406&content_id=9103930&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |archive-date=June 5, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Gordon was activated from the disabled list on April 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100417&content_id=9366844&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Royals' Gordon activated from disabled list|accessdate=April 17, 2010|last=Kaegel |first=Dick |date=April 17, 2010 |publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100420142146/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100417&content_id=9366844&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate= April 20, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>  He was demoted to the minor leagues in May, where he played left field.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2010/05/royals-demote-3b-draft-bust-gordon-to-minors-switch-to-left-field/1 | work=USA Today | title=Royals demote draft-bust Gordon to minors; switch from 3B to left field | date=May 3, 2010 | access-date=May 20, 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100526161229/http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2010/05/royals-demote-3b-draft-bust-gordon-to-minors-switch-to-left-field/1 | archive-date=May 26, 2010 | url-status=live }}</ref>  Gordon was recalled from Triple-A on July 23, 2010, to take the place of [[David DeJesus]] in the Royals' outfield, who was placed on the disabled list with a right thumb sprain.<ref>{{cite web |author=Alden Gonzalez |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100723&content_id=12543426&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Gordon recalled; DeJesus lands on DL |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104231810/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100723&content_id=12543426&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |archive-date=November 4, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nIn 2010, Gordon officially moved from being a third baseman to playing the outfield.<ref name=\"seven gold gloves\" />\n\nIn Spring Training in 2011, he led the major leagues in RBIs, with 23.<ref>{{cite web |title=2011 MLB Spring Training Stats |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/stats/sortable.jsp?c_id=mlb#playerType=ALL&elem=%5Bobject+Object%5D&tab_level=child&click_text=Sortable+Player+hitting&game_type='S'&season=2011&season_type=ANY&league_code='MLB'&sectionType=sp&statType=hitting&page=1&ts=1585962925182&sportCode='mlb'&split=&team_id=&active_sw=&position=&page_type=SortablePlayer&sortOrder='desc'&sortColumn=rbi&results=&perPage=50&timeframe=&last_x_days=&extended=0 |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> Gordon was selected as an American League finalist for the 2011 [[All-Star Final Vote]], but [[Paul Konerko]] won the vote.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dodd |first1=Mike |title=Paul Konerko, Shane Victorino Win Final Vote for All-Star Game Berths |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2011/07/paul-konerko-shane-victorino-all-star-game/1#.Xl8vvqhKhPY |publisher=USA Today Daily Pitch |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> He was also tied for sixth in the major leagues in doubles, with 45.<ref>{{cite web |title=2011 MLB Doubles Leaders |url=http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/stats/sortable.jsp?c_id=kc#elem=%5Bobject+Object%5D&tab_level=child&click_text=Sortable+Player+hitting&game_type='R'&season=2011&season_type=ANY&league_code='MLB'&sectionType=sp&statType=hitting&page=1&ts=1583296677633&playerType=ALL&sportCode='mlb'&split=&team_id=&active_sw=&position=&page_type=SortablePlayer&sortOrder='desc'&sortColumn=d&results=&perPage=50&timeframe=&last_x_days=&extended=0 |publisher=Kansas City Royals |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, he led all major league outfielders in [[Assist (baseball)|assists]], with 20<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2011-fielding-leaders.shtml |title=2011 Major League Baseball Fielding Leaders |publisher=Baseball-Reference |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111113162818/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2011-fielding-leaders.shtml |archive-date=November 13, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> and won his first American League [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove Award]].<ref name=\"seven gold gloves\" />  His success during Spring Training carried over into the regular season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robbins |first1=Bill |title=Kansas City Royals: The Real Alex Gordon Has Arrived |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/672906-kansas-city-royals-the-real-alex-gordon-has-finally-arrived |publisher=Bleacher Report |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=April 21, 2011}}</ref>  Gordon's 20 outfield assists also set a Royals franchise record.<ref>{{cite web |title=Royals Resign OF Gordon to 4-year, $37.5 Million Deal |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/ct-xpm-2012-03-30-chi-gordon-story.html |publisher=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 9, 2012, Gordon signed a one-year, $4.775 million deal with the Royals to avoid arbitration. In the process, Gordon filed for $5.45, while the Royals countered with $4.15. Under that agreement, he could have earned an additional $25K if he had reached 700 plate appearances, putting him at the original midpoint.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2012/02/royals-avoid-arbitration-with-alex-gordon.html |title=Royals Avoid Arbitration With Alex Gordon |work=MLB Trade Rumors |first=Mike |last=Axisa |date=February 9, 2012 |access-date=February 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212020358/http://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2012/02/royals-avoid-arbitration-with-alex-gordon.html |archive-date=February 12, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, on March 30, he signed a four-year, $37.5 million extension with the Royals with a player option for 2016, becoming the third Royal player to sign an extension in the off season. Gordon earned $6 million in 2012, $9 million in 2013, $10 million in 2014 and $12.5 million in 2015, but declined to exercise his player option of $12.5 million for 2016. Gordon would otherwise have become a free agent after 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2012/03/royals-alex-gordon-agree-to-extension.html |title=Royals, Alex Gordon Agree To Extension |work=MLB Trade Rumors |first=Zach |last=Links |date=March 30, 2012 |access-date=March 30, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331205147/http://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2012/03/royals-alex-gordon-agree-to-extension.html |archive-date=March 31, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Gordon won a [[Fielding Bible Award]] as the best fielding left fielder in MLB. He also won the Gold Glove Award.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 2012 Awards |date=October 25, 2012 |url=http://www.actasports.com/stats_detail/?StatId=345 |publisher=ACTA Sports |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BhthK48v?url=http://www.actasports.com/stats_detail/?StatId=345 |archivedate=October 26, 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nGordon finished the 2012 season with a .294 batting average and led the majors with 51 doubles.<ref name=\"bill james\" />\n\nGordon again performed well in 2013. He finished with the season with 90 runs scored, 168 hits, 27 doubles, six [[Triple (baseball)|triples]], 20 home runs, 81 RBIs, and a .265 batting average.<ref name=\"bill james\" /> He earned his third consecutive Gold Glove Award for his defense in left field<ref name=\"fielding bible\" /> and earned his first career All-Star selection.<ref name=\"capitol-journal\">{{cite web |last1=Fertig |first1=Todd |title=Royals Rundown |url=https://www.cjonline.com/sports/20190706/royals-rundown-seeing-only-one-star-kc-faces-looming-decision-on-alex-gordon |publisher=Topeka Capitol-Journal |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Playoff appearances: 2014-15===\n\nIn the 2014 season, Gordon scored 87 runs, had 150 hits, 34 doubles, one triple, 19 home runs, 74 RBI, 12 stolen bases, and a .266 BA.<ref name=\"ESPN\" /> On July 6, 2014, he was named to the 2014 All-Star Team for the second consecutive year.  On August 6, he recorded his 1,000th career hit when he [[Single (baseball)|singled]] off [[2014 Arizona Diamondbacks season|Arizona Diamondbacks]] pitcher [[Wade Miley]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCullough |first1=Andy |title=Alex Gordon Thrilled to Record 1,000 Hits |url=https://www.kansascity.com/opinion/article1137464.html |publisher=The Kansas City Star |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> On August 26, he tied [[Wade Boggs]] for the most home runs hit by a Nebraskan in the Major Leagues.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bruntz |first1=Michael |title=Gordon Hits Walk-Off Winner for KC |url=https://247sports.com/college/nebraska/Article/Gordon-hits-walk-off-winner-for-KC-30598750/ |publisher=24/7 Sports |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Royals qualified for the 2014 postseason.  Gordon mostly struggled during the playoffs, although he did hit a home run in the 10th inning of Game 1 of the [[2014 American League Championship Series|AL Championship Series]] against the [[2014 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Postseason History - 2014 ALCS |url=http://m.mlb.com/postseason/history/2014/alcs/ |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> He represented the tying run in the 9th inning of Game 7 of the [[2014 World Series]], when with two outs, he lined a long single to left center.  He reached third base when Giants' center fielder [[Gregor Blanco]] misplayed the ball, but was stranded when catcher [[Salvador P\u00e9rez]] fouled out to [[Pablo Sandoval]] to end the game and the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=341029107|title=Madison Bumgarner, Giants hold off Royals to win World Series|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=January 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116005620/http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=341029107|archive-date=January 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[2014 Major League Baseball season#Postseason|2014 postseason]], Gordon batted just .204, including six doubles, four stolen bases, and one home run.<ref>{{cite web |title=2014 Postseason Stats - Kansas City Royals |url=http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/stats/sortable.jsp?c_id=kc#elem=%5Bobject+Object%5D&tab_level=child&click_text=Sortable+Player+hitting&game_type='P'&season=2014&season_type=ANY&league_code='MLB'&sectionType=sp&statType=hitting&page=1&ts=1583104098248&playerType=ALL&sportCode='mlb'&split=&team_id=118&active_sw=&position=&page_type=SortablePlayer&sortOrder='desc'&sortColumn=avg&results=&perPage=50&timeframe=&last_x_days=&extended=0 |publisher=Kansas City Royals |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn July 8, 2015, against the Tampa Bay Rays, Gordon was injured attempting to chase down a fly ball hit by [[Logan Forsythe]], which resulted in an [[inside-the-park home run]] as Gordon could not get back up.  After being carted off the field, he was diagnosed with a left groin strain was and placed on the 15-Day [[disabled list]] (DL).<ref>{{cite web |title=Royals All-Star Alex Gordon Could Miss Eight Weeks With Groin Strain |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/07/09/kansas-city-royals-alex-gordon-injury-groin-strain |publisher=Sports Illustrated |date=8 July 2015|accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref>  Gordon had just come off a 7-hit double header the night before against the Rays (tying the Royals record for most hits in a double header) in which he hit a double and a home run.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brzezinski |first1=Alex |title=Alex Gordon Collects 7 Hits, 6 RBIs in Doubleheader Sweep of Rays |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/mlb/news/mlb-nightly-9-alex-gordon-collects-7-hits-6-rbis-in-doubleheader-sweep-against-rays/dk7yfpla4i6y1txeket8cg9zk |publisher=Sporting News |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref>  On September 2, Gordon was activated from the DL and went 2-for-3, with an RBI and run scored against the [[Detroit Tigers]] .<ref>{{Cite web|title = Alex Gordon returns from injury, goes 2-for-3 in Royals\u2019 loss to Tigers |last=Kerkhoff |first=Blair |date=1 September 2015|url = http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article33318009.html |publisher=The Kansas City Star|accessdate = September 8, 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150906024245/http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article33318009.html|archive-date = September 6, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nHe finished the regular season with a .271 batting average/.377 [[on-base percentage]]/.432 [[slugging percentage]] with 18 doubles, 13 home runs, and 48 RBIs.<ref name=\"bill james\">{{cite book |last1=James |first1=Bill |title=The Bill James Handbook 2016 |date=2015 |publisher=Acta Sports |location=Chicago |isbn=978-0-87946-545-2 |page=157}}</ref>\n\nThe Royals qualified for the postseason in 2015.  In Game 1 of the [[2015 World Series]], Gordon hit a ninth-inning home run off of [[2015 New York Mets season|New York Mets]] closer [[Jeurys Familia]] to tie the game at 4. The Royals would go on to win, 5\u20134, in 14 innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/gametracker/recap/MLB_20151027_NYM@KC/hosmer-sacrifice-fly-in-14th-lifts-royals-to-ws-game-1-win|title=MLB Recap - New York Mets at Kansas City Royals - Oct 27, 2015|date=October 28, 2015|publisher=CBSSports.com|accessdate=January 6, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116005620/http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/gametracker/recap/MLB_20151027_NYM%40KC/hosmer-sacrifice-fly-in-14th-lifts-royals-to-ws-game-1-win|archivedate=January 16, 2016}}</ref> Gordon became a [[List of World Series champions|World Champion]] when the Royals won the World Series in five games over the Mets, the first World Series won by the Royals since 1985. Combined in the postseason, Gordon hit .241 with 2 homers, 6 RBI and a .775 OPS.<ref>{{cite web |title=2015 Postseason Stats - Kansas City Royals |url=http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/stats/sortable.jsp?c_id=kc#elem=%5Bobject+Object%5D&tab_level=child&click_text=Sortable+Player+hitting&game_type='P'&season=2015&season_type=ANY&league_code='MLB'&sectionType=sp&statType=hitting&page=1&ts=1583104098248&playerType=ALL&sportCode='mlb'&split=&team_id=118&active_sw=&position=&page_type=SortablePlayer&sortOrder='desc'&sortColumn=avg&results=&perPage=50&timeframe=&last_x_days=&extended=0 |publisher=Kansas City Royals |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> Gordon, along with all of the Royals, attended the World Series parade and pep rally in downtown Kansas City, Missouri at [[Union Station (Kansas City, Missouri)|Union Station]] on November 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/kansas-city-royals-world-series-parade-champions-hosmer-perez-moustakas-escobar-zobrist-110315|title=Kansas City Royals fans jam the streets at their World Series parade|publisher=Fox Sports|accessdate=January 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116005619/http://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/kansas-city-royals-world-series-parade-champions-hosmer-perez-moustakas-escobar-zobrist-110315|archive-date=January 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Later career: 2016-present===\nOn January 6, 2016, Gordon signed a four-year deal worth $72 million to remain with the Royals with a mutual option for the 2020 season.<ref>{{cite web|last=Flanagan|first=Jeffrey|title=Gordon returns to fold for Royals|url=http://m.royals.mlb.com/news/article/161154866/alex-gordon-returns-to-royals|publisher=Major League Baseball|date=January 6, 2016|accessdate=January 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109164946/http://m.royals.mlb.com/news/article/161154866/alex-gordon-returns-to-royals|archive-date=January 9, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>  On May 22, 2016, Gordon collided with Royals' third-baseman [[Mike Moustakas]] while chasing a [[Melky Cabrera]] pop-up into foul territory down the left field line against the Chicago White Sox.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dodd|first=Rustin|title=Royals' Alex Gordon has broken bone in wrist, could miss three to four weeks.|url=http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article79381672.html|publisher=The Kansas City Star|date=May 23, 2016|accessdate=May 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921000426/http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article79381672.html|archive-date=September 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Gordon suffered a scaphoid fracture in his right wrist and was placed on the disabled-list where he missed 29 games.<ref>{{cite web|last=Doherty|first=Cole|title=Kansas City Royals: The Return of Alex Gordon|url=http://www.isportsweb.com/2016/06/22/kansas-city-royals-return-alex-gordon/|publisher=isportsweb|date=June 25, 2016|accessdate=May 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920190932/http://www.isportsweb.com/2016/06/22/kansas-city-royals-return-alex-gordon/|archive-date=September 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He finished 2016 hitting .220/.312/.380 with a career high 148 strikeouts in 445 at-bats.<ref name=\"ESPN\" />\n\nOn May 4, 2017, Gordon was [[hit by pitch|hit by a pitch]] from the White Sox's [[Derek Holland]].  This was Gordon's 79th career hit by pitch, setting the Royals' franchise record, previously held by [[Mike Macfarlane]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Dodd|first=Rustin|title=Royals\u2019 Alex Gordon is hit by a pitch for 79th time, breaking all-time franchise record|url=http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article148740239.html|publisher=The Kansas City Star|date=May 4, 2017|accessdate=May 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920190953/http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article148740239.html|archive-date=September 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> When asked about how he was able to be hit by so many pitches, Gordon responded \"[I] don't move.\"  While he stated that he didn't lean in towards the pitch to give himself a better chance of being hit, Gordon did admit that he had done so during his college career.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Flanagan |first1=Jeffrey |title=HBP-Magnet Gordon's Method? Don't Move. |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/alex-gordon-holds-royals-hit-by-pitch-record |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=6 April 2019}}</ref>  On September 19, Gordon hit the 5,694th home run of the [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] season against [[Ryan Tepera]], breaking the record for the most home runs in an MLB season, with the previous record having been set in the [[2000 Major League Baseball season|2000]] season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article174286581.html|title=Watch the Royals\u2019 Alex Gordon hit the record-breaking 5,694th homer of the MLB season|work=The Kansas City Star|access-date=2017-09-22|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922012730/http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article174286581.html|archive-date=September 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> For the season, he batted .208/.293/.315.<ref name=\"ESPN\" /> His .315 slugging percentage in 2017 was the lowest of all qualified major league batters.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=8&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=15,a |title=Major League Leaderboards 2017 |publisher=Fangraphs|access-date=December 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228035207/https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=8&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=15,a |archive-date=December 28, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the offseason before the 2018 season, Gordon was inducted into the Lincoln Southeast High School Athletics Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon Highlights LSE's 2018 Hall Class |url=https://journalstar.com/sports/high-school/baseball/alex-gordon-highlights-lse-s-hall-class/article_2a3720b7-909c-5791-980d-744edabd0ebc.html |publisher=Lincoln Journal Star |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=11 January 2018}}</ref>  In 2018, Gordon hit .245/.324/.370 with 13 home runs and 54 RBIs and won his sixth Gold Glove.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article221127630.html |title=KC Royals Gordon, Perez wins MLB Gold Glove awards<!-- Bot generated title --> |publisher=The Kansas City Star |access-date=November 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108031237/https://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article221127630.html |archive-date=November 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>  On May 8, Gordon collected a season-high four hits, and he drove in five runs on September 15.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon 2018 Batting Game Log |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=gordoal01&t=b&year=2018 |publisher=Baseball-Reference |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Gordon rebounded to hit .266/.345/.396 with 13 home runs and 76 RBIs in his best offensive season since 2015.<ref name=\"ESPN\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon Player Profile |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/player/stats/_/id/28636/alex-gordon |website=ESPN |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=November 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928032049/http://www.espn.com/mlb/player/stats/_/id/28636/alex-gordon |archive-date=September 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Early in April that season, Gordon recorded his first four-hit game since May 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Flanagan |first1=Jeffrey |title=Alex Gordon Honors Friend with Home Run in Six-Run First Inning |url=https://www.mlb.com/royals/news/alex-gordon-s-hr-highlights-six-run-first-inning |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=13 April 2019}}</ref>  In early May, Gordon reached a career total of 1,500 hits.  In the same game, Gordon also hit two home runs off of [[Jake Arrieta]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Flanagan |first1=Jeffrey |title=Gordon Happy to Homer Twice for 1,500 Hits |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/alex-gordon-multi-homer-game-for-royals |date=11 May 2019|publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>  On August 26, Gordon made his first professional pitching appearance, pitching {{frac|1|1|3}} innings in a blowout loss to the [[2019 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland A's]].<ref name=\"pitching\">{{cite web |last1=Flanagan |first1=Jeffrey |title=Gordon Happy to \"Pitch\" in for Royals Bullpen |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/alex-gordon-pitches-in-royals-loss-to-a-s |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214042456/https://www.mlb.com/news/alex-gordon-pitches-in-royals-loss-to-a-s |archive-date=December 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  He also won his seventh career Gold Glove.<ref name=\"Gold Glove Winners 2019\">{{cite web |last1=Casella |first1=Paul |last2=Harrigan |first2=Thomas |last3=Langs |first3=Sarah |title=Gold Glove Awards Handed Out |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/2019-gold-glove-winners |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=7 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105032427/https://www.mlb.com/news/2019-gold-glove-winners |archive-date=November 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn November 2, 2019, Gordon elected free agency.<ref name=\"mlb profile\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon Stats and Transactions |url=https://www.mlb.com/player/alex-gordon-460086 |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=21 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224032430/https://www.mlb.com/player/alex-gordon-460086 |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On January 22, 2020, he signed a one-year, $4 million contract to remain with the Royals for the 2020 season.<ref name=\"2020 contract\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon, Royals agree on deal |url=https://www.mlb.com/royals/news/alex-gordon-royals-deal |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=22 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200121104408/https://www.mlb.com/royals/news/alex-gordon-royals-deal |archive-date=January 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==2006 ''Topps'' baseball card==\nGordon's [[baseball card]] gained notoriety shortly after Gordon was drafted in 2006. ''[[Topps]]'' issued Gordon's [[rookie card]] prematurely, as only players on 25-man rosters or who have played in at least one Major League game are eligible. As a result, ''Topps'' stopped producing the card and cut holes in some of the existing cards. Examples that found their way into retail stores have garnered bids in the thousands of dollars on [[eBay]].<ref name=\"baseball card\">{{cite web |last1=Rovell |first1=Darren |title=This Card Costs 'Cause You Aren't Supposed to Have It |url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/news/story?id=2429888 |website=espn.com |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=23 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105015223/https://www.espn.com/mlb/news/story?id=2429888 |archive-date=November 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n\n===Collegiate career===\nIn 2004, Gordon was named to the First-Team All-Big 12 and was recognized as the Big 12 Player of the Year, both of which Gordon also received in 2005.<ref name=\"baseball cube\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon Awards |url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/profile.asp?ID=54849#Awards |publisher=The Baseball Cube |accessdate=22 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028032837/http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/profile.asp?ID=54849#Awards |archive-date=October 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Gordon won the [[Golden Spikes Award]], [[Dick Howser Trophy]], [[Brooks Wallace Award]], and the ''[[Baseball America]]'' College Player of the Year awards.<ref name=\"almanac\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon |url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/awards.php?p=gordoal01 |publisher=Baseball Almanac |accessdate=22 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912124908/https://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/awards.php?p=gordoal01 |archive-date=September 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Gordon was also a finalist for the ESPY Male College Athlete of the Year Award and was named a first team All-American, the latter of which Gordon was recognized as in 2004.<ref name=\"nebraska greatest\">{{cite web |title=Nebraska's Greatest Athletes: #33 Alex Gordon |url=https://dataomaha.com/neb100/player/33 |website=dataomaha.com |publisher=Omaha World-Herald |accessdate = 4 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Minor leagues===\nIn 2006, Gordon was named the Minor League Player of the Year by ''Baseball America'' and ''Topps''<ref name=\"mlpya\">{{cite web |title=Minor League Player of the Year |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Minor_League_Player_of_the_Year |publisher=Baseball-Reference |accessdate=22 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222153506/https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Minor_League_Player_of_the_Year |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the Texas League Player of the Year.<ref name=\"texas league awards\" />  He also was named the MLB.com Double-A Offensive Player of the Year.<ref name=\"double a\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon Profile |url=http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?sid=t3410&player_id=460086#/career/R/hitting/2019/ALL |publisher=milb.com |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Major leagues===\nOver the course of his career, Gordon has won seven [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award]]s (2011\u201314 and 2017\u201319).<ref name=\"seven gold gloves\">{{cite web |title=Alex Gordon Wins Seventh Gold Glove |url=https://www.mlb.com/press-release/alex-gordon-wins-seventh-gold-glove |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=22 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222001526/https://www.mlb.com/press-release/alex-gordon-wins-seventh-gold-glove |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Gordon's defensive abilities were also recognized through his receipt of four [[Fielding Bible Award]]s (2012\u201314 and 2018)<ref name=\"fielding bible\">{{cite web |title=Fielding Bible Awards - The Winners |url=http://fieldingbible.com/the-winners.asp |website=fieldingbible.com |publisher=Sports Info Solutions |accessdate=22 December 2019 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/62sERzLeS?url=http://fieldingbible.com/the-winners.asp |archive-date=November 1, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the 2014 [[Platinum Glove Award]].<ref name=\"plat glove\">{{cite web |title=2014 Rawlings Platinum Glove Awards |url=https://sabr.org/content/2014-rawlings-platinum-glove-award-winners  |publisher=Society for American Baseball Research |accessdate=22 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222001525/https://sabr.org/content/2014-rawlings-platinum-glove-award-winners |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGordon also represented the American League in the 2013, 2014, and 2015 MLB All-Star Games, although he did not play in the latter two due to injuries.  Gordon also won the [[Hutch Award]] in 2015 for his off-the field actions, including raising over $1 million for a nonprofit organization supporting cancer research and his support of youth baseball in his hometown of Omaha.<ref name=\"hutch\">{{cite web |last=Mapes |first=Diane |date=29 January 2015 |title=Gordon Receives 50th Hutch Award |url=https://www.fredhutch.org/en/news/center-news/2015/01/kansas-city-royals-alex-gordon-receives-50th-hutch-award.html |publisher=fredhutch.org |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nGordon and his wife, Jamie, have two sons and one daughter.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gordon, wife welcome baby girl to family |url=https://www.mlb.com/royals/news/alex-gordon-s-wife-gives-birth-to-baby-girl-c231795410 |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=12 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213004437/https://www.mlb.com/royals/news/alex-gordon-s-wife-gives-birth-to-baby-girl-c231795410 |archive-date=February 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> During his rookie year in with the Royals, Gordon lived in Lincoln. He moved to [[Leawood, Kansas]] in 2009. After his first child was born in 2010, he moved back to Lincoln to be closer to his grandparents. When he signed a four-year contract with the Royals in 2016, he moved back to Leawood with his family in order to pick a convenient full-time school for his children.<ref>{{cite web |title=Q&A: Gordon talks about Nebraska roots |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/alex-gordon-talks-about-nebraska-roots |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=12 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031093948/https://www.mlb.com/news/alex-gordon-talks-about-nebraska-roots |archive-date=October 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Baseballstats |mlb=460086 |espn=28636 |br=g/gordoal01 |fangraphs=5209|brm=gordon001ale}}\n\n{{Kansas City Royals roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes|title=Alex Gordon&nbsp;\u2013 College baseball navigation boxes|list1=\n{{Dick Howser Trophy}}\n{{Baseball America CollegePOY}}\n{{Golden Spikes Award}}\n{{Brooks Wallace Award}}\n{{Big 12 Conference Baseball Player of the Year navbox|state=collapsed}}\n{{2004 College Baseball Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{2005 College Baseball Consensus All-Americans}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes|title=Alex Gordon&nbsp;\u2013 Professional baseball navigation boxes|list1=\n{{Texas League Player of the Year}}\n{{2015 Kansas City Royals}}\n{{AL Platinum Glove Awards}}\n{{AL OF Gold Glove Award}}\n{{LF Fielding Bible Award}}\n{{Hutch Award}}\n{{Baseball America Minor League Player of the Year Award}}\n{{2005 MLB Draft}}\n{{Kansas City Royals first-round draft picks}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Baseball}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gordon, Alex}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All-American college baseball players]]\n[[Category:All-Star Futures Game players]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Arizona League Royals players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Gold Glove Award winners]]\n[[Category:Golden Spikes Award winners]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Royals players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball center fielders]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball left fielders]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball third basemen]]\n[[Category:Nebraska Cornhuskers baseball players]]\n[[Category:Northwest Arkansas Naturals players]]\n[[Category:Omaha Royals players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lincoln, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Surprise Scorpions players]]\n[[Category:Wichita Wranglers players]]\n[[Category:Wilmington Blue Rocks players]]\n", "name_user": "Muboshgu", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alex_Gordon"}
{"title_page": "Mark Wahlberg", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Marky Mark|the BBC music executive|Markie Mark|the Brazilian musician|DJ Marky}}\n{{for|the American television host|Mark L. Walberg}}\n{{short description|American actor, television producer and rap musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}} \n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Uglyass Idiotberg\n| image              = Mark Wahlberg 2017.jpg\n| caption            = Wahlberg in 2017\n| birth_name         = {{nowrap|Mark Robert Michael Wahlberg}}\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1971|6|5|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], U.S.<!--As per WP:LINKDIRECT and Template:infobox person, birth/death place indicates city, state, then country. No need to spell out \"United States; 'U.S.' is fine.-->\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actor|businessman|model|rapper|singer|songwriter|producer}}\n| years_active       = 1989\u2013present (actor) 1984\u20131997 (singer)\n| salary             = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Rhea Durham]]|August 1, 2009|}}\n| children           = 4\n| relatives          = {{unbulleted list | [[Donnie Wahlberg]] (brother) | [[Robert Wahlberg]] (brother) | [[Paul Wahlberg]] (brother) }}\n| homepage           = {{URL|markwahlberg.com}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background  = solo_singer\n| alias = Marky Mark\n| genre = {{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[Eurodance]]|[[contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Pop music|pop]]|[[new jack swing]]}}\n| instrument = Vocals\n| label = {{hlist|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch]]|[[Prince Ital Joe]]}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Mark Robert Michael Wahlberg''' (born June 5, 1971)<ref name=biography.com /> is an American actor, producer, businessman, [[Model (person)|model]], rapper, singer and songwriter. He is also known by his former stage name '''Marky Mark''', from his career as frontman for the group, [[Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch]], with whom he released the albums ''[[Music for the People (Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch album)|Music for the People]]'' (1991) and ''[[You Gotta Believe]]'' (1992).\n\nFrom his early music career Wahlberg transitioned to acting, with his screen debut in ''[[Renaissance Man (film)|Renaissance Man]]'' (1994) and his first starring role in ''[[Fear (1996 film)|Fear]]'' (1996). He received critical praise for his performance as porn actor Dirk Diggler in ''[[Boogie Nights]]''. In the early 2000s, he ventured into big budget action-oriented movies, such as ''[[The Perfect Storm (film)|The Perfect Storm]]'' (2000), ''[[Planet of the Apes (2001 film)|Planet of the Apes]]'' (2001) and ''[[The Italian Job (2003 film)|The Italian Job]]'' (2003). For playing a police officer in the neo-crime drama ''[[The Departed]]'' (2006), he earned a nomination for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]]. For the biographical sports drama ''[[The Fighter]]'' (2010), in which he starred as [[Micky Ward]], Wahlberg received a nomination for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe Award for Best Actor]]. In the 2010s, he landed successful comedy roles with ''[[The Other Guys]]'' (2010), ''[[Daddy's Home (film)|Daddy's Home]]'' (2015) and its [[Daddy's Home 2|2017 sequel]],  ''[[Ted (film)|Ted]]'' (2012) and its [[Ted 2|2015 sequel]], and became the protagonist in the ''[[Transformers (film series)|Transformers]]'' live-action film franchise (2014, 2017). He was the world's best-paid actor in 2017.\n\nWahlberg also served as executive producer of five [[HBO]] series: the comedy-drama ''[[Entourage (U.S. TV series)|Entourage]]'' (2004\u20132011), the period crime drama ''[[Boardwalk Empire]]'' (2010\u20132014), the comedy-dramas ''[[How to Make It in America]]'' (2010\u20132011) and ''[[Ballers]]'' (2015\u20132019) and documentary McMillions (2020) He is co-owner of the [[Wahlburgers]] chain and co-starred in the [[Wahlburgers (TV series)|reality TV series]] about it. Wahlberg received a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in 2010.\n\n== Early life ==\nWahlberg was born in the [[Dorchester, Boston|Dorchester]] neighborhood of [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], the youngest of nine children,<ref name=biography.com>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/mark-wahlberg-9542335 |title=Mark Wahlberg Biography: Film Actor, Rapper (1971\u2013) |publisher=[[Biography.com]] ([[FYI (TV network)|FYI]] / [[A&E Networks]]) |accessdate=August 14, 2010| archivedate=October 2, 2015| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151002105429/http://www.biography.com/people/mark-wahlberg-9542335 | url-status=live}}</ref> including actor [[Robert Wahlberg|Robert]] and singer and actor [[Donnie Wahlberg|Donnie]]. His mother, Alma Elaine (n\u00e9e Donnelly), was a bank clerk and a nurse's aide, and his father, Donald Edmond Wahlberg, was a delivery driver.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/mark-wahlberg-on-his-mom-shes-not-speaking-to-me-right-now-2013512|title=Mark Wahlberg: 'My Mom's Not Speaking to Me Right Now'|work=[[Us Weekly]]|first=Stephanie|last=Webber|date=December 5, 2013|access-date=December 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151227095217/http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/mark-wahlberg-on-his-mom-shes-not-speaking-to-me-right-now-2013512|archive-date=December 27, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=dadobit /> His parents divorced in 1982, and afterward, he divided his time between them.<ref>{{cite news|last=Galloway|first=Stephen|title=Mark Wahlberg on 'Entourage' Cast Apology, Wish to Own a Studio and 'Highway to Heaven' Reboot Pitch|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lone-survivor-mark-wahlberg-entourage-664601?page=3|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=January 8, 2014|page=3|date=December 12, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216211920/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lone-survivor-mark-wahlberg-entourage-664601?page=3|archive-date=December 16, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> His father was of [[Sweden|Swedish]] and [[Irish people|Irish]] descent, and his mother is of [[England|English]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wargs.com/other/wahlberg.html |title=Ancestry of Mark Wahlberg |publisher=Wargs.com |accessdate=January 10, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140127033328/http://www.wargs.com/other/wahlberg.html |archive-date=January 27, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> Maternally, Wahlberg is distantly related to author [[Nathaniel Hawthorne]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2011/05/14/just_call_chris_child_pop_cultures_genealogy_sleuth/?p1=Upbox_links | work=The Boston Globe | first=Kathleen | last=Pierce | title=Just call him pop culture's sleuth | date=May 14, 2011 | access-date=May 14, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103150258/http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2011/05/14/just_call_chris_child_pop_cultures_genealogy_sleuth/?p1=Upbox_links | archive-date=November 3, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> Wahlberg had a Roman Catholic upbringing<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/movies/mark-of-a-man/story-e6frf9h6-1111117540758|title=Mark of a man|work=Herald Sun|location=Australia|date=September 21, 2008|accessdate=September 9, 2010|first=Ileana Young|last=Robin Lynch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615062222/http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/movies/mark-of-a-man/story-e6frf9h6-1111117540758|archive-date=June 15, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=hs>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/confidential/reformed-bad-boy-mark-wahlberg-goes-to-church-during-australian-tour/story-e6frf96o-1225906318411|title=Reformed bad boy Mark Wahlberg goes to church during Australian tour|work=Herald Sun|location=Australia|date=August 17, 2010|accessdate=September 9, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615062314/http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/confidential/reformed-bad-boy-mark-wahlberg-goes-to-church-during-australian-tour/story-e6frf96o-1225906318411|archive-date=June 15, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> and attended [[Snowden International School|Copley Square High School]] on [[Newbury Street (Boston)|Newbury Street]] in Boston. By age 13, Wahlberg had developed an addiction to [[cocaine]] and other substances.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.markwahlbergfan.com/article_vanityfair.htm |title=Vanity Fair. Rogue Star |publisher=Markwahlbergfan.com |accessdate=August 14, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220085726/http://www.markwahlbergfan.com/article_vanityfair.htm |archive-date=February 20, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2008/0630/104.html|title=Changing Room|last=Burke|first=Monte|date=June 30, 2008|work=Forbes|access-date=August 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908191733/https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2008/0630/104.html|archive-date=September 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He did not receive his high school diploma until June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lewis|first=Raha|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20735589,00.html|title=Mark Wahlberg Earns His High School Diploma|date=September 16, 2013|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=September 17, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918044917/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20735589,00.html|archive-date=September 18, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1986, Wahlberg and three friends chased after three black children while yelling \"Kill the [[nigger]], kill the nigger\" and throwing rocks at them.<ref name=\"smokinggun2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=2|title=Back In The Day: Marky Mark's Rap Sheet|website=The Smoking Gun|page=2|accessdate=June 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624040006/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=2|archive-date=June 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, Wahlberg and others followed a group of schoolchildren taking a [[field trip]] on a beach, yelled racial epithets at them, threw rocks at them, and \"summoned other white males who joined\" in the harassment.<ref name=\"smokinggun2\" /> In August 1986, civil action was filed against Wahlberg for violating the civil rights of his victims, and the case was settled the next month.<ref name=\"smokinggun3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=3|title=Back In The Day: Marky Mark's Rap Sheet|website=The Smoking Gun|page=3|accessdate=June 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624035854/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=3|archive-date=June 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"smokinggun5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=3|title=Back In The Day: Marky Mark's Rap Sheet|website=The Smoking Gun|page=5|accessdate=June 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624035854/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=3|archive-date=June 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=elder>{{Cite book| last = Elder | first = Larry | title = Showdown: Confronting Bias, Lies and the Special Interests That Divide America | publisher = Macmillan | year = 2003 | page = 12 | isbn = 978-0-312-32017-1}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1988, Wahlberg assaulted a middle-aged Vietnamese man on the street, calling him a \"Vietnam fucking shit\" and knocking him unconscious with a large wooden stick. Wahlberg attacked a second Vietnamese man later the same day, punching him in the eye. When Wahlberg was arrested and returned to the scene of the first assault, he told police officers: \"I'll tell you now that's the mother-fucker whose head I split open.\"<ref name=\"smokinggun6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=6|title=Back In The Day: Marky Mark's Rap Sheet|website=The Smoking Gun|page=6|accessdate=December 7, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229221604/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=6|archive-date=December 29, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Investigators also noted that Wahlberg \"made numerous unsolicited racial statements about '[[gook]]s' and 'slant-eyed gooks'\".<ref name=\"Ambinder\">{{cite web|url=http://theweek.com/article/index/273108/mark-wahlberg-should-not-be-pardoned|title=Mark Wahlberg should not be pardoned|last1=Ambinder|first1=Marc|date=December 5, 2014|publisher=[[The Week#website|TheWeek.com]]|accessdate=December 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141206033144/https://theweek.com/article/index/273108/mark-wahlberg-should-not-be-pardoned|archive-date=December 6, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=smokinggun0 />\nWahlberg was charged with [[attempted murder]], pleaded guilty to felony [[assault]], and was sentenced to two years in jail, but served only 45 days of his sentence.<ref name=\"Ambinder\" /><ref name=\"Candid Chat\">{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Nightline/story?id=2509542&page=1 |title=A Candid Chat With Mark Wahlberg \u2013 ABC News |publisher=ABC News |date=September 29, 2006 |accessdate=August 14, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/65cksWHPt?url=http://abcnews.go.com/Nightline/story?id=2509542 |archive-date=February 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Wahlberg believed he had left the second victim (named Johnny Trinh) permanently blind in one eye, though Trinh stated that he had lost his eye years prior in the [[Vietnam War]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://jezebel.com/mark-wahlberg-beating-victim-says-actor-did-not-blind-h-1670074037|title=Mark Wahlberg Beating Victim Says Actor Did Not Blind Him in Attack|website=Jezebel|language=en-us|access-date=2019-11-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823235049/https://jezebel.com/mark-wahlberg-beating-victim-says-actor-did-not-blind-h-1670074037|archive-date=August 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=elder /><ref name=\"Ambinder\" /><ref name=smokinggun0>{{cite web|title=Back In The Day: Marky Mark's Rap Sheet|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/documents/crime/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0|website=The Smoking Gun|accessdate=December 7, 2014|date=July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210123510/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/documents/crime/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0|archive-date=December 10, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1992, Wahlberg fractured the jaw of a neighbor in an unprovoked attack.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rap Singer Marky Mark Settles Broken-Jaw Suit|work=[[Lakeland Ledger]]|date= April 6, 1993|page= 2| location=Lakeland, Florida |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1346&dat=19930406&id=gEtIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=t_wDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6692,4119661}}</ref> Court documents state that in 1992, Wahlberg \"without provocation or cause, viciously and repeatedly kicked\" a man in the face while another man held the victim on the ground.<ref>{{cite web|title=Back In The Day: Marky Mark's Rap Sheet|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=8|page=8|website=The Smoking Gun|accessdate=May 17, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420163859/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=8|archive-date=April 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 Wahlberg said the right thing for him to do would be to meet with Trinh and make amends, though he had not done so.<ref name=\"Candid Chat\" /> In 2016, while requesting a pardon for his conviction for the assault on Trinh, Wahlberg said he had met with Trinh and apologized \"for those horrific acts.\" Trinh released a public statement forgiving Wahlberg.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=wrap09132016>''The Wrap'', September 13, 2016 http://www.thewrap.com/mark-wahlberg-now-regrets-pardon-request-for-teenage-assault-conviction/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312074526/http://www.thewrap.com/mark-wahlberg-now-regrets-pardon-request-for-teenage-assault-conviction/ |date=March 12, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Wahlberg applied for a pardon for his convictions.<ref>{{cite web|title=PDF file of Massachusetts Pardon application|url=http://media.nbcbayarea.com/documents/wahlberg.pdf|publisher=NBC Universal|accessdate=December 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205080037/http://media.nbcbayarea.com/documents/wahlberg.pdf|archive-date=December 5, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Regan|first1=Helen|title=Mark Wahlberg Is Seeking a Pardon for His 1988 Assault Conviction|url=http://time.com/3619577/mark-wahlberg-pardon-assault/|accessdate=December 6, 2014|work=TIME|publisher=Time.com|date=December 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205163033/http://time.com/3619577/mark-wahlberg-pardon-assault/|archive-date=December 5, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> His pardon application engendered controversy.<ref name=\"Ambinder\" /> According to the [[BBC]], the debate about his suitability for a pardon raised \"difficult issues, with the arguments on both sides being far-reaching and complex\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-echochambers-30425288|title=Does Mark Wahlberg want a 'white privilege' pardon?|work=BBC News|accessdate=July 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821183353/http://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-echochambers-30425288|archive-date=August 21, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOne of the black children attacked by Wahlberg opposed the pardon, saying: \"a racist will always be a racist.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jan/20/mark-wahlberg-racism-pardon \"Mark Wahlberg harassment victim says actor should not be pardoned\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221113116/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jan/20/mark-wahlberg-racism-pardon |date=December 21, 2016 }} ''The Guardian''. January 20, 2015</ref> Judith Beals, who had been the prosecutor in some of the cases, argued that \"Wahlberg has never acknowledged the racial nature of his crimes\" and that a pardon would undermine Wahlberg's charity work, saying: \"a formal public pardon would highlight all too clearly that if you are white and a movie star, a different standard applies. Is that really what Wahlberg wants?\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/01/21/mark-wahlberg-racial-violence-victim-says-actor-shouldnt-be-pardoned/|title=Mark Wahlberg racial violence victim says actor shouldn't be pardoned|last=Moyer|first=Justin Wm|date=January 21, 2015|work=Washington Post|access-date=June 11, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140325/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/01/21/mark-wahlberg-racial-violence-victim-says-actor-shouldnt-be-pardoned/|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Wahlberg said that he regretted his attempt to obtain a pardon, and his petition was closed after he failed to answer a request from the pardon board as to whether he wanted it to remain open.<ref name=wrap09132016 /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-mark-wahlberg-pardon-request-dropped-20160916-snap-story.html |title=Mark Wahlberg drops pardon request for 1988 assaults |work=LA Times |date= |accessdate=September 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917003057/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-mark-wahlberg-pardon-request-dropped-20160916-snap-story.html |archive-date=September 17, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n=== Music ===\nWahlberg first came to fame as the younger brother of [[Donnie Wahlberg]] of the successful [[boy band]], ''[[New Kids on the Block]]''. Mark, at the age of 13, was one of the group's original members, along with Donnie, but quit after a few months. [[Danny Wood]], [[Jordan Knight]], [[Jonathan Knight]] and [[Joey McIntyre]] all joined the group after Mark had left.\n\nIn 1990, Wahlberg began recording with dancers/rappers Scott Ross (Scottie Gee), Hector Barros (Hector the Booty Inspector), Anthony Thomas (Ashley Ace), and Terry Yancey (DJ-T) as [[Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch]], earning a hit with \"[[Good Vibrations (Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch song)|Good Vibrations]]\" from their debut album ''[[Music for the People (Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch album)|Music for the People]]''. The record, produced by brother Donnie, hit number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], later becoming certified as a [[Platinum Single|platinum single]]. The second single, \"[[Wildside (Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch song)|Wildside]]\", peaked at number five on ''Billboard''{{'}}s [[Hot Singles Sales]] chart and at number 10 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} It was certified as a gold single. Marky Mark opened for the New Kids on the Block during their last tour. Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch also had their own video game, titled ''[[Make My Video (series)|Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch: Make My Video]]'', which despite the band's success, was a huge flop.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Townsend |first=Emru |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/127579-6/the_10_worst_games_of_all_time.html |title=The 10 Worst Games of All Time \u2013 Page 6 |magazine=PCWorld |date=March 14, 2012 |accessdate=March 29, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120413105301/http://www.pcworld.com/article/127579-6/the_10_worst_games_of_all_time.html |archive-date=April 13, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/segacd/587969-marky-mark-and-the-funky-bunch-make-my-video/ |title=Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch: Make My Video for Sega CD |publisher=GameRankings |date= |accessdate=March 29, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014093707/http://www.gamerankings.com/segacd/587969-marky-mark-and-the-funky-bunch-make-my-video/ |archive-date=October 14, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The second Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch LP, ''[[You Gotta Believe]]'', was not as successful as the first, yielding only a minor hit single in the title track.<ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r60116/review|first=Ron|last=Wynn}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1992, while performing on the British TV show ''[[The Word (TV series)|The Word]]'', Wahlberg praised [[Shabba Ranks]], who had stated gays should be crucified. [[Gay and Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation]] condemned him and berated Calvin Klein for using him to promote their products.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/pin-up-exposed-why-marky-mark-is-taking-the-rap-the-man-wearing-calvin-kleins-pants-could-be-undone-2322005.html|title=Pin-up exposed: why Marky Mark is taking the rap: The man wearing Calvin Klein's pants could be undone by his shady past and unguarded remarks. Will apologies save his skin? Mark Simpson reports|work=The Independent|accessdate=May 13, 2018|date=May 10, 1993|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180513081645/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/pin-up-exposed-why-marky-mark-is-taking-the-rap-the-man-wearing-calvin-kleins-pants-could-be-undone-2322005.html|archive-date=May 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A self-titled autobiographical [[picture book]] ''Marky Mark'', with images taken by [[Lynn Goldsmith]] and statements mostly by him was also released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/1993/01/15/marketing-marky-mark/|title=The marketing of Marky Mark|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=May 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517082259/http://ew.com/article/1993/01/15/marketing-marky-mark/|archive-date=May 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Trying to resuscitate his music career, he had shifted to [[Hamburg]] where he was produced under the label of [[East West Records]] by [[Frank Peterson]] and [[Alex Christensen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YQ8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA72&dq=marky+mark+Germany#v=onepage&q=marky%20mark%20Germany&f=false|title=Billboard \u2013 31 May 2017 |work=Billboard|accessdate=May 13, 2018|date=May 31, 1997 }}</ref>\n\nWahlberg later collaborated with the late reggae/[[ragga]] singer [[Prince Ital Joe]] on the album ''[[Life in the Streets]]''. The project combined rap vocals, electronic-infused ragga, and \"European dancefloor\" music, delivering the singles \"Happy People\", German number one hit \"United\", \"Life in the Streets\", and \"Babylon\", with Frank Peterson and Alex Christensen as producers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZwgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA54&lpg=PA54&dq=life+in+the+streets+marky+mark+1994#v=onepage&q=life%20in%20the%20streets%20marky%20mark%201994&f=false|title=Billboard|work=google.com|accessdate=July 28, 2015|date=December 3, 1994}}</ref> Many of these tracks featured on the hit film ''[[Renaissance Man (film)|Renaissance Man]]'', starring Wahlberg and [[Danny Devito]].\n\nIn 1995, he released a single titled \"No Mercy\" in support of his friend [[Dariusz Michalczewski]], whom he had befriended earlier in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/02/opinion/slawomir-sierakowski-Dariusz-Michalczewski-from-pugilist-to-activist.html?smid=tw-nytimes&_r=1&referrer= | work=The New York Times | first=Slawomir | last=Sierakowski | title=From Pugilist to Activist | date=October 1, 2014}}</ref> Michalczewski also appears in the music video of the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/straight-world-famous-boxer-makes-headlines-supporting-lgbt-equality-poland041014|title=Straight world-famous boxer makes headlines for supporting for LGBT equality in Poland|work=Gay Star News|accessdate=July 28, 2015|date=October 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715170502/http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/straight-world-famous-boxer-makes-headlines-supporting-lgbt-equality-poland041014/|archive-date=July 15, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Wahlberg and Prince Ital Joe released another album in 1995 for Ultraphonic Records. Titled ''[[The Remix Album (Prince Ital Joe album)|The Remix Album]]'', it featured remixes from the duo's previous album, ''Life in the Streets'', as well as the Mark's solo track, \"No Mercy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/artists/mark-wahlberg/biography/|title=Mark Wahlberg Bio \u2013 Mark Wahlberg Career|work=MTV Artists|accessdate=July 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150808232721/http://www.mtv.com/artists/mark-wahlberg/biography/|archive-date=August 8, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter his album with Ital Joe became a hit in Germany, he started putting together a [[Musical ensemble|musical act]] called One Love with him as its producer and also sometimes its lead singer. He also started production on a third studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HYc7AQAAIAAJ&q=success+ital+joe+one+love&dq=success+ital+joe+one+love|title=The New York Times Magazine|work=The New York Times|accessdate=May 14, 2018|date=July 1997}}</ref> He featured in their song titled \"That's the Way I Like It\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hitparade.ch/song/One-Love-feat.-Marky-Mark/That's-The-Way-I-Like-It-743758 |title=One Love feat. Marky Mark \u2013 That's The Way I Like It |work=hitparade.ch |accessdate=September 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906035532/https://hitparade.ch/song/One-Love-feat.-Marky-Mark/That%27s-The-Way-I-Like-It-743758 |archive-date=September 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1996, Wahlberg released a solo single titled \"Hey DJ\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitparade.ch/song/Marky-Mark/Hey-DJ-21180 |title=Marky Mark \u2013 Hey DJ \u2013 hitparade.ch |accessdate=January 22, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418130037/http://hitparade.ch/song/Marky-Mark/Hey-DJ-21180 |archivedate=April 18, 2015}}</ref> Two solo tracks titled \"Feel the Vibe\" and \"Best of my Love\" were released in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hitparade.ch/song/Marky-Mark/Feel-The-Vibe-41006 |title=MARKY MARK \u2013 FEEL THE VIBE |access-date=May 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626220125/https://hitparade.ch/song/Marky-Mark/Feel-The-Vibe-41006 |archive-date=June 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitparade.ch/song/Marky-Mark/Best-Of-My-Love-765570 |title=Marky Mark \u2013 Best of My Love \u2013 hitparade.ch |accessdate=January 22, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418130114/http://hitparade.ch/song/Marky-Mark/Best-Of-My-Love-765570 |archivedate=April 18, 2015 }}</ref> All the solo tracks, along with another song titled \"Here With Me\", were released on an album titled ''All Around the World'' in 1997 that also included the remixed versions of the songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Marky+Mark/All+Around+the+World|title=All Around the World|work=Last.fm|accessdate=July 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117135003/http://www.last.fm/music/Marky+Mark/All+Around+the+World|archive-date=January 17, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, he was also featured in the [[Black Label Society]] music video for \"[[Counterfeit God]]\", as a stand-in for the band's bassist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1431836/wahlbergs-dragon-megadeth-more-to-play-la/|title=Wahlberg's \"Dragon,\" Megadeth, More To Play L.A.|work=MTV News|accessdate=July 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527161658/http://www.mtv.com/news/1431836/wahlbergs-dragon-megadeth-more-to-play-la/|archive-date=May 27, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Advertising===\nWahlberg first displayed his physique in the \"Good Vibrations\" music video and most prominently in a series of underwear ads for [[Calvin Klein (company)|Calvin Klein]] (1992)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://explore.calvinklein.com/en_US/timeline/1992/9|title=Calvin Klein Underwear|work=Calvin Klein|access-date=November 23, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104044302/http://explore.calvinklein.com/en_US/timeline/1992/9|archive-date=January 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> shot by [[Herb Ritts]], following it with Calvin Klein television advertisements.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Eric|title=Stretching a Six-Pack|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/13/fashion/13calvin.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 28, 2011|date=May 12, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113225808/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/13/fashion/13calvin.html|archive-date=January 13, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Magazine and television promotions would sometimes feature Wahlberg exclusively or accompanied by model [[Kate Moss]]. [[Annie Leibovitz]] also shot a famous session of Wahlberg in underwear for [[Vanity Fair (magazine)|''Vanity Fair'']]'s annual Hall of Fame issue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jossip.com/category/annie-leibovitz/ |title=Annie Leibovitz / Jossip |publisher=Jossip.com |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906215433/http://www.jossip.com/category/annie-leibovitz/ |archive-date=September 6, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> He also made a workout video titled ''The Marky Mark Workout: Form... Focus... Fitness'' ({{ISBN|1-55510-910-1}}).\n\nIn 2012, Wahlberg began serving as a brand ambassador for a line of sports nutrition supplements by [[GNC (store)|GNC]] called Marked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nutraingredients-usa.com/Article/2012/04/18/Good-vibrations-Mark-Wahlberg-and-GNC-create-new-MARKED-sports-nutrition-range|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421025000/http://www.nutraingredients-usa.com/Industry/Good-vibrations-Mark-Wahlberg-and-GNC-create-new-MARKED-sports-nutrition-range|url-status=dead|title=Good vibrations? Mark Wahlberg and GNC create new MARKED sports nutrition range|archivedate=April 21, 2012|website=nutraingredients-usa.com}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, [[AT&T]] announced that Wahlberg would become a spokesman and he would create original content for the mobile network division. The deal would reportedly pay Wahlberg more than $10 million.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Emily |url=http://pagesix.com/2017/03/13/mark-wahlberg-lands-eight-figure-deal-with-att/ |title=Mark Wahlberg lands eight-figure deal with AT&T |work=[[New York Post]] |date=March 13, 2017 |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315162158/http://pagesix.com/2017/03/13/mark-wahlberg-lands-eight-figure-deal-with-att/ |archive-date=March 15, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Film ===\n[[File:Mark Wahlberg.jpg|thumb|upright|Wahlberg at the London premiere of ''[[Shooter (2007 film)|Shooter]]'' in 2007]]\n\nIn 1993, Wahlberg made his acting debut in the TV film ''The Substitute''. After this appearance, he dropped the \"Marky Mark\" name. His big screen d\u00e9but came the next year, with the [[Danny DeVito]] feature ''[[Renaissance Man (film)|Renaissance Man]]''. A basketball fanatic, he caught the attention of critics after appearing in ''[[The Basketball Diaries (film)|The Basketball Diaries]]'' in 1995, playing the role of Mickey alongside [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], in a film adaptation of the [[Jim Carroll]] book of the [[The Basketball Diaries (book)|same name]]. He had his first starring role in the 1996 [[James Foley (director)|James Foley]] thriller ''[[Fear (1996 film)|Fear]]''.\n\nHe earned positive reviews after films such as ''[[Boogie Nights]]'' (as Dirk Diggler), ''[[Three Kings (1999 film)|Three Kings]]'', ''[[The Perfect Storm (film)|The Perfect Storm]]'', and ''[[Four Brothers (film)|Four Brothers]]''. During the early 2000s, Wahlberg appeared in remakes of 1960s films such as ''[[Planet of the Apes (2001 film)|Planet of the Apes]]'', ''[[The Truth About Charlie]]'' (remake of ''[[Charade (1963 film)|Charade]]''), and ''[[The Italian Job (2003 film)|The Italian Job]]''. His performance in ''[[I Heart Huckabees]]'' was voted best supporting performance of the year in the 2004 ''[[The Village Voice]]'' Critics Poll. Wahlberg was originally cast as Linus Caldwell in ''[[Ocean's Eleven]]''; [[Matt Damon]] played the role instead. The two later worked together in ''[[The Departed]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmfodder.com/archive/oceans11 |title=filmfodder.com: archive: ocean's 11 |publisher=Filmfodder.com |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012213914/http://www.filmfodder.com/archive/oceans11/ |archive-date=October 12, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> Wahlberg was also considered for a role in the film ''[[Brokeback Mountain]]''. It was originally intended to star Wahlberg and [[Joaquin Phoenix]] (with whom he appeared in the 2000 film ''[[The Yards]]'') as [[Ennis Del Mar]] and [[Jack Twist]], respectively, but both actors were uncomfortable with the film's sex scenes. The roles ultimately went to [[Heath Ledger]] and [[Jake Gyllenhaal]], both of whom were nominated for Academy Awards for their performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2007/02/28/brokeback_mountain_script_creeped_out_ma |title='Brokeback Mountain' Script 'Creeped Out' Mark Wahlberg \u2013 Starpulse Entertainment News Blog |publisher=Starpulse.com |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210082039/http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2007/02/28/brokeback_mountain_script_creeped_out_ma |archivedate=December 10, 2008 |df=}}</ref>\n\nWahlberg starred in the American football drama ''[[Invincible (2006 film)|Invincible]]'', based on the true story of bartender [[Vince Papale]]. He was also the executive producer of the [[HBO]] series ''[[Entourage (U.S. TV series)|Entourage]]'' (2004\u20132011), which was loosely based on his experiences in Hollywood. In 2006, he appeared as an unpleasant, foul-mouthed [[Massachusetts State Police]] detective in [[Martin Scorsese]]'s critically acclaimed thriller, ''[[The Departed]]'', which netted him an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]], a [[Golden Globe]] nomination for Best Performance by an Actor in a Supporting Role in a Motion Picture, and a [[National Society of Film Critics]] Best Supporting Actor award. Wahlberg has confirmed that he was approached to star in a sequel to ''The Departed'', but it is still early in development. The sequel would reportedly revolve around the staff sergeant played by Wahlberg.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[File:Mark Wahlberg May 2014 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Wahlberg at the Australian premiere of ''[[Transformers: Age of Extinction]]'' in 2014]]\n\nDespite his felony conviction, which legally prohibits him from handling firearms, Wahlberg prepared for his role in ''[[Shooter (2007 film)|Shooter]]'' by attending long-range shooting training at [[Front Sight Firearms Training Institute]] near [[Pahrump, Nevada]]. He was able to hit a target at 1,100 yards on his second day, a feat which usually takes weeks to achieve.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visualhollywood.com/movies/shooter/about4.php |title=Wahlberg goes to sniper school: About training as a shooter |publisher=VisualHollywood.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110930131546/http://www.visualhollywood.com/movies/shooter/about4.php |archivedate=September 30, 2011 }}</ref> He had said in a number of interviews that he would retire at the age of 40 to concentrate on parenthood<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitytvworld.com/news/actor-mark-wahlberg-says-he-plans-retire-at-age-40-1004076.php|title=Actor Mark Wahlberg says he plans to retire at age 40|access-date=January 23, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011131411/http://realitytvworld.com/news/actor-mark-wahlberg-says-he-plans-retire-at-age-40-1004076.php|archive-date=October 11, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[professional golf]]. However, in early 2007 he indicated that the latter was no longer the plan as \"his golf game is horrible\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbo.com/entourage/interviews/mark_wahlberg.html?ntrack_para1=insidehbo6_text|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307223359/http://www.hbo.com/entourage/interviews/mark_wahlberg.html?ntrack_para1=insidehbo6_text|archivedate=March 7, 2008|title=HBO interview}}</ref> He played Jack Salmon, a leading role in [[Peter Jackson]]'s film of ''[[The Lovely Bones (film)|The Lovely Bones]]''.<ref name=\"DominionPost\">{{cite news | last = Cardy | first = Tom | title = Lovely Bones' Gosling in shock exit | publisher = Dominion Post | date = October 23, 2007 | url = http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/4247770a10.html | accessdate = October 23, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071024103617/http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/4247770a10.html | archive-date = October 24, 2007 | url-status = live}}</ref> In 2007, he starred opposite Joaquin Phoenix in ''[[We Own the Night (film)|We Own the Night]]'', a movie about a family of police officers in New York City.\n\nHe starred in [[M. Night Shyamalan]]'s ''[[The Happening (2008 film)|The Happening]]'' as Eliot Moore, which premiered in movie theatres on June 13, 2008. The same year, he played the title role in ''[[Max Payne (film)|Max Payne]]'', based on a video game of the [[Max Payne (video game)|same name]]. While promoting ''Max Payne'', Wahlberg became involved in a playful feud with [[The Lonely Island]]'s [[Andy Samberg]]. Samberg had done an impression of Wahlberg in a ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' sketch titled \"Mark Wahlberg Talks to Animals\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/red-101808-samberg,0,4155250.story |title=Wahlberg threatens to punch SNL's Samberg over impression |work=Chicago Tribune |author=RedEye |date=October 26, 2008 |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081028213729/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/red-101808-samberg%2C0%2C4155250.story |archivedate=October 28, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/digital-shorts/video/mark-wahlberg-talks-to-animals/727504/ |title=Saturday Night Live \u2013 Mark Wahlberg Talks to Animals \u2013 Video |publisher=Nbc.com |accessdate=January 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423010537/http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/digital-shorts/video/mark-wahlberg-talks-to-animals/727504 |archivedate=April 23, 2013 }}</ref> Wahlberg later appeared in a follow-up sketch parodying the original one, Samberg's impression of Wahlberg, and his own threats to Samberg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/digital-shorts/video/mark-wahlberg-backstage/773862/ |title=Saturday Night Live \u2013 Mark Wahlberg Backstage \u2013 Video |publisher=Nbc.com |accessdate=January 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313095447/http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/digital-shorts/video/mark-wahlberg-backstage/773862 |archivedate=March 13, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popeater.com/television/article/mark-wahlberg-cracks-jokes-not-noses/217025 |title=Mark Wahlberg Cracks Jokes, Not Noses |publisher=Popeater.com |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022053508/http://www.popeater.com/television/article/mark-wahlberg-cracks-jokes-not-noses/217025 |archive-date=October 22, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a February 2007 interview with ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'', updated in 2010, Wahlberg stated that there might be a sequel to ''The Departed'', focusing on his character, Dignam, with [[Robert De Niro]] potentially playing a corrupt senator. He also stated that [[William Monahan]] was writing the script.<ref>{{cite news |title=Exclusive: News On Departed 2... And 3! |publisher=EmpireOnline.com |date=February 7, 2007 |url=http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=20343 |accessdate=February 7, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070209055637/http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=20343 |archive-date=February 9, 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film is said to be on hold, because producer [[Brad Grey]] is now the head of [[Paramount Pictures]] and the film is a [[Warner Bros.]] project.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/761/761346p1.html|title=No Departed 2 Just Yet|author=Stax|date=February 5, 2007|accessdate=February 7, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206210415/http://movies.ign.com/articles/761/761346p1.html|archive-date=February 6, 2007|url-status=dead|website=IGN}}</ref> In June 2010, Wahlberg and Monahan continued to express interest in a sequel, then said to be projected for 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Departed Sequel Will Arrive in 2012 |url=http://thefilmstage.com/2010/06/10/the-departed-sequel-arriving-in-2012 |publisher=TheFilmStage.com |accessdate=June 10, 2010 |date=June 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618172958/http://thefilmstage.com/2010/06/10/the-departed-sequel-arriving-in-2012/ |archivedate=June 18, 2010 }}</ref> Nothing further has been announced.\n\nIn 2012, Wahlberg starred in Seth MacFarlane's hit comedy ''[[Ted (film)|Ted]]''. He returned in the same role in the 2015 sequel ''[[Ted 2]]''. Wahlberg later starred as [[United States Navy SEALs|Navy SEAL]] [[Marcus Luttrell]] in the war film ''[[Lone Survivor]]'' (2013), based on Luttrell's 2007 [[Lone Survivor (book)|book of the same name]]. The film received commercial success and mostly positive reviews, and Wahlberg's performance was highly praised. In 2014, Wahlberg starred in the [[The Gambler (2014 film)|remake]] of ''[[The Gambler (1974 film)|The Gambler]]'', the 1974 [[James Caan]] film that was loosely inspired by [[The Gambler (novel)|the Dostoyevsky novella]].<ref>Bahr, Lindsey (2013). \"Casting Net: Brie Larson in talks to star opposite Mark Wahlberg,\" October 17, 2013.</ref><ref>Bahr, Lindsey (2013). \"Casting Net: Brie Larson,\" October 17, 2013.</ref> In 2015, he starred opposite Will Ferrell in the comedy ''[[Daddy's Home (film)|Daddy's Home]]''. In 2016, he starred in two [[Peter Berg]] films, ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'' and ''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]''.\n\nWahlberg topped the list of the world's highest-paid actors in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/shah-rukh-khan-salman-khan-akshay-kumar-on-forbes-highest-paid-actors-list-topped-by-mark-wahlberg-1740826?pfrom=home-topstories|title=Shah Rukh Khan, Salman Khan, Akshay Kumar On Forbes' Highest Paid Actors List. Aamir Khan? Nope|publisher=|access-date=August 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170823115205/http://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/shah-rukh-khan-salman-khan-akshay-kumar-on-forbes-highest-paid-actors-list-topped-by-mark-wahlberg-1740826?pfrom=home-topstories|archive-date=August 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018, his salary of $1.5&nbsp;million for reshoots for ''[[All the Money in the World]]'' caused controversy because his female co-star [[Michelle Williams (actress)|Michelle Williams]] received less than $1,000. Wahlberg donated the money to [[Time's Up (movement)|Time's Up]], a movement against sexual harassment co-founded by Williams.<ref>{{cite news|last1=staff|first1=Guardian|title=Mark Wahlberg donates $1.5m reward for film reshoots to Time's Up fund|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/13/mark-wahlberg-all-the-money-in-the-world-michelle-williams|accessdate=January 13, 2018|work=The Guardian|date=January 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113230642/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/13/mark-wahlberg-all-the-money-in-the-world-michelle-williams|archive-date=January 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWalhberg produced and starred in the hacker film ''[[Mile 22]]'' and has set to appear in the Netflix film ''[[Spenser Confidential]]'' and the animated movie ''[[Scoob]]'' which is his first voicing acting role career. In November 2019, Wahlberg was cast in the upcoming ''[[Uncharted (film)|Uncharted]]'' film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/mark-wahlberg-tom-holland-uncharted-movie-sony-1203394336/ |title=Mark Wahlberg Joins Tom Holland in 'Uncharted' Movie (EXCLUSIVE) |website=[[Variety (website)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=November 13, 2019 |accessdate=November 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113210937/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/mark-wahlberg-tom-holland-uncharted-movie-sony-1203394336/ |archive-date=November 13, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Business interests===\nWahlberg co-owns [[Wahlburgers]] with his brothers Donnie and Paul.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aetv.com/wahlburgers/video/rheas-requests-for-mark|title=Watch the Rhea's Requests for Mark Video - Wahlburgers - A&E|work=aetv|accessdate=July 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150729102459/http://www.aetv.com/wahlburgers/video/rheas-requests-for-mark|archive-date=July 29, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It was Mark's idea to expand Paul's restaurant in [[Hingham, Massachusetts]], into a full-fledged chain with a reality show to promote it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-28/wahlburgers-donnie-mark-paul-wahlberg-plot-fast-food-empire|title=Wahlburgers: Donnie, Mark, Paul Wahlberg Plot Fast-Food Empire - Bloomberg Business|author=Joel Stein|date=May 28, 2015|work=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=July 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150819124936/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-28/wahlburgers-donnie-mark-paul-wahlberg-plot-fast-food-empire|archive-date=August 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Wahlberg bought an equity interest of the [[Barbados Tridents]] [[cricket]] team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wahlberg owns Barbados Tridents |author=Staff writer |url=http://www.cbc.bb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7622%3Awahlberg-owns-barbados-tridents&catid=25%3Alocal-sports&Itemid=88 |newspaper=[[Caribbean Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] |date=July 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |accessdate=September 18, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714122120/http://www.cbc.bb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7622%3Awahlberg-owns-barbados-tridents&catid=25%3Alocal-sports&Itemid=88 |archivedate=July 14, 2014  }}</ref> Wahlberg was introduced to the game by his friend Ajmal Khan, the club's chairman and [[Caribbean Premier League]] founder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity-life/mark-wahlberg-buys-stake-in-caribbean-cricket-team-claims-to-be-a-huge-fan/news-story/3ba4b4a937c546a028ff077054cea7d5|title=Wahlberg buys stake in cricket team|date=August 5, 2013|publisher=[[News Corp Australia Network]]|accessdate=August 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626220120/https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity-life/mark-wahlberg-buys-stake-in-caribbean-cricket-team-claims-to-be-a-huge-fan/news-story/3ba4b4a937c546a028ff077054cea7d5|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.caribjournal.com/2013/07/31/mark-wahlberg-takes-stake-in-caribbean-cricket-team/ |title=Mark Wahlberg Takes Stake in Caribbean Cricket Team |author=Journal staff |date=July 31, 2013 |publisher=Carib Journal |accessdate= |quote=Limacol CPL CEO Damien O'Donohoe said the league was \"thrilled\" that Wahlberg had taken an equity interest in the team. |ref= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130803072016/http://www.caribjournal.com/2013/07/31/mark-wahlberg-takes-stake-in-caribbean-cricket-team/ |archive-date=August 3, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following the announcement, Wahlberg stated, \"I am a huge cricket fan now. I'm excited to be a part of the Limacol Caribbean Premier League because I know cricket is huge in the Caribbean and a rich part of the region's heritage. Sports and entertainment are a powerful combination, and the LCPL will appeal to a huge audience worldwide.\"<ref name=\"GT\">{{cite web |url=http://www.guyanatimesgy.com/?p=25270 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130801090633/http://www.guyanatimesgy.com/?p=25270 |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 1, 2013 |title=Hollywood glamour comes to Limacol CPL, Mark Wahlberg on board with Barbados |author=Staff writer |date=July 30, 2013 |publisher=Guyana Times |accessdate= |quote=Limacol Caribbean Premier League cricket officials announced that American actor Mark Wahlberg has taken an equity interest in the Barbados Tridents team. |ref= |separator= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Wahlberg recruited rapper [[Sean Combs]] and billionaire [[Ronald Burkle]] to join him in investing in Aquahydrate, a bottled water brand Wahlberg discovered. Together, the three men own a majority stake in the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2015/02/04/liquid-asset-inside-mark-wahlberg-diddy-and-ron-burkles-aquahydrate/|title=Liquid Asset: Inside Mark Wahlberg, Diddy and Ron Burkle's Aquahydrate Investment|last=Greenburg|first=Zack O'Malley|date=February 4, 2015|website=Forbes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319120314/https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2015/02/04/liquid-asset-inside-mark-wahlberg-diddy-and-ron-burkles-aquahydrate/|archive-date=March 19, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> Wahlberg, together with former [[GNC (store)|GNC]] executive Tom Dowd, co-founded Performance Inspired, a [[sports nutrition]] company launched in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/news/2016/12/08/former-gnc-exec-mark-wahlberg-launch-new-product.html|title=Former GNC exec, Mark Wahlberg launch new product line|last=Schooley|first=Tim|date=December 8, 2016|website=Pittsburgh Business Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319124915/https://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/news/2016/12/08/former-gnc-exec-mark-wahlberg-launch-new-product.html|archive-date=March 19, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> In February 2017, Wahlberg was one of the investors who took part in a $6 million funding round for StockX, a sneaker resale marketplace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2017/02/15/mark-wahlberg-eminem-sneakers/|title=Mark Wahlberg and Eminem Have Invested in a Sneaker Stock Market|last=Kell|first=John|date=February 15, 2017|website=Fortune|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215184516/http://fortune.com/2017/02/15/mark-wahlberg-eminem-sneakers/|archive-date=February 15, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> On July 20, 2018, Wahlberg and his business partner, Jay Feldman, announced the purchase of Bobby Layman Chevrolet in Columbus, Ohio. The dealership was renamed Mark Wahlberg Chevrolet.<ref>Navera, Tristan (July 20, 2018). [https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/20/mark-wahlberg-is-buying-bobby-layman-chevrolet.html \"Mark Wahlberg \u2013 yes, that Mark Wahlberg \u2013 is buying Bobby Layman Chevrolet\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907032223/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/20/mark-wahlberg-is-buying-bobby-layman-chevrolet.html |date=September 7, 2018 }}. [[CNBC]]. Retrieved September 6, 2018.</ref> In March 2019, Wahlberg bought a stake in the F45 fitness franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/marky-mark-to-get-hands-on-with-the-f45-bunch-20190319-p515h1.html|title=Marky Mark to get hands-on with the F45 bunch|last=Croffey|first=Amy|date=March 19, 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319113940/https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/marky-mark-to-get-hands-on-with-the-f45-bunch-20190319-p515h1.html?js-chunk-not-found-refresh=true|archive-date=March 19, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Television production===\nIn 2014, Wahlberg was the producer of the reality show ''Breaking Boston'', which was pulled off the air after its premiere had 311,000 viewers.<ref name=Steinberg>{{cite news|last=Steinberg|first=Brian|title=A&E Pulls Mark Wahlberg's 'Breaking Boston' After One Week|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/ae-pulls-breaking-boston-from-schedule-1201140750/|accessdate=March 22, 2014|newspaper=Variety|date=March 20, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322075549/http://variety.com/2014/tv/news/ae-pulls-breaking-boston-from-schedule-1201140750/|archive-date=March 22, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He executive-produced one episode of ''[[Wahlburgers]]'', while co-starring in it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3333880/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Wahlburgers (TV Series 2014\u2013 )|publisher=|access-date=July 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407160939/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt3333880/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|archive-date=April 7, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Charities==\nWahlberg established the Mark Wahlberg Youth Foundation in May 2001 for the purpose of raising and distributing funds to youth service and enrichment programs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://markwahlbergyouthfoundation.com |title=The Mark Wahlberg Youth Foundation |publisher=Markwahlbergyouthfoundation.com |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/65ckyPSjy?url=http://markwahlbergyouthfoundation.com/ |archive-date=February 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nWahlberg is active with The Good Shepherd Center for Homeless Women and Children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_-_NXReiXtU |title=Mark Wahlberg on How He Helps the Homeless |publisher=Youtube.com |date= |accessdate=January 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWahlberg married model [[Rhea Durham]] on August 1, 2009 at the [[Church of the Good Shepherd (Beverly Hills, California)|Good Shepherd Catholic Church]] in Beverly Hills.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20295454,00.html|title=Mark Wahlberg Gets Married!|date=August 1, 2009|author=Pernilla Cederheim|magazine=People.com|accessdate=April 26, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601023006/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20295454,00.html|archive-date=June 1, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> They have four children: daughters Ella Rae (b. 2003) and Grace Margaret (b. 2010), and sons Michael (b. 2006) and Brendan Joseph (b. 2008).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20336350,00.html|title=It's a Girl for Mark Wahlberg|date=January 13, 2010|first=Julie|last=Jordan|work=People|accessdate=April 26, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930035607/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20336350,00.html|archive-date=September 30, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Mark Wahlberg Max Payne 2008.jpg|thumb|upright|Wahlberg at the premiere of ''[[Max Payne (film)|Max Payne]]'' in 2008]]\n\nWahlberg's father, Donald a [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] veteran of the [[Korean War]], died on February 14, 2008.<ref name=dadobit>{{cite web|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/obituaries/death_notices/view.bg?articleid=1073799 |title=Donald E. Wahlberg [obituary] |work=[[Boston Herald]]|date=February 18, 2008 |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080301184308/http://www.bostonherald.com/news/obituaries/death_notices/view.bg?articleid=1073799 |archivedate=March 1, 2008  }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Wahlberg was quoted in a magazine interview regarding what would have happened if he had flown aboard [[American Airlines Flight 11]] on [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001]]. He had been booked on Flight 11, but his plans changed the day before the scheduled flight and he cancelled his reservation. Wahlberg received public criticism for stating, \"If I was on that plane with my kids, it wouldn't have went down like it did,\" and \"There would have been a lot of blood in that first-class cabin and then me saying, 'OK, we're going to land somewhere safely, don't worry.{{'\"}} Wahlberg issued a public apology after family members of those killed on the flight expressed outrage about his statements.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2012/01/18/mark-wahlberg-said-would-have-defeated-11-terrorists-on-flight-3/|title=Mark Wahlberg sorry for saying he would have thwarted 9/11 terrorists|work=Fox News|accessdate=July 28, 2015|date=January 18, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102202329/http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2012/01/18/mark-wahlberg-said-would-have-defeated-11-terrorists-on-flight-3/|archive-date=November 2, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA committed [[Roman Catholic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.christiantoday.com/article/mark-wahlberg-talks-central-role-of-faith-and-prayer-in-his-daily-life/12692.htm|title=Mark Wahlberg talks central role of faith and prayer in his daily life|first=Stoyan |last=Zaimov|publisher=[[Christian Today]] Australia|date=January 18, 2012|accessdate=July 28, 2015| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826174701/http://christiantoday.com.au/article/mark-wahlberg-talks-central-role-of-faith-and-prayer-in-his-daily-life/12692.htm | archivedate=August 26, 2014}}</ref> Wahlberg openly supports [[same-sex marriage]], despite the church's opposition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/International/Actor-Mark-Wahlberg-raises-eyebrows-as-host-of-Philadelphia-Pope-concert-419211 |title=Conservative Catholic blog Rorate Caeli called Wahlberg out for his support of gay marriage, which the Church strongly opposes. |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |location=Israel |date=September 27, 2015 |accessdate=August 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315155422/http://www.jpost.com/International/Actor-Mark-Wahlberg-raises-eyebrows-as-host-of-Philadelphia-Pope-concert-419211 |archive-date=March 15, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2015, he apologized to [[Pope Francis]] about the crude jokes he made in the film ''[[Ted (film)|Ted]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/article/mark-wahlberg-jokes-pope-francis-ted-video |last=Mercedes Lara |first=Maria |title=Mark Wahlberg Jokes About Ted with Pope Francis: I Hope the 'Good Lord Has a Sense of Humor' About My Movies |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=September 27, 2015 |accessdate=August 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707122003/http://www.people.com/article/mark-wahlberg-jokes-pope-francis-ted-video |archive-date=July 7, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> and in October 2017, in a public interview conducted by [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Catholic Cardinal]] [[Blase J. Cupich|Blase Cupich]] of Chicago, stated that he has sought forgiveness from God for portraying a porn actor in ''[[Boogie Nights]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Janssen|first=Kim|title=Mark Wahlberg says he prayed to God for forgiveness for ''Boogie Nights''|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chicagoinc/ct-met-cupich-wahlberg-1022-chicago-inc-20171020-story.html|accessdate=October 25, 2017|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=October 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024225501/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chicagoinc/ct-met-cupich-wahlberg-1022-chicago-inc-20171020-story.html|archive-date=October 24, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title = Mark Wahlberg has prayed for forgiveness over 1997 film Boogie Nights|first = Broede|last = Carmody|date = October 26, 2017|accessdate = October 29, 2017|newspaper = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|url = http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/mark-wahlberg-has-prayed-for-forgiveness-over-1997-film-boogie-nights-20171024-gz7lpf.html|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171029065833/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/mark-wahlberg-has-prayed-for-forgiveness-over-1997-film-boogie-nights-20171024-gz7lpf.html|archive-date = October 29, 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> He later stated on [[Andy Cohen (TV personality)|Andy Cohen]]'s radio show, ''Radio Andy'', that the interview \"was a joke taken too seriously.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v0-_0gkYxvA|title=Mark Wahlberg: Asking forgiveness for \"Boogie Nights\" was a joke taken seriously|date=November 18, 2017|first=Andy |last=Cohen|work= People| accessdate=October 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1994\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Renaissance Man (film)|Renaissance Man]]''\n| Private Tommy Lee Haywood\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1995\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Basketball Diaries (film)|The Basketball Diaries]]''\n| Mickey\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1996\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Fear (1996 film)|Fear]]''\n| David McCall\n| \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|1997\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Traveller (1997 film)|Traveller]]''\n| Pat O'Hara\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Boogie Nights]]''\n| Eddie Adams / Dirk Diggler\n| \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1998\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Big Hit]]''\n| Melvin Smiley\n| \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; \"rowspan=2| 1999\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Corruptor]]''\n| Detective Danny Wallace\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Three Kings (1999 film)|Three Kings]]''\n| Troy Barlow\n| \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|2000\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Yards]]''\n| Leo Handler\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Perfect Storm (film)|The Perfect Storm]]''\n| Robert \"Bobby\" Shatford\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2| 2001\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Planet of the Apes (2001 film)|Pla