markwahlberg.com}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background  = solo_singer\n| alias = Marky Mark\n| genre = {{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[Eurodance]]|[[contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Pop music|pop]]|[[new jack swing]]}}\n| instrument = Vocals\n| label = {{hlist|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch]]|[[Prince Ital Joe]]}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Mark Robert Michael Wahlberg''' (born June 5, 1971)<ref name=biography.com /> is an American actor, producer, businessman, [[Model (person)|model]], rapper, singer and songwriter. He is also known by his former stage name '''Marky Mark''', from his career as frontman for the group, [[Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch]], with whom he released the albums ''[[Music for the People (Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch album)|Music for the People]]'' (1991) and ''[[You Gotta Believe]]'' (1992).\n\nFrom his early music career Wahlberg transitioned to acting, with his screen debut in ''[[Renaissance Man (film)|Renaissance Man]]'' (1994) and his first starring role in ''[[Fear (1996 film)|Fear]]'' (1996). He received critical praise for his performance as porn actor Dirk Diggler in ''[[Boogie Nights]]''. In the early 2000s, he ventured into big budget action-oriented movies, such as ''[[The Perfect Storm (film)|The Perfect Storm]]'' (2000), ''[[Planet of the Apes (2001 film)|Planet of the Apes]]'' (2001) and ''[[The Italian Job (2003 film)|The Italian Job]]'' (2003). For playing a police officer in the neo-crime drama ''[[The Departed]]'' (2006), he earned a nomination for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]]. For the biographical sports drama ''[[The Fighter]]'' (2010), in which he starred as [[Micky Ward]], Wahlberg received a nomination for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe Award for Best Actor]]. In the 2010s, he landed successful comedy roles with ''[[The Other Guys]]'' (2010), ''[[Daddy's Home (film)|Daddy's Home]]'' (2015) and its [[Daddy's Home 2|2017 sequel]],  ''[[Ted (film)|Ted]]'' (2012) and its [[Ted 2|2015 sequel]], and became the protagonist in the ''[[Transformers (film series)|Transformers]]'' live-action film franchise (2014, 2017). He was the world's best-paid actor in 2017.\n\nWahlberg also served as executive producer of five [[HBO]] series: the comedy-drama ''[[Entourage (U.S. TV series)|Entourage]]'' (2004\u20132011), the period crime drama ''[[Boardwalk Empire]]'' (2010\u20132014), the comedy-dramas ''[[How to Make It in America]]'' (2010\u20132011) and ''[[Ballers]]'' (2015\u20132019) and documentary McMillions (2020) He is co-owner of the [[Wahlburgers]] chain and co-starred in the [[Wahlburgers (TV series)|reality TV series]] about it. Wahlberg received a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in 2010.\n\n== Early life ==\nWahlberg was born in the [[Dorchester, Boston|Dorchester]] neighborhood of [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], the youngest of nine children,<ref name=biography.com>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/mark-wahlberg-9542335 |title=Mark Wahlberg Biography: Film Actor, Rapper (1971\u2013) |publisher=[[Biography.com]] ([[FYI (TV network)|FYI]] / [[A&E Networks]]) |accessdate=August 14, 2010| archivedate=October 2, 2015| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151002105429/http://www.biography.com/people/mark-wahlberg-9542335 | url-status=live}}</ref> including actor [[Robert Wahlberg|Robert]] and singer and actor [[Donnie Wahlberg|Donnie]]. His mother, Alma Elaine (n\u00e9e Donnelly), was a bank clerk and a nurse's aide, and his father, Donald Edmond Wahlberg, was a delivery driver.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/mark-wahlberg-on-his-mom-shes-not-speaking-to-me-right-now-2013512|title=Mark Wahlberg: 'My Mom's Not Speaking to Me Right Now'|work=[[Us Weekly]]|first=Stephanie|last=Webber|date=December 5, 2013|access-date=December 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151227095217/http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/mark-wahlberg-on-his-mom-shes-not-speaking-to-me-right-now-2013512|archive-date=December 27, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=dadobit /> His parents divorced in 1982, and afterward, he divided his time between them.<ref>{{cite news|last=Galloway|first=Stephen|title=Mark Wahlberg on 'Entourage' Cast Apology, Wish to Own a Studio and 'Highway to Heaven' Reboot Pitch|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lone-survivor-mark-wahlberg-entourage-664601?page=3|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=January 8, 2014|page=3|date=December 12, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216211920/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lone-survivor-mark-wahlberg-entourage-664601?page=3|archive-date=December 16, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> His father was of [[Sweden|Swedish]] and [[Irish people|Irish]] descent, and his mother is of [[England|English]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wargs.com/other/wahlberg.html |title=Ancestry of Mark Wahlberg |publisher=Wargs.com |accessdate=January 10, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140127033328/http://www.wargs.com/other/wahlberg.html |archive-date=January 27, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> Maternally, Wahlberg is distantly related to author [[Nathaniel Hawthorne]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2011/05/14/just_call_chris_child_pop_cultures_genealogy_sleuth/?p1=Upbox_links | work=The Boston Globe | first=Kathleen | last=Pierce | title=Just call him pop culture's sleuth | date=May 14, 2011 | access-date=May 14, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103150258/http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2011/05/14/just_call_chris_child_pop_cultures_genealogy_sleuth/?p1=Upbox_links | archive-date=November 3, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> Wahlberg had a Roman Catholic upbringing<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/movies/mark-of-a-man/story-e6frf9h6-1111117540758|title=Mark of a man|work=Herald Sun|location=Australia|date=September 21, 2008|accessdate=September 9, 2010|first=Ileana Young|last=Robin Lynch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615062222/http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/movies/mark-of-a-man/story-e6frf9h6-1111117540758|archive-date=June 15, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=hs>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/confidential/reformed-bad-boy-mark-wahlberg-goes-to-church-during-australian-tour/story-e6frf96o-1225906318411|title=Reformed bad boy Mark Wahlberg goes to church during Australian tour|work=Herald Sun|location=Australia|date=August 17, 2010|accessdate=September 9, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615062314/http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/confidential/reformed-bad-boy-mark-wahlberg-goes-to-church-during-australian-tour/story-e6frf96o-1225906318411|archive-date=June 15, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> and attended [[Snowden International School|Copley Square High School]] on [[Newbury Street (Boston)|Newbury Street]] in Boston. By age 13, Wahlberg had developed an addiction to [[cocaine]] and other substances.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.markwahlbergfan.com/article_vanityfair.htm |title=Vanity Fair. Rogue Star |publisher=Markwahlbergfan.com |accessdate=August 14, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220085726/http://www.markwahlbergfan.com/article_vanityfair.htm |archive-date=February 20, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2008/0630/104.html|title=Changing Room|last=Burke|first=Monte|date=June 30, 2008|work=Forbes|access-date=August 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908191733/https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2008/0630/104.html|archive-date=September 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He did not receive his high school diploma until June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lewis|first=Raha|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20735589,00.html|title=Mark Wahlberg Earns His High School Diploma|date=September 16, 2013|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=September 17, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918044917/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20735589,00.html|archive-date=September 18, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1986, Wahlberg and three friends chased after three black children while yelling \"Kill the [[nigger]], kill the nigger\" and throwing rocks at them.<ref name=\"smokinggun2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=2|title=Back In The Day: Marky Mark's Rap Sheet|website=The Smoking Gun|page=2|accessdate=June 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624040006/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=2|archive-date=June 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, Wahlberg and others followed a group of schoolchildren taking a [[field trip]] on a beach, yelled racial epithets at them, threw rocks at them, and \"summoned other white males who joined\" in the harassment.<ref name=\"smokinggun2\" /> In August 1986, civil action was filed against Wahlberg for violating the civil rights of his victims, and the case was settled the next month.<ref name=\"smokinggun3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=3|title=Back In The Day: Marky Mark's Rap Sheet|website=The Smoking Gun|page=3|accessdate=June 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624035854/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=3|archive-date=June 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"smokinggun5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=3|title=Back In The Day: Marky Mark's Rap Sheet|website=The Smoking Gun|page=5|accessdate=June 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624035854/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=3|archive-date=June 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=elder>{{Cite book| last = Elder | first = Larry | title = Showdown: Confronting Bias, Lies and the Special Interests That Divide America | publisher = Macmillan | year = 2003 | page = 12 | isbn = 978-0-312-32017-1}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1988, Wahlberg assaulted a middle-aged Vietnamese man on the street, calling him a \"Vietnam fucking shit\" and knocking him unconscious with a large wooden stick. Wahlberg attacked a second Vietnamese man later the same day, punching him in the eye. When Wahlberg was arrested and returned to the scene of the first assault, he told police officers: \"I'll tell you now that's the mother-fucker whose head I split open.\"<ref name=\"smokinggun6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=6|title=Back In The Day: Marky Mark's Rap Sheet|website=The Smoking Gun|page=6|accessdate=December 7, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229221604/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=6|archive-date=December 29, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Investigators also noted that Wahlberg \"made numerous unsolicited racial statements about '[[gook]]s' and 'slant-eyed gooks'\".<ref name=\"Ambinder\">{{cite web|url=http://theweek.com/article/index/273108/mark-wahlberg-should-not-be-pardoned|title=Mark Wahlberg should not be pardoned|last1=Ambinder|first1=Marc|date=December 5, 2014|publisher=[[The Week#website|TheWeek.com]]|accessdate=December 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141206033144/https://theweek.com/article/index/273108/mark-wahlberg-should-not-be-pardoned|archive-date=December 6, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=smokinggun0 />\nWahlberg was charged with [[attempted murder]], pleaded guilty to felony [[assault]], and was sentenced to two years in jail, but served only 45 days of his sentence.<ref name=\"Ambinder\" /><ref name=\"Candid Chat\">{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Nightline/story?id=2509542&page=1 |title=A Candid Chat With Mark Wahlberg \u2013 ABC News |publisher=ABC News |date=September 29, 2006 |accessdate=August 14, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/65cksWHPt?url=http://abcnews.go.com/Nightline/story?id=2509542 |archive-date=February 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Wahlberg believed he had left the second victim (named Johnny Trinh) permanently blind in one eye, though Trinh stated that he had lost his eye years prior in the [[Vietnam War]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://jezebel.com/mark-wahlberg-beating-victim-says-actor-did-not-blind-h-1670074037|title=Mark Wahlberg Beating Victim Says Actor Did Not Blind Him in Attack|website=Jezebel|language=en-us|access-date=2019-11-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823235049/https://jezebel.com/mark-wahlberg-beating-victim-says-actor-did-not-blind-h-1670074037|archive-date=August 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=elder /><ref name=\"Ambinder\" /><ref name=smokinggun0>{{cite web|title=Back In The Day: Marky Mark's Rap Sheet|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/documents/crime/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0|website=The Smoking Gun|accessdate=December 7, 2014|date=July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210123510/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/documents/crime/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0|archive-date=December 10, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1992, Wahlberg fractured the jaw of a neighbor in an unprovoked attack.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rap Singer Marky Mark Settles Broken-Jaw Suit|work=[[Lakeland Ledger]]|date= April 6, 1993|page= 2| location=Lakeland, Florida |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1346&dat=19930406&id=gEtIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=t_wDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6692,4119661}}</ref> Court documents state that in 1992, Wahlberg \"without provocation or cause, viciously and repeatedly kicked\" a man in the face while another man held the victim on the ground.<ref>{{cite web|title=Back In The Day: Marky Mark's Rap Sheet|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=8|page=8|website=The Smoking Gun|accessdate=May 17, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420163859/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/back-day-marky-marks-rap-sheet-0?page=8|archive-date=April 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 Wahlberg said the right thing for him to do would be to meet with Trinh and make amends, though he had not done so.<ref name=\"Candid Chat\" /> In 2016, while requesting a pardon for his conviction for the assault on Trinh, Wahlberg said he had met with Trinh and apologized \"for those horrific acts.\" Trinh released a public statement forgiving Wahlberg.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=wrap09132016>''The Wrap'', September 13, 2016 http://www.thewrap.com/mark-wahlberg-now-regrets-pardon-request-for-teenage-assault-conviction/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312074526/http://www.thewrap.com/mark-wahlberg-now-regrets-pardon-request-for-teenage-assault-conviction/ |date=March 12, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Wahlberg applied for a pardon for his convictions.<ref>{{cite web|title=PDF file of Massachusetts Pardon application|url=http://media.nbcbayarea.com/documents/wahlberg.pdf|publisher=NBC Universal|accessdate=December 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205080037/http://media.nbcbayarea.com/documents/wahlberg.pdf|archive-date=December 5, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Regan|first1=Helen|title=Mark Wahlberg Is Seeking a Pardon for His 1988 Assault Conviction|url=http://time.com/3619577/mark-wahlberg-pardon-assault/|accessdate=December 6, 2014|work=TIME|publisher=Time.com|date=December 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205163033/http://time.com/3619577/mark-wahlberg-pardon-assault/|archive-date=December 5, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> His pardon application engendered controversy.<ref name=\"Ambinder\" /> According to the [[BBC]], the debate about his suitability for a pardon raised \"difficult issues, with the arguments on both sides being far-reaching and complex\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-echochambers-30425288|title=Does Mark Wahlberg want a 'white privilege' pardon?|work=BBC News|accessdate=July 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821183353/http://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-echochambers-30425288|archive-date=August 21, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOne of the black children attacked by Wahlberg opposed the pardon, saying: \"a racist will always be a racist.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jan/20/mark-wahlberg-racism-pardon \"Mark Wahlberg harassment victim says actor should not be pardoned\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221113116/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jan/20/mark-wahlberg-racism-pardon |date=December 21, 2016 }} ''The Guardian''. January 20, 2015</ref> Judith Beals, who had been the prosecutor in some of the cases, argued that \"Wahlberg has never acknowledged the racial nature of his crimes\" and that a pardon would undermine Wahlberg's charity work, saying: \"a formal public pardon would highlight all too clearly that if you are white and a movie star, a different standard applies. Is that really what Wahlberg wants?\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/01/21/mark-wahlberg-racial-violence-victim-says-actor-shouldnt-be-pardoned/|title=Mark Wahlberg racial violence victim says actor shouldn't be pardoned|last=Moyer|first=Justin Wm|date=January 21, 2015|work=Washington Post|access-date=June 11, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140325/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/01/21/mark-wahlberg-racial-violence-victim-says-actor-shouldnt-be-pardoned/|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Wahlberg said that he regretted his attempt to obtain a pardon, and his petition was closed after he failed to answer a request from the pardon board as to whether he wanted it to remain open.<ref name=wrap09132016 /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-mark-wahlberg-pardon-request-dropped-20160916-snap-story.html |title=Mark Wahlberg drops pardon request for 1988 assaults |work=LA Times |date= |accessdate=September 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917003057/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-mark-wahlberg-pardon-request-dropped-20160916-snap-story.html |archive-date=September 17, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n=== Music ===\nWahlberg first came to fame as the younger brother of [[Donnie Wahlberg]] of the successful [[boy band]], ''[[New Kids on the Block]]''. Mark, at the age of 13, was one of the group's original members, along with Donnie, but quit after a few months. [[Danny Wood]], [[Jordan Knight]], [[Jonathan Knight]] and [[Joey McIntyre]] all joined the group after Mark had left.\n\nIn 1990, Wahlberg began recording with dancers/rappers Scott Ross (Scottie Gee), Hector Barros (Hector the Booty Inspector), Anthony Thomas (Ashley Ace), and Terry Yancey (DJ-T) as [[Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch]], earning a hit with \"[[Good Vibrations (Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch song)|Good Vibrations]]\" from their debut album ''[[Music for the People (Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch album)|Music for the People]]''. The record, produced by brother Donnie, hit number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], later becoming certified as a [[Platinum Single|platinum single]]. The second single, \"[[Wildside (Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch song)|Wildside]]\", peaked at number five on ''Billboard''{{'}}s [[Hot Singles Sales]] chart and at number 10 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} It was certified as a gold single. Marky Mark opened for the New Kids on the Block during their last tour. Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch also had their own video game, titled ''[[Make My Video (series)|Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch: Make My Video]]'', which despite the band's success, was a huge flop.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Townsend |first=Emru |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/127579-6/the_10_worst_games_of_all_time.html |title=The 10 Worst Games of All Time \u2013 Page 6 |magazine=PCWorld |date=March 14, 2012 |accessdate=March 29, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120413105301/http://www.pcworld.com/article/127579-6/the_10_worst_games_of_all_time.html |archive-date=April 13, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/segacd/587969-marky-mark-and-the-funky-bunch-make-my-video/ |title=Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch: Make My Video for Sega CD |publisher=GameRankings |date= |accessdate=March 29, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014093707/http://www.gamerankings.com/segacd/587969-marky-mark-and-the-funky-bunch-make-my-video/ |archive-date=October 14, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The second Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch LP, ''[[You Gotta Believe]]'', was not as successful as the first, yielding only a minor hit single in the title track.<ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r60116/review|first=Ron|last=Wynn}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1992, while performing on the British TV show ''[[The Word (TV series)|The Word]]'', Wahlberg praised [[Shabba Ranks]], who had stated gays should be crucified. [[Gay and Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation]] condemned him and berated Calvin Klein for using him to promote their products.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/pin-up-exposed-why-marky-mark-is-taking-the-rap-the-man-wearing-calvin-kleins-pants-could-be-undone-2322005.html|title=Pin-up exposed: why Marky Mark is taking the rap: The man wearing Calvin Klein's pants could be undone by his shady past and unguarded remarks. Will apologies save his skin? Mark Simpson reports|work=The Independent|accessdate=May 13, 2018|date=May 10, 1993|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180513081645/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/pin-up-exposed-why-marky-mark-is-taking-the-rap-the-man-wearing-calvin-kleins-pants-could-be-undone-2322005.html|archive-date=May 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A self-titled autobiographical [[picture book]] ''Marky Mark'', with images taken by [[Lynn Goldsmith]] and statements mostly by him was also released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/1993/01/15/marketing-marky-mark/|title=The marketing of Marky Mark|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=May 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517082259/http://ew.com/article/1993/01/15/marketing-marky-mark/|archive-date=May 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Trying to resuscitate his music career, he had shifted to [[Hamburg]] where he was produced under the label of [[East West Records]] by [[Frank Peterson]] and [[Alex Christensen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YQ8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA72&dq=marky+mark+Germany#v=onepage&q=marky%20mark%20Germany&f=false|title=Billboard \u2013 31 May 2017 |work=Billboard|accessdate=May 13, 2018|date=May 31, 1997 }}</ref>\n\nWahlberg later collaborated with the late reggae/[[ragga]] singer [[Prince Ital Joe]] on the album ''[[Life in the Streets]]''. The project combined rap vocals, electronic-infused ragga, and \"European dancefloor\" music, delivering the singles \"Happy People\", German number one hit \"United\", \"Life in the Streets\", and \"Babylon\", with Frank Peterson and Alex Christensen as producers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZwgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA54&lpg=PA54&dq=life+in+the+streets+marky+mark+1994#v=onepage&q=life%20in%20the%20streets%20marky%20mark%201994&f=false|title=Billboard|work=google.com|accessdate=July 28, 2015|date=December 3, 1994}}</ref> Many of these tracks featured on the hit film ''[[Renaissance Man (film)|Renaissance Man]]'', starring Wahlberg and [[Danny Devito]].\n\nIn 1995, he released a single titled \"No Mercy\" in support of his friend [[Dariusz Michalczewski]], whom he had befriended earlier in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/02/opinion/slawomir-sierakowski-Dariusz-Michalczewski-from-pugilist-to-activist.html?smid=tw-nytimes&_r=1&referrer= | work=The New York Times | first=Slawomir | last=Sierakowski | title=From Pugilist to Activist | date=October 1, 2014}}</ref> Michalczewski also appears in the music video of the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/straight-world-famous-boxer-makes-headlines-supporting-lgbt-equality-poland041014|title=Straight world-famous boxer makes headlines for supporting for LGBT equality in Poland|work=Gay Star News|accessdate=July 28, 2015|date=October 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715170502/http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/straight-world-famous-boxer-makes-headlines-supporting-lgbt-equality-poland041014/|archive-date=July 15, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Wahlberg and Prince Ital Joe released another album in 1995 for Ultraphonic Records. Titled ''[[The Remix Album (Prince Ital Joe album)|The Remix Album]]'', it featured remixes from the duo's previous album, ''Life in the Streets'', as well as the Mark's solo track, \"No Mercy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/artists/mark-wahlberg/biography/|title=Mark Wahlberg Bio \u2013 Mark Wahlberg Career|work=MTV Artists|accessdate=July 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150808232721/http://www.mtv.com/artists/mark-wahlberg/biography/|archive-date=August 8, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter his album with Ital Joe became a hit in Germany, he started putting together a [[Musical ensemble|musical act]] called One Love with him as its producer and also sometimes its lead singer. He also started production on a third studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HYc7AQAAIAAJ&q=success+ital+joe+one+love&dq=success+ital+joe+one+love|title=The New York Times Magazine|work=The New York Times|accessdate=May 14, 2018|date=July 1997}}</ref> He featured in their song titled \"That's the Way I Like It\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hitparade.ch/song/One-Love-feat.-Marky-Mark/That's-The-Way-I-Like-It-743758 |title=One Love feat. Marky Mark \u2013 That's The Way I Like It |work=hitparade.ch |accessdate=September 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906035532/https://hitparade.ch/song/One-Love-feat.-Marky-Mark/That%27s-The-Way-I-Like-It-743758 |archive-date=September 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1996, Wahlberg released a solo single titled \"Hey DJ\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitparade.ch/song/Marky-Mark/Hey-DJ-21180 |title=Marky Mark \u2013 Hey DJ \u2013 hitparade.ch |accessdate=January 22, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418130037/http://hitparade.ch/song/Marky-Mark/Hey-DJ-21180 |archivedate=April 18, 2015}}</ref> Two solo tracks titled \"Feel the Vibe\" and \"Best of my Love\" were released in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hitparade.ch/song/Marky-Mark/Feel-The-Vibe-41006 |title=MARKY MARK \u2013 FEEL THE VIBE |access-date=May 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626220125/https://hitparade.ch/song/Marky-Mark/Feel-The-Vibe-41006 |archive-date=June 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitparade.ch/song/Marky-Mark/Best-Of-My-Love-765570 |title=Marky Mark \u2013 Best of My Love \u2013 hitparade.ch |accessdate=January 22, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418130114/http://hitparade.ch/song/Marky-Mark/Best-Of-My-Love-765570 |archivedate=April 18, 2015 }}</ref> All the solo tracks, along with another song titled \"Here With Me\", were released on an album titled ''All Around the World'' in 1997 that also included the remixed versions of the songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Marky+Mark/All+Around+the+World|title=All Around the World|work=Last.fm|accessdate=July 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117135003/http://www.last.fm/music/Marky+Mark/All+Around+the+World|archive-date=January 17, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, he was also featured in the [[Black Label Society]] music video for \"[[Counterfeit God]]\", as a stand-in for the band's bassist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1431836/wahlbergs-dragon-megadeth-more-to-play-la/|title=Wahlberg's \"Dragon,\" Megadeth, More To Play L.A.|work=MTV News|accessdate=July 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527161658/http://www.mtv.com/news/1431836/wahlbergs-dragon-megadeth-more-to-play-la/|archive-date=May 27, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Advertising===\nWahlberg first displayed his physique in the \"Good Vibrations\" music video and most prominently in a series of underwear ads for [[Calvin Klein (company)|Calvin Klein]] (1992)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://explore.calvinklein.com/en_US/timeline/1992/9|title=Calvin Klein Underwear|work=Calvin Klein|access-date=November 23, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104044302/http://explore.calvinklein.com/en_US/timeline/1992/9|archive-date=January 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> shot by [[Herb Ritts]], following it with Calvin Klein television advertisements.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Eric|title=Stretching a Six-Pack|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/13/fashion/13calvin.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 28, 2011|date=May 12, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113225808/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/13/fashion/13calvin.html|archive-date=January 13, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Magazine and television promotions would sometimes feature Wahlberg exclusively or accompanied by model [[Kate Moss]]. [[Annie Leibovitz]] also shot a famous session of Wahlberg in underwear for [[Vanity Fair (magazine)|''Vanity Fair'']]'s annual Hall of Fame issue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jossip.com/category/annie-leibovitz/ |title=Annie Leibovitz / Jossip |publisher=Jossip.com |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906215433/http://www.jossip.com/category/annie-leibovitz/ |archive-date=September 6, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> He also made a workout video titled ''The Marky Mark Workout: Form... Focus... Fitness'' ({{ISBN|1-55510-910-1}}).\n\nIn 2012, Wahlberg began serving as a brand ambassador for a line of sports nutrition supplements by [[GNC (store)|GNC]] called Marked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nutraingredients-usa.com/Article/2012/04/18/Good-vibrations-Mark-Wahlberg-and-GNC-create-new-MARKED-sports-nutrition-range|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421025000/http://www.nutraingredients-usa.com/Industry/Good-vibrations-Mark-Wahlberg-and-GNC-create-new-MARKED-sports-nutrition-range|url-status=dead|title=Good vibrations? Mark Wahlberg and GNC create new MARKED sports nutrition range|archivedate=April 21, 2012|website=nutraingredients-usa.com}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, [[AT&T]] announced that Wahlberg would become a spokesman and he would create original content for the mobile network division. The deal would reportedly pay Wahlberg more than $10 million.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Emily |url=http://pagesix.com/2017/03/13/mark-wahlberg-lands-eight-figure-deal-with-att/ |title=Mark Wahlberg lands eight-figure deal with AT&T |work=[[New York Post]] |date=March 13, 2017 |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315162158/http://pagesix.com/2017/03/13/mark-wahlberg-lands-eight-figure-deal-with-att/ |archive-date=March 15, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Film ===\n[[File:Mark Wahlberg.jpg|thumb|upright|Wahlberg at the London premiere of ''[[Shooter (2007 film)|Shooter]]'' in 2007]]\n\nIn 1993, Wahlberg made his acting debut in the TV film ''The Substitute''. After this appearance, he dropped the \"Marky Mark\" name. His big screen d\u00e9but came the next year, with the [[Danny DeVito]] feature ''[[Renaissance Man (film)|Renaissance Man]]''. A basketball fanatic, he caught the attention of critics after appearing in ''[[The Basketball Diaries (film)|The Basketball Diaries]]'' in 1995, playing the role of Mickey alongside [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], in a film adaptation of the [[Jim Carroll]] book of the [[The Basketball Diaries (book)|same name]]. He had his first starring role in the 1996 [[James Foley (director)|James Foley]] thriller ''[[Fear (1996 film)|Fear]]''.\n\nHe earned positive reviews after films such as ''[[Boogie Nights]]'' (as Dirk Diggler), ''[[Three Kings (1999 film)|Three Kings]]'', ''[[The Perfect Storm (film)|The Perfect Storm]]'', and ''[[Four Brothers (film)|Four Brothers]]''. During the early 2000s, Wahlberg appeared in remakes of 1960s films such as ''[[Planet of the Apes (2001 film)|Planet of the Apes]]'', ''[[The Truth About Charlie]]'' (remake of ''[[Charade (1963 film)|Charade]]''), and ''[[The Italian Job (2003 film)|The Italian Job]]''. His performance in ''[[I Heart Huckabees]]'' was voted best supporting performance of the year in the 2004 ''[[The Village Voice]]'' Critics Poll. Wahlberg was originally cast as Linus Caldwell in ''[[Ocean's Eleven]]''; [[Matt Damon]] played the role instead. The two later worked together in ''[[The Departed]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmfodder.com/archive/oceans11 |title=filmfodder.com: archive: ocean's 11 |publisher=Filmfodder.com |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012213914/http://www.filmfodder.com/archive/oceans11/ |archive-date=October 12, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> Wahlberg was also considered for a role in the film ''[[Brokeback Mountain]]''. It was originally intended to star Wahlberg and [[Joaquin Phoenix]] (with whom he appeared in the 2000 film ''[[The Yards]]'') as [[Ennis Del Mar]] and [[Jack Twist]], respectively, but both actors were uncomfortable with the film's sex scenes. The roles ultimately went to [[Heath Ledger]] and [[Jake Gyllenhaal]], both of whom were nominated for Academy Awards for their performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2007/02/28/brokeback_mountain_script_creeped_out_ma |title='Brokeback Mountain' Script 'Creeped Out' Mark Wahlberg \u2013 Starpulse Entertainment News Blog |publisher=Starpulse.com |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210082039/http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2007/02/28/brokeback_mountain_script_creeped_out_ma |archivedate=December 10, 2008 |df=}}</ref>\n\nWahlberg starred in the American football drama ''[[Invincible (2006 film)|Invincible]]'', based on the true story of bartender [[Vince Papale]]. He was also the executive producer of the [[HBO]] series ''[[Entourage (U.S. TV series)|Entourage]]'' (2004\u20132011), which was loosely based on his experiences in Hollywood. In 2006, he appeared as an unpleasant, foul-mouthed [[Massachusetts State Police]] detective in [[Martin Scorsese]]'s critically acclaimed thriller, ''[[The Departed]]'', which netted him an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]], a [[Golden Globe]] nomination for Best Performance by an Actor in a Supporting Role in a Motion Picture, and a [[National Society of Film Critics]] Best Supporting Actor award. Wahlberg has confirmed that he was approached to star in a sequel to ''The Departed'', but it is still early in development. The sequel would reportedly revolve around the staff sergeant played by Wahlberg.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[File:Mark Wahlberg May 2014 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Wahlberg at the Australian premiere of ''[[Transformers: Age of Extinction]]'' in 2014]]\n\nDespite his felony conviction, which legally prohibits him from handling firearms, Wahlberg prepared for his role in ''[[Shooter (2007 film)|Shooter]]'' by attending long-range shooting training at [[Front Sight Firearms Training Institute]] near [[Pahrump, Nevada]]. He was able to hit a target at 1,100 yards on his second day, a feat which usually takes weeks to achieve.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visualhollywood.com/movies/shooter/about4.php |title=Wahlberg goes to sniper school: About training as a shooter |publisher=VisualHollywood.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110930131546/http://www.visualhollywood.com/movies/shooter/about4.php |archivedate=September 30, 2011 }}</ref> He had said in a number of interviews that he would retire at the age of 40 to concentrate on parenthood<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitytvworld.com/news/actor-mark-wahlberg-says-he-plans-retire-at-age-40-1004076.php|title=Actor Mark Wahlberg says he plans to retire at age 40|access-date=January 23, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011131411/http://realitytvworld.com/news/actor-mark-wahlberg-says-he-plans-retire-at-age-40-1004076.php|archive-date=October 11, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[professional golf]]. However, in early 2007 he indicated that the latter was no longer the plan as \"his golf game is horrible\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbo.com/entourage/interviews/mark_wahlberg.html?ntrack_para1=insidehbo6_text|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307223359/http://www.hbo.com/entourage/interviews/mark_wahlberg.html?ntrack_para1=insidehbo6_text|archivedate=March 7, 2008|title=HBO interview}}</ref> He played Jack Salmon, a leading role in [[Peter Jackson]]'s film of ''[[The Lovely Bones (film)|The Lovely Bones]]''.<ref name=\"DominionPost\">{{cite news | last = Cardy | first = Tom | title = Lovely Bones' Gosling in shock exit | publisher = Dominion Post | date = October 23, 2007 | url = http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/4247770a10.html | accessdate = October 23, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071024103617/http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/4247770a10.html | archive-date = October 24, 2007 | url-status = live}}</ref> In 2007, he starred opposite Joaquin Phoenix in ''[[We Own the Night (film)|We Own the Night]]'', a movie about a family of police officers in New York City.\n\nHe starred in [[M. Night Shyamalan]]'s ''[[The Happening (2008 film)|The Happening]]'' as Eliot Moore, which premiered in movie theatres on June 13, 2008. The same year, he played the title role in ''[[Max Payne (film)|Max Payne]]'', based on a video game of the [[Max Payne (video game)|same name]]. While promoting ''Max Payne'', Wahlberg became involved in a playful feud with [[The Lonely Island]]'s [[Andy Samberg]]. Samberg had done an impression of Wahlberg in a ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' sketch titled \"Mark Wahlberg Talks to Animals\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/red-101808-samberg,0,4155250.story |title=Wahlberg threatens to punch SNL's Samberg over impression |work=Chicago Tribune |author=RedEye |date=October 26, 2008 |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081028213729/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/red-101808-samberg%2C0%2C4155250.story |archivedate=October 28, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/digital-shorts/video/mark-wahlberg-talks-to-animals/727504/ |title=Saturday Night Live \u2013 Mark Wahlberg Talks to Animals \u2013 Video |publisher=Nbc.com |accessdate=January 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423010537/http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/digital-shorts/video/mark-wahlberg-talks-to-animals/727504 |archivedate=April 23, 2013 }}</ref> Wahlberg later appeared in a follow-up sketch parodying the original one, Samberg's impression of Wahlberg, and his own threats to Samberg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/digital-shorts/video/mark-wahlberg-backstage/773862/ |title=Saturday Night Live \u2013 Mark Wahlberg Backstage \u2013 Video |publisher=Nbc.com |accessdate=January 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313095447/http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/digital-shorts/video/mark-wahlberg-backstage/773862 |archivedate=March 13, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popeater.com/television/article/mark-wahlberg-cracks-jokes-not-noses/217025 |title=Mark Wahlberg Cracks Jokes, Not Noses |publisher=Popeater.com |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022053508/http://www.popeater.com/television/article/mark-wahlberg-cracks-jokes-not-noses/217025 |archive-date=October 22, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a February 2007 interview with ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'', updated in 2010, Wahlberg stated that there might be a sequel to ''The Departed'', focusing on his character, Dignam, with [[Robert De Niro]] potentially playing a corrupt senator. He also stated that [[William Monahan]] was writing the script.<ref>{{cite news |title=Exclusive: News On Departed 2... And 3! |publisher=EmpireOnline.com |date=February 7, 2007 |url=http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=20343 |accessdate=February 7, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070209055637/http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=20343 |archive-date=February 9, 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film is said to be on hold, because producer [[Brad Grey]] is now the head of [[Paramount Pictures]] and the film is a [[Warner Bros.]] project.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/761/761346p1.html|title=No Departed 2 Just Yet|author=Stax|date=February 5, 2007|accessdate=February 7, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206210415/http://movies.ign.com/articles/761/761346p1.html|archive-date=February 6, 2007|url-status=dead|website=IGN}}</ref> In June 2010, Wahlberg and Monahan continued to express interest in a sequel, then said to be projected for 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Departed Sequel Will Arrive in 2012 |url=http://thefilmstage.com/2010/06/10/the-departed-sequel-arriving-in-2012 |publisher=TheFilmStage.com |accessdate=June 10, 2010 |date=June 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618172958/http://thefilmstage.com/2010/06/10/the-departed-sequel-arriving-in-2012/ |archivedate=June 18, 2010 }}</ref> Nothing further has been announced.\n\nIn 2012, Wahlberg starred in Seth MacFarlane's hit comedy ''[[Ted (film)|Ted]]''. He returned in the same role in the 2015 sequel ''[[Ted 2]]''. Wahlberg later starred as [[United States Navy SEALs|Navy SEAL]] [[Marcus Luttrell]] in the war film ''[[Lone Survivor]]'' (2013), based on Luttrell's 2007 [[Lone Survivor (book)|book of the same name]]. The film received commercial success and mostly positive reviews, and Wahlberg's performance was highly praised. In 2014, Wahlberg starred in the [[The Gambler (2014 film)|remake]] of ''[[The Gambler (1974 film)|The Gambler]]'', the 1974 [[James Caan]] film that was loosely inspired by [[The Gambler (novel)|the Dostoyevsky novella]].<ref>Bahr, Lindsey (2013). \"Casting Net: Brie Larson in talks to star opposite Mark Wahlberg,\" October 17, 2013.</ref><ref>Bahr, Lindsey (2013). \"Casting Net: Brie Larson,\" October 17, 2013.</ref> In 2015, he starred opposite Will Ferrell in the comedy ''[[Daddy's Home (film)|Daddy's Home]]''. In 2016, he starred in two [[Peter Berg]] films, ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'' and ''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]''.\n\nWahlberg topped the list of the world's highest-paid actors in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/shah-rukh-khan-salman-khan-akshay-kumar-on-forbes-highest-paid-actors-list-topped-by-mark-wahlberg-1740826?pfrom=home-topstories|title=Shah Rukh Khan, Salman Khan, Akshay Kumar On Forbes' Highest Paid Actors List. Aamir Khan? Nope|publisher=|access-date=August 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170823115205/http://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/shah-rukh-khan-salman-khan-akshay-kumar-on-forbes-highest-paid-actors-list-topped-by-mark-wahlberg-1740826?pfrom=home-topstories|archive-date=August 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018, his salary of $1.5&nbsp;million for reshoots for ''[[All the Money in the World]]'' caused controversy because his female co-star [[Michelle Williams (actress)|Michelle Williams]] received less than $1,000. Wahlberg donated the money to [[Time's Up (movement)|Time's Up]], a movement against sexual harassment co-founded by Williams.<ref>{{cite news|last1=staff|first1=Guardian|title=Mark Wahlberg donates $1.5m reward for film reshoots to Time's Up fund|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/13/mark-wahlberg-all-the-money-in-the-world-michelle-williams|accessdate=January 13, 2018|work=The Guardian|date=January 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113230642/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/13/mark-wahlberg-all-the-money-in-the-world-michelle-williams|archive-date=January 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWalhberg produced and starred in the hacker film ''[[Mile 22]]'' and has set to appear in the Netflix film ''[[Spenser Confidential]]'' and the animated movie ''[[Scoob]]'' which is his first voicing acting role career. In November 2019, Wahlberg was cast in the upcoming ''[[Uncharted (film)|Uncharted]]'' film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/mark-wahlberg-tom-holland-uncharted-movie-sony-1203394336/ |title=Mark Wahlberg Joins Tom Holland in 'Uncharted' Movie (EXCLUSIVE) |website=[[Variety (website)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=November 13, 2019 |accessdate=November 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113210937/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/mark-wahlberg-tom-holland-uncharted-movie-sony-1203394336/ |archive-date=November 13, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Business interests===\nWahlberg co-owns [[Wahlburgers]] with his brothers Donnie and Paul.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aetv.com/wahlburgers/video/rheas-requests-for-mark|title=Watch the Rhea's Requests for Mark Video - Wahlburgers - A&E|work=aetv|accessdate=July 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150729102459/http://www.aetv.com/wahlburgers/video/rheas-requests-for-mark|archive-date=July 29, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It was Mark's idea to expand Paul's restaurant in [[Hingham, Massachusetts]], into a full-fledged chain with a reality show to promote it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-28/wahlburgers-donnie-mark-paul-wahlberg-plot-fast-food-empire|title=Wahlburgers: Donnie, Mark, Paul Wahlberg Plot Fast-Food Empire - Bloomberg Business|author=Joel Stein|date=May 28, 2015|work=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=July 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150819124936/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-28/wahlburgers-donnie-mark-paul-wahlberg-plot-fast-food-empire|archive-date=August 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Wahlberg bought an equity interest of the [[Barbados Tridents]] [[cricket]] team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wahlberg owns Barbados Tridents |author=Staff writer |url=http://www.cbc.bb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7622%3Awahlberg-owns-barbados-tridents&catid=25%3Alocal-sports&Itemid=88 |newspaper=[[Caribbean Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] |date=July 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |accessdate=September 18, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714122120/http://www.cbc.bb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7622%3Awahlberg-owns-barbados-tridents&catid=25%3Alocal-sports&Itemid=88 |archivedate=July 14, 2014  }}</ref> Wahlberg was introduced to the game by his friend Ajmal Khan, the club's chairman and [[Caribbean Premier League]] founder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity-life/mark-wahlberg-buys-stake-in-caribbean-cricket-team-claims-to-be-a-huge-fan/news-story/3ba4b4a937c546a028ff077054cea7d5|title=Wahlberg buys stake in cricket team|date=August 5, 2013|publisher=[[News Corp Australia Network]]|accessdate=August 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626220120/https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity-life/mark-wahlberg-buys-stake-in-caribbean-cricket-team-claims-to-be-a-huge-fan/news-story/3ba4b4a937c546a028ff077054cea7d5|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.caribjournal.com/2013/07/31/mark-wahlberg-takes-stake-in-caribbean-cricket-team/ |title=Mark Wahlberg Takes Stake in Caribbean Cricket Team |author=Journal staff |date=July 31, 2013 |publisher=Carib Journal |accessdate= |quote=Limacol CPL CEO Damien O'Donohoe said the league was \"thrilled\" that Wahlberg had taken an equity interest in the team. |ref= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130803072016/http://www.caribjournal.com/2013/07/31/mark-wahlberg-takes-stake-in-caribbean-cricket-team/ |archive-date=August 3, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following the announcement, Wahlberg stated, \"I am a huge cricket fan now. I'm excited to be a part of the Limacol Caribbean Premier League because I know cricket is huge in the Caribbean and a rich part of the region's heritage. Sports and entertainment are a powerful combination, and the LCPL will appeal to a huge audience worldwide.\"<ref name=\"GT\">{{cite web |url=http://www.guyanatimesgy.com/?p=25270 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130801090633/http://www.guyanatimesgy.com/?p=25270 |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 1, 2013 |title=Hollywood glamour comes to Limacol CPL, Mark Wahlberg on board with Barbados |author=Staff writer |date=July 30, 2013 |publisher=Guyana Times |accessdate= |quote=Limacol Caribbean Premier League cricket officials announced that American actor Mark Wahlberg has taken an equity interest in the Barbados Tridents team. |ref= |separator= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Wahlberg recruited rapper [[Sean Combs]] and billionaire [[Ronald Burkle]] to join him in investing in Aquahydrate, a bottled water brand Wahlberg discovered. Together, the three men own a majority stake in the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2015/02/04/liquid-asset-inside-mark-wahlberg-diddy-and-ron-burkles-aquahydrate/|title=Liquid Asset: Inside Mark Wahlberg, Diddy and Ron Burkle's Aquahydrate Investment|last=Greenburg|first=Zack O'Malley|date=February 4, 2015|website=Forbes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319120314/https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2015/02/04/liquid-asset-inside-mark-wahlberg-diddy-and-ron-burkles-aquahydrate/|archive-date=March 19, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> Wahlberg, together with former [[GNC (store)|GNC]] executive Tom Dowd, co-founded Performance Inspired, a [[sports nutrition]] company launched in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/news/2016/12/08/former-gnc-exec-mark-wahlberg-launch-new-product.html|title=Former GNC exec, Mark Wahlberg launch new product line|last=Schooley|first=Tim|date=December 8, 2016|website=Pittsburgh Business Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319124915/https://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/news/2016/12/08/former-gnc-exec-mark-wahlberg-launch-new-product.html|archive-date=March 19, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> In February 2017, Wahlberg was one of the investors who took part in a $6 million funding round for StockX, a sneaker resale marketplace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2017/02/15/mark-wahlberg-eminem-sneakers/|title=Mark Wahlberg and Eminem Have Invested in a Sneaker Stock Market|last=Kell|first=John|date=February 15, 2017|website=Fortune|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215184516/http://fortune.com/2017/02/15/mark-wahlberg-eminem-sneakers/|archive-date=February 15, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> On July 20, 2018, Wahlberg and his business partner, Jay Feldman, announced the purchase of Bobby Layman Chevrolet in Columbus, Ohio. The dealership was renamed Mark Wahlberg Chevrolet.<ref>Navera, Tristan (July 20, 2018). [https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/20/mark-wahlberg-is-buying-bobby-layman-chevrolet.html \"Mark Wahlberg \u2013 yes, that Mark Wahlberg \u2013 is buying Bobby Layman Chevrolet\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907032223/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/20/mark-wahlberg-is-buying-bobby-layman-chevrolet.html |date=September 7, 2018 }}. [[CNBC]]. Retrieved September 6, 2018.</ref> In March 2019, Wahlberg bought a stake in the F45 fitness franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/marky-mark-to-get-hands-on-with-the-f45-bunch-20190319-p515h1.html|title=Marky Mark to get hands-on with the F45 bunch|last=Croffey|first=Amy|date=March 19, 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319113940/https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/marky-mark-to-get-hands-on-with-the-f45-bunch-20190319-p515h1.html?js-chunk-not-found-refresh=true|archive-date=March 19, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Television production===\nIn 2014, Wahlberg was the producer of the reality show ''Breaking Boston'', which was pulled off the air after its premiere had 311,000 viewers.<ref name=Steinberg>{{cite news|last=Steinberg|first=Brian|title=A&E Pulls Mark Wahlberg's 'Breaking Boston' After One Week|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/ae-pulls-breaking-boston-from-schedule-1201140750/|accessdate=March 22, 2014|newspaper=Variety|date=March 20, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322075549/http://variety.com/2014/tv/news/ae-pulls-breaking-boston-from-schedule-1201140750/|archive-date=March 22, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He executive-produced one episode of ''[[Wahlburgers]]'', while co-starring in it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3333880/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Wahlburgers (TV Series 2014\u2013 )|publisher=|access-date=July 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407160939/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt3333880/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|archive-date=April 7, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Charities==\nWahlberg established the Mark Wahlberg Youth Foundation in May 2001 for the purpose of raising and distributing funds to youth service and enrichment programs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://markwahlbergyouthfoundation.com |title=The Mark Wahlberg Youth Foundation |publisher=Markwahlbergyouthfoundation.com |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/65ckyPSjy?url=http://markwahlbergyouthfoundation.com/ |archive-date=February 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nWahlberg is active with The Good Shepherd Center for Homeless Women and Children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_-_NXReiXtU |title=Mark Wahlberg on How He Helps the Homeless |publisher=Youtube.com |date= |accessdate=January 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWahlberg married model [[Rhea Durham]] on August 1, 2009 at the [[Church of the Good Shepherd (Beverly Hills, California)|Good Shepherd Catholic Church]] in Beverly Hills.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20295454,00.html|title=Mark Wahlberg Gets Married!|date=August 1, 2009|author=Pernilla Cederheim|magazine=People.com|accessdate=April 26, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601023006/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20295454,00.html|archive-date=June 1, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> They have four children: daughters Ella Rae (b. 2003) and Grace Margaret (b. 2010), and sons Michael (b. 2006) and Brendan Joseph (b. 2008).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20336350,00.html|title=It's a Girl for Mark Wahlberg|date=January 13, 2010|first=Julie|last=Jordan|work=People|accessdate=April 26, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930035607/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20336350,00.html|archive-date=September 30, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Mark Wahlberg Max Payne 2008.jpg|thumb|upright|Wahlberg at the premiere of ''[[Max Payne (film)|Max Payne]]'' in 2008]]\n\nWahlberg's father, Donald a [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] veteran of the [[Korean War]], died on February 14, 2008.<ref name=dadobit>{{cite web|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/obituaries/death_notices/view.bg?articleid=1073799 |title=Donald E. Wahlberg [obituary] |work=[[Boston Herald]]|date=February 18, 2008 |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080301184308/http://www.bostonherald.com/news/obituaries/death_notices/view.bg?articleid=1073799 |archivedate=March 1, 2008  }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Wahlberg was quoted in a magazine interview regarding what would have happened if he had flown aboard [[American Airlines Flight 11]] on [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001]]. He had been booked on Flight 11, but his plans changed the day before the scheduled flight and he cancelled his reservation. Wahlberg received public criticism for stating, \"If I was on that plane with my kids, it wouldn't have went down like it did,\" and \"There would have been a lot of blood in that first-class cabin and then me saying, 'OK, we're going to land somewhere safely, don't worry.{{'\"}} Wahlberg issued a public apology after family members of those killed on the flight expressed outrage about his statements.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2012/01/18/mark-wahlberg-said-would-have-defeated-11-terrorists-on-flight-3/|title=Mark Wahlberg sorry for saying he would have thwarted 9/11 terrorists|work=Fox News|accessdate=July 28, 2015|date=January 18, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102202329/http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2012/01/18/mark-wahlberg-said-would-have-defeated-11-terrorists-on-flight-3/|archive-date=November 2, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA committed [[Roman Catholic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.christiantoday.com/article/mark-wahlberg-talks-central-role-of-faith-and-prayer-in-his-daily-life/12692.htm|title=Mark Wahlberg talks central role of faith and prayer in his daily life|first=Stoyan |last=Zaimov|publisher=[[Christian Today]] Australia|date=January 18, 2012|accessdate=July 28, 2015| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826174701/http://christiantoday.com.au/article/mark-wahlberg-talks-central-role-of-faith-and-prayer-in-his-daily-life/12692.htm | archivedate=August 26, 2014}}</ref> Wahlberg openly supports [[same-sex marriage]], despite the church's opposition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/International/Actor-Mark-Wahlberg-raises-eyebrows-as-host-of-Philadelphia-Pope-concert-419211 |title=Conservative Catholic blog Rorate Caeli called Wahlberg out for his support of gay marriage, which the Church strongly opposes. |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |location=Israel |date=September 27, 2015 |accessdate=August 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315155422/http://www.jpost.com/International/Actor-Mark-Wahlberg-raises-eyebrows-as-host-of-Philadelphia-Pope-concert-419211 |archive-date=March 15, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2015, he apologized to [[Pope Francis]] about the crude jokes he made in the film ''[[Ted (film)|Ted]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/article/mark-wahlberg-jokes-pope-francis-ted-video |last=Mercedes Lara |first=Maria |title=Mark Wahlberg Jokes About Ted with Pope Francis: I Hope the 'Good Lord Has a Sense of Humor' About My Movies |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=September 27, 2015 |accessdate=August 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707122003/http://www.people.com/article/mark-wahlberg-jokes-pope-francis-ted-video |archive-date=July 7, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> and in October 2017, in a public interview conducted by [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Catholic Cardinal]] [[Blase J. Cupich|Blase Cupich]] of Chicago, stated that he has sought forgiveness from God for portraying a porn actor in ''[[Boogie Nights]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Janssen|first=Kim|title=Mark Wahlberg says he prayed to God for forgiveness for ''Boogie Nights''|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chicagoinc/ct-met-cupich-wahlberg-1022-chicago-inc-20171020-story.html|accessdate=October 25, 2017|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=October 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024225501/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chicagoinc/ct-met-cupich-wahlberg-1022-chicago-inc-20171020-story.html|archive-date=October 24, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title = Mark Wahlberg has prayed for forgiveness over 1997 film Boogie Nights|first = Broede|last = Carmody|date = October 26, 2017|accessdate = October 29, 2017|newspaper = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|url = http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/mark-wahlberg-has-prayed-for-forgiveness-over-1997-film-boogie-nights-20171024-gz7lpf.html|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171029065833/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/mark-wahlberg-has-prayed-for-forgiveness-over-1997-film-boogie-nights-20171024-gz7lpf.html|archive-date = October 29, 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> He later stated on [[Andy Cohen (TV personality)|Andy Cohen]]'s radio show, ''Radio Andy'', that the interview \"was a joke taken too seriously.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v0-_0gkYxvA|title=Mark Wahlberg: Asking forgiveness for \"Boogie Nights\" was a joke taken seriously|date=November 18, 2017|first=Andy |last=Cohen|work= People| accessdate=October 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1994\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Renaissance Man (film)|Renaissance Man]]''\n| Private Tommy Lee Haywood\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1995\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Basketball Diaries (film)|The Basketball Diaries]]''\n| Mickey\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1996\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Fear (1996 film)|Fear]]''\n| David McCall\n| \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|1997\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Traveller (1997 film)