 v. Arkansas Board of Education\n | court = Eastern District of Arkansas\n | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170716024320/http://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/529/1255/2354824/%7Caccessdate%3D16 Jul 2017\n | date = January 5, 1982\n }}\n}}\n* {{Cite book | ref = harv\n| last = Miller\n| first = David\n| title = Critical Rationalism : A Restatement and Defence\n| date = 1994\n| publisher = Open Court\n| title-link = Critical Rationalism\n}}\n* {{Cite journal | ref = harv\n| last = Miller\n| first = David\n| title = Sokal and Bricmont: Back to the Frying Pan|journal=Pli\n| volume = 9\n| year = 2000\n| pages = 156\u201373\n| url = http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/soc/philosophy/staff/miller/miller_pli_9.pdf\n| url-status = dead\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928003401/http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/soc/philosophy/staff/miller/miller_pli_9.pdf\n| archive-date = 2007-09-28\n| df =\n}}\n* {{Cite journal| ref = harv\n| last = Miller\n| first = David\n| title = Out of Error\n| year = 2006\n| publisher=Ashgate\n}}\n* {{cite journal | ref = harv\n| last1 = Miller\n| first1 = David\n| title = Some Hard Questions for Critical Rationalism\n| journal = Discusiones Filos\u00f3ficas \n| date = 2014\n| orig-year = [http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.482.6469&rep=rep1&type=pdf Original version in 2011]\n| volume = 15 \n| issue = 24\n| pages = 15\u201340 \n| url = http://www.scielo.org.co/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S0124-61272014000100002&lng=en&tlng=en\n| issn = 0124-6127\n}}\n* {{Cite book | ref = harv\n| last = Mises\n| first = Ludwig von\n| year = 1998\n| title = Human Action: A Treatise on Economics\n| chapter = Purposeful Action and Animal Reaction\n| chapter-url = https://cdn.mises.org/Human%20Action.pdf\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200109033531/https://cdn.mises.org/Human%20Action.pdf\n| archive-date = 2020-01-09\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last1 = Pennock\n| first1 = Robert T.\n| title= Tower of Babel: The Evidence Against the New Creationism\n| date = 2000\n| series = A Bradford Book\n| publisher = MIT Press\n| isbn = 978-0262661652\n| edition = 1st\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last = Popper\n| first = Karl\n| title = The Logic of Scientific Discovery\n| publisher = Routledge \n| edition = 2002 pbk; 2005 ebook\n| date = 1959\n| url = https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Logic_of_Scientific_Discovery\n| archive-url = https://archive.org/details/PopperLogicScientificDiscovery/page/n25/mode/2up\n| archive-date = 2013-11-18\n| isbn = 978-0-415-27844-7\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last = Popper\n| first = Karl\n| title = Conjectures and Refutations: The Growth of Scientific Knowledge\n| publisher = Routledge\n| location = London\n| date = 1963\n| isbn = 978-0-415-28594-0\n| edition=2002\n}}\n* {{cite web | ref = harv\n| last1 = Popper\n| first1 = Karl\n| title = Science as Falsification\n| year = 1963b\n| url = http://www.stephenjaygould.org/ctrl/popper_falsification.html\n| accessdate=2 May 2018\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180502201044/http://www.stephenjaygould.org/ctrl/popper_falsification.html\n| archive-date = 2018-05-02\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last = Popper\n| first = Karl\n| title =Objective Knowledge: An Evolutionary Approach\n| url = https://archive.org/details/objectiveknowled00popp\n| url-access = registration\n| date=1972\n| publisher = Oxford University Press\n| location = New York\n| isbn = 978-0198750246|edition=2003\n}}\n* {{cite book| ref = harv\n| last = Popper\n| first = Karl\n| title = The Philosophy of Karl Popper\n| chapter = Replies to my critics\n| volume = II\n| editor-first = Paul Arthur\n| editor-last = Schilpp\n| publisher = Open Court\n| location = Illinois\n| pages = 961\u20131197\n| date = 1974\n| isbn = 0875481426\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last1 = Popper\n| first1 = Karl\n| editor1-last = Bartley III\n| editor1-first = W.W.\n| title = Unended Quest: An Intellectual Autobiography\n| date = 1976\n| publisher = Routledge\n| location = London and New York\n| isbn = 0415285895\n| edition = 2002\n| url = https://books.google.com/?id=F_2WSLsDyvwC&pg=PA330#v=onepage&q&f=false\n}}\n* {{cite journal| ref = harv\n| last1 = Popper\n| first1 = Karl\n| journal = Dialectica\n| volume = 32\n| issue =3/4\n| pages =339\u2013355\n| title = Natural Selection and the Emergence of Mind\n| date = 1978\n| jstor = 42970324\n| doi=10.1111/j.1746-8361.1978.tb01321.x\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last1 = Popper\n| first1 = Karl\n| editor1-last = Bartley III\n| editor1-first=W.W.\n| title = Quantum Theory and the Schism in Physics: From the Postscript to the Logic of Scientific Discovery\n| date = 1982\n| orig-year = originally written in 1962\n| publisher = Routledge\n| isbn =  0415091128\n| edition=2005\n}}\n* {{Cite interview | ref = harv\n| last = Popper\n| first = Karl\n| interviewer = S. Lannes and A. Boyer\n| title = Les chemins de la verite: L'Express va plus loin avec Karl Popper\n| work = L'Express\n| date = 26 February 1982\n| year = 1982b\n| pages = 82-88\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last = Popper\n| first = Karl\n| title = Realism and the Aim of Science: From the Postscript to The Logic of Scientific Discovery\n| orig-year = originally written in 1962\n| date = 1983\n| publisher = Routledge\n| location = London and New York\n| isbn=0-415-08400-8\n| edition=1st\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| first = Karl\n| last = Popper\n| chapter = Zwei Bedeutungen von Falsifizierbarkeit [Two meanings of falsifiability]\n| language=german\n| editor1-first = H.\n| editor1-last = Seiffert\n| editor2-first = G.\n| editor2-last = Radnitzky \n| title = Handlexikon der Wissenschaftstheorie [Dictionary of epistemology]\n| publisher = Deutscher Taschenbuch Verlag \n| location = M\u00fcnchen \n| date = 1989\n| edition = 1992\n| isbn = 3-423-04586-8\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| first = Karl\n| last = Popper\n| year = 2009\n| orig-year = manuscript 1933, Published German 1979\n| editor-last = Eggers Hansen\n| editor-first = Troels\n| title = The Two Fundamental Problems of the Theory of Knowledge \n| publisher = Routledge \n| location = London and New York\n| translator-first = Andreas \n| translator-last = Pickel\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| title = Evolution\n| edition = 3rd\n| first = M\n| last = Ridley\n| publisher = Blackwell Publishing Limited\n| year = 2003\n| isbn = 1-4051-0345-0\n}}\n* {{Cite book| ref=harv\n| last = Rosende\n| first = Diego L.\n| chapter = Popper on Refutability : Some Philosophical and Historical Questions\n| title = Rethinking Popper\n| editor1-last = Parusnikova\n| editor1-first = Zuzana\n| editor2-last = Cohen\n| editor2-first = Robert S.\n| publisher = Springer\n| date = 2009\n| series = Boston Studies in the Philosophy of Science\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last1 = Ruse\n| first1 = Michael\n| title = Science and Spirituality: Making Room for Faith in the Age of Science\n| date = 2010\n| publisher = Cambridge university press\n| location = New York\n| isbn = 978-0-521-75594-8\n| edition =1st\n}}\n* Sokal, Alan, and Bricmont, Jean, ''[[Fashionable Nonsense]]'', Picador, New York, NY, 1998.\n* {{cite journal | ref = harv\n| last = Soler\n| first = L\u00e9na\n| date = 2001\n| journal = Le Portique\n| series = \n| title = Certitudes, incertitudes et enjeux de la philosophie des sciences contemporaine\n| volume = 7\n| veditors =\n| pages =\n| url= http://journals.openedition.org:80/leportique/pdf/236\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171216013830/http://journals.openedition.org:80/leportique/pdf/236\n| archive-date = 2017-12-16\n}}\n* Theobald, D.L. (2006). [https://web.archive.org/web/20110514101850/http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/comdesc/default.html#evidence 29+ Evidences for Macroevolution: The Scientific Case for Common Descent.] ''The Talk.Origins Archive''. Version 2.87.\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last1 = Thornton \n| first1 = Stephen \n| editor1-last = Zalta \n| editor1-first = Edward N.\n| title = The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy\n| date = 2016\n| orig-year=original publication 1997\n| edition = Summer 2017\n| chapter = Karl Popper\n| chapter-url=https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/sum2017/entries/popper/\n}}\n* {{Wikicite | ref = {{harvid|United States v. Prime|2002}}\n| reference={{cite court\n | litigants = United States v. Prime\n | court = W.D.Wash.\n | vol = 220\n | reporter = F. Supp. 2d\n | opinion=1203\n | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170908102653/https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp2/220/1203/2533848/%7Cdate%3D2002%7D%7D%7C\n }}\n}}\n* {{cite magazine | ref = harv\n| last = Wallis\n| first = C\n| title = The Evolution Wars\n| magazine= Time Magazine\n| date = 2005-08-07\n| url = http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1090909,00.html\n| url-access = subscription \n<!-- | archive-url = http://cchadley.free.fr/2ndYr/2ndYrCiv/TDTexts2008-09/B2TDTimeEvolutionWarsAug2005.pdf--> \n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last = Watkins\n| first = John\n| title =  Criticism and the growth of knowledge\n| date = 1970\n| chapter = Against 'Normal Science'\n| pages = 25\u201337\n| editor1-first = Imre\n| editor1-last = Lakatos\n| editor2-first = Alan\n| editor2-last = Musgrave\n| publisher = Cambridge University Press\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Abbreviated references==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n{{philosophy of science}}\n{{Karl Popper}}\n{{Positivism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Analytic philosophy]]\n[[Category:Epistemology of science]]\n[[Category:Epistemological theories]]\n[[Category:Karl Popper]]\n[[Category:Razors (philosophy)]]\n", "name_user": "Dominic Mayers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMathematics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falsifiability"}
{"title_page": "Framlingham, Victoria", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type                     = other\n| name                     = Framlingham\n| state                    = vic\n| image                    = \n| image_alt                = \n| use_lga_map              = yes\n| relief                   = \n| coordinates              = {{coord|38|14|0|S|142|42|0|E|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map_caption      = \n| pushpin_label_position   = right\n| map_alt                  = \n| pop                      = 158\n| pop_year                 = 2016\n| pop_footnotes            = <ref name=2016census>{{cite web | title=2016 Census QuickStats: Framlingham | website=Australian Bureau of Statistics | url=https://quickstats.censusdata.abs.gov.au/census_services/getproduct/census/2016/quickstat/SSC20938?opendocument | access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n| poprank                  = \n| density                  = \n| density_footnotes        = \n| established              = \n| established_footnotes    = \n| abolished                = \n| gazetted                 = \n| postcode                 = 3265\n| elevation                = \n| elevation_footnotes      = \n| area                     = \n| area_footnotes           = \n| timezone                 = \n| utc                      = \n| timezone-dst             = \n| utc-dst                  = \n| dist1                    = 233\n| dir1                     = SW\n| location1                = Melbourne\n| dist2                    = 12\n| dir2                     = E\n| location2                = [[Panmure, Victoria|Panmure]]\n| dist3                    = 18\n| dir3                     = W\n| location3                = Terang\n| lga                      = Shire of Moyne\n| seat                     = \n| region                   = \n| county                   = \n| division                 = \n| stategov                 = [[Electoral district of Polwarth|Polwarth]]\n| fedgov                   = [[Division of Wannon|Wannon]]\n| visitation_num           = \n| visitation_year          = \n| visitation_footnotes     = \n| managing_authorities     = \n| maxtemp                  = \n| maxtemp_footnotes        = \n| mintemp                  = \n| mintemp_footnotes        = \n| rainfall                 = \n| rainfall_footnotes       = \n| near-n                   = \n| near-ne                  = \n| near-e                   = \n| near-se                  = \n| near-s                   = \n| near-sw                  = \n| near-w                   = \n| near-nw                  = \n| near                     = \n| footnotes                = \n}}\n\n'''Framlingham''' is a rural township located by the [[Hopkins River]] in the [[Western District, Victoria|Western District]] of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia, about {{convert|20| km}} north-east of the coastal city of [[Warrnambool, Victoria|Warrnambool]]. In the [[2016 Australian census|2016 census]], the township had a population of 158.\n\nThe town lies within the traditional lands of the [[Girai wurrung]] (Kirrae Wuurong) people. In the decades following European settlement in the 1840s, a general store, post office, hotel, school and [[Presbyterian church]] were established in Framlingham, as increasing numbers of graziers and dairy farmers settled the area. The '''Framlingham Aboriginal Reserve''' was established by the [[Board for the Protection of Aborigines]] between [[Purnim, Victoria|Purnim]] and the township of Framlingham in 1861, upon the request of an [[Anglican Church of Australia|Anglican]] mission. It was located beside the [[Hopkins River]], not far from the boundary with the [[Gunditjmara]] people. After various attempts at closure, the [[Aboriginal reserve|reserve]] operated until 1916, albeit with the land reduced in size. Much of the Aboriginal community continued to live there until the present time. Some of the land that was originally part of the reserve became '''Framlingham Forest''', which is now part of the '''Framlingham Forest Indigenous Protected Area''' (IPA).\n\n==History==\n[[File:Kaawirn kuunawarn.jpeg|thumb|right|Kaawirn Kuunawarn (Hissing Swan), also known as King David, Chief of the Kirrae Wuurong, who lived in Framlingham from 1865 until his death in 1889. ]]\n===1861: Aboriginal reserve established===\nThe Church of England in Warnambool formed the Anglican [[Mission (Christian)|mission]] in 1861, which requested establishment of an [[Aboriginal reserve]] in the area. The Victorian Board for the Protection of Aborigines created Framlingham Aboriginal Reserve in response. The reserve was occupied in 1865 by many of the surviving members of the [[Girai Wurrung|Kirrae Wuurong]] clans, who originally inhabited the area between [[Mount Emu Creek]] and the Hopkins River, and much of whose language was recorded by a Scottish [[Squatting (pastoral)|squatter]], [[James Dawson (activist)|James Dawson]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ccmaindig.info/culture/Lng_Girai.html |title=Girai Wurrung |access-date=27 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305030025/http://ccmaindig.info/culture/lng_girai.html |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Members of the [[Djargurd Wurrung]] from the Camperdown area and [[Gunditjmara]] people from Warrnambool were also relocated to Framlingham, but [[Gunditjmara]] from Portland and Lake Condah refused to settle here due to tension with the other clans, leading to the establishment of Lake Condah reserve in 1869.<ref name=\"scars_on_the_landscape_pp12\">Ian D. Clark, pp12, ''Scars on the Landscape. A Register of Massacre sites in Western Victoria 1803\u20131859'', Aboriginal Studies Press, 1995 {{ISBN|0-85575-281-5}}</ref>\n\nIn 1867 the reserve was closed by the Central Board appointed by the [[Government of Victoria]] and attempts were made to relocate the residents to [[Lake Condah Mission]] but in September 1868 the Kirrae Wuurong won the re-establishment of the reserve. Residents of Warrnambool campaigned from 1877 to 1890 to close the reserve and turn it into an experimental agricultural farm, and in 1894 the reserve was reduced to {{convert|222|ha|km2}} and the majority of the land given to the Council of Agricultural Education. However, the agricultural farm plans never eventuated, with this land becoming the Framlingham Forest.<ref name=\"scars_on_the_landscape_pp125\" />  In 1889 the Board attempted to close the reserve again, but it finally agreed to reserve {{convert|500| acres}}} for Aboriginal use.<ref name=atns>{{cite web | title=Framlingham Aboriginal Reserve | website=ATNS | date=16 January 2003 | url=https://www.atns.net.au/agreement.asp?EntityID=1032 | access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1916 the Government of Victoria decided to concentrate [[Aboriginal Victorians]] at [[Lake Tyers Mission]] in Gippsland. The reserve was eventually closed but some residents were allowed to remain, with the community being granted ownership in 1971 of the {{convert|237|ha|km2}} they held at that time.<ref name=\"scars_on_the_landscape_pp125\">Ian D. Clark, pp125-133, ''Scars on the Landscape. A Register of Massacre sites in Western Victoria 1803\u20131859'', Aboriginal Studies Press, 1995 {{ISBN|0-85575-281-5}}</ref> In the 1930s, public concern over the conditions led the government to build extra housing and a school, and to provide rations.<ref name=atns/>\n\nWhen the reserve was established, it was declared to be {{convert|3500|acre|km2}} in area, although its actual size may have been closer to {{convert|4400|acre|km2}}. As parts of the reserve were sold to private landowners, its size diminished, until only the {{convert|586|acre|km2}} remained when it was closed in 1971. Some of this land was also set aside as a State Forest.\n\n===1970-1987: Land rights===\nIn 1957 the Board for the Protection of Aborigines was abolished, and in 1970 the ''[[Aboriginal Lands Act 1970]]''<ref name=lands1970>{{cite web | title=Aboriginal Lands Act 1970 | website=Australasian Legal Information Institute | url=http://www8.austlii.edu.au/cgi-bin/viewdb/au/legis/vic/consol_act/ala1970144/ | access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> was passed by the [[Parliament of Victoria]]. Under the provisions of that Act, ownership of Framlingham was handed over to a trust held by Aboriginal residents of the site, Framlingham Aboriginal Trust,<ref name=atns/> on 1 July 1971. Along with Lake Tyers, in the eastern [[Gippsland]] region of the state, Framlingham was the last reserve to close in Victoria.\n\nIn 1976 the Framlingham community began a campaign to regain rights to the Framlingham Forest, that had been excised from the original 1861 reserve in 1894. In April 1979 the community blockaded the road to the forest picnic ground. The Victorian Government proposed allowing Aboriginal management of the forest in 1980 but maintained that it would continue as crown land. The proposal was rejected by the community, who resumed the blockade.<ref name=\"scars_on_the_landscape_pp125\" /><ref>Kerry Wakefield, pp3, ''Warrnambool blacks had century of misery: report'', [[The Age]], 2 September 1980. Accessed from Google News Archive on 29 September 2009</ref><ref>ABC News archival video, ''[http://www.abc.net.au/missionvoices/framlingham/art_photos_videos/documentary_footage/default.htm Framlingham Blockade]'', Koorie Heritage Trust. Retrieved 29 September 2009</ref>\n\nIn 1987, the Victorian [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] government under [[John Cain II|John Cain]] attempted to grant some of the [[Framlingham State Forest]] to the trust as inalienable title, but the legislation was blocked by the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]] opposition in the [[Legislative Council of Victoria|Legislative Council]]. However, the federal Labor government under [[Bob Hawke]] intervened, passing the ''[[Aboriginal Land (Lake Condah and Framlingham Forest) Act 1987]]'',<ref name=allcff1987>{{cite web | title=Aboriginal Land (Lake Condah and Framlingham Forest) Act 1987 | website=Australasian Legal Information Institute | url=http://www8.austlii.edu.au/cgi-bin/viewdb/au/legis/cth/consol_act/alcaffa1987374/ | access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> which gave {{convert|1130|acre|km2}} of the Framlingham forest to the Framlingham trust. Although the title is essentially inalienable, in that it can only be transferred to another Indigenous land trust, the Framlingham trust has no rights to prevent mining on the land, unlike trusts or communities holding [[native title]].{{cn}} The Kirrae Whurrong Aboriginal Corporation was established under the ''Aboriginal Lands Act 1970'' in order to hold in trust \"the land of the Framlingham Forest and Reserve returned to the Aboriginal community\".<ref>{{cite web | title=Kirrae Whurrong Aboriginal Corporation | website=ATNS | date=25 January 2005 | url=https://www.atns.net.au/agreement.asp?EntityID=2487 | access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1983: Ash Wednesday===\nOn 16 February 1983, one of the [[Ash Wednesday fires]] started here and swept through the district killing nine people, destroying many homes, farm buildings and livestock. The cause was believed to be poorly maintained power lines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cfa.vic.gov.au/about/history/about_ash_wednesday.htm |title=About Ash Wednesday |accessdate=10 May 2008 |publisher=[[Country Fire Authority]] Victoria, Australia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080323132901/http://www.cfa.vic.gov.au/about/history/about_ash_wednesday.htm |archivedate=23 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===2009: Framlingham Forest IPA===\n\nIn 2009, an [[Indigenous Protected Area]] was dedicated, known as the Framlingham Forest IPA, covering {{convert|1,130| ha}} of native forests. It is the largest remnant of native forest containing the [[stringybark]] and [[manna gum]] savannah in the area. The Framlingham Aboriginal Trust manages the land.<ref>{{cite web | title=Framlingham Forest IPA | website=National Indigenous Australians AgencyVic Projects | date=10 December 2015 | url=https://www.niaa.gov.au/indigenous-affairs/environment/indigenous-protected-areas/framlingham-forest-ipa | access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n==Post Offices==\nFramlingham Post Office nearby opened on 1 March 1859 and closed in 1975. A Framlingham East Post Office was also open from 1925 until 1945.<ref name = \"a\">{{Citation\n  | last = Premier Postal History  | title = Post Office List | url = https://www.premierpostal.com/cgi-bin/wsProd.sh/Viewpocdwrapper.p?SortBy=VIC&country= | accessdate = 11 April 2008 }}</ref>\n==Description==\n\nThe town has a hall and a public reserve with tennis court and barbecue facilities. The [[fire station]] was opened in 2015. The school, established in 1872, was closed in 1993.<ref>''[http://www.victorianplaces.com.au/framlingham]'', Framlingham, ''Victorian Places''. Retrieved 27 March 2017</ref>\n\n==Notable citizens==\n* [[Reg Saunders]], famous Aboriginal soldier, was born in Framlingham in 1920.\n==See also==\n* [[Girai Wurrung|Kirrae Wuurong]] \n* [[Gunditjmara]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150402164811/https://open.abc.net.au/people/2993 Framlingham Community Stories]\n\n\n{{Towns in Moyne Shire}}\n\n{{Victorian Aborigines}}\n\n[[Category:Aboriginal communities in Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian reserves]]\n[[Category:Warrnambool]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type                     = other\n| name                     = Framlingham\n| state                    = vic\n| image                    = \n| image_alt                = \n| use_lga_map              = yes\n| relief                   = \n| coordinates              = {{coord|38|14|0|S|142|42|0|E|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map_caption      = \n| pushpin_label_position   = right\n| map_alt                  = \n| pop                      = 157\n| pop_year                 = 2016\n| pop_footnotes            = \n| poprank                  = \n| density                  = \n| density_footnotes        = \n| established              = \n| established_footnotes    = \n| abolished                = \n| gazetted                 = \n| postcode                 = 3265\n| elevation                = \n| elevation_footnotes      = \n| area                     = \n| area_footnotes           = \n| timezone                 = \n| utc                      = \n| timezone-dst             = \n| utc-dst                  = \n| dist1                    = 233\n| dir1                     = SW\n| location1                = Melbourne\n| dist2                    = 12\n| dir2                     = E\n| location2                = [[Panmure, Victoria|Panmure]]\n| dist3                    = 18\n| dir3                     = W\n| location3                = Terang\n| lga                      = Shire of Moyne\n| seat                     = \n| region                   = \n| county                   = \n| division                 = \n| stategov                 = [[Electoral district of Polwarth|Polwarth]]\n| fedgov                   = [[Division of Wannon|Wannon]]\n| visitation_num           = \n| visitation_year          = \n| visitation_footnotes     = \n| managing_authorities     = \n| maxtemp                  = \n| maxtemp_footnotes        = \n| mintemp                  = \n| mintemp_footnotes        = \n| rainfall                 = \n| rainfall_footnotes       = \n| near-n                   = \n| near-ne                  = \n| near-e                   = \n| near-se                  = \n| near-s                   = \n| near-sw                  = \n| near-w                   = \n| near-nw                  = \n| near                     = \n| footnotes                = \n}}\n\n'''Framlingham''' is a rural township located by the [[Hopkins River]] in the [[Western District, Victoria|Western District]] of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia, about {{convert|20| km}} north-east of the coastal city of [[Warrnambool, Victoria|Warrnambool]]. In the [[2016 Australian census|2016 census]], the township had a population of 157.\n\nThe town lies within the traditional lands of the [[Girai wurrung]] (Kirrae Wuurong) people. In the decades following European settlement in the 1840s, a general store, post office, hotel, school and [[Presbyterian church]] were established in Framlingham, as increasing numbers of graziers and dairy farmers settled the area. The '''Framlingham Aboriginal Reserve''' was established by the [[Board for the Protection of Aborigines]] between [[Purnim, Victoria|Purnim]] and the township of Framlingham in 1861, upon the request of an [[Anglican Church of Australia|Anglican]] mission. It was located beside the [[Hopkins River]], not far from the boundary with the [[Gunditjmara]] people. After various attempts at closure, the [[Aboriginal reserve|reserve]] operated until 1916, albeit with the land reduced in size. Much of the Aboriginal community continued to live there until the present time. Some of the land that was originally part of the reserve became '''Framlingham Forest''', which is now part of the '''Framlingham Forest Indigenous Protected Area''' (IPA).\n\n==History==\n[[File:Kaawirn kuunawarn.jpeg|thumb|right|Kaawirn Kuunawarn (Hissing Swan), also known as King David, Chief of the Kirrae Wuurong, who lived in Framlingham from 1865 until his death in 1889. ]]\n===1861: Aboriginal reserve established===\nThe Church of England in Warnambool formed the Anglican [[Mission (Christian)|mission]] in 1861, which requested establishment of an [[Aboriginal reserve]] in the area. The Victorian Board for the Protection of Aborigines created Framlingham Aboriginal Reserve in response. The reserve was occupied in 1865 by many of the surviving members of the [[Girai Wurrung|Kirrae Wuurong]] clans, who originally inhabited the area between [[Mount Emu Creek]] and the Hopkins River, and much of whose language was recorded by a Scottish [[Squatting (pastoral)|squatter]], [[James Dawson (activist)|James Dawson]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ccmaindig.info/culture/Lng_Girai.html |title=Girai Wurrung |access-date=27 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305030025/http://ccmaindig.info/culture/lng_girai.html |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Members of the [[Djargurd Wurrung]] from the Camperdown area and [[Gunditjmara]] people from Warrnambool were also relocated to Framlingham, but [[Gunditjmara]] from Portland and Lake Condah refused to settle here due to tension with the other clans, leading to the establishment of Lake Condah reserve in 1869.<ref name=\"scars_on_the_landscape_pp12\">Ian D. Clark, pp12, ''Scars on the Landscape. A Register of Massacre sites in Western Victoria 1803\u20131859'', Aboriginal Studies Press, 1995 {{ISBN|0-85575-281-5}}</ref>\n\nIn 1867 the reserve was closed by the Central Board appointed by the [[Government of Victoria]] and attempts were made to relocate the residents to [[Lake Condah Mission]] but in September 1868 the Kirrae Wuurong won the re-establishment of the reserve. Residents of Warrnambool campaigned from 1877 to 1890 to close the reserve and turn it into an experimental agricultural farm, and in 1894 the reserve was reduced to {{convert|222|ha|km2}} and the majority of the land given to the Council of Agricultural Education. However, the agricultural farm plans never eventuated, with this land becoming the Framlingham Forest.<ref name=\"scars_on_the_landscape_pp125\" />  In 1889 the Board attempted to close the reserve again, but it finally agreed to reserve {{convert|500| acres}}} for Aboriginal use.<ref name=atns>{{cite web | title=Framlingham Aboriginal Reserve | website=ATNS | date=16 January 2003 | url=https://www.atns.net.au/agreement.asp?EntityID=1032 | access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1916 the Government of Victoria decided to concentrate [[Aboriginal Victorians]] at [[Lake Tyers Mission]] in Gippsland. The reserve was eventually closed but some residents were allowed to remain, with the community being granted ownership in 1971 of the {{convert|237|ha|km2}} they held at that time.<ref name=\"scars_on_the_landscape_pp125\">Ian D. Clark, pp125-133, ''Scars on the Landscape. A Register of Massacre sites in Western Victoria 1803\u20131859'', Aboriginal Studies Press, 1995 {{ISBN|0-85575-281-5}}</ref> In the 1930s, public concern over the conditions led the government to build extra housing and a school, and to provide rations.<ref name=atns/>\n\nWhen the reserve was established, it was declared to be {{convert|3500|acre|km2}} in area, although its actual size may have been closer to {{convert|4400|acre|km2}}. As parts of the reserve were sold to private landowners, its size diminished, until only the {{convert|586|acre|km2}} remained when it was closed in 1971. Some of this land was also set aside as a State Forest.\n\n===1970-1987: Land rights===\nIn 1957 the Board for the Protection of Aborigines was abolished, and in 1970 the ''[[Aboriginal Lands Act 1970]]''<ref name=lands1970>{{cite web | title=Aboriginal Lands Act 1970 | website=Australasian Legal Information Institute | url=http://www8.austlii.edu.au/cgi-bin/viewdb/au/legis/vic/consol_act/ala1970144/ | access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> was passed by the [[Parliament of Victoria]]. Under the provisions of that Act, ownership of Framlingham was handed over to a trust held by Aboriginal residents of the site, Framlingham Aboriginal Trust,<ref name=atns/> on 1 July 1971. Along with Lake Tyers, in the eastern [[Gippsland]] region of the state, Framlingham was the last reserve to close in Victoria.\n\nIn 1976 the Framlingham community began a campaign to regain rights to the Framlingham Forest, that had been excised from the original 1861 reserve in 1894. In April 1979 the community blockaded the road to the forest picnic ground. The Victorian Government proposed allowing Aboriginal management of the forest in 1980 but maintained that it would continue as crown land. The proposal was rejected by the community, who resumed the blockade.<ref name=\"scars_on_the_landscape_pp125\" /><ref>Kerry Wakefield, pp3, ''Warrnambool blacks had century of misery: report'', [[The Age]], 2 September 1980. Accessed from Google News Archive on 29 September 2009</ref><ref>ABC News archival video, ''[http://www.abc.net.au/missionvoices/framlingham/art_photos_videos/documentary_footage/default.htm Framlingham Blockade]'', Koorie Heritage Trust. Retrieved 29 September 2009</ref>\n\nIn 1987, the Victorian [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] government under [[John Cain II|John Cain]] attempted to grant some of the [[Framlingham State Forest]] to the trust as inalienable title, but the legislation was blocked by the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]] opposition in the [[Legislative Council of Victoria|Legislative Council]]. However, the federal Labor government under [[Bob Hawke]] intervened, passing the ''[[Aboriginal Land (Lake Condah and Framlingham Forest) Act 1987]]'',<ref name=allcff1987>{{cite web | title=Aboriginal Land (Lake Condah and Framlingham Forest) Act 1987 | website=Australasian Legal Information Institute | url=http://www8.austlii.edu.au/cgi-bin/viewdb/au/legis/cth/consol_act/alcaffa1987374/ | access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> which gave {{convert|1130|acre|km2}} of the Framlingham forest to the Framlingham trust. Although the title is essentially inalienable, in that it can only be transferred to another Indigenous land trust, the Framlingham trust has no rights to prevent mining on the land, unlike trusts or communities holding [[native title]].{{cn}} The Kirrae Whurrong Aboriginal Corporation was established under the ''Aboriginal Lands Act 1970'' in order to hold in trust \"the land of the Framlingham Forest and Reserve returned to the Aboriginal community\".<ref>{{cite web | title=Kirrae Whurrong Aboriginal Corporation | website=ATNS | date=25 January 2005 | url=https://www.atns.net.au/agreement.asp?EntityID=2487 | access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1983: Ash Wednesday===\nOn 16 February 1983, one of the [[Ash Wednesday fires]] started here and swept through the district killing nine people, destroying many homes, farm buildings and livestock. The cause was believed to be poorly maintained power lines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cfa.vic.gov.au/about/history/about_ash_wednesday.htm |title=About Ash Wednesday |accessdate=10 May 2008 |publisher=[[Country Fire Authority]] Victoria, Australia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080323132901/http://www.cfa.vic.gov.au/about/history/about_ash_wednesday.htm |archivedate=23 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===2009: Framlingham Forest IPA===\n\nIn 2009, an [[Indigenous Protected Area]] was dedicated, known as the Framlingham Forest IPA, covering {{convert|1,130| ha}} of native forests. It is the largest remnant of native forest containing the [[stringybark]] and [[manna gum]] savannah in the area. The Framlingham Aboriginal Trust manages the land.<ref>{{cite web | title=Framlingham Forest IPA | website=National Indigenous Australians AgencyVic Projects | date=10 December 2015 | url=https://www.niaa.gov.au/indigenous-affairs/environment/indigenous-protected-areas/framlingham-forest-ipa | access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n==Post Offices==\nFramlingham Post Office nearby opened on 1 March 1859 and closed in 1975. A Framlingham East Post Office was also open from 1925 until 1945.<ref name = \"a\">{{Citation\n  | last = Premier Postal History  | title = Post Office List | url = https://www.premierpostal.com/cgi-bin/wsProd.sh/Viewpocdwrapper.p?SortBy=VIC&country= | accessdate = 11 April 2008 }}</ref>\n==Description==\n\nThe town has a hall and a public reserve with tennis court and barbecue facilities. The [[fire station]] was opened in 2015. The school, established in 1872, was closed in 1993.<ref>''[http://www.victorianplaces.com.au/framlingham]'', Framlingham, ''Victorian Places''. Retrieved 27 March 2017</ref>\n\n==Notable citizens==\n* [[Reg Saunders]], famous Aboriginal soldier, was born in Framlingham in 1920.\n==See also==\n* [[Girai Wurrung|Kirrae Wuurong]] \n* [[Gunditjmara]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150402164811/https://open.abc.net.au/people/2993 Framlingham Community Stories]\n\n\n{{Towns in Moyne Shire}}\n\n{{Victorian Aborigines}}\n\n[[Category:Aboriginal communities in Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian reserves]]\n[[Category:Warrnambool]]\n", "name_user": "Laterthanyouthink", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:update and cite population figure", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Framlingham,_Victoria"}
